slot machines line the walls of supermarkets and bars in this gaming resort, but they don't belong in doughnut shops or laundries, officials decided
clark county commissioners voted monday to prohibit new slot machine licenses for machines in laundries, bakeries, doughnut shops, fast-food restaurants, movie theaters and professional offices
existing licenses are not affected
several owners of self-service laundries said they depend on slot machine revenue to cover the high cost of doing business, with the slots generating about 25 percent of revenues. other laundry owners stressed that customers need something to do to keep occupied while their clothes spin and tumble
commissioners said it is too hard to regulate the machines if they are allowed to continue to proliferate in different businesses. details. pick up 15th graf pvs: journalists saw ... with deletions to trim and conform</note>
plainclothes police stormed a building housing an opposition party office and its radio station tuesday, setting off a rock-throwing protest by foes of gen. manuel antonio noriega's military rule
carlos ivan zuniga, leader and presidential candidate of the popular action party in 1984, was beaten and arrested. zuniga, owner of radio 10-fm, was released hours later
the plainclothes police and later a riot squad fired dozens of shots into the air to disperse the crowd outside the building. the brawl occurred as an anti-noriega strike called by the opposition civic crusade entered its second day and appeared to be picking up support
witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of reprisals, said plainclothes police with shotguns and pistols rushed into the popular action building on via espana, smashing furniture and equipment inside the radio station
radio 10-fm was under censorship orders to play only music, but had been broadcasting news supporting the strike
an angry crowd gathered outside the building and started throwing rocks at the officers. an unidentified radio station employee was slightly injured
leaders of the civil crusade, a coalition of 180 business, professional, labor, student and political groups, told a news conference tuesday night the strike shut down 85 percent of panama's economic activity. they said 90 percent of industry and construction were paralyzed
they conceded that transportation was down by only 10 percent, but said retail commerce was 40 percent of normal
carlos gonzalez de la lastra, a crusade leader and a strike organizer, said ``this demonstrates the panamanian people's repudiation of the dictatorship of gen. noriega and the fervent desire for complete democracy.''
the government, through some of the news media it controls, has been calling the strike ``a complete failure,'' alleging business and transportation were functioning normally
the young security men at the radio station, dressed in jeans and t-shirts, outnumbered the protesters and broke up the demonstration after 40 minutes
the demonstrators were banging pots and pans in the streets and distributing leaflets
at least four men were punched, kicked and beaten with rubber truncheons during the melee as they were arrested and shoved into police vehicles
two women were among those arrested on via argentina, an upper middle-class neighborhood. they were not beaten, but one was slapped on the buttocks as she was hustled into a car
at first only about 15 demonstrators from the popular action party were involved at the radio station building, but the crowd swelled to about 150 when residents came out on balconies or sidewalks to join in beating pans. many people bolted for cover, however, when security agents came to screeching stops in 4-wheel-drive toyotas
the agents jumped out and began shooting. some residents returned to balconies from time to time, shouting ``murderers!'' and ``cowards!''
zuniga, leader of popular action, was beaten and shoved into a vehicle. the car was blocked by another vehicle and zuniga, a white-haired man of about 60, fled down the street with his torn shirt fluttering and security men in pursuit
bystanders created interference and zuniga dived into a car that sped away, but he was caught later
eric arturo delvalle, ousted as president last week by noriega, remained in hiding tuesday. he predicted serious economic trouble
delvalle's successor, manuel solis palma, accused the united states of ``lies and defamation'' about noriega and the panama defense forces, the 17,000-member military and police organization commanded by noriega, the real power behind the civilian government
journalists saw at least three people wounded by birdshot fired by either the plainclothes agents or soldiers who arrived later. one man was bleeding from the head, but did not seem to be seriously injured
calm was reported elsewhere in panama city. by midafternoon, the strike had drastically thinned traffic and the crowds on the streets
strike leaders said 12 panamanian-owned banks were closed. most international banks opened, but did comparatively little business
only one employee and five guards occupied the main area of the large chase manhattan bank branch. the scenes were similar at citibank and the bank of boston
some international institutions shut down, including the bank of tokyo
solis palma, delvalle's replacement, inaugurated a new session of the legislative assembly with an anti-american speech. the assembly, which noriega controls, dismissed delvalle last friday
noriega has been the victim of the most violent and terrible campaign of lies and defamation that any leader has ever received,'' solis palma said. he accused the united states and opponents of the government of ``the clear political intention of bringing ill repute on the panama defense forces.''
he said the united states ``wants to asphyxiate the panamanian people economically.''
solis palma said the united states has been ``a traditional enemy'' of panama. ``they send to our country destabilizing agents who try to sow chaos in a nation that let its entrails be opened to serve the world,'' he said in a reference to the panama canal
panamanian officials have claimed protests at home and the indictment of noriega on drug charges in florida are the work of american conservatives who oppose the 1977 treaties under which the canal is to be turned over to panama on dec. 31, 1999
in a videotape of delvalle distributed by his associates, the former president pledged to remain in panama and continue resistance to noriega
he said the crisis would make it impossible for panama to get new loans from abroad and described the country as ``totally bankrupt.''
delvalle predicted the lack of credit would force the government to raise taxes, which he said ``will increase unemployment and social unrest.''
mandatory drug testing in the workplace will be studied for the first time by the supreme court in a case that involves government workers but could have an impact on private businesses as well
the justices on monday agreed to decide whether the u.s. customs service, in the interest of fighting drug smuggling, may force those applying for or holding drug-enforcement jobs to be tested
the court will hear arguments in the case next fall, with a decision on the constitutionality of the reagan administration program not expected until 1989
the court also may be called upon soon to study drug and alcohol testing for federal railway workers. a federal appeals court in san francisco ruled on feb. 11 that the railway testing program is unconstitutional and the reagan administration said it will appeal that ruling to the high court
allan adler of the american civil liberties union said the high court's action on testing of government workers could influence private employers, depending on how broad the court ruling is
the big question is whether the court is going to determine this on a narrow, fact basis or will it attempt to articulate broad principles'' involving workers' reasonable expecations of privacy, he said
he said a narrow ruling relying on the special security needs of the customs service would limit the impact in part because ``most (private) employers have shied away from random, generalized testing.''
but a sweeping endorsement of testing by the court could change that
the case before the justices is limited to whether public officials violate constitutional rights by testing those who are not suspected of using drugs
the outcome will affect tests conducted by federal, state or local governments but not by industry. under the law, governments may not violate any rights protected by the constitution, but private individuals or corporations have more leeway
customs service workers in sensitive jobs must provide urine samples in restroom stalls as a person overseeing the procedure waits outside the stall. the tests are conducted by an independent company hired by the service
administration lawyers said the tests are needed to prevent agents who used drugs from being bribed or blackmailed. they said any sacrifice of personal privacy is outweighed by the need to stop drug smuggling
government lawyers said the tests are particularly important now because the customs service plans to recruit some 3,000 new employees, including many in the 18-25 age range in which use of illegal drugs is most prevalent
the customs service adopted the test procedure under an executive order president reagan signed in 1986
the procedure is being challenged by the national treasury employees union, which said subjecting workers to the test is a humiliating invasion of privacy
the union welcomed the high court's intervention
union president robert m. tobias said the court's ruling will clear up ``a legal and moral morass ... and, we hope, destroy reagan's plans for wholesale testing of the federal work force.''
the transportation department, with 30,000 employees, has adopted random testing for its workers. the program covers those in safety-related jobs such as air traffic controllers, federal aviation administration pilots and workers with high-rated security clearance
the customs service tests, which are not administered randomly, were upheld by the new orleans-based 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals
the appeals court said the tests may be considered searches but do not intrude unnecessarily on the privacy rights of workers
in other actions monday, the court:
_agreed to decide whether states may bar a man from trying to prove he fathered the child of a woman married to someone else. the ``reverse paternity'' case challenges a california law, similar to those in many other states, that always considers the woman's husband the father
_asked the reagan administration, in a case from oklahoma, whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes
_said it will decide whether employees of a pentagon intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when the government fires them as security risks. candidate</head>
while massachusetts republicans searched for a candidate for what many believe is a hopeless situation, sen. edward m. kennedy raised $1.32 million in preparation for his re-election bid
federal election commission reports show the massachusetts democrat has $1.01 million in his campaign account after spending $457,640 during 1987. he raised $826,790 in the last six months of 1987 alone
we will have a strong candidate,'' promised joe malone, executive director of the state republican party, in a recent interview. ``as of now, discussions are still going on.''
but it is no secret that the state's few big-name republicans, including party chief raymond shamie, have no desire to put on a quixotic campaign against kennedy, who is seeking his sixth term
one potential candidate is thomas carhart, a program analyst at the pentagon's strategic defense office who is considering a senate run. his family is from the amherst area
carhart said in a recent interview he would decide in several weeks whether to run
carhart, 44, is a graduate of west point and the university of michigan law school. he has been a platoon leader in vietnam, an analyst at the rand corp., the editor of a tax journal, author of a book about vietnam, an attorney and a leading activist against the controversial vietnam memorial in washington
but carhart has little experience in politics and is a virtual unknown in massachusetts. republican party strategists are quietly working to get a better-known candidate to run against kennedy
the senator's year-end fec report showed he received most of his 1987 campaign contributions _ $1.06 million _ from individual contributors. the remaining $263,000 came from political action committees
president reagan is indicating he would sign a bill giving only humanitarian aid to nicaragua's rebels if it preserves his option of seeking military funds in the future
reagan told the american legion convention that ``preventing the consolidation of a pro-soviet regime on the american mainland is a crucial test of national security.''
on the eve of today's scheduled house rules committee consideration of a humanitarian aid package, he seemed resigned to the fact there will be no immediate vote for military aid
some say they're willing to support some type of humanitarian aid, but are doing everything they can do disband the freedom fighters,'' reagan said. ``but there's nothing humanitarian about asking people to go up against soviet attack helicopters armed only with boots and bandages.''
reagan used the american legion address to remind congress of his intentions as he prepared to leave for the summit with nato partners in brussels, belgium. he is concerned about possible showdown votes on contra aid, first in the rules committee and later in the week on the house floor
the committee is weighing a $30.5 million contra aid bill, sponsored by rep. david bonior, d-mich., and other democrats, which would provide no military assistance
a rival republican bill would be in much the same form as the $36.2 million piece of legislation that reagan had sought earlier this year, except there would be no money contained in the bill for a military escrow account
in an attempt to win enactment of the $36.2 million measure in early february, reagan told congress he would consult with leading lawmakers before releasing the $3.6 million in an escrow fund for military use. the house defeated the bill by eight votes. it was passed in the senate, but the vote was only symbolic
the cia's authority to carry out airlifts of supplies to the rebels expired at midnight. reagan did not mention this monday. but he did say that ``whatever package emerges from the congress must include a provision for expedited procedures that would allow us to request official military aid to the freedom fighters should the peace process break down.''
reagan said that since the $36.2 million contra aid package was defeated, the sandinistas have been ambivalent about promised reforms, causing cardinal obando y bravo to suspend peace talks he has been mediating
unless the freedom fighters remain a viable force, the peace process will remain what it was before _ an empty charade, dragging endlessly and fruitlessly on while the soviets continue the military buildup on the american mainland,'' reagan said
reagan told his audience that if all assistance is stopped, the rebels ``will be picked off one by one'' by the leftist sandinista regime in managua
are we going to cut them off now and leave them defenseless against the sandinistas? if we do, who will ever trust in the united states again? how can we remain a world power if we gain a reputation for pulling the plug on the people that placed their trust in us?''
congress may be upset about the number of officers in the u.s. military, but the armed forces of some of america's closest allies are much more top-heavy, a survey has found
of 11 nations surveyed by a military journal, only two had a lower ratio of admirals and generals to active-duty personnel than the united states _ austria and west germany
moreover, the no. 1 country among those surveyed _ canada _ has built a military force whose ratio of generals and admirals to active-duty forces is more than three times that of the united states
the survey was conducted by the monthly magazine ``armed forces journal'' and the results summarized in its march issue, published today. the magazine said it contacted the defense ministries directly or else turned to foreign embassies in washington for the information needed to make a comparison of active-duty forces
austria possesses easily the leanest of the military establishments surveyed, with just 5 generals leading an active-duty force of 54,700, the survey found. that translates to just 0.9 generals per 10,000 active-duty personnel, the magazine reported
the next eight countries fall into a range that runs from 4 generals and admirals per 10,000 active-duty personnel to about 9 generals per 10,000. the united states is in this group with a ratio of 4.9 generals and admirals for every 10,000 active-duty personnel
the final two countries _ britain and canada _ are in a class by themselves, the magazine reported. britain has 476 generals and admirals to lead its 320,000 men and women on active duty, or a ratio of 14.9 per 10,000, while canada has 141 generals and admirals for 87,254 active-duty personnel, or a ratio of 16.2 per 10,000
at the other end of the scale, west germany followed austria with 199 generals and admirals for its 495,000 on active duty, or a ratio of 4.0 generals and admirals per 10,000 troops
the united states has slightly more than 2.1 million men and women under arms. as of november, when the information was compiled, congress had authorized 1,073 slots for generals and admirals and 1,057 of those jobs were filled
either number produces the same ratio of roughly 4.9 per 10,000
congress, complaining about what it calls ``grade creep,'' imposed the cap of 1,073 active-duty slots for generals and admirals in 1981. lawmakers have refused ever since to raise it despite repeated pentagon entreaties
congress also ordered the defense department in its fiscal 1987 budget to begin reducing the number of lower-ranking officers in the military. the pentagon is under orders to reduce its officer corps of colonels and captains by 6 percent by fiscal 1990 _ or more than 18,000 job slots
before the cutting began, the army, navy, air force and marine corps had more than 308,700 officers on active duty, or roughly one officer for every 5.9 enlisted personnel. by next september, that number must fall to 302,620, with additional cuts to follow
the contra rebels, looking for a tax-exempt organization to carry out fund raising, used a legal shortcut to take over a foundation begun by political conservatives to promote understanding of ``governmental systems.''
by reconstituting an existing foundation, the contras avoided the time nd lengthy application process generally entailed in applying to the internal revenue service for tax-exempt status
what now goes by the name of the nicaraguan resistance educational foundation was originally the john davis lodge foundation for international studies, according to irs records
the contra foundation has not filed its first tax return yet because the changeover occurred just last fall
the lodge foundation stated in its application for tax-exempt status in 1982 that its purpose would be to ``foster, develop and promote, among people of the world, in a nonpartisan basis, a greater understanding and awareness of comparative governmental systems, international policies and the relationships between sovereign states.''
the late john davis lodge was a connecticut governor and congressman, and ambassador to argentina, switzerland and spain. the grandson of sen. henry cabot lodge of massachusetts, he was an ardent anti-communist and chaired ronald reagan's 1980 presidential campaign in connecticut. he died in 1985 at age 82
he was also a mentor to conservative political consultant roger stone of virginia. stone set up the lodge foundation in 1982 to host forums and publish educational materials
it was set up as a hardline anti-communist'' organization, but the foundation never really got off the ground and published only one monograph by former united nations ambassador jeane kirkpatrick, stone said
last fall, stone learned from his wife that the rebels needed a foundation to collect money for their cause
it so happens that ann stone has a direct mail fund-raising business and the contras are one of her clients. ``she had something to do with it,'' roger stone said of the idea to turn his foundation over to the contras
she made the argument it was consistent with the original purposes of the foundation.''
so last october, stone and two business partners, charlie black and paul manafort, whom stone had installed as original board members, met and voted themselves off the board. they turned the organization over to newly elected board members ernesto palazio, the contras' washington spokesman, and two miami contra officials, leonardo somarriba and mario zeledon
now the foundation is the principal conduit for funds the contras are raising privately. the rebels have placed increasing emphasis on these efforts in the wake of congress' recent rejection of new u.s. aid
the contras say the money they are raising from u.s. citizens is for humanitarian aid only
raising money for weapons is not a tax-exempt function, and contra backers ran afoul of that law in last year's iran-contra scandal
the irs permits changes in purpose and makeup of a foundation as long as the new group is still within the guidelines of tax-exempt purposes, said irs spokesman wilson fadely
the contra foundation in december received $140,000 from the fund created in memory of the late cia director william j. casey, and contra officials said the money was for a rehabilitation hospital for their wounded and maimed soldiers. card user</head>
the government still prints money on paper for all debts public and private, but the reagan administration says it will gladly take plastic
the office of management and budget on monday announced a new progam to increase dramatically the government's use of credit cards _ both for buying and selling
not only will the government start accepting credit cards from the public for such items as passports and payments on college loans, but the omb said it also hopes to develop a plan under which government officials and purchasing agents will use cards
eventually, the office of management and budget will be able to require that all purchases made (by the government) under $2,500 be by credit card,'' the omb said in president reagan's ``management'' report on the federal government
in fact, the report itself can be purchased by mail with visa or mastercard, for $6.50. (the president's fiscal 1989 budget costs $18)
budget director james c. miller iii told a white house news briefing he did have a few qualms about use of credit cards as an alternative to legal tender _ for a goverment that was $150 billion in the red last year
but, he added, by allowing citizens to repay their government debts with credit cards, ``we're collecting some of this (debt) rather than just letting it ride.''
under the expanded program, the government is expected to process 130 million credit-card transactions annually by 1991, or $6.5 billion worth, said joseph wright, deputy omb director
it will make us the largest credit card user in the world,'' wright said
wright said, however, that the cards won't be accepted for tax payments _ at least not yet. that would require seeking legislation from congress, something the administration isn't now prepared to do
however, wright said the subject is being explored with the internal revenue service
the government for some time has accepted credit cards for specified items, including publications of the government printing office
more recently, the customs service has accepted credit cards for duty collection at most u.s. airports and the u.s. mint is now accepting them for coin sales
the management report also said that the government is studying, for possible future use, a system under which ``smart cards'' would be issued by the government to people who receive social security and other payments and benefits
these cards (would) have embedded on them information about the cardholder that can be accessed electronically. potentially (the) cards could make available funds for food stamps, social security payments, or grants and control their use electronically through central computers.''
and what's to keep the government from running up large interest payments on its past-due credit card accounts, just like it has with the national debt?
we're not going to pay (interest) because we're not going to let them go beyond 30 days,'' wright said. companies, efforts to reach macy's for comment, other detail. no pickup. a version moved on financial wires.</note>
r.h. macy &amp; co. has proposed a $6.6 billion merger with federated department stores inc., topping a rival $6.1 billion offer from toronto-based campeau corp., federated said late monday night
the $73.80-a-share offer from macy's was disclosed as federated's board considered a $68 a share negotiated offer from campeau for all of federated's 89.6 million common shares outstanding
the board took no action on the campeau bid but directed its management, and advisers to investigate macy's proposals, to negotiate a definitive agreement and submit both negotiated agreements to the board as soon as possible, the company stated
officials of federated, the nation's largest operator of department stores including such well-known retailers as bloomingdale's, filene's and bullock's, did not know when the board would get the proposals, according to spokeswoman carol sanger
macy's would make a cash tender offer for approximately 80 percent of federated's outstanding shares at $73.80 per share, federated said
the board of directors of the merged company, which would be renamed macy's-federated inc., would include significant representation from the existing federated board, federated said
federated operates more than 650 department stores, specialty stores, mass merchandising stores and supermarkets in 36 states. annual sales exceeded $11 billion in 1987
macy's, which was taken private in a $3.6 billion management leveraged buyout in 1986, operates 100 department stores and recently opened three specialty clothing stores. its annual sales were $5.21 billion in the fiscal year that ended last aug. 1
macy's offices in new york were closed when federated announced the proposal late monday, and a spokesman could not be reached for comment
federated had announced earlier that its board was considering a third-party proposal that was competitive to campeau's offer
a campeau spokeswoman declined earlier monday to comment on the last-minute bid, although campeau repeatedly has stated it wanted the opportunity to meet competing offers
soviet officials are optimistic about a strategic arms accord being reached before a summit this summer despite president reagan's remark last week that not enough time is left
the soviets hope major disagreements in the strategic arms reduction talks can be settled at a march 22-23 meeting in washington between secretary of state george p. shultz and his soviet counterpart eduard a. shevardnadze
we remain optimistic,'' said a soviet diplomat who has been involved in the negotiations in geneva on long-range weapons. he spoke only on condition of anonymity
we are near the finishing line,'' he said, and ``there is still plenty of time'' before shultz and shevardnadze meet
shultz and shevardnadze ordered their aides to draft, before that march meeting, agreements on three areas: verifying compliance, dismantling weapons, and exchanging data on the arsenals
these three drafts constitute the bulk of the work to be done'' on the treaty, although several major points of disagreement remain, the soviet official said
reagan, in an interview published last friday by the washington post, said he did not think it possible to reach an accord before the summit, which is expected in late may or early june
we're not at this moment anticipating that it would be ready for signature then,' reagan told the post. but he said the deal was possible before he leaves office next january
the proposed treaty would cut strategic nuclear arsenals by 35 percent to 50 percent, setting a limit of 6,000 on the overall number of warheads with ranges of more than 3,400 miles
the soviets are balking at a u.s. demand to limit the number of warheads on land-based missiles to 3,300 and the number of warheads aboard so-called heavy missiles to 1,650, according to u.s. officials
and the soviets want to set a limit on numbers of sea-launched cruise missiles, above the 6,000 warhead ceiling. u.s. officials have objected to such a limit, in part because it would be difficult to verify
the soviet official repeated a remark by kremlin leader mikhail s. gorbachev that technology exists to detect nuclear weapons aboard naval vessels, a statement that u.s. experts question
such things as sublimits need to be worked out at the highest political levels,'' such as the shultz-shevardnadze meeting in march, the official said
the bulk of the work, the technical details, is in the three drafts and needs to be worked out at the expert level'' before the tough political decisions, he said
the official also said the kremlin might drop its objections to tests in space of reagan's star wars missile defense system if some limits could be negotiated beforehand
he said the soviet union would countenance some space tests as long as both sides agreed they did not violate the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
the diplomat noted that reagan and gorbachev agreed at the december summit in washington to abide by the abm treaty
but the joint communique issued at summit did not address u.s.-soviet disagreement on the extent to which the treaty restricted space tests of weapons such as lasers and other devices that were not in use when the abm pact was signed
the soviets are seeking a u.s. response to their proposal to set limits on tests for various star wars components such as lasers, the official said
u.s. negotiators have rejected such limits, saying that compliance would be impossible to verify in space
here, at a glance, is the latest on aids
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that destroys the body's immune system. it is incurable and usually fatal. death comes from infections or cancers that the body cannot fight
aids is caused by the human immunodeficiency virus, or hiv, and is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, transfusion of infected blood or blood products, or from an infected birthing mother to her baby
chief victims of aids have been homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers. health officials estimate that heterosexual contact is responsible for 4 percent of cases and that between 1 million and 1.5 million americans have been exposed to the virus
screening for aids is conducted by testing blood for the presence of antibodies to the aids virus. the test tells only if a person has been exposed to the virus. a person with a positive test has a 20 percent to 30 percent chance of developing aids over a five-year period, according to the federal centers for disease control
as of feb. 22, aids had been diagnosed in 54,233 americans, of whom more than half, or 30,355, have died since june 1, 1981, according to the centers for disease control. no one is known to have recovered from aids
numerous types of medicines against the aids virus are now being studied. they are in three categories: antivirals that combat the virus; anti-infectives that treat the opportunistic infections and malignancies that occur with aids; and immune modulators that strengthen the immune system. an antiviral, azt (for azidothymidine), has received food and drug administration approval and early results show it is effective in halting progress of the aids virus. at least 16 other antivirals are in some stage of development and testing
scientists also are searching for a vaccine against the virus, but this research is in early stages
a congressional critic of federal officials' flying in style on taxpayer-supplied executive aircraft says he's unhappy with an army move to clip the wings of the corps of engineers
rep. mike synar, d-okla., expressed his displeasure monday after the army told him the corps had been been stripped of day-to-day control of three aircraft that have been called wasteful by army and congressional auditors
james ambrose, who stepped down friday as undersecretary of the army, said he ordered the executive aircraft placed in a central pool, forcing the corps brass to compete against other army commanders for their use
the pooled operation, we anticipate, will yield economies,'' ambrose told synar's government operations subcommittee on environment, energy and natural resources
lt. gen. elvin heiberg iii, the three-star chief of engineers, told the hearing that ``i concur with the decision made by my boss. ... we'll have to compete.''
last summer, the army audit agency said the corps had been using the aircraft not for emergencies such as floods but for routine and ceremonial matters, many of them overseas trips on which leaders were accompanied improperly by spouses
ambrose said that before they can use any of the aircraft, heiberg and other corps leaders will have to get flight-by-flight permission from the director of army staff in the pentagon
synar said he was displeased because the director of staff has been responsible for authorizing travel by corps spouses, who army regulations say must have an ``unquestionable official'' role in a government-financed trip
unless he does a better job than he has done with spouse travel, this isn't going to be much of a safeguard,'' synar said
heiberg and other corps officials have defended their use of the aircraft on grounds that they are more efficient than commercial flights
ambrose's action partially settled an in-army fight between the corps and the army auditors, who said last year that tax dollars could be saved by selling the planes and having corps officials use commercial or charter flights
ambrose said the army would decide later this year whether to sell the aircraft, including castle i, the 14-passenger jet that has been used to ferry key members of congress on trips to visit water projects around the nation
before the aircraft can be sold, however, congress will have to repeal a law forbidding such a sale. the prohibition was quietly enacted in december at the behest of one of those flyers, rep. tom bevill, d-ala., chairman of the house appropriations subcommittee that handles corps funding
bevill said he disagreed with the army auditors and with similar findings made over the years by the congressional general accounting office
all three planes are needed,'' bevill said. ``they do their best work when there's floods and emergencies.''
u.s. district judge emmett r. cox's handling of the 1985 vote fraud trial of three alabama civil rights activists has come under fire during a senate judiciary committee hearing on his nomination to the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals
morton stavis, president of the center for constitutional rights in new york, told the panel monday that cox displayed ``an intolerance toward and a failure to respect'' a black lawyer involved in the trial and issued rulings that raised questions about his sensitivity to racial issues
stavis' testimony marked the second time that the vote fraud trial has been used as the basis for opposing one of president reagan's judicial nominees
the trial, which civil rights groups charged was part of an effort by the reagan administration to intimidate black voters in the south, ended in innocent verdicts for all three activists
it then became the focal point of a 1986 campaign by civil rights groups against reagan's nomination of u.s. attorney jefferson b. sessions iii to a federal judgeship in south alabama
sessions, who was prosecutor at the vote fraud trial, was rejected by the judiciary committee, marking the first time that one of reagan's judicial nominees has been voted down in committee
while the sessions nomination drew opposition from a host of civil rights groups, stavis was the only witness monday who testified in opposition to cox. the committee did not vote on the nomination, but sen. howell heflin, d-ala., who presided at the hearing, predicted that cox would win senate confirmation within a month
stavis criticized cox's decision during the 1985 trial to bring criminal contempt of court charges against howard moore, a california lawyer who represented one of the activists. cox had ruled that moore's questioning of a witness violated his order barring defense attorneys from raising the issue of selective prosecution
that contempt ruling later was reversed by the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals in atlanta. stavis, who represented moore, told the judiciary committee that ``there was absolutely no foundation'' for the contempt charge
cox acknowledged monday that the appeals court had ``fairly concluded'' that he had been wrong to cite moore for contempt. ``they educated me on the law of criminal contempt,'' he said
stavis also charged that cox had shown a lack of racial sensivitity by refusing to delay the trial for two weeks so the jury could be selected from a jury pool drawn from the selma, ala., area, which had a much larger percentage of blacks than did the jury pool drawn from the mobile, ala., area
cox declined during the hearing to respond specifically to stavis' testimony about the jury selection issue. but he told reporters afterwards that racial considerations played no part in his handling of the case
the reagan administration says it won't go forward with $105 million in retaliatory sanctions against brazil at this time, citing ``some progress'' in relaxing trade barriers against u.s. computer software sales
the administration earlier this year announced that it would slap the duties on a variety of brazilian products to protest the restrictions
however, since then there has been a thaw in u.s.-brazilian relations, both on the trade and third world debt front
a new software law in brazil, which calls for a new set of regulations governing imports of foreign-made computer programs and other software, helped prompt the administration decision to delay its sanctions
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter, citing ``recent progress,'' in the dispute, said in a statement on monday: ``the united states will delay sanctions against brazil pending review of the implementing regulations for brazil's new software law
subsequent to that, we will review our options and consider what actions, if any, to take.''
the list of specific brazilian exports to be targeted had never been released, even though a preliminary list included brazilian-made shoes, aircraft, automobiles and electronics equipment
the issue of access of u.s. computer software companies to markets in brazil ``will remain a high priority for the u.s. government,'' yeutter said
recent brazilian actions, and discussions with representatives of the government of brazil, demonstrate progress on this issue,'' yeutter said. ``some of our immediate concerns have now been met.''
the new brazilian law will regulate commercial sales of all software, both domestic and foreign. it calls for new regulations to be issued by april 19
as a result, we feel it would be inappropriate and counterproductive to proceed with our previously announced plans to retaliate,'' yeutter said. ``that proposed action will be placed on hold until we have a chance to evaluate brazil's response on the software regulations.''
adding to the atmosphere of eased relations between brazil and its key trading partners has been brazil's participation in negotiations on a loan restructuring package
key portions of that pact were reached over the weekend as brazil, latin america's largest debtor nation, agreed to make a $700 million interest payment to make it current for all of 1988 and the last quarter of 1987
brazil hasn't repaid any principal on its $114 billion foreign debt since 1983. in february 1987, it decreed a moratorium on interest payments but late last year agreed to resume them
a throat operation couldn't stop katharine hepburn from making the upcoming tv film ``laura lansing slept here,'' but it wasn't an easy decision
hepburn said her problem became evident when she showed up for the first script reading last fall in vancouver, british columbia
she opened her mouth and ``no voice. total hoarse. just a rasp,'' she wrote in the march 5 issue of tv guide. ``i was thinking: do it _ don't do it. ... if i can't talk, then there is no movie _ that's a lot of people out of work.''
she identified herself as her doctor's aunt nora when she checked into vancouver general hospital, but ``everyone immediately recognized me, and they were trying not to show it.''
a day later, she found out the growth wasn't cancerous. it was ``just one of those growths that the human body throws out to torment us,'' hepburn said
