carter donned a turban and pretended to divine the contents of sealed envelopes monday as he imitated ``carnac the magnificent,'' the character created by talk-show host johnny carson
the former president was at the crested butte ski resort briefly to help raise money for handicapped skiers. he planned to be back in plains, ga., today to meet with democratic presidential hopeful richard gephardt
former secretary of defense caspar w. weinberger is joining a law firm headed by former secretary of state william p. rogers as a washington-based specialist in international law and finance
the announcement was made monday by the 275-lawyer firm of rogers &amp; wells, whose headquarters is in new york
the firm said weinberger will not engage in any work involving the federal government, defense contracts or any other matters connected with the defense department
weinberger served as secretary of health, education and welfare and as budget director during the nixon administration. he was senior vice president and general counsel of bechtel corp. from 1975 until 1980, and became secretary of defense in 1981. he resigned from president reagan's cabinet late last year
several months ago, pulitzer prize-winning playwright and actor jason miller looked at his 80-year-old father and realized theater could benefit from the energy and experience of the elderly
miller then decided to start a theater group for senior citizens in this former coal mecca
we're talking about the vitality of senior citizens, the intelligence, the talent that's lying dormant because there hasn't been an opportunity to express themselves,'' he said
rehearsals began last week for the group's first play, ``it's a sin to tell a lie,'' written by miller, who played a priest in the movie ``the exorcist.''
senior citizens' theater should be as viable and as energetic as children's theater, but nobody has senior citizens' theater,'' said miller, winner of a 1973 pulitzer prize for ``that championship season.''
the one-act play is scheduled to open april 9 at the scranton public theater and will tour nursing homes in northeastern pennsylvania, offering senior citizens free admission, miller said
a soviet film crew is making a documentary to honor the 90th birthday of industrialist armand hammer, who has been dealing with soviet leaders since lenin
the crew from gosteleradio, the soviet union's government television company, accompanied hammer to northeastern new mexico to visit the college he funded here, the armand hammer united world college of the american west
the crew spent a couple of hours filming at the college monday before heading on to new york with hammer, who is chairman of occidental petroleum corp
gosteleradio requested the one-hour film be made in honor of hammer's birthday may 21. the documentary is slated to be broadcast the night of may 21 on soviet television
hammer first went to the soviet union in the 1920s as a physician to battle a typhus epidemic. he decided the soviets needed a trade representative more than they needed his medical skills
actor eric roberts was put on probation for six months by a judge who told him to ``stay out of trouble.''
roberts, 31, was sentenced monday for a dec. 3 incident in which he went to a woman's apartment at 2:30 a.m., pounded on the door and demanded to be let in. the woman instead called police
roberts was charged with attempted assault, resisting arrest and other lesser charges after he allegedly took a swing at one of the officers. the major charges were dropped in january, and roberts agreed to plead guilty to harassment, which is punishable by up to 15 days in jail
judge bruce allen told the actor that if he stayed out of trouble during the next six months his record for the current offense will be sealed
roberts starred in the movies ``king of the gypsies,'' ``the pope of greenwich village'' and ``star 80.''
interest rates on short-term treasury securities were mixed in the latest auction with three-month bills dropping to the lowest level since november while rates on six-month bills edged up
the treasury department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills monday at an average discount rate of 5.62 percent, down from 5.64 percent last week. another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.86 percent, up from 5.83 percent last week
the rates on three-month bills were the lowest since 5.49 percent on nov. 30 while the six-month bills were the highest since they averaged 6.03 percent on feb. 16
the new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 5.78 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,857.90 and 6.12 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,703.70
in a separate report, the federal reserve said the average yield for one-year treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, dropped to 6.63 percent last week, down from 6.70 percent the previous week
the cat came to stay but the capitol mice played anyway _ around an ambassador's feet
house majority leader thomas foley, d-wash., has a mouse problem
he shares it with other members of the democratic leadership who occupy offices in the oldest part of the capitol, the part that survived after the british burned the building in 1814
the mice call it home but house leaders and their staffs call it disturbing
so traps were set and baited with cheese
the mice ignored then
then foley called in reinforcements
he brought his cat to work, a feline with a proven reputation as a champion mouser
the cat moved in with the foleys a dozen years ago while they were on vacation in the caribbean
since the cat had chosen them, and not they the cat, they gave the animal an appropriate name _ ``roger the lodger.''
roger was brought in to lodge for awhile in foley's office suite on the first floor of the capitol, sharing quarters not only with the mice but with foley's dog, alice, who accompanies the majority leader to work on a daily basis
expectations ran high for roger. but the results were poor
roger the lodger bagged no mice
the mouser's failure was underscored on monday during a meeting in an adjoining office used by rep. david bonior, d-mich., the chief deputy democratic leader
bonior was conferring over coffee with jan kinast, the polish ambassador to the united states
suddenly a mouse darted out from behind a small chest
it ran across the carpet and disappeared under the conference table, literally at the startled ambassador's feet
the house leadership is looking for a new weapon in its war against mice
the senate's sergeant at arms _ henry giugni _ became an instant celebrity last week when he followed orders and arrested sen. bob packwood, r-ore
giugni's posse had packwood carried onto the senate floor to constitute a quorum so consideration could continue of a controversial campaign financing act, then besieged by a filibuster
it was not the first time a senate sergeant of arms has been the focus of attention by the senate and the press
on feb. 7, 1935, the senate voted to fire sergeant at arms david s. barry
barry's offense: the 72-year-old former journalist had written a magazine article entitled ``over the hill to demagoguery'' which he had thought would be published after he left office
but the publication date was moved up and when the article appeared it began with these words:
contrary, perhaps, to the popular belief, there are not many crooks in congress; that is out and out grafters, or those who are willing to be such
there are not many senators or representatives who sell their votes for money, and it is pretty well known who those few are
but there are many demagogues.''
senate republican leader bob dole, who recounted the incident on the senate floor recently, said the article probably would have been ignored had it been written by a journalist
but for the senate's sergeant at arms it was an entirely different matter,'' dole said. ``so the senate voted him out of office, less than a month before his term would have ended.''
it doesn't take much time. and it doesn't cost much money. and it makes somebody somewhere happy
so congress over the decades has busily subdivided the calendar into days, weeks, months and even years in honor of some historic figure, event, cause, profession or industry or thing
it was in that spirit early last month that rep. robert w. kastenmeier, d-wis., offered a resolution designating the week of oct. 30 through nov. 5 as national jukebox week
as a rich chronicler of music, culture and technology, the jukebox is without peer,'' kastenmeier informed the house. ``it has brought great joy and memories to generations of americans. its popularity is unequaled in the eyes of young and old alike.''
besides, he said, the juke box is on the advent of its centennial
the very first juke box, a wax cylinder edison phonograph fitted with a coin slot, was installed in san francisco's palais royale saloon in 1889
just the thing, the kastenmeier resolution said, to be observed ``with appropriate programs, ceremonies and activities.''
but if juke boxes bore, perhaps doll houses are the ticket
rep. robert c. smith, r-n.h., wants to designate the week of october 9 as national dollhouse week
after all, smith contended, ``about 10 percent of our population has some involvement with dollhouse and miniature collecting.''
the source of that statistic, he disclosed, is the miniatures industry association of america
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,435.90 points, up 193.09 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on tuesday
senate majority leader robert c. byrd is hinting he may delay senate consideration of the new u.s.-soviet nuclear arms reduction treaty if the white house ends u.s. military aid to insurgents in afghanistan before a complete and final soviet troop withdrawal
byrd, d-w.va., commented shortly before the senate voted 77-0 on monday to adopt a resolution urging the white house not to cut off, suspend or reduce military aid to the afghan resistance ``until it is absolutely clear that the soviets have terminated their military occupation.''
the non-binding resolution also urged formation of an interim government in kabul acceptable to the afghan resistance
byrd said the resolution is intended to ``send a clear message'' to the administration that the senate wants no part of any u.s.-soviet agreement in which u.s. aid to the afghan resistance is ended merely on moscow's promise to withdraw its troops, not on their actual removal
byrd and sens. gordon humphrey, r-n.h., and steven symms, r-idaho, took strong exception to congressional testimony last week in which robert a. peck, an assistant deputy secretary of state, said the united states would be prepared, ``if completely satisfied with the overall agreement, to prohibit u.s. military assistance to the afghan resistance.''
peck also testified last week: ``we will continue our assistance ... until that support is no longer needed. but the question of when to cut off aid is one that should be left to the president.''
symms said peck's testimony leads many to fear a ``superpower deal ... that will allow the soviets to gain politically what they could not gain on the battlefield.''
byrd said, ``i'd like to know what's in these agreements before i call up the inf (intermediate-range nuclear forces) treaty,'' byrd said
i don't want the senate kept in the dark,'' he added
the inf treaty, which calls for the elimination of medium-range nuclear missiles from europe, is under examination by the senate foreign relations committee and two other senate panels
it could reach the senate floor for action by the end of march or early april
byrd supports senate ratification of the treaty without reservations that would force its renegotiation. he said last week that includes a reservation linking implementation of the pact to complete soviet withdrawal from afghanistan
students in most other countries are far better educated in science than are american students, according to an international study that one u.s. official said emphasizes ``the troubled state of science education in the united states.''
in a report released monday by the national science foundation, u.s. students at three different grade levels all scored well behind those from most other nations, with some american 14-year-olds scoring at the level of the ``scientifically illiterate.''
for a technologically advanced country, it would appear that (in the united states) a re-examination of how science is presented and studied is required,'' said the study, which was conducted by the international association for evaluation of educational achievement, an association of research centers
erich bloch, director of the national science foundation, said of the study: ``these findings emphasize again the troubled state of science education in the united states. ... america's future as a world technological and economic leader and the quality of life we enjoy depend on confronting the real problems in science education with vigor, determination and a sense of urgency.''
the study was conducted by the international association for evaluation of educational achievement, an association of research centers. early findings, which compared the united states only with japan and england, and with partial findings from israel and sweden, were reported by the associated press in september
the comparative study was based on tests administered to 204,308 students at 7,581 schools in 24 countries between 1983 and 1986. the tests were given at three academic levels: near the end of primary grades, at about age 10; at grades eight and nine, about age 14; and in the final year of high school
among 10-year-olds, students in japan, korea and finland scored around 15.4 out of 24 possible correct answers. u.s. students scored just below the middle of the scale at 13.2
among 14-year-olds, hungary, japan and the netherlands scored at the top, while americans ranked third from last with a mean score of 16.5 out of 30 possible correct answers. the lowest-scoring quarter of this age group, the report said, ``were scientifically illiterate'' with their test scores ``at chance level.''
tests for the high school seniors were given only to those specializing in science subjects. hong kong, england and singapore scored highest, with the united states students receiving among the lowest marks
in an analysis of the u.s. results, the report said: ``the achievement of advanced science students in biology, chemistry and physics is low. the biology results are especially low.''
the study said that the united states, along with australia, canada, finland, italy and sweden, has ``many poor scoring schools and it would seem likely that the school authorities would have grounds for concern.''
secretary of education william j. bennett, responding to a report of the study, said it supports an assessment on u.s. education that his department released last week
now comes this international report card showing that compared to students in other countries, american elementary and high school students are not just in a `dead stall,' they're doing even worse,'' bennett said. ``they're in reverse and going downhill.''
the international study also compared the difference in science achievement based on gender. in grades five and nine, boys scored higher than girls in all countries. for grade 12, boys outperformed girls in biology, chemistry and physics, except in australia, hong kong and sweden, where girls had top marks in biology
owens-illinois inc. has acquired virtually all outstanding shares of brockway inc. stock to the tune of about $740 million and is on the verge of creating the nation's largest glass container company, offcials say
monday's move followed a decision by the government against appealing a court decision in favor of the merger
owens-illinois spokesman sam allen said the company bought 12,337,630 shares of common brockway stock, 98.7 percent of the outstanding shares. allen said the actual merger will likely occur in a couple of weeks, at which time the remaining shares will be purchased
robert lanigan, chairman of owens-illinois, said the merger will make the combined operations and the glass container industry ``significantly more competitive with can, plastic and other materials in the worldwide packaging business.''
susan ticknor, spokeswoman for the federal trade commission, declined to specify why the agency decided against appealing a decision by the u.s. court of appeals that, in effect, paving the way for the merger
however, ms. ticknor said the ftc has scheduled administrative hearings on potential anticompetitive effects of the merger. and she said owens-illinois could be ordered to divest itself of brockway holdings if the agency determines that the merger violates antitrust laws
the toledo, ohio, based owens-illinois proposed to buy brockway, of jacksonville, fla., last september for $60 a share
the merger will make the combined company the nation's largest manufacturer of glass containers, which are used in packaging foods and beverages. the largest producer of glass containers has been anchor glass container corp., according to the ftc
owens-illinois officials have said the only weapon the glass container industry has against plastics and metal packaging producers is competitive pricing and the merger with brockway is designed to increase productivity and lower costs
the ftc had attempted in court to block the merger, saying it might violate antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition and creating the conditions for price discrimination
however, last month u.s. district court judge joyce hens green denied the ftc's request for a preliminary injunction on the basis that the agency had failed to prove the deal would harm competition
and last friday, the appeals court sided with judge green, saying that the agency had failed to make its case
jesse jackson's surprise second-place finish in the maine democraatic caucuses was a ``breakthrough,'' proving conclusively that he has broadened his appeal, his backers say
jackson reaped 28 percent of the vote in the maine contest on sunday, on the heels of respectable showings in three other states which, like maine, all have voting age black populations of 1 percent or less
the maine results came after he spent just $13,000 in the state and campaigned there only two days. the well-funded winner, michael dukakis, is well known to maine voters as governor of nearby massachusetts, and he captured 42 percent
it shows that we can get votes in any part of the country,'' jackson said monday in pembroke, n.c. ``it shows we have the broadest base...and our campaign has the strongest appeal.''
the rainbow coalition is coming alive,'' he added, invoking the name he has given to his target constituency of all minority groups and the economically oppressed
political consultant ann lewis, an informal jackson adviser, called maine ``the most significant breakthrough state for him so far.''
bob beckel, a top political strategist for walter mondale's 1984 presidential bid, said jackson's performance is``a sign of a growing movement among non-black supporters of jackson, and for people to try to ignore it, they're making a great mistake.''
in iowa and new hampshire, jackson finished fourth out of seven contenders. in minnesota he was second with 20 percent in last week's caucuses
in maine, jackson's 28 percent contrasted to the 1 percent that he got when he ran in 1984
campaign manager gerald austin said he knew his candidate would do well in maine and the goal was to come in second. but jackson's margin, well above the single-digit results of the other democrats, was better than he had anticipated
he credited it to organizing by students and dedicated volunteers _ the campaign had only two paid staff people in maine
it was basically, totally indigenous and independent,'' he said of the maine organization. ``they did things on their own.''
jackson's core support came out of the university communities in orono and portland, and striking paper workers in jay, he said
he carried portland and another of the state's largest cities, bangor
jackson bought $10,000 worth of tv ads in the days before the caucuses, and $2,000 on radio. the 10-second tv spots showed the winning u.s. goal in the 1980 olypic hockey game against the soviets, with an announcer saying as jackson's picture appeared: ``just like in the olympics, one man can make a difference.''
beckel, who called jackson ``one of the best hidden political stories of the year,'' commented also, ``people don't want to buy the notion that jesse jackson has got a message that people listen to and that has begun to rise above his blackness ... somebody in this party has to to recognize that this is a significant guy in the party.''
political analyst william schneider, however, questioned whether jackson's white votes are really the downtrodden whom he has targeted. he cited exit polls from iowa and new hampshire showing a good portion of his votes came from upscale, well-educated liberals, ``the radical chic.''
but he also noted that jackson has a strong message that appeals to many democrats
there is no other candidate in the race who really stands for the old politics ... what i would call democratic fundamentalism,'' as espoused by the late sen. hubert humphrey, sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., and new york gov. mario cuomo, said schneider
beckel said people ``consistently underestimate'' jackson
he's the most charismatic candidate in the field. he's got a message that's concise, that does not change from place to place.''
maine democratic chairman rick barton said timing was a key for jackson
jackson's successful appearance at the university of maine in orono on feb. 11, just after iowa's caucuses and just before the new hampshire primary, was ``just the right time ... when maine democrats were starting to lock in,'' he said
barton said jackson probably also picked up about 5 percentage points from people who defected from the flagging campaigns of paul simon and hart
public television stations are offering gavel-to-gavel coverage of gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial, and several radio stations are covering portions of the proceedings
public stations kuat-tv in tucson and kaet-tv in phoenix started providing full live coverage when the trial began monday
kfyi, a phoenix news and talk radio station, put together a telephone network to feed continuous live coverage to stations in tucson, flagstaff, yuma, bullhead city, lake havasu city, sierra vista, prescott valley, window rock and payson. some of the stations were carrying only part of the proceedings, however
none of arizona's commercial television stations carried gavel-to-gavel coverage, but many chipped in to set up pool coverage with the public stations, in which all participants are entitled to broadcast parts of the live proceedings or use excerpts on later news programs
the pool costs could exceed $100,000, said jim willi of kpnx-tv in phoenix
president reagan has issued an early st. patrick's day message, saying he wanted to acknowledge ``the world of debt we owe to the irish people.''
although his message came two and a half weeks ahead of time, reagan on monday took note of the march 17 commemoration, saying the irish people ``have created and perpetuated a unique heritage of faith and freedom, of humor and hope, of scholarship and sanctity and sacrifice.''
reagan, who is of irish ancestry, went on to say:
with faith and fearlessness, st. patrick brought christianity to ireland a millennium and a half ago. the annals reveals the irish people's eagerness to embrace the faith and to keep it; that trait remains to this day, a tribute to the apostle of ireland and to his flock in every generation
may america and ireland always cherish each other and the kinship in which we hold st. patrick's day.'' impeachment-watching</head>
it's a far cry from the capitol, but it's got most of the comforts of home
impeached gov. evan mecham still goes to work early and stays late. but his office-in-exile is in a house he once lived in, across an alley from a hay barn in the far reaches of this phoenix suburb
his days are filled with meetings and phone calls, he says, leaving not much time to follow his televised impeachment trial, which opened monday in the state senate
no, i didn't watch,'' mecham said. ``i've been busy. i've got a lot to do.''
mecham met with supporters and attended a meeting downtown. he took time to hold a news conference in what used to be a sunken living room. but he didn't hang on every vote in the senate, which on monday decided the house's impeachment document was sufficient for trial
frankly, i haven't tracked the vote and i haven't tried to interpret anything,'' he said
his paid staff of five worked on one side of the 7,000-square-foot ranch-style house while volunteers worked on the other side to raise money for the governor's legal defense and recall election campaign
plans were being readied for a wednesday night rally. some 300 phone calls come in each day, spokesman tanner brown said
the house was converted into office space before mecham was impeached feb. 5 and replaced by acting gov. rose mofford, the former secretary of state
outside, a simple sign identifies the ``governor evan mecham headquarters,'' and adds, ``office space available. inquire within.'' the building sits between a farm full of sheep, chickens and roosters, and a mormon church
police sometimes guard the front door, and a security system is in place. monday's proceedings made the switchboard light up, a receptionist said, including a series of obscene phone calls
mecham said he won't venture downtown to the senate unless it's necessary
when my attorney tells me i should be there, i'll be there,'' he said
he said he was disappointed the senate chose not to grant requests for a delay in the trial since his new chief counsel has been on the case less than a week, but was confident in his defense
we have no choice. we have a time to get ready by,'' he said
i feel confident we'll be able to get our case out and i think we'll be successful,'' the governor said. ``if the decision is made on the evidence, i expect to get 29 votes.''
one member of the 30-member chamber is absent from the trial because of illness. a two-thirds vote is needed to convict mecham
mecham was impeached on allegations of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state official
he also has been indicted in state district court on six felony counts involving the $350,000 loan, which amounted to about a third of his campaign funds, and faces a criminal trial march 22. mecham also faces a recall election may 17
prime minister margaret thatcher has turned distinctly chilly toward mikhail s. gorbachev ahead of this week's nato summit here, apparently worried the soviet leader may be wooing the west too well
the russian bear was easier to deal with when it looked more like a bear than it does now,'' aides quoted mrs. thatcher as telling a private meeting of nato ambassadors on feb. 17
the nicer the russians get, the more dangerous they are.''
her remarks underlined the dilemma of the right-wing british leader who has developed a warm personal relationship with gorbachev
she now appears in a bind over how to keep encouraging gorbachev's internal reforms without also encouraging sentiment for a further erosion in nuclear weapons and military spending in western europe on grounds the soviet union is no longer much of a threat
thatcher aides deny she has done a u-turn on the soviet leader she once hailed as someone ``i can do business with,'' and who gave her a red carpet welcome on an official visit in moscow last spring
but british officials acknowledge alarm over gorbachev's relatively benign image in the west
lord carrington, nato secretary-general, indicated that gorbachev may succeed in dividing the 16-nation north atlantic treaty organization by generating complacency
it is rather a curious paradox that it's much easier to hold the alliance together when they're frightened than when they're not,'' carrington said in a recent british broadcasting corp. radio interview
but the fact still remains that there is an enormous military potential on the other side of the eastern border.''
polls indicate a more relaxed attitude among west europeans to the neighboring communist giant under the urbane gorbachev
a survey by datagroep of the netherlands among 6,064 people in nine west european countries last spring indicated that nearly two-thirds thought that public views of the soviet union had recently grown warmer
mrs. thatcher, who has been among gorbachev's most outspoken admirers in the west, appears to have helped the shift in public opinion
after her moscow visit last spring a gallup sounding reported that 58 percent of britons thought the soviet union ``really wanted to be friendly with the west.'' just 33 percent thought soviet advances should be treated ``with the greatest suspicion.''
britain's economist weekly commented: ``could that in part be a result of the flattering attentions the prime minister has been happy to receive from mr. gorbachev?''
the debate-a-day democratic presidential field was scattered across the super tuesday landscape today after a forum in which rep. richard gephardt was singled out for attacks on his trade policy, tax vote and the contributions he has taken from special interests
in one of the liveliest debates of the campaign, the democrats spelled out differences on trade, taxes and foreign debt with bare-knuckled zest, sparing not even the moderator who was chided by jesse jackson for asking ``a race-based question.''
after the third democratic debate in as many days, the contenders were campaigning in states that will hold primaries or caucuses on march 8, the most delegate-rich day in the history of presidential politics
shortly after monday's debate ended, gephardt flew south to meet with former president jimmy carter in georgia and receive the endorsement of two former governors of south carolina
sen. albert gore jr. was campaigning in virginia and kentucky; jackson in maryland and north carolina; gov. michael dukakis in maryland, former colorado sen. gary hart in north carolina; and illinois sen. paul simon in the state of washington
gephardt took heat for his acceptance of campaign contributions from political action committees, for his vote for president reagan's 1981 tax cut and for his trade policy
when dukakis criticized gephardt for taking pac contributions, the missouri congressman retorted that to suggest that members of congress would ``take direction on how to vote is an affront.''
then gephardt said he was certain the massachusetts governor accepted contributions from people who did business with his state, which prompted dukakis to reply, ``i am not running around the country beating up on the establishment.''
gephardt said he often got contributions from people even though they opposed his position on individual issues
jackson interjected that ``lobbyists would lose their jobs if they gave money continuously against the interests of who they were working for.''
do you think the reagan-gephardt tax bill of 1981 was fair?'' asked gore
the senator from tennessee kept repeating the question and gephardt kept saying, ``are you finished?''
finally, gephardt said he thought the bill was fair because it cut taxes for middle-income families
when gore asked his question once again, gephardt snapped, ``can you hear, al?''
during an exchange on how to deal with mexico's foreign debt, dukakis said the oil import fee supported by gephardt would ruin the mexican economy
are you running for president of mexico or america?'' asked the congressman
if i'm president of the united states, i'm going to pay attention to that country,'' responded dukakis
twice, hart interjected, ``let the record show, gov. dukakis didn't answer the question.''
simon passed up the debate, which was held on the campus of the college of william and mary and was sponsored by the democratic leadership council, an organization of democratic officials who banded together out of concern over what they saw as the party's leftward drift and the failure of its presidential candidates to appeal to voters in the south and west
one of the most dramatic exchanges took place when moderator judy woodruff, chief washington correspondent of the public broadcasting service macneil-lehrer news hour, asked gore why he hadn't been ``nearly as vocal talking about the differences between yourself and rev. jackson. would that be because you don't want to offend his black supporters?''
gore replied that ``the reason is he doesn't have a record to talk about in public life.''
gore went on to say he had disagreed with jackson on issues such as defense spending
jackson was bristling and he turned to woodruff and said: ``that is a race-based question. ..
i am a bona fide democrat. i have registered more democratic voters than anyone on this stage. i am the reason why some democrats are on this stage, because of that work. ... my race is self-evident and my leadership is obvious.''
the stock market has jumped to its highest level since the october market meltdown
analysts said there was no major economic news to account for the burst of stock-buying on monday that sent the widely watched dow jones industrial average up by 48.41 points to 2,071.62. but they said the market continued to be buoyed by the brisk pace of takeover bids in recent weeks
on the new york stock exchange, seven stocks rose for every two that fell. investors traded 236.05 million shares on the nyse
the previous highest closing since the oct. 19 crash was 2,051.89 on jan. 7. the dow industrials finished february some 333 points above the close on black monday, when the dow plunged a record 508 points
twenty-one people died of food poisoning in the the central java district of banyumas after eating fermented soybean cake, a health ministry official said today
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 40 others remained hospitalized in serious condition
the officials said the dead and hospitalized were among 260 people in the village of dermaji, 300 miles southeast of jakarta, who required medical treatment over the past two weeks after consuming the cake
china today declined comment on vietnamese charges that chinese troops had landed on two tiny contested islands in the south china sea
vietnam's communist party daily, nhan dan, said friday that chinese troops had landed on two coral reefs in the spratly chain that are claimed by vietnam and china as well as malaysia, the philippines and taiwan
vietnam calls the islands truong sa, and china refers to them as the nansha archipelago
china's foreign ministry, asked to comment on vietnam's allegations, said a statement it made on feb. 22 ``has already made clear our consistent position.'' that statement said earlier vietnamese claims that four chinese warships had ``provoked and obstructed'' operations of its cargo vessels on jan. 31 off the spratly group were ``brazen charges.''
the two nations, which have occasional armed clashes along their tense border, also both claim the paracel island group to the north of the spratlys. large oil deposits are said to be located in the vicinity
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev will pay an official visit to yugoslavia this month, according to the official tass news agency
tass, in its announcement monday, gave no details of the communist party chief's schedule, and said only that the visit would take place in ``mid-march.''
leonid brezhnev was the last kremlin leader to go to the non-aligned communist nation. he attended the 1980 funeral of the late yugoslav leader, josip broz tito
the defense ministry claimed 229 contra rebels and 90 soldiers loyal to the leftist sandinista government were killed in 4,801 combat engagements in february
a statement issued monday night said 39 civilians also were killed, 55 injured and 115 kidnapped during the period
the statement said u.s. air force planes violated nicaraguan airspace 13 times. it said other planes, mostly leaving honduras to resupply the contra rebels, were detected 35 times in february
the contra rebels, trained and supplied by the united states, have been fighting to oust the sandinistas since november 1981. deletes extraneous words in 4th graf, ``john a. ...'', corrects agency title in 9th graf, ``despite the...,'' and corrects 12th graf, ``the old..., to show that 9 percent is component of 14 percent figure.</note>
the environmental protection agency says it will continue to focus on asbestos hazards in schools even though an agency study estimates that the problem exists in other buildings to which the public has access
the agency on monday sent to congress a report calling for stepped-up research, training and enforcement on the problems of asbestos in non-school buildings, but no new regulatory requirements
the successful implementation of the school program should remain our first concern, and we all have much to learn from it,'' wrote epa administrator lee m. thomas in his cover letter to congress. ``i fear a major initiative in other buildings could do more harm that good.''
john a. moore, assistant administrator for pesticides and toxic substances, said at a news conference that the agency is hampered by limited resources
the report dealt with so-called ``friable'' asbestos, which will crumble under slight pressure and throw fibers into the air. the fibers can cause lung cancer, cancer of the lining of the chest or abdominal cavity and asbestosis
asbestos-containing material that is damaged, such as insulated pipe wrappings and tiles, can release the fibers
the service employees international union said epa should be writing regulations or seeking legislation to give those workers the right to know what they're dealing with. the union has 150,000 of its 850,000 members in building service jobs
the agency's report contained new information about a still-unreleased survey of 43 federal buildings containing friable asbestos
despite the condition of the asbestos, the average concentration in the air of the buildings was 560 fibers per cubic yard, about 0.4 percent of the workplace concentration permitted by the occupational safety and health administration
that concentration is about 10 times the typical outdoor background level, and epa said such a difference from background could be the result of chance alone _ that the buildings might not be significantly contaminated at all
the report also contained old and new information from a 1984 epa survey of 231 buildings, a survey designed to be representative of some 3.6 million buildings to which the public has access. elementary and secondary schools, state and local government buildings and apartments with fewer than 10 units were excluded
the old information, reported in 1985, was that an estimated 20 percent of buildings contained friable asbestos. the new information further broke down that estimate to show that 14 percent of the buildings contain damaged friable asbestos. that category was further broken down to show that 9 percent of the buildings had seriously damaged asbestos
epa said too few buildings were sampled for the figures to be precise
epa said the 20 percent likely could be anywhere from 14 percent to 27 percent; the 14 percent could be anywhere from 6 percent to 22 percent; and the 9 percent could be zero to 19 percent
rep. james florio, d-n.j., whose pressure has helped win passage of existing asbestos-in-schools programs, said in a statement, ``everything in this report points toward aggressive federal intervention except epa's recommendations, which amount to nothing more than sweeping this alarming problem under the rug.''
the agency has said about 35,000 school buildings, roughly 35 percent of the total, contained friable asbestos in 1984. under new epa regulations required by congress school districts must develop asbestos management plans, with the advice of certified experts, by october 1988 and start carrying them out in july 1989
epa said the school program will cost $3 billion, and a comparable program for buildings to which the public has access would cost $51 billion
a bomb apparently detonated by remote control exploded today near a bus carrying military personnel, damaging the bus and nearby homes but causing no injuries, police said
the blast occurred at 6:10 a.m. in benoni, about 20 miles east of johannesburg. it sent shrapnel against the bus, collapsed the ceilings of two nearby homes and shattered the windows of other houses, police said
an air force spokesman, commandant koos smit, said the bus was en route to pretoria, with 18 army, air force and medical personnel on board
there was no claim of responsibility, and police made no accusations
authorities have blamed the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement for many previous bomb attacks, including a remote-control blast that killed four policemen in johannesburg last year
by law and custom, white-led south africa's apartheid policy establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the penalties for violating government safety laws has not kept up with inflation and has pulled the enforcement teeth from many of the laws by reducing the impact of fines, according to a coalition of consumer groups
penalties for violating various health and safety laws have remained essentially unchanged over the years, while inflation has reduced the value of the amounts involved, the consumer federation of america and the u.s. public interest research group said monday in a report
letting civil penalties be eroded by inflation operates as if there were a built-in depreciation schedule in our key health and safety statutes,'' said michael waldman of the group public citizen's congress watch, in a statement released with the study
as one example the study cited the occupational safety and health act of 1970 retains its original penalties of $1,000 per violation and $10,000 for failure to provide a safe workplace. to keep place with inflation these would have to increase to $2,970 and $29,700, the report said
president reagan says he hopes the summer olympics in seoul, south korea, will be incident-free and that he has confidence in newly inaugurated president roh tae woo
in responses to questions submitted by the south korean newspaper, dong-a ilbo, reagan said a smoothly run olympics competition in september ``is in everyone's interests.''
the prospect of north korea, or anyone else's, attempts to disrupt the games through violence is a danger that we and the soviets can agree to work against.''
we hope that moscow will use its close relations with pyongyang to urge moderation and to encourage the resumption of direct north-south contacts on practical ways to reduce tension,'' the president said. ``it is time for the north to eschew violence and get down to the serious business of resuming dialogue with seoul.''
people in other countries are becoming less willing to lend money to the united states, according to the head of the international monetary fund
i have looked at a very long historical set of figures,'' said michel camdessus, the fund's managing director. ``and i have to tell you that there are no precedents. each time similar imbalances have been... reduced, it was through recession ..
our latest projections suggest that, on present policies and exchange rates, the imbalances would still continue to be very large over the medium term,'' he said monday to a conference sponsored by the overseas development council, a private study group concerned with problems of the third world
for some time, the growth of u.s. debt has not been matched by the willingness of business people in other countries to lend more, he said
the congressional joint economic committee has predicted that u.s. debt would reach about $400 billion at the end of last year. it is growing at about $150 billion annually
