pentagon scientists say they are more confident that they can defeat attempts to fool a missile defense by using decoy warheads following a recent star wars space experiment
lt. gen. james a. abrahamson, the air force general in charge of the strategic defense initiative organization, said monday the so-called delta 181 space experiment conducted three weeks ago had provided a ``tremendous amount of data'' that already was expanding scientific understanding of how objects look as they travel through space
that, in turn, will be crucial to devising infrared, radar, laser radar and other types of sensors that can tell the difference between a real nuclear warhead and a fake one traveling through space, abrahamson said at a pentagon briefing
while months if not years of research are still ahead, ``i think all of our evidence, so far ... is that, yes, we should be able to find effective ways to discriminate'' between decoy and real warheads, he said
the three-star general also acknowledged, however, that budget cuts imposed by congress this year have slowed the star wars program by at least a year and possibly more. the reagan administration had wanted to spend $5.2 billion on research this year, but received $3.5 billion. interviewed declined to give their full names. pickup 9th graf pvs, ``but the...'' ^an ap extra</note>
three months of violence in the occupied west bank and gaza strip have led to a fundamental change in the attitude of palestinians, particularly the young
the new aggressiveness and self-confidence spawned by the uprising could bode ill for israel's future
after two decades of israeli rule viewed by most arabs as harsh, unjust and capricious, residents in the territories have discovered they can to some extent move events. their outrage, their stones and bottles, have drawn an international response
it is a result of 20 years of humiliating measures,'' said sumeye naser, a biology professor at bir zeit university in the west bank. ``now, they all feel they have nothing to lose.''
the effect is most evident among those born after the 1967 war, when israel seized the west bank and gaza. those young people have never known anything but israeli occupation. at the barricades of stone and burning tires throughout the occupied lands the spearhead is the teen-ager
youths throw stones and taunt the soldiers, daring them to retaliate. other boys so young they can't possibly understand the political implications of what they are doing boldy confront tear gas and guns, stone cars, wave v-signs and outlawed palestinian flags
in the west bank, in the village of bir zeit west of ramallah, a teen-ager named ahmed loitered near the post office with a group of friends, waiting for something to happen
i hope they come,'' he said of the israeli army. ``i would like to fight them. i'd be happy to sacrifice my life.'' he and other palestinians interviewed declined to give their full names, saying they feared arrest for rioting or israeli reprisals against their families
but the movement is not exclusively young. talks with scores of palestinians in the territories reveal an almost universal willingness to push the confrontation to the limit
we have to depend on ourselves to liberate our own land,'' said khaled, an elderly man hobbling on his cane at the rear of a demonstration in the village of kfar naami. ``we have reached this conclusion, and i am ready to give my life.''
the killings, the beatings, the tear gas attacks, the broken bones inflicted by the israelis in an effort to stifle the uprising have had the opposite effect, instilling a sense of defiance among palestinians, and in some, a desire for revenge
also evident is a new feeling of self-esteem among a people treated as second-class citizens for so long that they came to believe they were second class. by going to the barricades, by participating in the general strike, by demonstrating, they are asserting a newfound aggressiveness. and they are seeing results
secretary of state george p. shultz's peace mission to the middle east was sparked by the violence. with elections planned in the united states and israel this year, it is unlikely any peacemaking efforts would have been undertaken without the direct pressure of the mounting death toll and israeli crackdown
they have recognized something about themselves,'' said ron verber, education director of the golda meir association, a group that promotes arab-jewish coexistence
they look at themselves differently now,'' verber said. ``they see independence from israel as something solid. they feel they can do something about it
a year ago, this feeling didn't exist. from that point of view, it is the point of no return. we will not be able to put things back they way they were before. they have made a statement.''
for years, inhabitants of the territories have looked for leadership to the palestine liberation organization, which sought to control the struggle from the outside, limiting the locals to a secondary role
the locals saw the situation as out of their hands, beyond their control. the plo remains a potent force in the occupied lands. but the uprising has taught local palestinians that they themselves can strike directly at the israelis. they are no longer awed by the israeli military might that for so long cowed them into submission
the uprising has given us a sense of pride and a lack of fear,'' said hammad, another west bank villager. ``we think we can control our future.''
for years, the israelis kept palestinians under control with a minimal force _ less than 1,000 soldiers in the west bank, for example. now, although authorities refuse to reveal numbers, it is said there are almost as many soldiers in the west bank as were needed to seize it in 1967
when the demonstrations began, they were mostly in the large towns and cities and in the refugee camps. now, they have spread to the smallest villages
nobody knows what the aftermath is going to be,'' said munir naser, a professor at bir zeit university. ``there are darker aspects. the people who have been beaten or buried, people who have had their hands broken, will have psychological problems
i think they are going to wait for the first opportunity to take revenge.''
late-afternoon dollar purchases by speculators pushed the u.s. currency higher in uninspired tokyo trading today, while stock prices rose in unusually heavy trading on the tokyo stock exchange, dealers said
the dollar opened at 128.45 yen, up 0.33 yen from monday's close, following gains on overseas markets. it then edged up in afternoon trading to close the day at 128.63 yen, up 0.51 yen. spot volume totaled a moderate $4.7 billion
despite the large day-to-day rise in the dollar's value, traders said there was little news that was influencing trading in the u.s. currency
the actual range in trading during the day wasn't very great, only about 0.2 yen,'' said a trader at a tokyo commercial bank who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``most of the increase was due to speculators trying to cover dollar-short positions in the late afternoon.''
the 225-share nikkei stock average, which ended 13 consecutive days of gains with a decline of 42.06 points monday, rose 193.09 points, or 0.8 percent, to finish the day at 25,435.90
stocks in many sectors rose, with trading in the market's first section an exceptionally heavy 1.6 billion shares, the highest so far this year
the second-section index also rose, gaining 1.56 points to hit an all-time high of 2,927.31
dealers said stocks were spurred upward by a surge on wall street on monday that pushed the dow jones industrial average up 48.41 points to 2,071.61, its highest level since last year's market crash
but they said the market received additional impetus from bullishness resulting from favorable japanese economic trends
lately, the tokyo market has been acting more independently of wall street,'' said michio katsumata of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage. ``stocks in tokyo are being buoyed by predictions of higher japanese corporate profits in march. also, the large amount of capital in circulation is boosting the market, resulting in an excess of buy orders over sell orders.''
the announcement today that japan's unemployment rate in january rose 0.1 percent from december had little impact on the market, traders said. january's 2.7 percent rate was down from 3.0 percent for the same month last year
the winter olympics on television and a drop in the number of new movies contributed to a sluggish weekend at the box office. ``good morning, vietnam'' was the no. 1 film for the seventh week
the openings weren't strong and the olympics did very well in the ratings, particularly on sunday. the box office was hurt on sunday,'' said john krier of exhibitor relations co., which compiles the weekly turnstile figures
good morning, vietnam,'' which got robin williams an oscar nomination for his portrayal of a raucous saigon disc jockey, earned $5.2 million for a nine-week total of $78.5 million. in second place was roman polanski's ``frantic'' with $4.35 million in ticket sales
