a rapidly growing number of u.s. college students are studying abroad, especially in great britain, according to a new study
in 1985-86, 48,483 students took courses for academic credit in foreign schools, according to latest figures released monday by the institute for international education, the nation's largest higher education exchange agency
in 1982-83, the most recent previous study, 27,145 u.s. students studied abroad, said edrice howard, iie's senior publications editor
the survey was conducted by mail last year to 2,896 accredited u.s. colleges and universities, of which 1,898 reported students earning academic credit for study abroad
the study did not explain the rise in popularity of foreign study. but administrators on u.s. college campuses said that at least som students may be finding that study overseas is economical compared with the more expensive u.s. schools where tuitions have been soaring throughout the 1980s
at beaver college in glenside, pa., a school noted for study-abroad programs that students from some 225 u.s. colleges participate in, president bette landman said she believed the increase stemmed from ``an increasing sensitivity among students to foreign study, not only to help their careers, but especially in the last year or two, to the kinds of understandings we as world citizens must bring to our lives.''
the school is sending over 1,700 students from u.s. campuses to study in the british isles and vienna this year, landman said, compared with about 750 students in 1980-81
at northern illinois university, where the numbers of students in overseas programs have risen at least 10 percent in that period, orville jones, assistant dean of international programs said that as more students have traveled during their high school years, the thought of studying overseas is no longer as strange or frightening
the survey found that 76.8 percent of u.s. students abroad were studying in western european countries
the most popular single country, great britain, attracted 29.3 percent of all students studying abroad, followed by france with 13.7 percent, spain with 8.8 percent, italy 7.8 percent, and west germany 6.1 percent
latin america attracted 7 percent, with smaller percentages studying in asia, the middle east, eastern europe and africa
nearly 90 percent of the students were in programs sponsored by u.s. colleges and universities, the survey found. the most popular field of study was liberal arts, with 18.2 percent, followed by foreign language with 16.7 percent
almost two-thirds, or 63.8 percent, of u.s. students abroad were female, according to the report
park west high school, where book bags have been known to contain machetes and switchblades, is the kind of school that prompted the city's new chancellor to declare that public education is on trial here
richard green, the former minneapolis school superintendent who begins work today as head of the nation's largest school system, soon will have an invitation to see park west for himself
senior class officers want him to speak at graduation, and their letter asks, ``why would a chancellor want to link himself to the so-called `worst school in manhattan'?''
their answer: ``to send a signal to the media and to the public that park west is a school worthy of respect.''
the 10-year-old, fortress-like concrete structure in the section once known as hell's kitchen lost most claims to respectability five weeks ago, when a state education department team suspended a routine inspection
the reviewers said administrators were unable to provide them with basic records for test scores, attendance and promotions. they also cited ``chaotic'' conditions, including the stabbing of a student just outside the building _ the second in as many days
the school was overrun by groups of students, split along racial lines, at battle with each other,'' said charles carpenter, a department spokesman. in a gym class, students ``were just running around with no easily identifiable teacher or sign of organized activity.''
under a new, interim principal, conditions have improved. security has been tightened, enrollment limited, tutoring increased and student activities added
twelve teachers patrol the school's hallways at a time, and students must display their schedule card at the door before they are allowed to leave early. visitors must provide identification, sign in and sign out
even so, almost a third of the 2,500 students are absent each day, and half of those who do come are late. more than half fail at least one subject. so many drop out that seniors account for only 7 percent of the enrollment
some students stay home out of fear of gangs outside the school, and dozens more have transferred, including the nephew of the parents' association vice president
he was failing two classes because he was leaving early to avoid the scene at the end of the school day,'' said barbara lowe-tabman. ``kids say they will not wear nice clothes to school because they'll be stolen.''
some teachers told a reporter for the new york times they believed a majority of students carry weapons. a veteran guidance counselor said some parents encourage children to carry them for protection
although the vast majority of teachers and administrators are white, principal eileen petruzillo says she knows of only one white student. relations have been tense between some groups of black, puerto rican, dominican and haitian students
the school's problems began to surface in december, when a group of hispanic bilingual education students staged a sit-in to protest attacks
asked at that time about violence, principal edward morris said, ``kids have been bringing weapons to school for years. it's almost a habit.'' a month later, after a study by a board of education team, the 66-year-old morris requested reassignment
some students feel park west is not that bad. eric vasquez, a college-bound senior, said the high schools his brothers attended make park west sound tame. ``it's a city high school,'' he shrugged
park west's problems are not unique in a system of 936,000 students, between a third and half of whom drop out before graduation. in the 1986-87 school year, more than 9,700 violent incidents were reported, about 3,500 of them ``serious,'' such as assaults and robberies
the state plans to resume its review of park west. if conditions have not improved, carpenter said, administrators will be told that ``if they don't clean up their act, the school will be closed down.''
after being named chancellor in january, green said he rejected the idea that new york's schools are ``failed institutions,'' but said ``public education is on trial'' here
he faces a system full of emerging or potential park wests. but solutions, says petruzillo, cannot be uniformly imposed from board of education headquarters ``because each school is different. you can't replicate a success in one school at another.''
at least, she said, ``dr. green is coming to a city that is ready for change. he's going to have a very interesting time.''
members of dartmouth college's afro-american society planned more protests this week after a black professor came under renewed attack from a conservative student newspaper
the dispute between the dartmouth review and music professor william cole threatened to reignite tensions that shattered the ivy league campus after a january 1986 sledgehammer attack by review members on anti-apartheid shanties on the college green
the independent weekly's editor, christopher baldwin, who also was involved in the shanty attack, faces college disciplinary charges with three other review members stemming from a confrontation with cole last week after the paper printed a cover story questioning his competence
cole had sued the newspaper for libel for a january 1983 article that said he ``looks like a used brillo pad'' and called his music course ``the most outrageous'' on campus. cole dropped the suit in 1985 and received no damages. he and the newspaper each claimed vindication
a member of the afro-american society, sophomore kimberly robinson, said monday the newspaper's new attacks were ``obviously racially motivated.''
about 250 students held a rally monday in front of the college administration building, and robinson said the afro-american society planned to start a boycott today of hanover businesses that advertise in the review
the group also planned a march down dartmouth's ``fraternity row'' wednesday night and a rally with students from other area colleges thursday
robinson said members of afro-american society also met twice monday with dartmouth president james freedman to detail allegations of other recent racial incidents on campus
in its cover story two weeks ago, the review revived charges that cole is incompetent and printed excerpts from a transcript of one of his classes that week
the story also leveled criticisms at an english professor who is white. baldwin said both stories originated from complaints to the newspaper by students in the classes
baldwin denied the article was racially motivated and said the review is the victim of a ``witch hunt'' as it tries to root out incompetence at dartmouth
he said he and two review colleagues, with a fourth as an observer, approached cole after his class thursday to advise him that he could publish an unedited response in the newspaper, but also to seek his explanation for remarks about the review he allegedly made during a class
baldwin said an ``altercation'' ensued. the next day, the review published on its cover a picture of cole during the incident and a story about it
dartmouth spokesman alex huppe said baldwin and the other three students face college charges of disorderly conduct, harassment and violation of the right to privacy because of the confrontation
to have four students exercise their will over the institution, we're not going to let four students do that,'' said huppe. the four are scheduled to appear before a disciplinary board next tuesday
cole could not be reached for comment. he did not return a message left on his telephone answering machine monday night
baldwin was among a dozen students involved in a pre-dawn sledgehammer attack on symbolic anti-apartheid shanties set up by student protesters in january 1986. after a series of hearings and appeals, he was sentenced to serve 180 hours of community service
the shanty attack sparked sit-ins and protests that continued all semester and led to a one-day moratorium on classes for discussions of racism. failing</head>
the reagan administration's war on drugs has been little more than a skirmish that failed to stem the movement of drugs across u.s. borders, says the head of a task force of prosecutors
the federal government, despite all the talk, has failed to stop the drug trafficking across the borders,'' state's attorney richard daley of chicago told the national district attorney's association's annual conference monday. ``and it's increasing each year. it's not going down.''
daley, head of the association's drug control committee, said drug enforcement administration border patrols capture only 15 percent of the illegal drugs coming into the united states, while marijuana and cocaine worth $130 billion a year is entering from latin american countries
daley also said the federal government is not properly funding local efforts to prosecute criminals as promised when the war on drugs was declared
i don't think it's a war on drugs. i think it's only been skirmishes,'' daley said. ``they don't really have a national policy. that's where it fails.''
when the reagan administration first attacked drug use in america, it set aside $225 million to help local prosecutors, who handle at least 95 percent of the drug cases in the u.s., daley said
but this year funding was cut to $70 million, although the drug problem is getting worse and more violent, he said
the federal government should put its money where its mouth is,'' said daley, the son of the late chicago mayor richard daley. ``we local prosecutors are on the offensive and we need federal help
the drug people are going to corrupt this country more and more. and you're going to see more violence. you're just seeing the beginning.''
the association delegates approved four resolutions dealing with drug enforcement, including one urging federal funding for local anti-drug programs to be reinstated to ``adequate levels.''
they called for combining state and federal efforts to block the importation of illegal drugs into the united states
a third resolution asked the internal revenue service to channel its efforts toward helping ``prevent drug dealers from enjoying the profits of their illegal activity.''
the association also asked for a federal program to help fund the construction of county and state prisons to house the increased number of convicted drug offenders
daley said the idea of educating the public to ``just say no'' has gone far enough and the concentration should be placed on people who have said yes to drugs for years
i'm not a social worker and i'm not a teacher,'' daley said. ``i'm a prosecutor.'' commoners</head>
andrew and sarah, the duke and duchess of york, transformed into andy and fergie, the down-home celebrities, snacking at a supermarket deli, decorating a cake and shaking hands with screaming fans
the royal couple's ``walkabout'' along the edge of a crowd outside a supermarket monday was their closest unplanned contact with everyday americans during a southern california tour that has included much hobnobbing with hollywood celebrities
i love them both. i think fergie and di are just _ american,'' said susie clayton, referring also to diana, the princess of wales
ms. clayton, 27, visiting from arizona, waited for two hours in on-and-off rain that could have been imported from britain for the royal retinue to arrive at the von's pavilions market in suburban arcadia
