the early trend followed sharp gains in new york on monday, where the dow jones industrial average rose 48.41 to 2,071.41, and a rise overnight in tokyo, where the nikkei index climbed 193.09 to 25,435.90.   
police said two ira guerrillas killed in a huge explosion in a border area may have been installing explosives in a van in preparation for an attack on an army observation post
the blast, which occurred monday in the south armagh border area, destroyed a van and a barn about two miles outside crossmaglen village, badly damaged two cars and left a crater in the ground
in another development, irish and british authorities on monday said libya has sent soviet-made, anti-aircraft missiles to the irish republican army
police said four armed and masked men hijacked the van and a car shortly before the blast, which the ira called an accident
authorities speculated that ira guerrillas were installing explosives in the van when the explosives accidentally detonated. a police officer, speaking anonymously in keeping with british practice, said the ira's intended target probably was an army observation post near the border with irish republic
the mostly roman catholic ira often uses explosives in its violent campaign to drive the british out of the predominantly protestant province and unite it with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic
the ira issued a statement monday saying two of its men died in the blast, which it described as ``an unfortunate accident.'' the group gave no details, and said names and ira ranks of the dead men would be released after families are notified. the british domestic news agency press association said the two dead men had been named locally as brendan burnes and brendan moley
irish and british authorities said in a tv program broadcast from london monday that the ira is equipped with soviet-made sam-7 anti-aircraft missiles
the surface-to-air missiles were contained in more than 100 tons of weaponry sent by libya to ireland for the ira in four shiploads in 1985 and 1986, according to the british broadcasting corp.'s ``panorama'' program
the program said british army helicopters operating along northern ireland's border with the irish republic would be the most likely targets
the irish justice minister, gerry collins, said some of the missiles ``may very well be'' in northern ireland already
john hermon, chief constable of the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, said he had ``no reason to doubt'' the sam-7s are hidden somewhere in ireland
officials said one shipment in october was unloaded one night at an isolated jetty near arklow, 40 miles south of dublin, ireland
police have uncovered some of the weapons recently in both the irish republic and northern ireland, but no sam-7s have been found
the european economic community is prepared to back a central american plan to boost economic development in the troubled region, west germany's foreign minister said
foreign minister hans-dietrich genscher said monday the 12-member european community ``is prepared to take constructive part in seeing this plan through.''
genscher, who was chairing the eec session, did not say by how much the community was prepared to raise its relatively small amount of economic aid to central america, but emphasized the group was interested in helping the region achieve stability. eec aid to the region last year was about $96 million, community officials said
the central american states have worked out a $1.4 billion total aid package they say is needed from foreign doners
earlier, the eec reaffirmed its support for a regional peace plan and warned against outside interference in central america
the peace plan calls for an end to outside support for insurgencies, cease-fires, amnesties and democratic reforms
french foreign minister claude cheysson, who heads the eec commission for latin american relations, also reassured central american countries of the eec's economic support without providing specific figures
the eec ministers were in hamburg for a one-day meeting that centered on central american issues. they met with representatives of costa rica, nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, and honduras _ the countries whose presidents signed the arias peace plan in august
they also met with representatives from mexico, panama, venezuela and columbia, members of the contadora group that is trying to mediate an end to violence in the region
a respected linguist who says he was enticed by yale university to leave the soviet union in the 1970s says he is going broke on a school pension after being forced to retire two years ago
sebastian k. shaumyan, a 72-year-old professor emeritus of linguistics, said monday he never would have emigrated had he known he faced mandatory retirement on a $750-a-month pension 11 years later
i lived quite well (in moscow) and here i don't know what to do. i am without means to live,'' he said. ``i think it's very strange why a university professor must retire at 70. now i do even better work than before.''
shaumyan, who became an american citizen in 1980, said he is happy with his new country, but he is considering a lawsuit against yale. his lawyer wants shaumyan's pension doubled to $1,500 a month
yale is un-american,'' shaumyan said. ``if i knew that i would jeopardize my work, my family, my existence, i wouldn't have left moscow.''
he said yale wooed him from established academic positions in moscow in 1975 without telling him he would be automatically retired at the age of 70, as are all faculty members
they promised me a good position and prominent work,'' he said. ``they deceived me.''
university spokesman walter littell declined to comment because of the possibility of a lawsuit
shaumyan said he was paid $20,000 during 1975, his first year at yale, and was making nearly $55,000 by the time he retired in 1986
now, he said, he has depleted his savings and is going broke, even with the $900 he receives in monthly social security benefits. mortgage, car and student loan payments for his three children eat up $1,100 a month, he said
he's not asking for a large sum and he's not asking to hit the lottery here,'' said his lawyer, mark arons
shaumyan is a specialist in mathematical linguistics. in his 1987 book, ``a semiotic theory of language'' published by indiana university press, he discusses how mathematics can set uniform rules for languages, which in turn have applications for writing new computer languages. his 11 books have been translated into at least seven languages
president daniel arap moi won a third five-year term after no one contested his seat in parliament and his ruling party nominated him as the only presidential candidate
moi in effect won the contest monday after filing unopposed as a member of parliament for baringo central constituency
the filing was a formality since moi was the sole presidential candidate nominated saturday by the ruling kenya africa national union, which he leads. by law, it is kenya's only political party
joseph mwangovya, supervisor of elections, announced moi's election after the president presented his election papers during a ceremony at the kabarnet high school playground
moi, 63, has been president of this east african nation since 1978, when as vice-president he succeeded the late jomo kenyatta, the country's first leader
the constitution requires the president to be a member of parliament and for general elections to be held at least every five years
monday was the deadline for candidates to file papers for the march 21 general election
the party approved 787 parliamentary candidates for the primary election and 360 of them made it through to the general election, which will be held by secret ballot for 188 seats
besides moi, 61 other members of the previous parliament were elected monday because they have no general election opposition
