president roh tae-woo appealed today to communist north korea to take part in the 1988 olympic games and pledged not to impose any conditions on the north's participation
there is no condition. ... we will welcome you, the breathren in the north, more than anyone else as the same countrymen and brothers,'' roh told an audience of 4,000 people at the sejong cultural center in seoul
roh made the strongest appeal in recent months to the north to take part in the games, speaking during celebrations of samil day, a national holiday commemorating a 1919 uprising against japanese rule. he also appealed for national reconciliation in the south
today, we recall our breathren ... who rose up with bare fists against the japanese imperialist colonial rule,'' roh said
less than one mile away, police today kicked and punched dissidents and dragged away dozens of them after breaking up an anti-government protest in pagoda park, where the 1919 uprising took place. prominent dissident leaders were among those detained
roh hinted at his willingness to meet with north korean leaders by saying he was ready to deal with anybody. he repeated that the south would seek to establish relations with north korea's main allies, the soviet union and china
i will meet with anyone, anytime and anywhere and will not hesitate to open that road however rugged it might be,'' he said
the new president, formally sworn in feb. 25, said the olympic games could help speed reunification of the divided korean peninsula
north korea is demanding to co-host the olympic games and says it will boycott the games if its request is denied
south korea and the international olympic committee have rejected the demand, but said the north could stage five events if it takes part in the seoul events
the two nations have existed since 1948 and fought the bloody korean war from 1950 to 1953. the bitter rivals have clashed repeatedly over the years
roh also appealed to the south korean opposition to work with his government in ending decades of authoritarian rule and introducing full democracy. ``the curtain has been raised for the era of national self-esteem in which democracy will blossom,'' he said
roh, a former general, won the first democratic presidential elections in 16 years last december with 36.6 percent of the vote after rival opposition candidates split the opposition vote. roh campaigned on the platform that he alone could ensure democracy and stability
about 150 dissidents staged a demonstration today in seoul's pagoda park to denounce roh and demand the immediate release of all political prisoners
protesters waved placards, shouted slogans and applauded speeches as hundreds of onlookers watched
down with the roh government!'' and ``release all the political prisoners!,'' the protesters shouted
scuffles began when plainclothes police tried to detain some protesters and other dissidents protested
a column of about 100 police suddenly charged into the protest, kicking and punching people to the ground and chasing others. police hauled away about 40 dissidents, some of whom were badly beaten
police also hit a number of press photographers covering the demonstration
the rev. moon ikhwan and several other prominent dissident leaders were taken away by police. some of those detained included radicals released from prison saturday as part of a government amnesty
opposition leaders rejected the amnesty as insufficient and have demanded the release of all political prisoners. the government says only dissidents guilty of violent crime or subversion remain in jail. museum</head>
county commissioners have approved a $2.3 million contract to construct an elevator tower and visitors center in the former texas schoolbook depository as part of an exhibit on the assassination of president john f. kennedy
the commissioners voted 3-2 monday to award the contract to thomas j. hayman construction co., which will begin work on the project as early as this week
the eyes of the world will be on this project,'' said lindalyn adams, president of the dallas county historical foundation, which has worked for 11 years to get the exhibit funded. ``as sad as it is, it is the most important historical site in dallas.''
the foundation plans to raise $1.5 million from private sources for additional renovations on the sixth floor of what is now known as the dallas county administration building
the warren commission determined that lee harvey oswald fired a high-powered rifle at kennedy from the sixth floor of the building where he worked on nov. 22, 1963
the elevator tower is intended to carry up to 500,000 visitors a year to the exhibit without disrupting work at county government offices
architect tony callaway said construction could be completed by november, but foundation officials say they are unlikely to schedule the exhibit's opening on nov. 22, the 25th anniversary of kennedy's assassination
we think it would be inappropriate,'' adams said
pakistan is trying to undermine u.n.-sponsored afghanistan peace talks, afghanistan's ambassador to the soviet union charged today
the ambassador, mohamadulah subhani safi, made the comment on the eve of a new round of negotiations, telling a news conference that pakistan ``doesn't want peace'' for its afghan neighbors
pakistan, which represents the afghan guerrillas in the talks that resume in geneva on wednesday, is trying to ``raise issues that have no relevance to pakistan,'' he charged
safi complained about pakistan's demand that any accord signed in geneva that would facilitate a withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan be linked to the formation of a transitional, coalition government in kabul
without such an interim government, unending civil strife would follow a soviet pullout, pakistani diplomats have argued
but safi said the composition of the afghan government cannot be dictated by pakistan or any outside power
his comments were echoed in an article in pravda, the soviet communist party daily, which said pakistani leaders have ``apparently forgotten their previous statements that the presence of the soviet troops in afghanistan was the sole obstacle in the way toward resolving the afghan problem.''
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has pledged _ if peace talks are successful _ to begin withdrawing an estimated 115,000 troops from its embattled neighbor may 15 and complete the pullout in 10 months
gorbachev has said the kremlin has no intention of trying to determine the composition of the government left behind when it leaves the country it entered in december 1979 in support of a marxist regime
pravda called it ``an open secret'' that the united states and its nato allies have a decisive influence over pakistan and leaders of the afghan resistance
their attitude to the afghan settlement, which is now entering its crucial stage,'' will be a touchstone for the world to judge the real worth of their calls for a political settlement of regional crises of every kind,'' the newspaper said
the united states has been ambivalent in its reaction to the calls for an interim government. a senior american official returning with secretary of state george p. shultz from moscow hinted last week that washington does not back such demands
but the u.s. senate, in a non-binding resolution monday, urged the formation of an interim government in kabul that would be acceptable to the afghan resistance
there also has been a lack of clear signals on when washington would be prepared to cut off its aid to the guerrillas, which was reported to have totaled about $700 million last year
local officials pocketed or misappropriated $48 million in state funds to poverty-stricken areas over two years, using the money to build hotels, apartments and movie houses, an official report said
the state auditing administration said the sum represents 6 percent of the $816 million it audited, but officials said they believe much more was embezzled during 1985 and 1986, the official people's daily reported monday
the state allocated more than $1.62 billion to poverty-stricken areas in the two-year period, the paper said
statistics at the end of 1986 showed that 60 million people in about 200 counties live below china's poverty line of $40 annually plus 440 pounds of grain
auditors also found more than 110 people involved in graft cases totaling more than $91,000, it said
the state council is planning to change distribution of the funds so that the money will go directly to enterprises that can improve the area's financial situation
in yanchi county, ningxia autonomous region, more than $243,000 or 42.9 percent of the county's funds for the poor, were used to build apartments, hotels and cinemas, the paper said
in seven cities and counties in hunan, officials used $132,432 to buy 22 cars and other motor vehicles
in feixian county, shandong province, officials used $4,300, collected illegally as administrative fees for the distribution of the help-the-poor funds, to buy motorcycles, tape recorders and cameras, the paper said
sue hall's fourth-grade science students are saying ``rats'' to junk food after a month of experiments in which they compared school-food and junk-food diets by feeding them to rodents
it seems like children sort of know what they're suppose to be eating but you're wondering if it has any impact,'' ms. hall said. ``with the kids doing this, they notice the difference.''
on monday, a pair of rats named sweetie and boss hog munched on french fries and a candy bar while fellow rodents rascal and casey dined on a kennedy school lunch consisting of salad, asparagus and a hamburger casserole
the children ``all say things about the rats on junk food like, `boy, are they hyper. ... their hair isn't very shiny,''' ms. hall said
the rodents nibbling on school lunches and sipping milk and water gain weight steadily, are calm and have shiny fur and alert eyes, she said
they let the children pet them,'' she said
but the junk food rats gain and lose weight, do not finish meals and race around the cage when the children try to pick them up to be weighed
the kids say, `gosh, look what happens when you eat this,' '' ms. hall said. ``it seems to increase their lesson.''
ms. hall, who has taught the six-week rat lesson on nutrition eight other times, said she watches for signs the rats are becoming too ill and switches their diets if necessary
a wayward japanese macaque monkey that wandered through western pennsylvania and ohio for six months has ``gone hollywood'' and will be the featured attraction in a new monkey exhibit at the pittsburgh zoo
mayor richard caliguiri and zoo officials launched a drive monday to use the monkey, named alphie, to raise $15,000 for a new exhibit called monkey business inc
alphie escaped from the zoo july 23 and made his way through western pennsylvania and into ohio, where he was captured jan. 27 in a backyard
his six-month odyssey created headlines. while he was on the lam, zoo officials spelled his name alfie. now that he has ``gone hollywood,'' as they put it, they spell it alphie
we hurriedly signed him to a long-term contract. one of the terms was that he be given star billing at the children's zoo this summer and that suitable exhibit facilities be provided for a star of his magnitude,'' said zoo director charles wikenhauser
he said alphie would live in the exhibit beginning in mid-may
denouncing what it called south africa's ``escalation of acts of terrorism'' against blacks, the u.n. human rights commission has renewed its call for mandatory sanctions against the white-led nation
the 43-country panel, at its annual meeting monday, urged that south africa be economically isolated
it said children were increasingly being targeted for repression
the united states, britain and west germany dissented in the 36-3 vote. belgium, france, japan and portugal abstained
the resolution accuses south africa of continuing ``gross and cruel violations of human rights'' under apartheid
it calls for the immediate release of nelson mandela, imprisoned leader of the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement and freedom for all political prisoners in south africa
massacres and daily killings of defenseless men, women and children have become the order of the day,'' the resolution says
it says human rights violations have risen under a government-imposed state of emergency that went into effect in june 1986, and urges the u.n. security council to impose mandatory sanctions on south africa
separately, the commission asked all governments to immediately cut trade, manufacturing and financial ties with south africa and namibia, or south-west africa, the territory ruled by south africa in defiance of u.n. resolutions
the vote was 32-7. the united states, britain, belgium, france, west germany, italy and portugal opposed the draft. spain, ireland, japan and norway abstained
on namibia, 34 delegations voted without dissent to accuse south africa of wide-ranging oppression there and to call anew for namibian independence. nine western countries abstained
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the government's new policy of glasnost will suffer if theaters are barred from performing a play criticized for its portrayal of soviet history, eight leading theater figures said
the soviet people have gotten glasnost through suffering and ``that's why any attempts to turn the process backwards ... arouse deepest concern,'' said the three actors, three producers and two playwrights in a letter published monday in the communist party newspaper pravda
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or more openness on some issues, has led to greater artistic freedom. lately, soviet artists have produced plays on subjects they would not have touched before
the eight accused several critics of trying to block the staging of mikhail shatrov's play ``onward _ onward _ onward'' by ``pinning political labels'' on its author
earlier this month, three historians told pravda the play compared soviet founder vladimir i. lenin to josef v. stalin _ denounced after his death as a dictator _ and portrayed soviet history in a negative way
the eight said the timing of the criticism indicated it was aimed at dissuading theaters from booking the play
it is not by chance that in the provinces they manage to hear this voice. we have information at the union of theater workers that this new play, devoted to lenin, already was banned in some towns,'' the eight wrote
shatrov's new work takes the form of a debate among bolsheviks and their opponents as they look back on soviet history since the 1917 revolution that brought the communists to power
the historians accused shatrov of using lenin as a conduit for his own ideas and treating the bolshevik revolution as an accident
in their letter, the eight said shatrov has written about lenin for 30 years and his plays have been well received
shatrov's new play was published in january in the literary magazine znamya and is scheduled to be performed in moscow this spring
in the play, shatrov makes stalin answer for his purges in which millions of people perished, but in one scene lenin accepts blame for not making certain stalin could not gain power after lenin's death in 1924
in the closing scene, stalin and lenin are on stage. the desire is expressed for stalin to leave, but he will not
yes, we do want stalin to leave, not only the stage, but our lives,'' the eight said in the letter. ``we want his methods to vanish, his `morality,' his ways to solve disputes, in particular in art. but unfortunately, the heritage of the past cannot be overcome by pronouncements.''
we are not going to defend the play or attack it,'' they added. ``it hasn't been staged yet and a play without being staged is a soul without a body. we are concerned with other things.''
in a seven-paragraph comment on the letter, pravda said it would not take sides. ``pravda's point of view is well known,'' it said. ``it has always been against anybody's monopoly for truth and against the position `there is my opinion and there is a wrong opinion'.''
an american denied a first-class honors degree from bristol university after he was accused of cheating petitioned queen elizabeth ii, saying he's honest and is not getting a fair appeal hearing
francis foecke, 30, a native of south bend, ind., has spent the last 21 months trying to clear his name after writing his final exams in mathematics and computer science at the school in the western city of bristol in june 1986
the london times said today that he and his english wife, priscilla, have spent $53,100 trying to disprove allegations that he illicitly gained access to examination papers before the examination
i do not think i am ever going to get an objective hearing or an objective decision from the (university's) appeal committee because they are so close to the people who say i am guilty,'' said foecke
i do not think they realize what a devastating effect this has had on my wife and me,'' he said. the couple lives in the bristol suburb of clifton
when foecke went to pick up his results after the final exams, the university registrar told him he was suspected of cheating and would not receive the degree, the highest the university offers
he was told his examination answers too closely mirrored the lecturers' model answers and that he even had repeated their mistakes in working out some of the mathematical equations
foecke has maintained he worked up to 18 hours a day for more than a year preparing for the exams and that he used the methods taught by his lecturers
the times said the university authorities did not prove foecke cheated but stated they believe he may have stolen a key to get into an office where the papers were stored
foecke's lawyer guy dorman said monday: ``we are petitioning (the queen) on the grounds of a breach of natural justice.''
a legal concept enforced by the senior courts, natural justice says any group making an official ruling, such as the university authorities, must give a fair hearing to the person involved before announcing its decision
the queen holds the post of visitor at the university. the visitor is appointed to look after student interests among other matters but petitions to her in this capacity are rare
because she is a constitutional monarch, the queen would not make a ruling in her own right in foecke's case and there was no comment on the case from buckingham palace
the petition was sent through lord belstead, who holds the post of lord president of the privy council and is the cabinet member responsible for supervising the government's legislative program
cartoonist milton caniff, creator of the steve canyon and terry and the pirates comic strips, has begun chemotherapy treatments for lung cancer in new york city
caniff was in the mood to talk monday in a telephone interview from beth israel hospital
first thing this morning i reached for the old drawing board but it wasn't even there,'' caniff told the dayton daily news
caniff, who learned about the cancer friday, thinks it will be at least a month before he is able to draw steve canyon again. he said he doesn't know how long he will be in the hospital
this cancer thing has kind of stopped me in my tracks for a bit, so right now i'm just taking it one day at a time,'' he said
caniff said he has about 30 days worth of the canyon strip finished. if he's unable to work when those are gone, his assistant, richard rockwell, and others will keep the storyline running
caniff, who grew up in dayton, has been producing a daily comic strip for 54 years and had planned to continue drawing in the hospital
but when it came right down to it, i didn't feel like it,'' the 81-year-old artist said
even so, he said, his spirits are high
i'm just naturally ornery, anyway, but when this happened, i had to decide what i was going to do,'' he said. ``i could be an old curmudgeon or i could make life easier for my family, friends and the medical staff here. i decided on the latter approach.''
a gang of bumbling burglars dressed up as japanese ninja warriors has botched most of its heists so far, managing to burn up $7,000 while trying to open safes with a blowtorch
but police say the group of three or four people is getting better with practice, and last weekend their fifth known job resulted in about $500 in unsinged cash for the thieves
the gang members dress in black like the ninja, a feudal japanese society of mercenary assassins, and enter buildings through a roof or by forcing employees working odd hours to let them in
they started out like they've been watching too many movies,'' joked detective rich berendsen of the concord police department. he said in three of the burglaries, the gang's blowtorches burned up most of the cash they were after
the gang's first known burglary was of emil vlla's restaurant in concord on jan. 25. they gave up trying to break into a safe when their drill bit broke off in the lock
rhythm-and-blues musician ike turner, former husband of pop superstar tina turner, surrendered monday on a week-old warrant that sought his arrest because he failed to appear in court to face cocaine charges
turner, 55, was charged with possession of cocaine, conspiracy to sell cocaine and maintaining a residence for the purpose of selling cocaine
he appeared before superior court judge gilbert alston and was released after posting $15,000 bail
pre-trial motions for turner and co-defendant richard lee griffin are set march 18. two other co-defendants return march 18 for sentencing on conspiracy charges
turner was arrested in june 1985, after he allegedly tried to sell $16,000 worth of cocaine to an undercover officer in hollywood
a trial is sheduled on another charge march 14 in santa monica superior court on separate felony drug-trafficking charges that include alleged transport of cocaine and possession of rock cocaine for sale
those charges stem from an august 1987, incident in which los angeles county sheriff's deputies stopped turner after the car he was in allegedly was seen moving erratically
in october 1986, turner admitted he had used cocaine every day for at least 15 years and said he was undergoing rehabilitation
turner formed the ike and tina turner revue with his wife, and they produced hits such as ``proud mary'' before splitting up in 1976
miss turner went on to record the 1985 grammy-award winning record and song of the year, ``what's love got to do with it.'' her ``private dancer'' album garnered two other grammys. camps</head> with document appearing to be identical to document reviewed in austria. picks up 10th graf, `the world ...' edits elsewhere to tighten.</note>
while serving in the german army, kurt waldheim forwarded a request for the mass deportation of greek civilians to labor camps in 1943, according to a nazi document
the authenticity of the document, found in the u.s. national archives and made public monday, was confirmed by u.s. justice department spokesman john russell. he said it was among the crucial documents on which the government based its decision to place waldheim, now austria's president and formerly u.n. secretary-general, on a list barring him from entering the united states
under the nuremberg charter adopted at the end of the war, deportation of civilians is both a war crime and a crime against humanity. when the u.s. justice department barred waldheim from the united states, it said he had ``assisted or otherwise participated'' in ``mass deportation of civilians.''
waldheim has repeatedly declared he is innocent of any war crimes
the document is a message between german army officers in the balkans in world war ii and indicates the information was received by radio by waldheim, who signed its transcription and forwarded it on aug. 15, 1943
waldheim at that time was a lieutenant serving as deputy operations officer of the german general staff attached to the 11th italian army in athens
the communication from a german army field officer was addressed to his headquarters and said there is ``hope of success only if all male civilians are seized and deported'' in the area in northern greece where his division was operating. it also said ``cleansing operations are deemed necessary.''
nazi ``cleansing operations'' often meant the destruction of towns and deportation or execution of their inhabitants
the captured nazi document was made available to the associated press by the world jewish congress in the original german text, with excerpts in english. justice department sources concurred in the translation
gerold christian, waldheim's spokesman, said today he had no comment on the document
the document apparently has been used before, according to manfred messerschmidt, a west german historian who was a member of an international commission that investigated waldheim's world war ii past
the historians' commission and a white book published last year by waldheim's aides both reviewed what seems to be the same document, messerschmidt said
the commission's report, released feb. 9, contradicts the white book, saying waldheim's initials on the aug. 15, 1943 document indicate he must have known about persecutions of civilians in greece
the white book says waldheim's initials signify ``nothing but his certifying the correctness of a copy of the message for inclusion'' in the official war diary of his unit
the world jewish congress said waldheim did not authorize the deportation of the greeks to labor camps in germany but that he was aware of the plan
it also said a deportation order later was countermanded by an italian commander whom the congress did not identify
the historians' commission appointed by the austrian government reported last month that waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to nazi atrocities in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. the report did not support allegations made by various groups, including the world jewish congress, that waldheim was involved in war crimes
waldheim, who has rejected calls for his resignation from the presidency, said the report vindicated him
the austrian government has protested that the united states did not disclose the documents on which it based its decision to bar waldheim from entry. washington responded by saying its investigation was based on documents available to waldheim and he could appeal the decision. he has not done so
the executive director of the world jewish congress, elan steinberg, said the document signed by waldheim was located by congress researchers at the u.s. national archives in 1986 and turned over to the justice department
reporters asked why the document was not made public until monday. steinberg said there is now increasing interest in why waldheim was placed on a list barring him from the united states. he did not elaborate. trial</head>
lt. col. oliver north and two other figures in the iran-contra affair were ordered to testify at a federal trial about an alleged scheme to smuggle marijuana and cocaine into michigan from south america
the defense lawyer who obtained the subpoenas said north might be able to provide information about a pilot who flew supplies to nicaraguan rebels under contract with the cia and also was accused of transporting the drugs
north, the former national security council aide fired in november 1986 as the iran-contra affair transpired, last week was ordered to appear march 15 before u.s. district judge anna diggs taylor in detroit
defense attorney ronald c. dresnick of miami said he wanted to determine north's relationship with michael b. palmer. according to the indictment of dresnick's client and seven other defendants, palmer was aboard a dc-6 aircraft allegedly used to ship drugs into michigan last summer
dresnick represents frank ivan turek correa of colombia, one of eight defendants indicted sept. 24 on charges of conspiring to import tons of cocaine and marijuana into michigan between july and sept. 6, 1987
assistant u.s. attorney robert donaldson, referring to dresnick's claim that palmer was a contract employee of the cia, said the defense was a diversion and ``a red herring.''
palmer was a vice president of southern air transport, a cia-backed operation, dresnick said. according to court documents, palmer contracted with the state department to fly food and clothing to the contra rebels trying to topple the government of nicaragua
palmer never was charged in the detroit case despite his apparent role in the alleged trafficking
dresnick, in his court filing seeking north's testimony, provided a page from north's desk calendar dated aug. 9, 1985, with a hand-written notation reading: ``dc-6, which is being used (for contra supply) runs out of new orleans, is probably being used for drug runs into the u.s.''
the same calendar page also noted a ``meeting with rob,'' who dresnick said he believed was robert owen, north's liaison with the contras. both owen and palmer also have been subpoenaed to testify in detroit, although palmer's whereabouts are unknown
barry simon, a washington attorney representing north, refused to say monday night whether north had received the subpoena or to answer any other questions
witnesses who refuse to answer a subpoena can be subject to a bench warrant for their arrest
the rescuers of jessica mcclure are not forgotten, as evidenced by a public spirit award honoring their work, presented by the american legion auxiliary
midland, texas, fire chief james l. roberts received the plaque at monday's national meeting of the auxiliary, which cited the citizens of midland for ``a courageous act _ a young life saved.''
jessica, who was then 18 months old, was trapped in a well last october, but was rescued in an intense 58-hour effort that involved hundreds of people from the community and riveted attention nationwide
the award for the community was presented by legion auxiliary national president pearl behrend of racine, wis
after a month of preparation, it took only 17 minutes to roll over an upside-down oil barge that had been raised from the bottom of guemes channel and partially unloaded
a floating sheen of oil reached the shore of shannon point before and during the rollover monday in a release estimated at 300 gallons to 500 gallons of a light grade of oil. much of it was sopped up with absorbent materials
i'm relieved, because it eliminates an ecological time bomb,'' said coast guard lt. eldo delong
the 176-foot barge sank jan. 31 in 130 feet of water four miles west of anacortes. it was raised from the bottom sunday by two giant derricks
the site is about 75 miles north of seattle on washington's inner coast in an area of dungeness crabs, salmon farms, bottom fish and other saltwater life
officials had said that 70,000 gallons of oil escaped from the barge when it sank, and another 344,000 gallons was still on the barge when the lifting operation began sunday. roughly 92,610 gallons of oil was pumped out sunday night and monday
more oil was to be pumped out of the barge until it was stable enough to be towed to port
some oil has been detected in kelp beds and in bottom-dwelling sea cucumbers, and at least one bird has died
the barge, operated by olympic tug and barge co. of seattle, was being towed from an oil refinery at anacortes to seattle when it sank
a zimbabwean diplomat who was expelled from the united states for allegedly abusing his 9-year-old son said the boy returned home today from new york accompanied by a zimbabwean social worker
diplomat floyd karamba said his son, terrence, was immediately placed under the care of the foreign affairs ministry, the semi-official zimbabwe inter-african news agency reported
my son arrived this morning accompanied by a zimbabwean social worker and is in normal condition,'' karamba was quoted as saying
u.s. officials said terrence karamba left new york for zimbabwe on sunday accompanied by a zimbabwean social worker. he will not be returned to his father's custody, according to reports today in the new york daily news, the washington post and the washington times
zimbabwe has said it will place the boy in the auspices of the courts and the state ministry of social welfare, said robert j. mcmahon, director of the new york social services agency that cared for the boy for the past two months
mcmahon, head of st. christopher-ottile services for children and families, was also quoted today saying the zimbabwean government said the karamba family will undergo counseling in hopes of eventually reuniting terrence with the family
a new york government agency had charged that floyd karamba had beaten the boy, who in december was removed from his home and placed in foster care
the father, who served for more than a year as a member of zimbabwe's delegation to the united nations, was ordered dec. 21 to leave the united states because of what state department officials called ``clear evidence of child abuse.''
in january, the supreme court refused to block the u.s. government from sending the boy home despite arguments from the legal aid society that the boy was afraid to go home
mcmahon said sen. daniel patrick moynihan, d-n.y., interceded and persuaded the state department that the boy should not be returned immediately
the state department had a psychiatric consultant accompany the boy on his trip home and also engaged a law firm in zimbabwe to monitor his case, the post reported
