a police officer who was shot to death while he guarded a witness in a drug case was given a farewell by 10,000 police officers amid vows to find his killer and hopes that his death helps the fight against drug dealers
the throng of officers, some from as far away as texas and ohio, lined eight blocks approaching st. james church on monday for the funeral of edward byrne, a 22-year-old rookie officer
if drug trafficking has become so bold that they can engage in the assassination of a police officer, then our whole society is at risk,'' mayor edward i. koch said at the funeral service. ``that is why his death is so important.''
in his homily, the rev. thomas devita said, ``eddie's murderers need to be pitied and also prayed for. they do not know about the sanctity of life. they cannot really know or understand what they have done, even though this is such a terrible sin.''
eight officers served as pallbearers as a bagpiper played ``when the battle is over.''
police have been rounding up suspected crack dealers since the murder early friday in hopes of finding someone who will shed light on the killing. officer peter o'donnell, a police spokesman, said that as of monday night, 108 had been arrested in the south jamaica section of queens, where the killing took place
byrne was guarding the house of a man who had complained to police about crack dealers in that neighborhood. the officer, who had been on the force just eight months, was hit by three shotgun blasts as he sat in a radio car
others attending the funeral included police commissioner benjamin ward, cardinal john j. o'connor and officer steven mcdonald, who was paralyzed below the neck by a gunman's bullet in 1986
koch had taken out a full page in the new york times on monday. it bore byrne's picture, and called upon the federal government to take tough measures with foreign governments that allow drug trafficking
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., echoed koch's sentiments outside the church
our nation's leaders appear to be isolated from our people in the streets who are being killed and from our youngsters who are becoming addicts,'' said d'amato. ``our nation's leaders don't have the guts to cut off aid to countries run by narcotics dealers such as panama.''
in texas, more than 2,000 people attended a memorial service monday for officer gary d. mccarthy, the third dallas policeman killed in six weeks
he was off duty and moonlighting as a part-time security guard at a grocery store when he was gunned down friday during an attempted robbery. three men have been arrested, one of them a parolee who served less than a year of a five-year sentence for aggravated assault on a police officer
