two men riding a motorbike shot and killed a greek industrialist today as he drove to work in the capital, police said
a left-wing terrorist group that staged an almost identical slaying of a u.s. navy officer at the same athens intersection in 1983 claimed responsibility for the assassination, authorities said
alexandros athanassiadis, 59, died of chest and stomach wounds from bullets that were fired through his car's open window while it was stopped at a red light on kifissias avenue, a police spokesman said
the spokesman, who requested anonymity, said the gunmen sped away and the motorbike was found abandoned
doctors at the hygeia hospital said athanassiadis died during surgery
he had multiple wounds in the chest and stomach. we tried heart massage for 15-20 minutes, but couldn't revive him,'' dr. vassilis georgoulis said
athanassiadis was chief executive officer of the hellenic chemical products and fertilizers company
the terrorist organization november 17 claimed responsibility for his killing in leaflets found in the street, the police spokesman said
the typewritten leaflet said the organization killed athanassiadis because ``he was a classic capitalist...indifferent to the health of the workers and the environment.''
the leaflet claimed that hellenic chemical products, which has a plant in a western industrial suburb of athens, was a major contributor to pollution. it also criticized the government, saying it had led greece into ``economic, social and cultural crisis.''
a government statement expressed ``deepest sorrow and condolences'' and said the greek ``people as a whole condemn such terrorist actions.''
athanassiadis' wife, katerina, told reporters her husband drove the same route to work every morning from their home in the ekali suburb. ``he hadn't told me of anything suspicious,'' she said
the police spokesman said the assailants pulled up beside athanassiadis' car and tapped on the passenger side window. as it opened, they started firing. the attack took place at 8:15 a.m., he said
the shooting occurred at the same junction where a u.s. navy officer was gunned down by the same terrorist group in november 1983, the spokesman said
the navy officer, capt. george tsantes, was attached to the u.s. embassy in athens. his driver also died in the attack
it was a carbon copy of the tsantes killing _ the same traffic light, the same method with two men on a motorbike,'' the police spokesman said
november 17 has claimed responsibility for a dozen attacks against americans, greek police officers and businessmen since 1975. none of its members has been arrested
the left-wing group is named for the day in 1973 when troops and tanks crushed a student rebellion against the 1967-74 military dictatorship
november 17 says american bases in greece should be closed and that premier andreas papandreou's socialist government has failed to change greek society
before today, the group had staged three attacks over the past year, none of which resulted in deaths. in april and august the group claimed responsibility for remote-control bomb blasts against buses carrying american military personnel, but in each case the bomb exploded prematurely
the group's most recent attempt involved a failed bomb attack in january against a u.s. embassy staff member
a civil war cannonball still capable of exploding has been turned over to bomb squad investigators by a man who believes as many as 25 others may have been taken as souvenirs
thomas l. combs sr., 64, of clements, md., gave a rusted, six-inch, 120-year-old cannonball to the maryland fire marshal's bomb squad monday
he became concerned after hearing news reports 10 days earlier that an identical cannonball that was given to the st. clements island museum had been found to be live, said fire marshal's spokesman bob thomas
the bomb squad determined combs' cannonball also was live and took it to a bomb laboratory in harford county, where investigators are trying to defuse and salvage the museum's cannonball, which a potomac river clammer found in his net
thomas said both cannonballs have a fuse and contain black powder
if it detonates, it would send shrapnel from inside in all directions. (it was) meant to inflict numerous casualties,'' thomas said
combs said his cannonball had been collecting dust in a tool shed behind his home since 1961, when he found it while deer hunting near chantilly, va., thomas said
combs told officials he took the cannonball from a pyramid of about 20 to 25 others in a heavily wooded area, and that the stack appeared to have been left there since the civil war, thomas said
combs noticed the pyramid of cannonballs becoming smaller during his hunting excursions over the next 20 years, until none were left, thomas said
that means that at least 25 citizens might have a (live bomb) in their house or on their property,'' thomas said
investigators suspect it was a cache of confederate munitions, he said
thomas said the bomb squad would pick up any suspect cannonballs for free and return them if they can be defused without damage
maryland officials plan to notify state and county authorities in virginia about the discovery, thomas said
former queen maria jose, widow of the last king of italy, made a brief return to the country without fanfare today after a 42-year exile imposed by the constitution
the belgium-born maria jose, who lives in switzerland, crossed the border by car this morning with her daughter, maria gabriella, to attend a conference on st. anselm in this city near mount blanc
after three hours, they drove back home
the italian news agency ansa said the 81-year-old former queen of the house of savoy initially went unnoticed as she took a seat in the back row of the conference hall. when officials realized who she was, they interrupted the meeting and invited her to sit in the front as the audience applauded, the report said
maria jose was invited to the conference last month by the st. anselm academy, of which she is an honorary member. st. anselm of canterbury was born in aosta in the 11th century
i knew that she had been invited to the conference but i really didn't think she would actually come. she took us all by surprise,'' said gianni bondaz, president of the regional council
the former queen, who walked with a cane, wore a black pants suit, black cap, black gloves and a bright red scarf. she spoke only a few words to journalists, saying ``i didn't feel any special emotions entering italy but i am happy
this morning when we crossed the border i was much more excited than she was,'' ansa quoted her daughter as saying
she quoted maria jose as saying once they emerged from the mount blanc tunnel in italy, ``oh how beautiful. the sun is out. i told you that the aosta valley is beautiful.''
the government last year lifted the constitutional ban on the entry of the former queen, who had made a request a year earlier to return to italy. there have been unconfirmed media reports that she has secretly slipped into the country in the past
her husband, umberto ii, reigned for 26 days before being forced into exile in 1946 after a referendum abolished the monarchy. he died in exile in geneva five years ago at the age of 78
the house of savoy ruled over piedmont for nine centuries and its kings reigned in italy from 1861 to 1946
former boxer rubin ``hurricane'' carter, breaking a 12-year silence after finally winning his long battle for freedom, says he was sentenced to ``a life of living death'' but is not bitter
for 20 years, i was considered a danger to society, a scourge upon humanity. i was locked away in an iron cage for not one, but three lifetimes,'' the former middleweight title contender said monday in a news conference
carter was convicted in the 1966 murder of three white men in a paterson bar and served 19 years in prison before the indictment was finally dismissed last week
but carter, 50, dressed in a tan suede jacket, dark tie and navy blue pants, said during the 90-minute news conference that he harbors no bitterness over the system that jailed him
if i have learned anything in my life, it's that bitterness consumes the vessel that contains it,'' he said
the 1966 verdict against carter and john artis was overturned, but the two black men were again convicted in 1976
carter, who was serving a life term, was freed in 1985 by u.s. district judge h. lee sarokin in newark, n.j., who found the conviction was tainted by racism and the witholding of information by prosecutors
the u.s. supreme court upheld the judge's 1985 decision, and a passaic county judge last friday signed the papers dismissing the indictment, as requested by county prosecutors
carter had remained in seclusion, declining to discuss the case publicly. but on monday he condemned over-zealous prosecutors, the horrors of the state prison system, the jailing of innocent people and racism
they sentenced me to a life of living death,'' he said. ``and there is no other way to describe the nature of a prison. prison destroys everything valuable in the life of a human being.''
artis, paroled in 1981, is serving a six-year prison term on an unrelated drug charge. his lawyer, lewis steel, issued a plea for artis' freedom, saying the judge who sentenced him in the drug case improperly took the voided murder convictions into account in the sentencing. the drug sentence is on appeal
carter's cause was taken up in the 1970s by celebrities, who championed him as a symbol of racial injustice. bob dylan wrote a ballad about the case, which played repeatedly in the background before the news conference
carter refused to blame the trial's prosecutors directly for his fate, but said ``racism is sleazy'' and referred to sarokin's finding that the prosecution made ``an appeal to racism rather than reason.''
since being freed, he said he has worked on his case nearly every day and his third book, ``no holds barred, no bars to hold,'' while living in southern new jersey
carter said he had difficulty understanding how he came to serve nearly two decades in prison
one moment i'm a championship prize fighter, the next moment and 20 years after i'm reviled as a triple murderer,'' he said
the fact that the most productive years of my life, the ages of 29 and 50, have been stolen, the fact that i was deprived of seeing my children grow up, wouldn't you think i would have a right to be bitter?'' he said
but being bitter would give the state another victory, he said.``that would make me an accomplice to their crime.'' murder case</head>
police recently questioned pornographic film star john holmes, hospitalized and gravely ill bed with aids, about a 1981 mass murder for which he was tried and acquitted, a newspaper reported today
the appearance of a new witness and reports holmes may soon die from acquired immune deficiency syndrome prompted the bedside questioning, the los angeles times reported
holmes, 43, a premier male sex film star of the 1970s and early 1980s, made hundreds of sexually explicit films and thousands of peep shows in his career
citing unnamed sources, the newspaper reported a new witness has surfaced with information about the grisly beating deaths of four people in a house in the affluent hillside neighborhood of laurel canyon
mitchell egers, one of two lawyers who successfully defended holmes in 1982, refused to disclose what, if anything, holmes told homicide detectives
egers confirmed that holmes is hospitalized with a serious illness but would not say if he suffers from aids
however, the newspaper quoted unidentified sources as saying holmes' illness has been positively diagnosed as aids, the incurable disease transmitted through sex, shared hypodermic needles and transfers of infected blood products
holmes was cleared of killing four people who were found beaten to death in a laurel canyon home. detective tom lange, supervisor of the investigation, declined to discuss the case monday except to say it remains active
prosecutors said the four were part of a theft ring for which holmes acted as a middleman to los angeles nightclub owner adel nasrallah, also known as eddie nash. holmes allegedly fenced stolen property for the group to nash, who allegedly paid for the loot with drugs
nash's business had been robbed two days before the murder. prosecutors alleged holmes staged the robbery and, when discovered, led killers to the laurel canyon home. prosecutors claimed he committed one of the murders with his own hands
jurors cited a lack of corroborating evidence for their vote for acquittal
nash was sentenced in a separate case to eight years in prison for possession of two pounds of cocaine worth an estimated $1 million. he was released after serving less than two years
lange said nash remains a suspect in the laurel canyon killings, as does his one-time bodyguard, and that police have other suspects
two classmates from stuyvesant high school in new york won the top awards in the 47th annual national science talent search
in results announced monday night, chetan nayak, 16, was awarded the top prize for a mathematical analysis of gravitation and electromagnetic fields. he will receive a $20,000 college scholarship
janet tseng, 17, whose project was a study of a parasitic infection common in aids victims, was awarded a $15,000 scholarship as the second-place winner
both students are seniors at stuyvesant high school in new york city. nayak lives in manhattan and ms. tseng lives in queens
the third-place winner was benjamin s. abella, 17, of chicago. his project studied genes that affect protein production in a certain bacterium. he is a senior at the university of chicago laboratory schools high school and will receive a $15,000 college scholarship
the winners were announced at a banquet that followed judging of the projects from 40 finalists in the annual national competition that had included 1,339 entrants. the finalists, 24 boys and 16 girls from 17 states, came to washington last week for the final judging
under the sponsorship of westinghouse electric corp., the science talent search has been conducted annually since 1942. former contest finalists include five nobel prize laureates and 27 members of the national academy of sciences
winners for fourth-through-10th place and the prizes received were, in order:
vijay satyanand pande, 17, mclean, va., $10,000
brian david conrad, 17, selden, n.y., $10,000
weiva yu sieh, 17, bronx, n.y., $10,000
stacey ellen beaulieu, 16, palm beach gardens, fla., $7,500
kurt marshall cuffey, 18, state college, pa., $7,500
brian casey hooker, 17, atlanta, ga., $7,500
meredith ann albrecht, 17, evanston, ill., $7,500
each of the other 30 finalists will receive cash awards of $1,000
a man who spent almost two years in prison after he confessed to a murder he didn't commit was freed four days after another man confessed to the crime
steven ferndo, 20, of south st. louis, said he confessed to stabbing charles oxenhandler in january 1986 because he was a drug addict and ``sick of life.''
ferndo was freed by st. louis circuit judge robert dowd jr. after douglas weems of jefferson county confessed last thursday to the killing
drugs had ruined my life,'' ferndo said of his decision to confess. ``i was down. i was a drug addict. i gave up on life
now i don't even remember that life. now i just want to go up in the world and put my life together.''
ferndo was sentenced to 20 years in prison in 1986 after he entered an ``alford plea,'' which makes no attempt to counter the evidence while offering no admission of guilt
the case was reopened in october after a young woman who had been punched by weems told authorities that weems had killed oxenhandler
weems, 23, was charged with second-degree murder in the killing of oxenhander, a radio consultant who used the stage name of robert hattrick. weems told police that a fight had broken out after oxenhandler made homosexual advances
ferndo's mother, janie gillian, wept at the hearing monday and said, ``my baby's out ... i knew he was not a killer.''
a convicted mafia boss was shot dead on a busy street in the center of city about 200 feet from police headquarters, officials reported
a policewoman gave chase but the killer disappeared into the crowd and escaped
the italian news agency ansa first reported that the assassin wore a minskirt and high heels, but officials said the killer was a man and that witnesses were confused by the police officer running with her pistol in hand
the victim was identified as domenico cavo, 29, considered the no. 2 man in the mafia clan that controls the rackets in this city in eastern sicily. he was killed instantly by two bullets fired at close range while standing in front of a coffee bar, police said
cavo was sentenced to eight years in prison last april after a mass trial of mafia suspects. he was out on provisional liberty while appealing the conviction
the nation has a new postmaster general today, the fourth in as many years
anthony m. frank, a san francisco banker, took office as head of the u.s. postal service without formal ceremony. he started his service with a meeting of top postal executives
frank takes over the troubled agency with a rate increase pending at the same time cuts in services have been forced by congressionally required spending reductions. the cuts include reduced sorting time, collections and window hours
he brings to the job a reputation as an innovator who encourages initiative in his managers and is willing to try new ideas
a decision by the independent postal rate commission is expected within a week on a rate increase proposed by the agency last year. the complex series of rate changes would include a 25-cent first class rate, if approved, and could take effect by mid-april
the service cuts are not likely to change, even with higher rates, since the new stamp prices were proposed to cope with other cost pressures and are not related to the budget changes imposed by congress
frank succeeds new york businessman preston r. tisch, who had held the post since aug. 6, 1986. tisch followed albert v. casey, who held the job for only seven months. casey replaced paul n. carlin, who served for just a year from january 1985 to 1986
a 16-month-old girl bitten last week by a swarm of ants has died, a hospital spokeswoman said today
tiffany cheatham died monday night, according to kathy musial of sacred heart hospital here. the spokeswoman said she did not yet know the official cause of death
tiffany was rushed to the hospital feb. 23 after a playful dog pushed her into an ant hill near her florida panhandle home of navarre, 20 miles outside pensacola
the girl's mother, lynn cheatham, and a neighbor had desparately tried to remove the ants, taking off tiffany's clothes and putting her in a bathtub, but many of the insects were entangled in her hair
there were ants all around all of us,'' said the neighbor, janet streaker
the girl initially lapsed into unconsciousness, but was revived at the scene, said chief don van derryt of the holley-navarre fire and rescue association
ann papadelias, another hospital spokeswoman, said she suspected the girl was attacked by fire ants, known for painful and sometimes deadly stings
concealing marijuana, playing tag with patrol cars and making love atop a squad car were among misconduct allegations filed against a group of suspended policemen, town officials have disclosed
police chief robert peyer and four policemen were suspended with pay by the police and fire commission last month. on monday, town chairman wayne polzin detailed the accusations against the five
no criminal charges have been filed. the commission has scheduled personnel hearings march 21, and peyer has said he would insist on an open hearing
peyer has been accused of giving information to a nightclub owner who was under investigation by police and the internal revenue service, and of lying about selling uniform patches and other apparel to a nightclub stripper
evidence seized last year under a search warrant included a photograph showing a woman in a town of delavan police uniform
the town had originally refused to release the allegations, but polzin said town officials wanted to avoid a legal challenge by news media under the state's open records law
we are releasing them,'' polzin said, ``after considering the threats by the media about charges against the town and the consideration we may have to pay court costs and fines.''
the suspended patrolmen are william mortlock, ernest hardwick, edward rome and jeffrey lofy. documents quoted by the milwaukee sentinel accuse:
_ hardwick and peyer of providing information to jerry petrone during an investigation of petrone's nightclub
_ peyer and hardwick of playing golf during duty hours
_ peyer of failing to turn in confiscated marijuana, of failing to investigate reports that rome and lofy played chase in squad cars and failing to act on a traffic investigation of a juvenile living at petrone's house
_ rome of having sex with a woman on a police car
_ mortlock and peyer of gaining free admission to petrone's club in violation of department rules that forbid accepting gratuities
delavan is a town of 5,700 residents about 40 miles southwest of milwaukee
waterbeds work wonders for babies born addicted to narcotics used by their mothers, a new study indicates, but researchers say they aren't sure why
such infants have easier withdrawal, are more comfortable and are more likely to thrive if they lie on waterbeds instead of traditional bassinets, the study found
infants going through drug withdrawal suffer many of the same symptoms that afflict adult addicts, including irritability, tremors, vomiting, abnormal sleeping and poor feeding
but a waterbed provides improved care that is ``safe, noninvasive, inexpensive and effective,'' said the researchers, whose findings were published in the february issue of the american journal of diseases of children
one of the researchers, dr. suzanne d. dixon, cautioned that this is essentially an improved nursing technique and not even a partial solution to the problem posed by addicted infants
this study was to evaluate a simple nursing change to see if it could make life just a little better for children who have a lot of things stacked against them,'' said dixon, with the pediatrics department at the univerity of california in san diego
waterbed use makes the early days of newborn addicts more comfortable, helps in some traditional treatments and hopefully gives youngsters a better chance for normal development, she said
she said researchers aren't sure why the waterbeds seem to help
more expensive oscillating waterbeds have been used successfully with premature non-addicted babies to provide movement stimulation. but the researchers found that newborn addicts can benefit from non-oscillating beds that are less expensive than traditional bassinets
over half of the narcotic-exposed neonates required medication to control withdrawal symptoms,'' the researchers said
those on waterbeds required a significantly lower maximum phenobarbital dose and had a lower incidence of hospital discharge with medication, thereby reducing the newborn's exposure to additional drugs.''
when discharged from the hospital, 63 percent of the waterbed babies had been weened from withdrawal medication, as opposed to 38 percent of infants in bassinets
the research was conducted on 30 infants born with an addiction to narcotics, mostly heroin or methadone. half were put on waterbeds, half in bassinets
by the fifth day, researchers said, it was clear the waterbeds were having an impact
withdrawal symptoms such as vomiting, tremors and congestion were less severe among the waterbed babies, the study found. they also went to sleep more easily and had improved weight gain
a woman charged with involuntary manslaughter says it was her husband who locked their two young children in a sun-baked car last summer, leading to the youngsters' deaths, her lawyer says
lisa shields, 19, of white township, relied on her husband, john shields, 24, to take care of their children, kristle, 3, and calvin, 1, on aug. 22, said lawyer thomas johnson
shields will ``testify his wife told him to watch the children while she went inside the house because she was ill,'' thomas said during opening remarks monday in the first day of mrs. shield's trial
prosecutors called 11 witnesses monday and were expected to call several more today before the defense began its case
the couple left a party early on aug. 22 and drove to a relative's farmhouse, according to an affidavit by state police. mrs. shields slept in the car with the children from about 5 a.m. to 9 a.m., and shields went into the house, police said
then mrs. shields went into the house and asked her husband to take care of the children, johnson said. shields moved the car to a sunnier location and rolled up the windows, police said
when mrs. shields checked the children several hours later, she found calvin unconscious and kristle gasping for breath, according to police. calvin was pronounced dead at the scene and his sister died the next day in pittsburgh's mercy hospital. autopsies showed both died of high temperatures
mrs. shields also is charged with endangering the welfare of children. her husband faces identical charges and is scheduled to go on trial later this month in mifflin county
each defendant won a change of venue from indiana county after defense attorneys argued pre-trial publicity made seating an impartial jury impossible there. they have been jailed since their arrests
fifty-two people were arrested and at least $85,000 worth of exotic animals and organs were seized during an undercover investigation, according to a published report
the oakland tribune reported today that officers seized a variety of animal parts including genitalia from tigers and sea lions, rhinoceros horns and dried abalone
several hundred male sex organs from other species were also seized, said chuck monroe, a california department of fish and game patrol chief at the department's yountville headquarters in napa county
the operation began as an investigation into illegal trafficking in bear gall bladders, said monroe
most of the charges involve poaching and commercialization of wildlife, both misdemeanor violations of the state fish and game code, he said
munroe said the animal parts were marketed mostly to the asian community as aphrodisiacs and general health foods. in some cases, he said, gall bladders from cows or pigs were sold as bear organs
a soviet government spokesman said today a curfew was imposed in sumgait, the city in azerbaidzhan where rioting broke out two days ago. he said ``some mistakes'' had been made concerning a disputed territory that is home to tens of thousands of armenians
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov said the situation was calm but tense in azerbaidzhan and neighboring soviet armenia, where ethnic hatred triggered demonstrations, violence and at least two deaths in recent days
he suggested the unrest resulted from a ``mistake'' made 65 years ago when a territory composed largely of ethnic armenians was made part of neighboring azerbaidzhan
there were certain injuries'' in sumgait, an industrial city where hooligans were blamed for touching off a riot sunday, gerasimov said
at his regular briefing today, the soviet spokesman was peppered with questions about the unrest in the southern republics of armenia and azerbaidzhan. however, he said he had few details
foreign journalists have been barred from the region, and only sporadic reports from witnesses, activists and the official media have reached moscow
gerasimov was asked about reports that soviet tanks are patrolling sumgait, that ethnic azeris are attacking armenians there and that there have been at least two deaths in the city
he responded that ``there is a curfew'' in sumgait, but that he had not heard anything about tanks being sent into the city. ``the situation is calm there today, but it is tense,'' gerasimov said
asked if troops remained in the city today, he said, ``i don't know, but i guess so. presumably.''
the violence in sumgait, reported monday by the official soviet news agency tass, followed outbreaks 150 miles away in nagorno-karabakh, the contested region in azerbaidzhan, and mass demonstrations in yerevan, the capital of soviet armenia
the demonstrators demanded that nagorno-karabakh, which has been part of azerbaidzhan since 1923, be made part of armenia. three-quarters of the area's 157,000 residents are armenian
gerasimov said he did not have detailed reports from the entire region but that what information he had indicated ``everything is calm'' in yerevan and surrounding areas
the events that took place caused great concern to us,'' he said. ``we think it is not a proper way to settle the problems that have accumulated.''
gerasimov acknowledged, however, that the unrest apparently stemmed from ``some mistakes made in the national relations, and these mistakes should be rectified.''
soviet authorities have pledged to reconsider the issue of nagorno-karabakh's parent republic, and gerasimov's statement seemed to indicate the region might be turned over to armenia. he did not, however, say when that might occur
asked if he meant to say that nagorno-karabakh should be made part of armenia, gerasimov said: ``i meant there were some mistakes in nagorno-karabakh.''
he described the region as ``a kind of enclave'' in azerbaidzhan with 49 nationalities represented among the population that is nonetheless mostly armenian
that is why we should be very tactful in handling this question in order not to cause differences between brothers and nationalities. the previous policy had some mistakes in this area,'' he said
on friday, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed for ``civil maturity and restraint'' and promised the communist party central committee would review relations among the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
azerbaidzhan is the largest of three soviet republics in the caucasus. it is bordered on the west by largely christian armenia and georgia and on the north by the russian republic. quotes, picks up 6th pvs: the joint...; edits thereafter to tighten</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz turned today to king hussein of jordan to back the u.s. drive for mideast peace talks
he's a key, in my opinion,'' shultz said. ``he has immense standing and a person who's been here a long time. through all of these issues, up and down, he's a man of experience and judgment.''
talking to reporters on his flight from the middle east, shultz hinted he was inclined to return to the region after a nato summit meeting in brussels wednesday and thursday
nobody has signed up to our proposal, but everybody wants us to keep working, so we will keep working,'' shultz said in a departure statement in israel
we will continue our efforts,'' he said
after arriving at london's heathrow airport, he met hussein at a private residence owned by the king in central london. shultz also was to see prime minister margaret thatcher and foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe before flying to brussels later today
in jerusalem, diplomatic sources, demanding anonymity, said shultz had told israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir he would return after the nato summit if hussein gave at least qualified support to the u.s. proposal
it calls for israel, jordan, and palestinians to open negotiations on about april 1 on self-rule of the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live on the west bank and in gaza. talks on an overall middle east settlement would begin by december
we are still very much in a process of working,'' shultz said as he left israel
while in the middle east, he met with jordanian officials including crown prince hassan. but only the king, who went to london for dental treatment, can give an authoritative response for the arab country that occupied the west bank from 1949 to 1967
king hussein is a very critical factor in it all,'' shultz said aboard his air force jet
he said he would report to president reagan in brussels and go back to the middle east after the summit if ``he wants me to.''
shultz acknowledged he had made little concrete progress during four days of talks with israeli and arab leaders. while he said he could see a narrowing of differences, ``i don't know if i could describe them in a way that would be perceptible to anyone else.''
and yet, shultz said, ``assuming everyone continues the attitude they have to keep working, to keep working, we'll do it.''
a senior israeli official who demanded anonymity said jordanian officials had surprised shultz by hardening their insistence on holding an international conference and by abandoning previous support for a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation
shamir has opposed a u.n.-sponsored conference attended by the five permament members of the u.n. security council: the united states, soviet union, britain, france and china. he has argued such a forum would be biased against the jewish state
the joint delegation was a key element of u.s.-sponsored peacemaking efforts because it got around israeli refusal to talking with yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization
foreign minister shimon peres, speaking to children in the resort city of elat, suggested that king hussein sought a plo role in selecting a negotiating team
hussein says he wants the plo without arafat. let's go along with him on this formula ... plo, yes, arafat, no,'' peres said in remarks aired on israel's army radio
his remarks were initially interpreted as a change in position, but peres aides said there had been a ``misunderstanding.''
peres' spokesman uri savir issued a clarification, stressing peres is against talks with the plo and was referring to hussein's position
shultz, who put his personal prestige on the line during the shuttle, found the middle east deeply divided by distrust and a volatile west bank and gaza strip, where 76 arabs have been killed since rioting began dec. 8
shamir is scheduled to visit washington in two weeks for talks with reagan and shultz
but it could be a third key figure, chairman yasser arafat of the palestine liberation organization, who has been most instrumental in upsetting shultz's mission. one major shultz objective was to meet with a delegation of palestinian arabs in order to get their goals in negotiations
but under plo instructions, all 15 he invited to a session last friday in jerusalem stayed away
in amman, reporters briefed under rules that prevented them from disclosing their sources were told jordan no longer would put pressure on the plo to form a joint negotiating team. now, reporters were told, the palestinians all look to the plo as their sole representative and jordan did not intend to stand in their way
the hardened arab stance was said to be in response to israel's suppression of palestinian protests. however, a u.s. official suggested that jordan was more flexible in the private talks with shultz
i don't see any sign that arab positions are hardening.'' but the official added, ``we are not at the point where anybody is saying yes or no.''
