elizabeth dovydenas' $2.56 million bid for property of the bible speaks church in lenox was the third highest bid, charles normandin, attorney for the court-appointed trustee managing the church estate, said monday
he said the high bid of $2.81 million came from a group called lenox associates. its lawyer, richard howard, declined to reveal the partners' identities
second was kaslin properties of new york with a bid of $2.61 million, normandin said
mrs. dovydenas had argued in u.s. bankruptcy court last april that she was duped out of a third of her chain-store fortune by the founder and leader of the fundamentalist sect, rev. carl h. stevens jr., while she was a parishioner from 1983 to 1986
the bible speaks campus closed last year after mrs. dovydenas prevailed in her $6.6 million claim. lawyers for the church plan to appeal a federal judge's recent decision upholding the claim
her claim is by far the largest of hundreds of creditors, who claim they are owed more than $7 million by the church
monday was the deadline for bids on the 65-acre estate with its 28 buildings. normandin said the final round of bidding could come at a hearing monday at u.s. bankruptcy court in worcester
mrs. dovydenas had been the high bidder at a november auction of the church headquarters, but the bankruptcy court rejected her $1.8 million bid as too low. the campus has been appraised at $6 million
forty minority students at hampshire college have reached an agreement with the administration to end their week-long takeover of a dormitory, a college spokeswoman said today
the students had complained of racism at the private liberal arts school
by the end of the day we expect the agreement to be fully signed,'' said administration spokeswoman melissa stephen
spokesmen for the protesters holding the dakin house office were out of the building and could not be reached for comment
college president adele simmons met monday with representatives of the blacks, hispanics, indians and other minorities who have held the small brick building since feb. 23
their 16 demands included the creation of the post of dean of multicultural affairs and for a full-time coordinator for the minority student group
simmons last week offered the students $25,000 to spend as they please on their programs, but the negotiators rejected the offer
that's really an absurd amount for what is needed,'' protest spokeswoman anita fearman said monday
college spokeswoman lee wicks said the students evidently did not understand the college's budget
when you see our high tuition, you think there must be lots of extra money on campus,'' she said. ``we're ending this year on a deficit and they're asking us to come up with bucks in march. yes, we want to be supportive, but in fact we don't have the money.''
tuition at the private liberal arts school was nearly $16,000 this year, she said. minorities represent about 10 percent of the school's 1,100 students
more women are working in entertainment and the news media, but they bump into a ``glass ceiling'' that prevents them from rising into top management jobs, experts told a conference on women, men and media
while more women are hired, that doesn't always translate up,'' said university of missouri journalism professor jean gaddy wilson, citing data gathered during a five-year study of women in media
i do see that glass ceiling,'' ms. wilson told the conference monday at the university of southern california. she described the ``glass ceiling'' as ``a transparent barrier'' that allows women to see top echelon jobs but blocks access to them
women account for 66 percent of the nation's journalism graduates, but less than 2 percent of newspaper corporate management, 5 percent of publishers and general managers, and 13 percent of directing editors, she said
the employment of women in news media lags behind employment in the society overall,'' ms. wilson said. ``if current trends continue, women won't attain directing editorships on par with their level of the population until 2055.''
despite gains in front of the television camera, ms. wilson reported similar patterns in broadcast management. she said no networks had a woman heading their news division, and only nine of 51 network news vice presidents are women
local television stations also have few women in management, ms. wilson said. but she said radio stations employ women in proportion to the workforce
linda alvarez, anchor on los angeles television station knbc, said some women in television are treated as ``shadow anchors'' to a male co-anchor, are assigned to ``soft stories'' and are not allowed to age
you don't see very many female charles kuralts on television, or women who look like irving r. levine,'' said ms. alvarez, naming two veteran male newscasters
the three-day conference, which started sunday, was organized by betty friedan, author of the best-selling ``the feminine mystique'' and a visiting journalism professor at usc
an analysis of credits on 1986-87 network entertainment series found women employed more often as writers than as producers or directors, said sally steenland of wider opportunities for women. seventeen of the top 20 shows had women writers. half had women producers and six had directors
futurist alvin toffler said women have a chance to manage new media as communication becomes diversified by cable television and other outlets targeting ``micro markets'' within the mass audience
we're going to see two-tiered media,'' said toffler. mass media will cover major events, but customized media will provide information and entertainment to audiences defined by such characteristics as race, sex, interest or geographic area, he said
the conference was co-sponsored by the gannett foundation, usc's school of journalism, the institute for the study of women and men, women in film, and the times mirror corp
