republican bob dole, playing catch-up in the southern presidential primaries, attacked george bush in public and in new television commercials today as a vice president without record or accomplishment and a supporter of the arms-for-hostages deal with iran
dole's campaign began airing tough ads striking at bush in florida and north carolina, as dole escalated criticism of the vice president at appearances at duke university
that's precisely what he did _ he supported the sale of arms to iran,'' dole said when asked about the new television attack
dole, the senate minority leader, accused bush of offering ``nine different answers'' on the iran-contra affair. ``but it's a fact he did support it,'' dole said
now we're talking about credibility,'' dole said at a news conference. ``when somebody gives you nine different answers on the same question, i think it's an issue.''
trailing bush in the polls in most of the states voting next week, dole began a test-run of strong television ads in miami and other selected florida cities, dole campaign manager bill brock said
the ads, which the dole campaign produced but did not run during the new hampshire campaign, depict bush as walking through snow but leaving no footprints, brock said. he said the message was that bush ``has held all these big jobs'' yet left no mark
in north carolina, dole began airing a different ad that injected the iran-contra affair into the campaign, saying that bush ``supported arms for hostages.''
it also says bush ``waffles on taxes'' and opposes legislation limiting textile imports, a bill that dole supports and that is popular in the textile-producing carolinas. bush said in south carolina last week that he opposes the textile bill as protectionist
dole spoke to students on the campus of duke university, where his wife elizabeth attended college. while there he lashed at bush for saying repeatedly that he wants to be ``the education president.''
well he's certainly been quiet the last seven years when the administration's been whacking billions and billions of dollars out of the education budget,'' dole said. ``haven't heard one word.''
a day earlier in fort lauderdale, dole told a downtown crowd to question bush on his record. ``ask him what's he done in the last seven years,'' dole said. ``what's he done anywhere in america or the world to make a difference?''
dole, the kansas senator and senate minority leader, cited his own record in congress and raised anew his claim that bush had distorted dole's stand on tax increases in television commercials that helped bush win the new hampshire primary
dole said voters want to elect ``someone who is not out trying to distort somebody else's record when they don't have a record of their own.''
bob dole is not going to raise your taxes,'' he said. ``we don't know what george bush is going to do.''
tough'' was a word dole brandished as he flew around the south drawing comparisons with bush in advance of the big round of primaries across the region and elsewhere on super tuesday, a week away
i have a quality that some may be lacking. i am tough,'' dole said in atlanta and echoed in mississippi and florida. and for anyone missing his comparison with the vice president, dole said: ``i'm tougher.''
reacting to the crisis in panama, dole called for a full trade embargo against that country if its military strongman manuel noriega stays in power, and he urged the use of force if necessary to protect u.s. interests there, including the panama canal
dole said the reagan administration has sent mixed signals on noriega, who is accused of drug trafficking. and dole suggested the united states reconsider transferring the panama canal to that country if noriega appears able to retain power
you just ought to say no to drugs, no to noriega, and no, maybe, to giving them the canal,'' dole said
he said some u.s. officials have made conciliatory statements about noriega and ignored old evidence of drug involvement in the panamanian military
it seems to me we have one signal indicating noriega ought to stay or noriega isn't such a bad guy,'' dole said. he singled out daniel murphy, former chief of staff to vice president george bush, who he said described noriega as cooperative, and cited ``other indications they didn't know about noriega and drugs until a few weeks ago.''
strange thing,'' dole said. ``we knew about it when we were debating the panama canal treaty 10 years ago. in fact many of us talked about it on the senate floor.''
dole frequently mentioned his vote against the treaty, tranferring eventual ownership of the panama canal to panama, that was narrowly ratified 10 years ago. he said that if it appears panama's situation will go unchanged, ``we may want to go back and take another look at that canal.''
 we may not want to turn it over to panama, if they're going to be in this state,'' dole said
republican presidential candidate pat robertson said today a transcript of 1967 senate subcommittee testimony supports his belief there are nuclear missiles in cuba
the former religious broadcaster quoted testimony from two people:
_paul bethel, a state department official who said cuban refugees had told him about seeing missiles
_one of the refugees, identified only as mr. apud, who said members of the cuban military had told him about missiles aimed at washington before he left in 1966
in the 1967 judiciary subcommittee transcript, apud said he was told by cuban soldiers he had known for many years that the missiles were nicknamed ``washington left,'' ``washington right'' and ``washington central.''
the transcript also showed that bethel said in response to questioning by sen. strom thurmond, r-s.c., that numerous refugees had told him they had seen missiles left in cuba after the cuban missile crisis and new ones put in in 1964
bethel testified he could not say for sure that intermediate or intercontinental ballistic missiles were in cuba, but that the state department also couldn't be certain they weren't there
this is documented evidence,'' robertson said today at a breakfast attended by about 600 supporters
he first brought the subject up in a debate in new hampshire last month, contending there are missiles in cuba aimed at the united states
the reagan administration immediately denied it
at a news conference on monday, robertson produced a cuban refugee who he said had seen the weapons. the cuban, who spoke through an interpreter and identified himself only as e. rodriguez, said he had seen missile sites, but did not know whether the weapons had nuclear warheads
the first morning of reconstruction on the city's major highway link to the south passed without major traffic jams, police said today
so far, so good,'' state police sgt. dolores enright said of the traffic on the dan ryan expressway, one of the nation's busiest highways
most commuters apparently heeded warnings about potential traffic problems and took other routes or public transportation
the project will widen the dan ryan from four lanes each way to five
during 6{ months of construction on southbound lanes this year, all traffic will share four lanes. the northbound lanes will be out of commission next year during the project's second phase
some motorists had planned novel ways to cope with massive traffic jams they had expected
julie coenen said bought tape-recorded ``talking books,'' such as james michener's ``texas,'' to listen to while she sits in traffic
i think it's going to be like a huge, huge parking lot,'' says ms. coenen, who lives in northwest suburban elk grove village and uses the dan ryan expressway to commute to her job as a health educator at michael reese medical center on the city's south side
i have visions of people taking folding chairs and tables and playing cards.''
i think it's going to be a real bad nightmare,'' says norma hill, 35, a hospital secretary who commutes from her home in south suburban evergreen park to her job in south chicago
the dan ryan expressway, an 11-mile stretch of concrete and asphalt, is the main link between chicago and points south. traffic from at least six other expressways feeds the dan ryan just south of downtown chicago
state officials say the $210 million rebuilding job will be the largest highway project in illinois history
the road is simply wearing out from old age and the pounding it has taken from traffic, particularly trucks,'' says dick adorjan, a spokesman for the illinois department of transportation
the state plans to close all four southbound lanes from march 13 to october 31, rerouting southbound traffic onto two of the four northbound lanes. the process will be reversed in the spring of 1989
the work began today with the closing of several lanes on each side of the freeway for a week to build traffic crossovers and patch the northbound side
as the project began, a psychiatrist recommended deep breaths, exercise or conversation as tension easers for stalled commuters
drivers who are mentally prepared to face these difficulties can reduce the stress,'' says dr. richard glass, associate psychiatry professor and director of adult outpatient services at the university of chicago medical center
he said drivers could also use their stall time to learn a foreign language from taped lessons or dictate letters into a tape recorder
the supreme court, making it easier to deport some aliens, today blocked further hearings for a california man seeking to avoid return to his native ghana
the court ruled 8-0 that immigration officials, having decided an alien should be deported, generally are under no duty to reconsider the case when the alien says he has new evidence to support a bid for asylum
the decision is a defeat for dr. assibi l. abudu, a native and citizen of ghana who graduated from the university of southern california medical school and married a u.s. citizen
immigration officials moved to deport him in 1981 after he was convicted in california of illegally attempting to obtain the narcotic drug demerol by fraud. he was given a one-year suspended prison sentence and was placed on probation for three years
the immigration and naturalization service found him deportable and the board of immigration appeals upheld that decision
abudu sought to reopen his case in 1985 and seek asylum in the united states from the military dictatorship of flight lieutenant jerry rawlings, who regained power in ghana in a dec. 31, 1981, military coup
abudu said he had new evidence that his life might be in danger if he was forced to return to ghana based on a 1984 visit to him by abukari alhassan, secretary of housing and construction in the rawlings regime
abudu said he believed alhassan was trying to lure him back to ghana so officials there could torture him to extract information about opponents of the rawlings regime
abudu said his brother escaped capture by the regime and fled into hiding and also said his lifelong friend, lt. col. joshua hamidu, is regarded as the number one enemy of the rawlings government
the board of immigration appeals refused to reopen abudu's case, noting that abudu did not initially seek asylum when he contested his deportation
but the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals in 1986 ordered the board to reconsider granting abudu asylum
the supreme court today agreed with the reagan administration that the appeals court should have deferred to the decision of the immigration board
justice john paul stevens, writing for the court, said aliens seeking to reopen their deportation cases have the difficult task of proving that immigration officials abused their discretion in refusing to do so
there is a strong public interest in bringing litigation to a close as promptly as is consistent with the interest in giving the adversaries a fair opportunity to develop and present their respective cases,'' stevens said
we have no hesitation in concluding that the board of immigration appeals did not abuse its discretion when it held that abudu had not reasonably explained his failure to apply for asylum prior to the completion of the initial deportation proceeding,'' he said
justice anthony m. kennedy, who only recently joined the court, did not take part in the decision
the case is ins vs. abudu, 86-1128. obstetricians. officials, who released incorrect figure, said 55 percent were sued at least twice, sted at least three times.</note>
a survey released today says that the threat of malpractice suits caused 12 percent of obstetricians to close their practices last year and that two-thirds leave the field before age 55
the survey, conducted in october and november for the american college of obstetricians and gynecologists, showed that the national rate for physicians dropping obstetrics has remained at 12 percent for the last two years, but that the age of those quitting is getting younger
if this trend continues, we are going to see more and more physicians leaving obstetrics at the height of their professional ability,'' said dr. jimmie gleason, chairman of the doctors' committee on professional liability. ``we are looking at a situation where obstetrics is being concentrated more and more in large urban and suburban areas.''
in florida, the number of doctors no longer delivering babies has reached 25 percent, about twice the national average, and 75 percent of those quitting in florida are doing so before the age 55, also far above the national average
malpractice insurance premiums for obstetricians in florida and new york now average about $52,000 a year, the survey shows. the national average has risen from $10,946 in 1982 to $37,015 in 1987, according to the report
gleason said the survey revealed ``several disturbing trends'' in the care of high-risk pregnancies
twenty-seven of the surveyed doctors said they were limiting the number of high-risk cases they will take, compared to 23 percent in 1985, and 18 percent in 1982
the survey showed that seven out of 10 obstetrician-gynecologists nationally have been sued at some point in their career. in new york, 55 percent of the practicioners have been sued two or more times
fifty-two percent of the suits involved obstetric cases, with 31 percent of these cases for claims of neurologically-impaired infants, and 15 percent for claims of stillbirths or infant deaths, the survey showed
of the claims resolved, 36 percent were dropped without payment. of those not dropped, 79 percent were settled with payment
the survey showed that obstetrician-gynecologists had a mean gross income in 1986 of $296,133, with the highest gross in new york, with $387,022, and in florida, with $323,252. the mean gross income increased by $81,122 from 1984 to 1986, the survey showed
the average medical practice overhead reported was $147,029, with the average for florida at $190,882
opinion research corp. of princeton, n.j. conducted the survey for the american college of obstetricians and gynecologists. controls gulf area</head> not participate.</note>
the supreme court today declined to decide yet whether the state or the federal government should control a gulf of mexico area off mississippi's southwestern coastline
rejecting arguments by the state's lawyers, the court ruled 7-0 that more information is needed before such a determination is made
mississippi had sought a ruling that its southwestern coastline extends beyond several barrier islands and into chandeleur sound, south of the mississippi sound
control of an area of about 150 square miles of the gulf, along with control of the natural resources there, remains in dispute
the case acted on today has, in varying forms, been before the high court since 1956, when the justices first invoked their ``original jurisdiction'' to hear the controversy before it had been aired in any lower court
in such cases, the supreme court functions as a trial court and acts on the recommendations of a court-appointed ``special master.'' in this case, retired judge walter p. armstrong jr. is serving as the special master
he recommended that mississippi's pressing for a ruling that gives it control of the disputed gulf area should be ruled premature
writing for the court today, justice harry a. blackmun agreed
he said mississippi's arguments ``are overruled but without prejudice to the advancement of such claims as any party might have with respect to the area south of mississippi sound in the vicinity of chandeleur sound in an appropriate separate chapter of these proceedings.''
the mississippi sound is a body of water between the state's mainland and a line of barrier islands several miles offshore
in 1985, the justices ruled that alabama and mississippi _ and not the federal government _ own their respective portions of the sound's bed and therefore control the natural resources there
blackmun said the high court would retain jurisdiction in the case, raising the likelihood that still another ruling on the issue is in the court's future
justices thurgood marshall and anthony m. kennedy did not participate in the decision
the case is alabama and mississippi boundardy case, 9 original
a ``puff'' of tritium escaped from the department of energy's savannah river plant today, but posed no hazard to the public, officials said
spokesman jim felder said about 20,000 curies of tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen, were released at 6:18 a.m. this morning during routine operations
felder characterized the release as ``a puff'' and said it lasted less than a minute
the weapons production facility at the plant makes material used in the production of nuclear weapons, and felder said details on the process under way when the release occurred are classified
the exposure at the plant boundary, about six miles from the h chemical separations area where the release occurred, was about 0.04 millirems, felder said. by comparison, he said a normal chest x-ray is 20 millirems
two employees in the work area at the time of the release were undergoing tests to see if they suffered any ill effects. they were wearing full protective gear at the time, he said
all plant operations have returned to normal, he said
felder said an initial assessment of the cause of the release indicates equipmment malfunction. however, an investigation will be conducted
the last such release at the plant occurred july 31, 1987, when a dosage of .2 millirems was measured at the plant's boundary
the plant's reactors were reduced to half power last year amid concerns over the cooling system, and department of energy officials told a u.s. senate subcommittee in washington on monday that the reactors could be running at full capacity by 1990
felder said this morning the process in which the tritium was released is separate from that involving the reactors and would not affect the reactor plans. pvs ``at the outset...; delete final 3 grafs to tighten</note>
how does a presidential candidate campaign for 20 far-flung contests held on the same day? the answer is television
the primaries and caucuses of march 8, super tuesday, are being held in states and territories from florida to washington, an unprecedented sweep across more than 150 media markets with more than 500 television stations
television is as critical on the vast super tuesday battleground as grass-roots organizing was in iowa and new hampshire
kansas sen. bob dole fired an opening salvo, starting a test-run of tough television ads in florida and north carolina
the florida ad, which the dole campaign produced but did not run during the new hampshire campaign, depicts vice president george bush walking through snow but leaving no footprints. the message, said dole campaign manager bill brock, was that bush ``has held all these big jobs'' yet left no mark
the other dole ad, running in north carolina, injects the iran-contra affair into the campaign. it says bush ``supported arms for hostages,'' ``waffles on taxes'' and opposes legislation limiting textile imports, a bill dole supports and that is popular in the textile-producing carolinas. bush said in south carolina last week that he opposes the textile bill as protectionist
rep. richard gephardt also was taking the offensive with two critical ads. one featured rep. marvin leath of texas criticizing gephardt rivals michael dukakis and albert gore jr. the other was a retooled version of an ad that was considered a key factor in gephardt's victory over dukakis last week in south dakota
at the outset of his campaign, dukakis mentioned belgian endive, a kind of yuppie lettuce, as an example of how iowa farmers could diversify their crops. the gephardt ad criticizes the massachusetts governor's positions on trade and farm issues, and ends with a voice saying sarcastically: ``belgian endive?''
many observers said dukakis made a major error in not responding with an ad of his own _ a situation that won't be repeated. dukakis aide leslie dach said the dukakis campaign had prepared a negative ad about gephardt and would use it soon, possibly starting today, in super tuesday states
gephardt has also revived an ad that was seen as having a big impact in iowa _ in which he criticizes south korea for stifling u.s. auto sales in that nation with stiff tariffs, and threatens to respond in kind. see how many hyundais the koreans can sell here at $48,000 apiece, he tells viewers
and gephardt has a commercial featuring the popular rep. claude pepper, a democrat who has ample clout with senior citizens. pepper is from florida, the second-biggest super tuesday state
dukakis has ads featuring fellow massachusetts politician tip o'neill, the former house speaker, and has been running a biographical spot in which he stresses his economic accomplishments as governor
dukakis has mounted particularly strong efforts in four states with pockets of ethnic or liberal voters: florida, texas, north carolina and georgia
gephardt and dole have focused on the border states that lie near their respective homes of missouri and kansas
tennessee sen. albert gore jr., who bypassed early contests to stress the super tuesday states, took out a loan monday to pay for a media blitz, a campaign spokesman said
we're going to saturate super tuesday. ... we want to pour it on,'' said press spokesman mike kopp
gore's state campaign treasurer in tennessee, johnny hayes, said gore had taken a $1 million line of credit against which money would be borrowed for a 20-state advertising campaign. kopp said new gore commercials would go on the air today
gore has already made national cable television buys and purchases of time on individual stations in most of the super tuesday states
bush was first on the air in texas, where he once lived. he has been running a biographical ad. republican rival rep. jack kemp has concentrated his advertising money in seven super tuesday states, said his political director, charles black
rarely are the candidates engaging in the small-scale, ``retail'' campaigning of the early contests _ visiting diners, plant gates and firehouses, taking door-to-door strolls down residential streets. when they do, it's mostly for the benefit of television cameras
it's too vast a primary to even bother, other than for media events,'' said larry sabato, a political media expert at the university of virginia. ``it's a wholesale day. the candidates have to rely heavily on their strategic consultants and media consultants.''
a well-heeled candidate could spend upwards of $2 million blanketing the territory with tv commercials, radio spots and satellite feeds. the trick is to spend shrewdly as well as heavily
it's a matter of consultants sitting down with polling data and census data and deciding where you have your best bet,'' said bob lichter, a media analyst and co-director of the center for media and public affairs. ``it's applied science meets gut political instinct.''
the typical super tuesday technique calls for finding targets within states, such as individual congressional districts, and keeping mum about where they are
strong waves off puerto rico's west coast hampered a search today for possible survivors of a small craft carrying illegal aliens from the dominican republic to this u.s. commonwealth, police said
police maj. cesar gracia said two bodies were found monday and a third has been spotted floating at sea. one survivor was hospitalized monday
authorities and a survivor said the majority of the 45 people aboard the craft made it to shore safely
the boat, estimated at 20 to 30 feet long, sank sunday night near the small fishing village of aguada, about 85 miles west of the capital san juan, the landing site for many boats bringing illegal aliens to the united states in recent years. the exact number of illegals making the trip during that period is unknown
according to gracia, the dominican residents boarded the craft on the east coast of dominican republic on saturday night, when the weather was clear. as they neared puero rico, the boat was overturned by large waves about 180 feet from shore. specific churches and groups; picks up 7th graf pvs: another section...</note>
the government intensified its crackdown on apartheid opponents today by introducing a bill that would outlaw foreign funding of political activity
the legislation, expected to be adopted during parliament's current session, could cripple the operations of anti-apartheid organizations and churches spared during last week's crackdown on major black opposition groups
eighteen groups, including the largest anti-apartheid coalition and largest labor federation, were barred from political activity
the new legislation, called ``the promotion of orderly politics bill,'' would prohibit all organizations from receiving money from abroad for political purposes. many anti-apartheid, human rights and religious groups receive the bulk of their funds from overseas
the bill would empower the justice minister to declare certain organizations ``restricted'' and to take control of foreign funds sent to them
money which is deemed to be earmarked for undesirable political activities will ``either be returned to the foreign source or dealt with as determined by the minister,'' the bill says. no court challenge of the restrictions would be allowed
the funding restrictions could be applied to politically related activities of anti-apartheid church organizations, which have vowed to step up protests because of bans on other groups
the south african council of churches, which includes most major protestant denominations and is deeply engaged in civil rights work, has received more than 90 percent of its funds from abroad in recent years
the roman catholic church, which cooperates with the council of churches but receives funds separately, also relies heavily on overseas financing
the rev. smangiliso mkhatshwa, secretary-general of the southern african catholic bishops conference, said the bill might prove difficult to enforce
if the church says supporting the families of detainees and paying legal fees is the work of love, the work of evangelism, it is dificult to see how the government can define for the church what it pastoral and what is political,'' he said
another section of the bill sets a penalty of two years in jail or a $2,000 fine for anyone who ``says or does anything'' to foment hostility or violence between of different racial, cultural or religious groups. the penalties would apply to anyone who displays any banner, emblem or slogan deemed to convey such hostility, and also to anyone who attends a gathering where such items are displayed
helen suzman, veteran parliament member of the anti-apartheid progressive federal party, said she planned to demand a special debate today on the arrests of prominent clergymen who were protesting the government crackdown
about 25 church leaders, including anglican archbishop desmond tutu, and more than 100 other protesters were detained briefly monday after riot policeman blocked them from marching to parliament with a petition protesting the bans on opposition groups
one of the arrested churchmen, roman catholic archbishop stephen naidoo, said in an interview today that he and his colleagues considered it their duty to continue challenging the government
the church has got to take a stand on the morality of the use of political power,'' he said. ``if it being used by a minority for the protection of the minority and the oppression of the majority, then the church has got to point this out.''
in another development, government officials warned the country's largest conglomerate, the anglo american corp., that they would not tolerate its announced plan to defy the group areas act _ the law that establishes racially segregated living areas
apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the nation's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
an executive in anglo's property division, graham lindrop, recently described the act as a sham and said his company was prepared to negotiate leases directly with black tenants renting apartments in the ``white'' johannesburg neighborhood of hillbrow
currently, most of the thousands of blacks living illegally in hillbrow are forced to have their leases signed by a third party and are vulnerable to exploitation and threats from their landlords
the government has indicated it might allow hillbrow and a few other areas to become integrated, but it says violations of the group areas act will not be tolerated in the meantime
the act still stands until changes are approved by parliament, piet badenhorst, a deputy cabinet minister, said monday. ``there will be prosecutions.''
anglo american's stance was praised by foes of the group areas act and denounced as civil disobedience by the extreme-right conservative party
a former philadelphia common pleas judge who presided over what prosecutors called a ``cesspool of corruption'' was sentenced today to 12 years in a federal prison and fined $10,000
the former judge, kenneth harris, was permanently removed from the bench last week by order of the pennsylvania supreme court
harris had been found guilty on jan. 26 of racketeering, extortion and conspiracy for soliciting $5,800 in payoffs from defendants, their relatives or lawyers in 14 criminal cases. he faced a maximum sentence of 120 years in prison and a $1.5 million fine
harris' lawyers pleaded for leniency because he has diabetes and other ailments
i was hoping the sentence would be shorter. but because of the parole guidelines as i understand them, he would be eligible within 24 or 36 months. so, i'm not that unhappy,'' said defense attorney samuel stretton
u.s. attorney edward dennis had indicated harris would have to serve at least a third of his sentence before he could be freed
a federal jury convicted the 67-year-old harris on jan. 26 of running a case-fixing operation out of his city hall courtroom
still to be sentenced are two co-defendants, former federal and local prosecutor romaine g. phillips, and harris associate matthias ``big sonny'' brown, were convicted of conspiring in the case-fixing scheme. the maximum sentence for that crime is 20 years in prison and a $250,000 fine
a key part of the government's case against harris was secretly recorded video and audio tapes that recorded case-fixing in harris' robing room in city hall
only one major issue still separates northwest airlines and its flight attendants, who continued working as usual today even though their strike deadline passed last week, company and union officials say
another union official said there was a possibility that northwest could be faced with simultaneous strikes by the flight attendants and ground workers
a federal mediator is scheduled to hold talks between the company and district lodge 143 of the international association of machinists a week from today, said guy cook, president of that union
if those talks break down and the mechanics declare a strike deadline, the flight attendants, represented by the teamsters, could invoke their own walkout, cook said
but cook said he does not know how long the flight attendants can maintain their right to strike or how long it will take for the mechanics to set a strike deadline in accordance with labor laws
i think that's the game that is going on right now,'' said chuck davis, a labor expert at the university of minnesota. ``if the machinists are going to begin negotiations, it may be to (the flight attendants') advantage to work without a new contract until the machinists take a position
the more coordination that goes on, the larger the numbers, the more strength they have in dealing with northwest.''
there are about 6,700 union flight attendants and about 20,000 mechanics, baggage handlers and other ground workers at northwest
talks between northwest and teamsters officials broke off at dawn saturday after an all-night negotiating session. a strike deadline of 11:01 p.m. friday passed without a strike and no job actions have been taken against the company, said company spokesman william wren
wren and teamsters spokesman jeff musto said monday that there is only one major sticking point in the talks: a company proposal to delay the promotion of workers on a lower b-scale pay schedule to the higher-paid a-scale bracket
all new employees hired since a 1982 contract have started as b-scale employees at pay rates lower than the previous system, musto said
the 1982 contract called for b-scale employees to jump to a-scale levels in their sixth year of employment, but the company has proposed extending that wait until the ninth year, musto said
wren said a large number of senior flight attendants make more than $40,000 a year, plus meal payments when they're working. most entry-level flight attendants are making about $15,000 a year, he said
about a third of the company's flight attendants are at the b-scale level, musto said
the posh fontainebleau hilton hotel is not liable for the garrote death of a nevada mortgage banker who was killed there five years ago, a jury has found
john masegian's body was found by a hotel worker in a stairwell with a 32-inch nylon cord with wooden knobs wrapped around his neck
his widow sued, contending the death could have been prevented if hotel security was better. defense lawyers told jurors the death was a contract killing that took place in masegian's room and that the body was dragged to the stairwell
this crime was not foreseeable, nor was it preventable,'' hotel lawyer leland stansell jr. argued
jurors deliberated about 2{ hours monday before deciding the hotel shouldn't be liable for someone murdered in his room, jury foreman nora langford said
the incident would have had to happen outside the room,'' she said
widow carol masegian, 43, had sought more than $1 million for herself and for five of the victim's five children from a previous marriage
police initially treated mrs. masegian as a suspect after uncovering a mysterious telephone message she received at the hotel the day before the killing. however, she was never charged
during the trial, defense attorneys portrayed her as a woman with much to gain from the death of her wealthy husband, who planned to divorce her and leave her with nothing
because of her husband's death, mrs. masegian receives $857 a month from her husband's worker's compensation benefits and $140,000 from his estate. graf pvs, from georgia</note>
a week before southern voters assert themselves in the 1988 presidential campaign, rep. richard gephardt paid a call today on former president carter and said, ``i come here today not to enhance my prospects but to greet an old friend.''
carter made it clear that with fellow georgian sam nunn not in the race he had no plans to endorse any of the democratic presidential candidates before the nominating convention next july
on one of gephardt's major issues, the former president also said that he could accept the congressman's trade legislation ``if the president has the authority to moderate any sort of protectionist trends.''
asked about carter's less than ringing endorsement of a proposal that has been a centerpiece of his presidential campaign, the gephardt said that he and carter ``shared the view we've got to create a better more open world trade.''
standing on the front walk in front of his brick home in this small town that he put on the map, carter said he thought there was a 50-50 chance that no one will have clinched the presidential nomination before the convention
my hope is that out of the primary and caucus season will come a clear winner,'' he said. ``i'm not sure that's a likelihood now.''
the former president said he would attend the convention as a delegate and that if there was a deadlock ``i would not personally favor turning to someone outside the active candidate group for the nomination.''
carter said he has met with all of the active candidates
from georgia, gephardt was flying to columbia, s.c., to pick up the endorsement of former govs. richard riley and robert mcnair
as the campaign entered the final week before super tuesday on march 8, the day 20 states, most of them in the south, hold primaries and caucuses, gephardt started running a new television commercial throughout the region
the ad takes on sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee and gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts
in it, rep. marvin leath of texas says gephardt ``stood with us for lower taxes, for an oil import fee to make america strong, for a tough trade bill to stand up for american workers.''
on all these issues, gore and dukakis were opposed to us. gore and dukakis even think the gephardt trade bill is too tough on the japanese, europeans and koreans. we're tired of hearing that you can't fight for america anymore. that's why 35 southern congressman are fighting for dick gephardt for president.''
gephardt won favorable comment from several fellow democrats attending a meeting of the democratic leadership council the past two days in williamsburg, va
gephardt is the only candidate who is running a message campaign,'' said sen. bob graham of florida. ``so he has the benefit of operating almost in a vacuum.''
graham said he thought super tuesday would play a major role in determining whether gephardt or gore survives in the presidential race
bill carrick, gephardt's campaign manager, said,``i don't think it's going to be that definitive.''
carrick said the gephardt campaign would spend $1 million on television advertising during the week before super tuesday, most of it in florida and texas, the two biggest states voting on march 8
carrick described riley, who was governor of south carolina from 1977 to 1985, as a leader of the progressive wing of the democratic party in the state
he said mcnair, who was governor from 1965 to 1971, was a leader of the ore conservative wing of the party
he said their dual backing was ``a nice little bookend endorsement.'' turtles</head>
a federal judge today cleared the way for enforcement of a federal regulation intended to save endangered sea turtles by throwing out a suit filed by shrimpers who say the rule will ruin their business
shrimpers said they would defy the regulation, which goes into effect today
u.s. district judge patrick carr brushed aside vehement arguments from shrimpers battling the requirement that they use bulky traps called turtle excluder devices, commonly called teds, which are intended to eject trapped turtles from nets
i don't care if he upheld it. it's a bad law, and the shrimpers ain't going to live by it,'' said tee john mialjevich of concerned shrimpers of louisiana, which filed suit against the law
critics say the devices don't always work and that they allow shrimp to escape. mialjevich said shrimpers in florida, where the law has been in effect since jan. 1, experienced reductions of 35 percent to 50 percent of their catches
the law was also scheduled to go into effect off the coast of texas today
shrimpers had argued that there was not enough evidence to show that the teds would be effective in protecting the endangered turtles
a review of the administrative record demonstrates that (shrimpers') arguments are unfounded in most aspects,'' carr wrote. ``from the outset, the secretary (of commerce) through the national marine fisheries service collected scientific information from sea turtle experts from states, universities and the private sector.''
carr had said in advance that his ruling would not determine the usefulness or effectiveness of the controversial devices, but would address only whether the government had followed proper procedures when it imposed the legislation
the outcry against the teds spread even to the state legislature, where a law was passed forbidding state officials from enforcing the new regulations
the state attorney general's office had joined the shrimpers' suit, but carr dismissed the state from the case, saying the shrimpers were capable of speaking for themselves
state officials were not sure how they would act
corky perret, assistant secretary of wildlife and fisheries, said his department is caught in a ``catch-22'' situation between state and federal law
until i get some legal, firm position to sit on, i guess i'm up in the air,'' perret said
senators lawton chiles, d-fla., and pete wilson, r-calif., called on president reagan today to strictly penalize latin american countries that fail to cooperate with the united states in its effort to combat drug trafficking
chiles, wilson and rep. charles b. rangel, d-n.y., told the white house conference for a drug free america the reagan administration must decide the national security interest of the united states before being concerned about latin america, particularly panama, mexico and columbia
reagan was to officially announce that panama has failed to cooperate with the united states, but will not impose forceful sanctions in an effort to force the ouster of central american country's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega
the president also was to reject calls to decertify mexico and colombia, which have been criticized heavily for failing to cut the flow of drugs to this country
chiles said many members of congress believe the certification process has not been used properly by the reagan administration
under the 1986 law, the u.s. is to decertify and cut off aid to countries ``not fully cooperating'' with the united states to combat drug traffic.
this year, the good news is that panama is on the list,'' said chiles. ``on the other hand, mexico and colombia aren't. we'll have to examine why mexico is certified. colombia is a country under siege and we will have to examine that. we have to ask ourselves what is the national interest. i think we have to continue to apply pressure against these countries.''
he said the law will be changed next year to require a bilateral agreement between the united states and latin american nations ``so that there will be a country-by-country certification, rather than one list including all of them. we will tell them in advance what we expect of them and we will be able to grade them on how they do. that will be more helpful to this country.''
wilson was particularly upset that the administration did not decertify mexico, a country that borders on his state of california
how can we delude ourselves into thinking that mexico should be certified,'' he said. ``they should not. they have not cooperated fully with the united states. if we are going to send young drug agents into mexico, we should demand full cooperation and not wink at it. the 1986 act spelled out what is to be expected, and it has not been done.''
chiles and wilson both said the president relies too heavily on the state department for the basis of his certification of a country. ``state is willing to be too tolerant in this area,'' said wilson
rangel, chairman of the house select committee on narcotics abuse and control, said the u.s. felt for years that colombia was the primary cause of concern for the nation's drug problem but now ``it seems that we have an entire hemisphere to worry about. the so-called spread of communist influence is the least of our worries in this region at this point in time.''
vermont's ``beauty contest'' primary today has been largely overshadowed by preparations for next week's delegate-heavy super tuesday primaries, political observers say
republican george bush and democrat michael dukakis _ who won the maine caucuses over the weekend _ were considered the front-runners here, continuing to play on their ties to the region. bush, a connecticut native, has a summer home in maine; dukakis is the governor of massachusetts
vermont secretary of state james douglas predicted a record turnout of 125,000 voters. several communities reported strong voting today under sunny skies, but turnout in the state's largest city, burlington, was running behind four years ago
some had predicted that the vermont primary _ falling between the new hampshire primary and super tuesday, march 8 _ would take on more importance this year. but the primary has attracted little attention
i think what we're seeing is we're getting jumped by super tuesday,'' said craig fuller, executive director of the vermont democratic party
vermont just got lost in the shuffle,'' said garrison nelson, a political science professor at the university of vermont. ``those timing factors when combined with the fact the vermont primary is a beauty contest ... led to an incredible loss of interest.''
tuesday's voting does not choose delegates; vermonters merely state their preferences in the non-binding primary. delegates to the national conventions will be elected at state conventions, a process that begins in april with local caucuses to elect delegates to the state convention
the candidates sent a lot of surrogates to stump for them, but made few personal appearances
we got to see very little of the candidates. we saw their mothers, their wives, their children, but we didn't see much of them,'' nelson said
spokesmen for the candidates say attention now is on winning delegates in local caucuses
that's our focus, that's where our energy is going even now,'' said chris wood, a campaign coordinator for jesse jackson, who scored a surprisingly strong second in the weekend maine democratic caucuses
i think there's a recognition that the (vermont) primary is the beginning of building for the caucus,'' said marilyn yager of the dukakis campaign
but yager maintains vermont probably gets more attention from candidates than some of the 20 individual super tuesday states
no single state gets a lot of one-on-one attention,'' she said
although non-binding, the vermont primary has served an important purpose in past years
in 1980, former president jimmy carter used a win in vermont to embarrass sen. ted kennedy, d-mass., in his own back yard. the same year, a strong second-place finish in vermont gave republican john anderson's campaign a major boost
in 1984, gary hart's overwhelming defeat of walter mondale in vermont helped him shed his image as a dark horse
apparel manufacturing is mississippi's leader in employment. besides that, furniture building is centered in the tupelo area, and catfish processing employs people in the delta
since the 1960s, manufacturing has employed more people than farming in this state where 70 percent of the people live outside urban areas _ and yet in some recent years the leading source of income in mississippi was neither. it was government ``transfer payments'' _ aid to families with dependent children, social security, food stamps
as the economy becomes more automated, more geared toward people with skills,'' pepper said, ``you're going to see more people left out.''
asked the solution, he quoted mississippi's new governor, ray mabus: ``education, education, education.''
without that, high-technology companies will continue to stay away, agreed jane jackson, a lawyer working for the mississippi house of representatives. ``you've got to get them (students) enough math and english so that the vo-tech can teach them to work for a sony.''
in rural areas nationally, 18 percent of people fall below the poverty level, about $11,200 for a family of four, according to 1986 census bureau figures. that's the same rate as in inner-cities
i don't think the people who are masterminding this economy are paying attention to this,'' said john zippert of the federation of southern cooperatives, a group based in alabama that helps family farmers hold onto their land
it's a little like the underclass question of the urban ghetto _ that there's going to be a permanent class that's going to be left behind.''
left behind is a fitting description
in one year, rural areas across the country lost 632,000 people to metro areas due to migration,'' leahy, d-vt., has said. ``that's like saying that all of north dakota migrated in one year.'' those who leave tend to be the best educated, say officials, lamenting the rural ``brain drain.''
it's not that nothing is being done to address the rural-urban economic restructuring that jesse white of the southern growth policies board has termed ``just as profound as what was happening in the rustbelt.'' but many observers of the rural poor say the efforts of government are piecemeal and inadequate
federal funding for a variety of rural development programs added up to about $1.6 billion last year, according to a study just completed by the center for community change, a research and advocacy group in washington, d.c. those programs included grant and loan programs of the department of housing and urban development _ from which tchula received its grant _ and the agriculture, commerce and other departments
the funding levels have shrunk radically from what they were at the end of the carter administration,'' said norm deweaver, who led the study
the reagan administration's policy has been to decentralize efforts to aid rural development, noted the economic research organization mdc inc., of chapel hill, n.c., in a report last month
the federal government now dictates fewer rules and provides fewer dollars. as a result,'' said mdc, ``... there is a surge of economic and social initiatives in state governments throughout the country.''
besides a new emphasis on improving education in virtually all southern states, initiatives cited by mdc included: a bank in arkansas that focuses mainly on rural economic development; innovative literacy projects in kentucky; and a biracial group in struggling noxubee county, miss., that promotes home-grown businesses
nonetheless, the study cited ``many more dark rural places still lacking the resources, the information, and the encouragement'' to make significant economic progress, and it called for more carefully targeted federal and private-sector help in giving isolated places access to capital and management assistance, education and training
just outside of tchula, the members of the mileston co-op know what a little outside help can mean
sitting in the spare country store that the co-op of black farmers has owned for 40 years, willie lacy, the acting president, talked about the donation they received from farmaid, the charity fund created by country musicians
some of the members, whose cotton farms average about 50 acres, used the money to pay delinquent taxes or overdue rent on land or old fertilizer bills
i can remember one fella,'' lacy said, ``he had everything, but he couldn't get diesel _ so that helped him.''
in the store, the afternoon gathering place now a month before planting time, the co-op members say they could use a different kind of outside help
they'd like to restart their cotton gin, which closed a few years ago because of drought-stricken crops and lack of money _ and they'd like to diversify, maybe open a plant that would process, package and freeze vegetables grown in their fields
a plant like that would employ some of the workers displaced by planting and picking machines. first, though, they'd need the expertise to help ensure profitability, and second, the start-up investment
the idea is not to get rich, the men said, but to employ people and give the next generation a chance to stay here
i realize it wouldn't cure the problem,'' lacy said, ``but that would help some.''
lower prices for lettuce, tomatoes, cotton and milk helped pushed down the agriculture department's index of farm-level commodity prices in february
the price index declined 0.8 percent from january but still averaged 6.6 percent above a year earlier, the department's agricultural statistics board said monday
higher prices for cattle, hogs, corn and soybeans helped soften the declines for the other commodities, however
most commercial vegetable prices dropped sharply from a month earlier as supplies became plentiful,'' the report said. ``warm weather in the southwest pushed vegetable crops to maturity.''
but cattle and calf prices ``were the highest since may 1979'' and hog prices rose for the second month in a row, the report said. corn prices at the farm were the highest since july 1986, while soybeans were the highest in more than three years
department economists say net cash income of farmers set a record in 1987 of about $57 billion. this year's net _ the difference between cash receipts and cash expenses _ may be in the range of $50 billion to $55 billion
consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987
according to the preliminary february figures, based mostly on mid-month averages, the index for crop prices was down 4.3 percent from january but averaged 11 percent more than a year ago
commercial vegetable prices dropped 33 percent from january and were down 2.2 percent from february 1987. sweet-corn prices rose from january, while all other vegetables declined. lettuce prices dropped to $11.90 per 100 pounds from $35.60 in january
feed grains and hay, collectively, showed a 3.2 percent price gain from january, averaging 23 percent more than a year earlier. corn, sorghum, oats and hay were up, while barley prices declined from january levels. cotton prices were down 6 percent from january but averaged 22 percent more than a year earlier
the index for livestock and livestock products was up 2 percent from january and 4.2 percent above februrary 1987. prices were higher for beef cattle, calves and hogs, which more than offset declines in milk, poultry and egg prices
prices of beef cattle averaged $67.90 per hundredweight, up $2.50 from january. calf prices, at $93.10, were up $4.90 per hundredweight. market hog prices rose $3.60 from january to $47.50 in february but were still below a year earlier
february farm commodity prices averaged 130 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures, down from a revised january reading of 131 percent. a year ago, the february index was 122 percent
no new figures for farm production costs were included in the report. those have been confined to quarterly averages because of budget cutbacks
in january, however, farm expenses were up 0.6 percent from last fall but averaged 1.4 percent below a year earlier. the next quarterly figures will be reported in april
the report said:
_ cattle averaged $67.90 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up from $65.40 in january and the $58.80 reported for february 1987. those are averages for all types of cattle sold as beef
_ hogs averaged $46.70 per 100 pounds, compared with $43 in january and $48.20 a year earlier
_ corn, at $1.83 a bushel, was up from $1.77 in january and the average of $1.42 per bushel a year earlier
_ wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures, averaged $2.83 per bushel, compared with $2.75 in january and $2.58 a year earlier
_ rice averaged $7.85 per 100 pounds, compared with $7.70 in january and $3.83 a year earlier
_ soybeans were $5.90 per bushel, compared with $5.73 in january and $4.69 a year earlier
_ upland cotton was reported at 57.1 cents per pound, compared with 60.6 in january and 46.4 cents in february 1987
_ milk was $12.30 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.50 in january and $12.90 a year earlier
the agriculture department is making some progress but still lags in expanding jobs and services to black americans, according to a panel's report
in 1986, agriculture secretary richard e. lyng directed all agencies in the department to carry out new guidelines to improve usda compliance with civil rights and equal opportunity standards
as part of the department's february observance of black history month, five study groups looked at how usda has performed since then
black employees continue a modest but upward movement in all occupational categories,'' the report said monday. ``some increases have been realized both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of total usda employment. this is especially important because the increases have occurred at a time when overall employment in usda was declining.''
the usda employs the equivalent of approximately 102,000 full-time employees, according to recent budget documents. the task force report said blacks comprise 8.4 percent of the department's employees, up from 8.1 percent in 1986. but that ``is low compared with other federal agencies,'' it added
to continue to improve its equal opportunity posture, usda must realize larger increases in the number of blacks hired, promoted and trained,'' the report said. ``and such increases must be realized at a faster pace. additionally the department must place emphasis on retention strategies once black employees are recruited and hired.''
the task force report said there are ``encouraging signs'' that usda agencies are beginning to address the complex problems of black farmers and their declining numbers
coordinated efforts between the soil conservation service, farmers home administration and extension service are just beginning to show limited success at eliminating the historical factors militating against small and economically disadvantaged farmers,'' the report said. comment from voa director. picks up 3rd graf pvs ``there have been..''</note>
the foreign ministry has lodged a protest with the u.s. embassy over the ``subversive thrust'' of voice of america broadcasts on nationalist unrest in the baltic republics, tass reported
the official news agency charged monday that voa reports beamed into the soviet union ``have been crudely distorting historical facts, making provocative insinuations about the growth of nationalist sentiment in the baltic republics of the soviet union and expressing u.s. support for forces that do not accept the social system in this country.''
in washington, voa director richard w. carlson said today:
the soviet charges are false. we are covering stories about nationality problems in the baltics and elsewhere in the ussr fairly and honestly. we have tens of millions of listeners in the ussr and the soviet authorities don't want them to hear the message so they attack the messenger. the complaints are unfounded and we'll just keep doing our job.''
there have been a number of nationalist demonstrations in recent months in the once-independent republics of latvia, lithuania and estonia on the baltic sea
tass said the u.s. government-operated radio has taken a ``dramatically increased subversive thrust'' in reporting on the situation in the baltic region
the news agency said the protest was made to the u.s. embassy in moscow
the soviets last may stopped routine jamming of voa russian-language broadcasts, but there have been occasional complaints in the official media about information broadcast by the service. 3-4, and subbing 1 graf for grafs 8-9 pvs, one southern ... democratic caucuses.</note>
gop presidential contender bob dole struck at george bush in new tv ads today, including one declaring bush supported arms deals with iran, as pat robertson sought cuban-americans' support with new talk about missiles in cuba
the biggest delegate day of the primary season is a week from today, and the presidential candidates were swarming across the south, where most of the 20 super tuesday states are located. jesse jackson started his day in new york, but then he, too, headed south, to baltimore for more campaigning
rep. richard gephardt paid a call today on former president carter, who made it clear that with fellow georgian sam nunn not in the race he had no plans to endorse anyone before the democratic convention next july
carter also said he thought there was a 50-50 chance that no one will have clinched the party's nomination before the convention
dole, in durham, n.c., trails vice president bush in southern polls, and he began the final week before super tuesday with public and televised attacks
the senate minority leader accused bush of offering ``nine different answers'' on the iran-contra affair. ``but it's a fact he did support it,'' dole said
in fort lauderdale, meanwhile, robertson said today a transcript of 1967 senate subcommittee testimony supports his belief there are nuclear missiles in cuba
the former television evangelist quoted testimony from a state department official who said cuban refugees had told him about seeing missiles
this is documented evidence,'' robertson said today at a breakfast attended by about 600 supporters. the reagan administration has denied his contention about missiles in cuba, which he first made in a debate in new hampshire last month
vermont began its non-binding ``beauty contest'' primary today under sunny skies with a record turnout predicted and michael dukakis, the governor of neighboring massachusetts, the demcratic favorite
on the gop side, bush, who won maine's gop caucuses, has a strong organization in vermont, but dole has won endorsements from some top republicans
bush was campaigning in another pre-super tuesday state _ south carolina, which holds its primary saturday. as he did in new hampshire, the vice president brought in former arizona sen. barry goldwater, a hero to conservatives, to stump for him
polls have given bush a comfortable lead in south carolina, but he said he was taking nothing for granted
two days before new hampshire, some of the most respected pollsters showed me down and almost out,'' he said monday in charleston. bush won the feb. 16 new hampshire primary by a solid margin, after polls suggested rival bob dole was breathing down his neck
dole, on a southern swing that took him to mississippi, georgia and florida, heaped scorn on the vice president, characterizing him as a passive figure
ask him what's he done in the last seven years,'' dole said at a fort lauderdale rally. ``what's he done anywhere in america or the world to make a difference?''
continuing that theme, dole unleashed a television ad which depicts the vice president walking through the snow without leaving any footprints. dole's campaign said the commercial was having a test run in miami and other selected cities
robertson, in miami on monday, produced a cuban refugee who he said had seen missiles in cuba. the cuban, who spoke through an interpreter and identified himself only as e. rodriguez, said he had seen missile sites, but did not know whether the weapons had nuclear warheads
robertson also told cuban-american senior citizens he would work with them for an independent and democratic cuba. ``viva cuba libre!'' he said. at a mostly hispanic high school, he called castro a ``butcher and a tyrant.''
meanwhile, democratic rivals dukakis and gephardt, who have been trading victories in the early caucuses and primaries, traded jabs at a democratic debate in williamsburg, va
dukakis ridiculed the missouri congressman for ``running around the country beating up on the establishment'' while accepting political contributions from special interest groups. gary hart was also critical of the practice
gephardt called it ``an affront'' to suggest that such contributions would influence the way he votes in congress
during the debate, jackson said he has sometimes been singled out for different treatment during the campaign because of his race. he cited an exit poll in which voters were asked if they would support a black candidate for president
i said, did you ask how many would vote for a greek?'' said jackson, referring to dukakis, who is of greek descent. ``my race is self-evident and my leadership is obvious.''
earlier in the day, jackson visited racially troubled robeson county in north carolina and drew a comparison with white-ruled south africa
in south africa people have been abandoned by the law. no law protects them,'' he said. ``what is happening right here ... is a whole body of people has been abandoned by the law.''
he made the same comparison in houston, where he walked through a trash-strewn neighborhood. jackson suggested city officials want to force poor residents out and redevelop the property, likening it to the south african government relocating blacks
he told college students at pembroke state university that his strong second-place showing in the maine caucuses proves he has broadened his appeal. ``talk about mainstream; try the state of maine!'' he said
at monday night's democratic debate, at jackson's suggestion, the candidates wore yellow ribbons on their jackets in protest of the arrest of anglican archbishop desmond tutu in south africa
the government tuesday defended a treasure hunt at a historic spanish fort and extended the u.s. contractor's digging permit for another month
on monday, the senate approved a resolution calling for a halt to the search for japanese treasure believed buried at fort santiago, which was active during the spanish occupation that ended in 1898 and later was used by the japanese as a garrison during world war ii
the senate action followed a speech by opposition sen. juan ponce enrile, who said the search was being conducted ``by foreigners whose only reason for being here is perhaps their greed for gold.'' enrile charged it was an insult to national honor
international precious metals inc., a u.s. concern, began excavating this month at a chamber in fort santiago for gold believed buried there by japanese soldiers at the end of world war ii. the company has agreed to give the government 75 percent of whatever is recovered
national security adviser emmanuel soriano, who is monitoring the project for the government, told reporters tuesday the government approved the company's request to extend the dig for 30 days. the contract would have expired this week
nothing is going on right there in fort santiago that would desecrate the national shrine,'' soriano said in response to enrile's speech. he said enrile had known of digging at the same site when he was defense minister under president ferdinand marcos in 1975 but had not moved to block it
soriano said the dig was an ``authorized and legitimate project of which the beneficiary would be the filipino people,'' and that the contractors would restore the excavated portions of the fort
soriano said charles macdougald, an official of the u.s. company, had reported they expect to recover gold bullion believed hidden in the fort within 10 to 15 days
the treasure hunt was widely publicized after two filipino workers were killed last week when a tunnel they were digging collapsed
soriano said his company would give the equivalent of $5,000 to each to the families of the two workers. work has since resumed, with troops now guarding the site around the clock
manila mayor gemiliano lopez, who inspected the site tuesday, said the dig was about 17 feet deep
authorities in southwestern poland detained 20 people for a march in which demonstrators wore hats, black raincoats and dark glasses to mock secret security police, an opposition activist said
the event in downtown wroclaw was staged by the opposition group orange alternative, which often uses satire to poke fun at poland's communist government
spokesman jozef pinior said young men dressed in traditional spy garb and sporting arm bands with the letters ``sb,'' the polish initials for security service, evoked laughter from onlookers
after about a half-hour, they were intercepted by real police and 20 were taken into custody, he said. authorities began releasing them shortly afterward, he said
in the past, orange alternative demonstrators have donned santa claus outfits and costumes of lenten penitents to mock the government's economic policies
investigators say a marriage in trouble may have prompted a man to kill his wife and their three children before setting the family's home on fire and fatally shooting himself
firefighters discovered the bodies of lawrence delabarto, 32, his wife and their children, all in bed, late sunday night after responding to the fire
i am told by family and friends that there were some marital difficulties,'' livingston county sheriff richard kane said monday. ``his (delabarto's) wounds are consistent with suicide, plus we found that all the doors were locked and the phone was off the hook which would indicate that this was planned.''
delabarto's body was found in bed next to his wife, 32-year-old linda, and a .16-gauge shotgun, kane said
a preliminary examination indicated that mrs. delabarto had been strangled, and that delabarto and the children _ 12-year-old anthony, 10-year-old danielle, and 6-year-old dominic _ had been shot, kane aid
investigators said the fire was started with fuel oil that had been poured in several rooms
kane said the family had gone to church on sunday and had breakfast with delabarto's parents, who live in geneseo
the father had no indication of any problems,'' kane said
there also didn't seem to be anything unusual at riverside wine and liquor co. in mount morris where delabarto had worked as a truckdriver for 2{ years
richard radesi, the company's owner, said delabarto was dependable, well-liked, proud of his family and ``just as congenial as he could be.''
ed rebrook, a candidate for the state house and the democratic national convention, has won a ``capital case.''
rebrook has been trying to persuade secretary of state ken hechler to list his name as rebrook, not rebrook, on the may 10 primary election ballot
hechler argued the candidate has always signed his name rebrook and the bid for the capital letter was just a play for publicity and an effort to make his name stand out on a crowded ballot
kanawha county circuit judge patrick casey on monday sided with rebrook, ruling that state election rules don't cover name spelling, so hechler ``is without constitutional or statutory authority to determine the proper spelling or capitalization of (a candidate's) name.''
hechler had no immediate comment
convicted ``onion field'' murderer jimmie lee smith was ordered jailed for 180 days after he pleaded guilty to misdemeanor possession of a hypodermic needle
municipal court commissioner alan s. kalkin sentenced smith on monday
smith, 57, was arrested in november for allegedly driving under the influence of an opiate after he was stopped for a traffic violation
smith has been on parole since march 1987 after serving three years for a 1984 conviction on possession of heroin for sale. if probation authorities deem he violated parole, smith could go immediately to state prison to serve the term
convicted with gregory ulas powell for shooting an officer in an onion field in 1963, smith served 19 years and was released on parole in 1982. powell is serving a life term
the case was made famous by joseph wambaugh's 1973 novel ``the onion field,'' which later was made into a movie. proposal</head>
education secretary william j. bennett visited capitol hill on tuesday to promote his education spending proposal for 1989 and found a friendlier reception than in past years, when he was seeking cuts
the reagan administration is asking for $21.2 billion in education spending authority _ about $850 million or 4 percent above the current level
this is a bill that should go through the house in one hour,'' rep. william natcher, d-ky., chairman of the appropriations subcommittee on labor, health and education, told bennett
i would imagine the seat that you're sitting in is quite a bit cooler than it has been in the last few years,'' added rep. silvio conte, r-mass
bennett laughed and denied conte's assertion that he had undergone a conversion and become a ``born-again education spender.''
i'm the same old mad catholic i always was,'' bennett said
bennett said the education request was as high as possible under the outlines of the deficit reduction agreement reached last year between congress and the administration
that agreement limited overall domestic spending increases to 2 percent. the proposed 4 percent education hike is ``way above average,'' bennett said. ``this is pretty much to the limit of what we could in good conscience ask for.''
natcher questioned bennett closely on proposed cuts in certain types of student loans, a public libraries program and grants meant to offset tax losses in areas with federal installations
he hinted the house might not go along with those cuts but promised bennett, ``we're going to bring you out a good bill. we're going to bring out a bill that both you and i will like.''
the administration has proposed expansions in a number of programs, including pell grants to needy college students, aid to disadvantaged children, magnet schools and a college loan program under which repayments are pegged to future income
congress has consistently appropriated more for education than the reagan administration has sought. the fiscal 1989 education increase is only the second one requested by the reagan administration. the first came in 1984, another election year
rep. david obey, d-wis., pointed that out in a statement and noted that ``our kids go to school every year, not just election years. ... local school boards need help that isn't turned on and off with election cycles.''
janet cunningham, leap year baby of 1960, gave birth to a daughter exactly 28 years later
erin michelle cunningham was born monday, two days ahead of doctors' expectations
i never expected it,'' said mrs. cunningham, who lives in severna park. ``it's not something you plan.''
erin is the second child for gregory and janet cunningham. their son is 2
mrs. cunningham was baltimore's first leap year baby in 1960
sodium cyanide pellets were spilled on a snowy section of interstate 80 because of a truck wreck, and nearly 100 miles of the highway was shut down as a small amount of deadly cyanide gas formed
a nearby rail line crossing the unpopulated area was also closed for a time
state motor vehicles director wayne teglia said a tractor-trailer rig overturned seven miles east of battle mountain, injuring the driver and spilling about 100 pounds of pellets
some gas formed when the pellets, used in mining operations, reacted with the wet snow, teglia said
if it had been raining it would have been worse,'' said teglia
he said clean-up crews from the trucking company, wells cargo, and a mining company were dispatched to clean up the spill
two police officers have been reprimanded for persuading a deputy u.s. marshal to shoot out a light fixture in a crowded bar, the police chief said tuesday
the bullet richocheted behind the bar after striking the light, but no one was injured
officers david sanders and robert kind were told they ``acted in a way that brought unfavorable criticism upon the department,'' chief doug franks said tuesday
sanders and kind were sitting at a table with deputy u.s. marshal garry carroll at a feb. 18 party attended by as many as 20 off-duty lawmen when they challenged carroll to shoot out the light, franks said
carroll was charged with reckless endangerment and is to appear at a preliminary hearing march 7
sanders and kind will be suspended for a minimum of three days if they are involved in a similar incident within the next 18 months, franks said. letters of reprimand will remain in their personnel files, he said
no action has been taken against any other officers
it would be counterproductive to create a new, independent agency to oversee safety at federal nuclear weapons materials facilities, a top department of energy official to congress on tuesday
but rep. norm dicks, d-wash., urged the subcommittee to approve legislation creating such a watchdog agency, calling the department's plan to establish an advisory committee ``an inadequate response.''
doe operates 40 major facilities in 34 states, including reactors that produce plutonium and tritium and plants that refine it for use in nuclear weapons
joseph salgado, a doe undersecretary, told the house armed services procurement and military nuclear systems subcommittee it would be ``premature'' to create an outside agency
the advisory committee needs time to work, to prove its credibility,'' salgado said
the doe official said a new agency would be ``regulatory, counterproductive and adversarial'' and could ``severely hamper the department's ability to perform its national security and energy research missions
dicks has introduced legislation that would create a defense nuclear facilities safety agency. it would have the authority to shut down any reactor or plant that was found unsafe
a new agency would cost between $6 million and $10 million a year to operate and funds could be taken from current doe safety oversight programs to pay for it, dicks said
the administrator of the agency would be appointed by the president and confirmed by the senate
dicks said that doe was caught between the department of defense's demands for nuclear materials and the need to operate the facilities safely
studies conducted in recent years have revealed disturbing evidence that doe's defense facilities are not only operating with deteriorating and unpredictable equipment, but receive oversight through a poorly managed and ineffcient safety assurance process,'' dicks said
the supreme court on tuesday made it easier for immigration officials to deport aliens who seek reconsideration of their claims to remain in the united states
by a vote of 8-0, the justices barred further hearings for a california physician, dr. assibi l. abudu, who said he might be tortured or killed if forced to return to his native ghana
abudu asked the board of immigration appeals for asylum in this country after it denied his initial bid to avoid deportation
justice john paul stevens, writing for the court, said immigration officials, having decided an alien should be deported, generally are under no duty to reconsider the case when the alien says he has new evidence to support a bid for asylum
stevens said aliens seeking to reopen their deportation cases have the difficult task of proving that immigration officials abused their discretion in refusing reconsideration
there is a strong public interest in bringing litigation to a close as promptly as is consistent with the interest in giving the adversaries a fair opportunity to develop and present their respective cases,'' stevens said
he continued, ``we have no hesitation in concluding that the board of immigration appeals did not abuse its discretion when it held that abudu had not reasonably explained his failure to apply for asylum prior to the completion of the initial deportation proceeding.''
abudu is a native and citizen of ghana who graduated from the university of southern california medical school and married a u.s. citizen
immigration officials moved to deport him in 1981 after he was convicted in california of illegally attempting to obtain the drug demerol by fraud. he was given a one-year suspended prison sentence and was placed on probation for three years
the immigration and naturalization service found him deportable, and the board of immigration appeals upheld that decision
he faces deportation to england, according to court papers. but abudu said he might be barred by that country and forced to return to ghana
abudu asked immigration officials to reopen his case in 1985 and grant him asylum in the united states from the military dictatorship of flight lt. jerry rawlings, who regained power in ghana in a dec. 31, 1981, military coup
abudu said he had new evidence that his life might be in danger if he was forced to return to ghana
the board of immigration appeals refused to reopen abudu's case, noting that abudu did not initially seek asylum when he contested his deportation
but the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals in 1986 ordered the board to reconsider granting abudu asylum
the supreme court agreed with the reagan administration that the appeals court should have deferred to the immigration board
justice anthony m. kennedy, who only recently joined the court, did not take part in the decision
in other developments, the court:
_declined to decide yet whether the state or the federal government should control a gulf of mexico area off mississippi's southwestern coastline. rejecting arguments by the state's lawyers, the court ruled 7-0 that more information is needed before such a determination is made
_heard arguments over the constitutionality of texas' death penalty law. a ruling is expected by july
john roger, the alligator who was flushed into the hobbs sewer system as a baby and lived a pampered life in his own solar home at the city water treatment plant, was buried tuesday
the alligator was buried 16 years after sewer workers named john and roger found the 24-inch reptile swimming in an effluent pond
john roger was 7 feet, 9 inches long at the time of his death monday. he lived in a fenced compound that included a solar-heated home, diving pond and grass knoll for sunbathing
the alligator's body was found at the compound at the bottom of his pool. he apparently had gone for a post-hibernation swim. no necropsy was scheduled but officials suspected the alligator died of pneumonia
state sen. joe harvey, who was city manager at the time john roger was adopted, recalled the alligator was fond of frogs
there were months where there wasn't a live frog in this town,'' harvey said. ``kids found out that john roger liked frogs _ live frogs _ and they'd go out and find them, then throw them over the fence of his compound.''
a small passenger plane exploded in flight tuesday and crashed in an industrial area east of johannesburg, killing all 17 people on board, the south african broadcasting corp. reported
the radio said the plane was operated by comair, a private commercial airline that flies between johannesburg and towns in north and central south africa
the twin-engine plane, a brazilian-made bandeirante turboprop, was en route to johannesburg from the northern border town of phalaborwa when it crashed, state-run south african broadcasting reported. it said all 15 passengers and two crew members aboard were killed
there was no immediate indication what caused the crash. witnesses told reporters they heard an explosion and saw what appeared to be two pieces of the plane plunge to the ground
the plane went down in an area called wadeville, about six miles east of downtown johannesburg
the identities of the victims were not immediately known
the bandeirante can accommodate up to 18 passengers
ridership on new york subways increased for the third straight year in 1987 to its highest level in 13 years, the transit authority reported tuesday
ta president david gunn attributed much of the increase to new and overhauled cars on some lines and a boost in the number of clean cars
officials also said subway crime was down 8.1 percent for serious felonies from 1986. ta spokesman albert o'leary said there were 12,888 felonies on the subways last year compared with 14,030 in the previous 12 months
gunn said 3,626,000 people rode the subways on an average weekday last year, up by 216,000 from 1984 and 103,000 from 1986. in all, 1.059 billion passengers rode the subways last year, up 29 million from 1986 and 62 million from 1984
gunn said that 94 percent of the subway fleet should be graffiti-free by the end of this year
singer michael jackson presented a $600,000 check to the united negro college fund on tuesday and told a jam-packed news conference, ``i love you all.''
there aren't many days like this,'' uncf president christopher edley said after accepting the check from jackson
the singer, wearing a striped shirt and bright red blazer, waved as more then two dozen camera crews and twice as many still photographers took hundreds of pictures of the usually reclusive superstar
thank you. i'm very honored and very thankful,'' jackson said during his 15 seconds at the microphone. ``i love you all. thank you.''
the check represented the proceeds from jackson's scheduled thursday night show at madison square garden, his first solo performance in new york
jackson earlier created a ``michael jackson scholarship'' for the uncf. in the past three years, 97 students have received financial aid through the program
the judge presided in the banquet room at the quality inn. tourists by the pool did a double-take when a prisoner went by in handcuffs, while lawyers consulted under beach umbrellas
the court reporter said she wasn't sure she got a good transcript because of the noise from the kitchen,'' said circuit judge gil goshorn
such incongruous scenes have been taking place in titusville this week as judges, prosecutors, clerical workers and other county employees moved out of the brevard county courthouse, which was closed because of asbestos contamination
county officials quarantined the courthouse saturday when air tests showed asbestos levels far above federal standards in several rooms. some levels were considered dangerously high, and most employees were urged to get medical tests
asbestos was widely used for insulation and fireproofing until the federal government banned its use in 1979
the county clerk's office set up shop in modular buildings in the courthouse parking lot. workers wearing breathing masks hurried to build a plywood and plastic ``cocoon'' to provide safe access to the clerk's computers inside the courthouse
all documents were locked inside when the courthouse was evacuated. experts said all paperwork and even many computer terminals were contaminated and would have to be carefully dusted and cleaned as they are removed piece-by-piece from the building
the closing of the court house also affects real estate transactions, court-ordered child support payments and other operations. with testimony from first witness; deletes grafs 23-24, ``this man xxx, and grafs 28-9, ``the first xxx, to tighten</note>
gov. evan mecham should be removed from office for obstructing an investigation of an alleged death threat, senators were told today during opening arguments of the first-term republican's impeachment trial
but a defense attonrey for mecham told senators in an impassioned statement that mecham was the victim of a ``mutiny'' by the state attorney general and director of the state department of public safety
prosecutor william french said the man accused of making the alleged threat, former state official lee watkins, had claimed that jobs in the mecham administration ``relate to the amount of money that you were able to bring into the campaign.''
french said the evidence was ``overwhelming'' that mecham violated criminal laws and his oath of office and committed malfeasance in office, ``any one of which call for impeachment.''
however, defense attorney fred craft told senators in his opening statement that mecham broke no laws and was acting within his authority
what has this man done?'' craft said. ``there's something wrong in this state when you can depose the constitutionally elected officer of the state and throw the book at him ... based upon evidence that's being presented by people who have a stake in the outcome to have him ousted.''
craft said the accusations resulted from a ``mutiny'' by attorney general bob corbin and dps director ralph milstead. the dps includes the highway patrol and investigative personnel
craft also said he would present testimony that would cast dubt on milstead's integrity
mecham, who also faces a march 22 criminal trial and a may 17 recall election, did not appear at the senate on the second day of his impeachment trial
the impeachment counts against mecham include an allegation that he ordered milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's probe of an alleged death threat by watkins, then the state prison construction chief
there was an obstruction with regard to an ongoing investigation that was being conducted by the attorney general's office,'' french said
watkins has denied making a threat against donna carlson, a former top mecham aide who testified before the state grand jury on mecham's failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan
dps officer frank martinez, a former member of mecham's security detail who was called as the trial's first witness, testified this morning that mecham administration official peggy griffith told him about a conversation she had with watkins
ms. griffith said watkins had told her that if ms. carlson ``did not keep her mouth shut, she could wind up taking a long boat ride ... and i know the right people who can help me,'' martinez testified
martinez said that he met with milstead, other dps officers, corbin and several assistant attorneys general several days later and that milstead told of a conversation he had with mecham
martinez said milstead told the group that mecham ``stated he didn't want him helping the attorney general.''
the overall mood was just amazement,'' martinez testified
craft said milstead and other officials did not fully advise mecham about the alleged threat, adding that milstead ``was a feckless employee of this state and he did not serve that governor well.''
french said watkins complained about the job he was given by mecham and told corrections director sam lewis, ``if they don't treat me right i can bring mecham's administration down.''
french warned the senate to ``keep your eye on the ball'' and not be distracted by any attacks on witnesses in the case. ``know that this is being done because there is no defense,'' french said
the opening arguments today dealt only with the alleged threat. arguments will precede discussion of the other allegations against mecham as they are reached during the trial
on the trial's opening day monday, the senate strongly rejected efforts to dismiss impeachment charges against mecham
also, the arizona supreme court was expected to rule today on a defense claim that the impeachment trial, the first of a u.s. governor in 59 years, should be delayed until after mecham's march 22 criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
the high court last week refused to grant a temporary delay, and mecham said he planned to take the issue to federal court if necessary
senate president carl kunasek, a republican, said ``it was the first-day jitters for everyone'' in the impeachment trial's opening day monday
it crosses everybody's mind _ the importance to do justice to the governor and the state,'' said senate majority leader bob usdane, also a republican. ``it's a large burden and we take it seriously.''
senators refused to dismiss the 23 articles of impeachment against mecham, whose attorney, jerris leonard, entered an innocent plea on his behalf
on 11 separate motions, the largest number of the 29 senators voting for dismissal was seven. several senators said the vote should not be considered an indication that mecham is likely to be convicted, saying they want to hear the evidence first
however, sen. jeff hill, a republican who has strongly backed mecham, said the governor's conviction was virtually a foregone conclusion. ``i think that it's not likely that he's going to prevail,'' he said
if convicted by the senate, mecham would be removed from office and could be permanently barred from holding elective office in arizona
mecham, 63, won election in a three-way race after five tries
he has repeatedly denied wrongdoing and insisted he will survive both trials and a may 17 recall election and return to the office he gave up to acting gov. rose mofford, a democrat, when he was impeached by the house on feb. 5
a federal judge ordered the u.s. parole commission on tuesday to free an anti-castro activist who has been in a venezuelan prison for 11 years on bond, but he stayed his order to allow the agency to appeal
even if orlando bosch won his freedom, u.s. immigration and naturalization service officials were waiting in the wings to take custody of him, they said tuesday
bosch, a hero in miami's cuban community, has been in jail since he arrived last month from venezuela, where he spent 11 years in prison despite being acquitted three times of bombing a cuban airliner
u.s. authorities said bosch had violated parole by fleeing this country in 1974 while on probation for planning a bazooka attack on a polish ship in the port of miami in 1968, and conspiring to plant bombs on other ships
bosch's daughter, lourdes, said outside court that she was pleased with u.s. district judge kenneth l. ryskamp's order. but, she added, ``i am just confused and upset that now this is going to be appealed and they can stall another week or more. to me, it's just a farce, a political farce.''
ryskamp called bosch's imprisonment until a scheduled march 21 parole hearing ``totally arbitrary and capricious.''
ryskamp said parole commissioner g. mackenzie rast used ``tunnel vision in picking out those facts he wants to rely upon'' when he ordered bosch to remain jailed
assistant u.s. attorney chuck senatore said he would appeal ryskamp's decision to the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals in atlanta, and the judge granted a temporary stay of his release order
even if the appeals court upholds ryskamp, bosch also cannot be released until his lawyers convince the ins
we of course have a detainer on him and would be holding him on an immigration violation,'' said ins district director perry rivkind
the ins has targeted bosch for exclusion hearings and possible deportation because he entered the united states without legal immigration documents last month after his release from a venezuelan prison
ins officials have said they will not permit bosch's release and have labeled him a terrorist because of his conviction for conspiring to bomb the polish ship. parole officials also accused him of consorting with known criminals
on the probation commission order, ryskamp said rast went beyond the facts on record to conclude that bosch should be held. the judge said rast apparently considered bosch's acquittals in venezuela as a strike against him and wrongly considered ``reported'' past associations of bosch with known criminals
if that's going to be the basis of denying somebody their liberty rights, then it's a sad day for the constitution,'' said ryskamp. the judge also noted that rast evidently reviewed information in bosch's parole file which was never disclosed to bosch
the judge also noted that rast ignored the recommendation of a probation officer who interviewed bosch and concluded there was no risk that he would flee
ryskamp set bond at $250,000 and said that if bosch is freed he cannot make public appearances or statements or identify himself with any militant groups opposing the cuban government of fidel castro. he also could not receive more than five visitors in his home at any one time and would be required to report in three times a day by telephone
pick a political persuasion and there is no doubt a party for it in bangladesh, a nation so philosophically fragmented that even groups committed to political unity are split into factions
the nation's major opposition parties _ all 21 of them _ are boycotting thursday's elections to parliament, but there certainly is no lack of election interest. as many as 102 political groups are vying for the 330 seats
many, obviously, are quite small
one has to use a microscope or a telescope to see if they are really political parties,'' says shamsul huda haryn, a political science professor at dhaka university
sorting out the groups in the parliamentary fray is difficult because one group on the ballot is known as ``the 23-party alliance'' and another is listed as the ``combined opposition party,'' which is made up of 73 separate factions
whatever the number, the parliamentary contest illustrates just how fractured the political system is in this nation of 105 million people
a government booklet on the country's ``multi-party political system '' notes that the ``polycentric political system in bangladesh has marked a phenomenal fragmentation of existing organizations and growth of new ones.''
the booklet gives the history of 130 separate political parties. some experts, however, believe there many be more than 200 separate political groups
included in the political patchwork are 11 different islamic parties, reflecting the predominant moslem population, along with six communist parties, a social democratic party, a socialist party, and two republican parties
there are even two separate united people's parties
harun, who studied in both england and the united states, said bangladesh's political groups are not really parties as defined in the west
call them pressure groups, or lobbies, or even sections,'' he said
harun said that many have no cohesive philosophy and were formed around a single issue, tending to split or fall apart once the issue waned
that politics is a passion here is evident in the grim toll it often takes. at least eight people have died in the past two weeks of parliamentary campaigns. in local elections feb. 10, more than 100 were killed, according to government figures
the election thursday was prompted by a campaign by the 21 opposition parties to topple president hussain muhammad ershad
after more than 20 general strikes called by the opposition since nov. 10, which included 25 deaths in police clashes with mobs, ershad dissolved parliament in december and ordered a new election. the opposition groups, however, have vowed to boycott it
those groups are the self-proclaimed ``eight-party alliance'' led by sheik hasina of the awami league, the ``seven-party alliance'' headed by khaleda zia, a group known as the ``five-party alliance,'' and the jamaat-e-islami, the largest moslem fundamentalist party
diplomats and political observers say the awami league is the best organized. it was founded by hasina's father, sheik mujibur rahman, the country's first president who was assassinated in a 1975 coup
ershad, 58, is a former general who took power in a coup and became president in 1986 in an election his opponents say was rigged. they say thursday's balloting also will be rife with fraud
the bengalis were noted for their passion for politics even in the days when britain was ruling the subcontinent. bangladesh was east bengal during british reign, then east pakistan after the partition of the subcontinent in 1947. it gained independence as bangladesh in 1971
while theories abound on why politics here is so splintered, some say the bengali people are by nature a divisive people
as one oft-repeated saying goes: `two bengalis equal a political party, three equal a party plus one faction.''
president reagan, pretty fast with an ad-lib or quip, has many of his daily lines finitely scripted, ranging from the ``welcome to the house'' greeting to the ``god bless you'' sendoff
one of the president's recent meetings _ a brief session known as a ``drop by'' in the cabinet room with several corporation executives _ was scheduled to last 20 minutes. for that get-together, reagan was provided with the following ``sequence of events:''
_`11:30 a.m. _ you enter cabinet room, are introduced by senator baker and deliver remarks. at the conclusion of your remarks you open the meeting to discussion
_`11:47 a.m. _ rebecca range will signal the end of the official portion of the meeting
_`you move to the end of the cabinet room (under president coolidge's picture) for handshake photos with the participants
_`11:50 a.m. _ you depart.''
in the briefing paper provided for reagan's 30-minute meeting with leaders of congress who had recently met with north atlantic treaty organization allies about the arms control treaty signed in december, the president was reminded, among other things, to say: ``bob (byrd), i appreciate you and your colleagues coming down today.''
a 20-page package of these briefing papers, obtained by abc white house correspondent sam donaldson, was made available to the associated press
the unintended disclosure of reagan's talking points left white house aides red-faced, with communications director thomas c. griscom maintaining that reagan often ignores these scripts anyhow
at least part of the reason for this embarrassment is that reagan long has been considered by political observers to be too heavily scripted by his aides. the president, a former actor, generally is relatively quick with responses to questions raised by reporters during picture-taking sessions and during chance encounters
though he often is seen cupping his ear because of difficulty in hearing the questions, reagan is fairly adept at answering them when he chooses to do so
the package of talking points included remarks prepared for outside visitors to the white house, ranging from singer wayne newton to an interview with washington post reporter lou cannon
absent from the package were any comments prepared for the president's daily top-level staff meeting or national security briefing
some white house staff members dismiss the disclosures with a laugh, contending the paperwork is similar to that provided other high administration officials or corporate officers and is nothing more than the product of an overzealous staff
i think the insinuation that president reagan needs to be told to say `goodbye' or `god bless you' is a cheap shot,'' said reagan's domestic policy adviser, gary bauer
anyone who's around the president frequently knows that the best stuff he says at meetings are the things he comes up with on his own. it's unfair and silly to insinuate that he can't function without those papers,'' said bauer
it's little worker bees who have little jobs to do,'' said elaine crispen, press secretary to first lady nancy reagan
white house communications director thomas griscom said reagan ignored the scripted dialogue during the meeting. he said such texts are given to reagan only to ``refresh his memory,'' if necessary
he knew what points he wanted to make, so he didn't use the talking points at all,'' griscom said
is it so unnatural for a staff person to tell his boss about a meeting he's arranged, that these people are coming, this is what we're doing?'' griscom asked. ``he hasn't got the time to sit there making notes about what each little meeting's supposed to be about _ he has more important things to do.''
mrs. crispen argued that some white house staffers are so eager to do their jobs correctly that they include items and remarks that are actually taken for granted by the official involved, including the first lady
both she and the president know to say, `hello, how do you do,''' mrs. crispen said
besides, she said, ``show me a (television) correspondent who doesn't use a script.''
surgeon general c. everett koop told a white house panel tuesday he is concerned about the spread of the aids virus among teen-agers and expressed outrage at suggestions the disease cannot be spread through heterosexual intercourse
reiterating his call for sex education programs beginning at the elementary grade levels, koop said, ``i think it is quite possible to raise a generation of adolescents down the road that would be far less sexually active than the present one.''
he emphasized that such programs should involve parents and incorporate moral and social values along with anatomical studies
but in the best of future worlds, he said, ``that leaves the teen-agers of today.''
many people are discouraged about teen-agers because some of them are so sexually active,'' he said
while it is important to recommend abstinence, koop said, ``i think it is also realistic to understand that sexually active teen-agers are unlikely to reverse their pattern and go backward, and therefore prevention for them has to be our third line of defense. ..
we have to teach them about the protection of themselves and others through the use of condoms and spermicides
i know that goes against the grain of many people in this country,'' he continued, ``but we cannot abandon more than half of our teen-agers because they are sexually active. and we have to reach them where they are and tell them about those things they have to do.''
although only a relative handful of the more than 50,000 aids cases reported so far involve teen-agers, koop said little information is available on the extent to which the virus may be lying dormant among that group
because of the long incubation period of the disease _ five years or more _ koop said he is reluctant to rule out an outbreak of aids cases in young heterosexual adults who contracted the virus as teen-agers
largely because of that concern, koop criticized some press accounts that have suggested there is virtually no danger of aids being spread through vaginal intercourse
we know from the infected spouses of persons with hemophilia that (this virus) can be spread through normal vaginal intercourse. what concerns me is the potential for a more rapid spread ... into the general population,'' he said
i am outraged at recent newspaper and magazine articles stating that there is no danger of heterosexual transmission from normal vaginal intercourse,'' said koop. ``although homosexual sex and iv drug abuse are the principal modes by which most cases are transmitted, it is just not true that there is no danger from normal vaginal intercourse
what is unknown is the level of danger. there is always a danger whenever people engage in casual sex.''
he did not mention any specific articles, but other public health service officials _ responding to specific queries _ have criticized a recent article in a magazine aimed at young single women which downplayed the risk of acquiring aids through intercourse
koop was the main witness tuesday as the 13-member commission began three days of hearings into some of the most controversial aspects of aids, including education and prevention
education secretary william bennett, who has differed publicly with koop about the emphasis to put on advising sexually active people to use condoms, is scheduled to testify thursday
retired navy adm. james d. watkins said monday he is confident that the commission can reach consensus recommendations on such controversial topics by the time it submits its final report to president reagan june 24
responding to questions at the national press club a day before koop's testimony, watkins also called attention to the concern of health authorities that little is known about the rate of dormant aids infection among teen-agers
we don't know what it is in adolescents,'' he said. ``there may be lurking on the horizon a real problem that has yet to unfold.''
here is a transcript of president reagan's remarks as he left tuesday for the nato summit meeting in belgium
thank you all very much, and good morning
i'm going to europe to meet with a group of friends and colleagues, the leaders of the north atlantic alliance
we and our foreign affairs and defense ministers see a good deal of each other, just as friends should
but the meeting that begins in brussels tomorrow will be special
it will be the first time in almost six years that leaders of all the nato countries have met together for a summit
much has happened in those six years that we can be very proud of, including the inf treaty with the soviet union that removes an entire class of u.s. and soviet nuclear weapons, weapons that on the soviet side have held the european continent at risk
that historic agreement was possible because the alliance's steadfast political and military resolve backed up our negotiations with the soviets
but the purpose of this summit is not self-congratulations
our responsibility is to the future, and it will be to the future that we turn our attention tomorrow
our first priority is to maintain a strong and healthy partnership between north america and europe, for this is the foundation on which the cause of freedom so crucially depends
we will never sacrifice the interests of this partnership in any agreement with the soviet union
nato's agenda for peace and freedom has always been ambitious, and it must remain so
in the arms control area, we will continue to press for soviet agreement to 50 percent reductions in the strategic nuclear forces on both sides, and for a truly global and verifiable ban on chemical weapons
my colleagues and i will be working to give negotiations on conventional forces a new start as well
we will also discuss soviet behavior toward its own citizens and toward other countries, since problems of human rights and external aggression remain key obstacles to long-term improvement of east-west relations
if our common approach to the east over the years has given coherence to our message of peace and world freedom, it has been our unwavering commitment to defend ourselves that has given it credibility
arms reduction can only succeed if it is backed up by a strong defense
my atlantic colleagues and i will rededicate ourselves to maintaining the deterrent that has protected our freedom and prosperity for almost 40 years
i will repeat to my colleagues my strong conviction that american troops will remain in europe, under any administration, so long as europeans want them to stay
we can be rightfully proud of these 40 years of peace that our common commitment has brought
but the job is not finished
we in the alliance will not be satisfied merely with a record period without war
we seek nothing less than permanent peace with freedom in the north atlantic
this bold objective can be obtained, but we must have the courage to follow the course that we have set for ourselves
for four decades, a combination of a strong common defense and pursuit of dialogue with the east has been a winning formula for nato
it is a combination that can lead us to a future of peace, freedom and prosperity for generations to come
thank you. god bless you. and thank you all for coming out here to see us off
authorities have clamped a curfew on a southern city where weekend rioting broke out and tensions are still running high because of a territorial dispute between ethnic groups, a soviet official said tuesday
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov suggested that the sunday unrest in sumgait, as well as demonstrations and other violence elsewhere in the caucasus region in which at least two people died, were due to ``mistakes'' made 65 years ago when a territory composed largely of armenians was made part of neighboring azerbaidzhan
he told a government news briefing that ``there were certain injuries'' in sumgait, an industrial city of more than 160,000 people in azerbaidzhan where hooligans were blamed for touching off the sunday riot
the situation is calm there today, but it is tense,'' gerasimov said
the official was peppered with questions about the civil unrest in the southern soviet republics of armenia and azerbaidzhan at his regular tuesday news briefing, but he said he had few details about events there
moscow-based foreign journalists have been barred from the region, and only sporadic reports from witnesses, activists and the official media have reached the soviet capital
when passions calm down and life starts to normalize, the appearance of some journalists in this region can lead to intensification of nationalistic feelings,'' gerasimov said, explaining why restrictions have been imposed to keep correspondents from visiting the area
asked about reports that soviet tanks are patrolling the streets of sumgait, that ethnic azeris are attacking armenians in the streets, and that there have been at least two deaths in the city, gerasimov said,``there is a curfew.''
he said he had not heard anything about tanks being sent to the city
asked if troops remained in the city tuesday, gerasimov said, ``i don't know, but i guess so. presumably.''
the violence in sumgait, reported monday by the official news agency tass, followed earlier outbreaks 150 miles away in nagorno-karabakh, the contested region in azerbaidzhan, and massive but apparently peaceful demonstrations in yerevan, the capital of armenia
the demonstrators demanded that nagorno-karabakh, which has been part of azerbaidzhan since 1923, be made part of armenia. about three-quarters of the region's population of 157,000 are ethnic armenians
gerasimov said he did not have detailed reports from the entire region but that what information he had indicated ``everything is calm'' in yerevan and surrounding areas
the events that took place caused great concern to us,'' the spokesman said. ``we think it is not a proper way to settle the problems that have accumulated.''
gerasimov acknowledged, however, that the unrest apparently stemmed from ``some mistakes made in national relations, and these mistakes should be rectified.''
soviet authorities have pledged to reconsider the issue of whether nagorno-karabakh should remain part of azerbaidzhan. gerasimov's remarks seemed to indicate the region would be turned over to armenia. he did not, however, say when that might occur
asked if he was indeed saying nagorno-karabakh should be made part of armenia, the spokesman said, ``i meant there were some mistakes in nagorno-karabakh.''
gerasimov described the region as ``a kind of enclave'' in azerbaidzhan with 49 nationalities represented among the population that is nonetheless mostly armenian
that is why we should be very tactful in handling this question in order not to cause differences between brothers and nationalities. the previous policy had some mistakes in this area,'' he said
on saturday, a soviet prosecutor reported that two people living in a region of azerbaidzhan that borders on nagorno-karabakh had been slain in unrest caused by the territorial dispute
on friday, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed for ``civic maturity and restraint'' in azerbaidzhan and armenia, and promised that the communist party central committee would review relations among the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
that same day gorbachev also met with two prominent armenian writers to help work out a solution to the problem over nagorno-karabakh
azerbaidzhan is the largest of three soviet republics in the caucasus. it is bordered on the west by largely christian armenia and georgia and on the north by the russian republic. the caspian sea runs for nearly 800 miles along its eastern edge
the republic is mainly shiite moslem, except for armenian christians living in the nagorno-karbakh region
state medical authorities want to revoke the license of a psychologist who has been beach boy brian wilson's therapist, alleging the man financially exploited the eccentric songwriter
in documents released monday, the board of medical quality assurance accused psychologist eugene landy of drug violations, patient sexual abuse and ``grossly negligent'' conduct
seven causes of action were filed against landy, wilson's near-constant companion for the last five years
the accusations largely concern landy's relationship with wilson, saying multiple business relationships with wilson caused the singer ``severe emotional damage, psychological dependence and financial exploitation.''
a request for comment was left at the office of a spokesman for wilson and landy on tuesday but there was no immediate response
attorney john mason, representing wilson, said the accusations were false
brian wilson has made a miraculous recovery with the help of dr. landy, psychologically, physically and financially. he's in the best shape he's ever been in his life,'' mason said
landy has said he became a virtual 24-hour guardian of wilson to save him from obesity and a dependence on drugs and alcohol that left him cloistered in a sand box in his house for a year
in a 1983 interview in people magazine, landy said his staff controlled wilson's every moment, monitored everything he ate and drank and recorded everything he said
the medical board said landy abused his privileges as a psychologist by serving as wilson's business manager, business adviser, executive producer and co-songwriter while also as a therapist
last year, the beach boys formed a management advisory committee to make business decisions. the state board said landy used his influence over wilson to be picked as the singer's representative, and was paid $140,000 for serving on the committee for 11 months
also questioned was landy's control of wilson's prescription drugs for a five-year period. psychologists are not permitted to prescribe drugs
the board said landy would have wilson examined by a physician who would prescribe medications that were kept in wilson's home in a locked cabinet. wilson didn't have a key, but landy's unlicensed assistants did
landy was also accused by the board of using cocaine and amyl nitrate with an unidentified female patient to induce her to have sex with him
linda mccready, a spokeswoman for the board's sacramento office, said the next step in landy's case is for the state attorney general to schedule a hearing before an administrative law judge, which usually takes six months
the judge would make a recommendation to the board's psychology examining committee, which will determine what action to take. ms. mccready said if landy disagrees with the committee's decision he can appeal to superior court. ballot</head>
pro-choice groups filed 229,128 signatures tuesday in support of a statewide vote on whether michigan should continue to pay for poor women's abortions
that gave the people's campaign for choice coalition more than 100,000 names above the minimum needed to put the issue on the nov. 8 ballot and suspend a new law that will halt welfare abortion funding beginning march 29
however, the petitions may have been filed too late to avoid a temporary funding cutoff
we have every reason to believe that 29 days is enough time'' to confirm the required 119,829 valid signatures and put the law on hold, said judith frey, speaking for the coalition
i would find that very unlikely,'' responded elections director christopher thomas. he said election-year petition certification normally takes 45 days to 60 days
both frey and right to life of michigan president barbara listing said they were confident the signatures will be certified
it's a large pad. it's certainly enough to, i think, place it on the ballot,'' listing said
both sides have estimated the statewide campaign to sway referendum votes will cost $2 million to $3 million
the petition drive that ended tuesday was the second in as many years dealing with welfare abortion funding
since 1978, gov. james blanchard, a democrat, and his republican predecessor, william milliken, have used their veto power 17 times to preserve state-paid abortions for the poor
right to life initiated the no-funding law last year with a petition drive intended to avoid the veto
in michigan, anyone who can gather 191,726 valid signatures can place before the legislature a measure that, if approved by both houses, becomes law without the governor's signature
after gathering about 400,000 signatures, the right to life-written proposal breezed through the legislature and became law
michigan is one of 14 states that uses taxpayer money to finance abortions for the poor. in 1986, the most recent year for which a final tally is available, michigan paid about $5.8 million for 18,600 abortions
the states took disciplinary action against 1,277 of the nation's half-million physicians in 1986, but a consumer group that compiled the figures said tuesday that too many doctors are still getting away with shoddy work
the actions taken in 1986 represented a 17 percent increase over the previous year and contrasted with a 46 percent jump in disciplinary actions from 1984 to 1985
even though the 1986 total ... is better than in any previous year, it falls very short of catching most of the incompetent doctors in this country,'' said a report by the public citizen health research group founded by ralph nader and director dr. sidney m. wolfe
in most states, the majority of disciplinary actions are for drug and alcohol problems, only a fraction being for incompetence,'' it said
the absence ... of the maximum effort to discipline doctors is one of the most serious threats to the health of american patients.''
although the federal government can suspend doctors from participating in federal health programs such as medicare and medicaid, the underlying permission to practice medicine is determined solely by the individual states
surveying data from the federation of state medical boards, public citizen ranked all 50 states and the district of columbia according to the number of 1986 ``serious actions'' per 1,000 doctors. a serious action was defined as a revocation or suspension of the license to practice medicine, or a probation
the national average was 2.37 actions per 1,000 doctors
georgia led with 6.94 actions per 1,000, followed by indiana, iowa, west virginia, utah, oregon, oklahoma, missouri, kentucky and colorado
wyoming was in 51st place with none. new hampshire ranked 50th, preceded by vermont, maryland, michigan, connecticut, pennsylvania, south dakota, tennessee, washington, rhode island and alabama in 40th place
nationwide, the group found there were 745 serious actions in 1984, 1,089 in 1985 and 1,277 in 1986, the last year for which figures from all localities were available
since there is no evidence that doctors settle in certain states depending on how competent they are, differences in the rate of doctor discipline reflect differences in how serious states are about disciplining doctors,'' the report said
we continue to believe that until the rate of doctor discipline in this country significantly increases, there is no realistic possibility of a major decrease in the amount of medical malpractice.''
a county supervisor who prides himself on doing right by his district and recently offered $1 to any constituent who spotted a pothole, has issued a $5 bounty on flooded intersections
whether i pay off one or two, it'll be the best survey the flood control district ever had,'' said kenneth hahn, who is running for an unprecedented 10th term
it'll keep the flood control engineers out of their offices in downtown and down in the streets where they belong,'' he said
the offer, intended to pull the plug on storm-caused flooding, is good from tuesday through march 10
hahn paid $3 on his pothole offer _ $2 of it to a los angeles herald examiner reporter who cruised the byways of the 2nd district in a near-fruitless search for poor pavement
i pride myself on taking care of my district,'' hahn said. ``if you do your homework and take care of the little things in your district, the big things will take care of themselves.'' death</head>
prime minister charles haughey on tuesday challenged the british army's contention that one of its soldiers accidentally shot and killed an unarmed civilian from an observation post just inside northern ireland
a suggestion that death was due to a freak accident of an extraordinary kind must give rise to disbelief,'' haughey told the irish parliament
haughey's administration launched its own investigation into the feb. 21 shooting of 23-year-old aidan mcanespie, which strained already tense relations between britain and ireland. an irish police officer said he witnessed the shooting from across the border
police in the british-ruled province charged an 18-year-old soldier with unlawful killing. he is being held in military custody
the army said the bullet that hit mcanespie ricocheted after being fired accidentally from an observation post at a checkpoint near auchnacloy, less than half a mile from the irish republic's border
relatives said mcanespie, a campaign worker for sinn fein, the legal political arm of the irish republican army, had been harassed by the british army. his sister, eilish mccabe, claimed her brother had received a number of death threats from the army
haughey's inquiry angered the british government and protestant political leaders in northern ireland, who see it as interference in their affairs
haughey said the irish investigation was obligatory because of the ``considerable concern'' over the incident among the province's roman catholic minority
he said mcanespie's death, along with the british government's refusal to prosecute northern ireland police officers who killed six unarmed roman catholics in 1982 and the release from prison of a british soldier who served just three years of a life sentence for killing a catholic ``have combined to create the impression that the security forces are above the law.''
any such impression among the public in northern ireland must have disastrous consequences on the community and impinge on every aspect of british policy for the administration of justice in northern ireland,'' haughey said
mcanespie's body was exhumed sunday after his family requested an autopsy by an irishman in addition to that held by the british in the north. the family said they wanted to determine the course of the fatal bullet. he was later reburied in the irish republic
president reagan announced today that panama and three other countries long hostile to the united states _ afghanistan, iran and syria _ have not cooperated with u.s. efforts to stop the smuggling of drugs to american markets
but reagan plans no steps to penalize panama economically beyond measures already taken, said ann wrobleski, a state department official responsible for narcotics matters
reagan will ``wait and see'' if panama's military-dominated government improves its cooperation before deciding on additional sanctions, she said
the decisions concerning afghanistan, iran and syria will have no economic impact on them, partly because none is a u.s. aid recipient
under law, reagan is required to suspend all economic and military aid to countries found not to be cooperating in u.s. drug enforcement efforts. ms. wrobleski noted that all such aid to panama was suspended in 1987
such a finding also requires the united states to vote against loan requests by the offending country in international lending institutions. ms. wrobleski said the united states has been abstaining on panama's requests for some time and that, in any case, panama has no loan applications pending
ms. wrobleski raised the possibility that the administration may increase tariffs on panamanian products if that country's attitude on drug-smuggling does not improve
she said a contributing factor in the decision on panama was the drug-smuggling indictments handed down a month ago against military strongman manuel antonio noriega. the indictment said panama has become a major transit point for u.s.-bound cocaine from colombia
reagan certified that mexico and colombia are cooperating with u.s. drug enforcement efforts, but ms. wrobleski said the president indicated that ``these countries should do more.''
under a 1986 law, reagan is required to take punitive measures against countries found not to cooperate in curbing drug-smuggling to the united states. countries which are ``decertified'' are subject to the penalties
today was the deadline for the announcement of reagan's findings
the announcement on panama's lack of cooperation in drug enforcement carried heavy political overtones, given the dramatic developments over the past few days
the administration has refused to extend recognition to the new panamanian government which took office following the ouster last friday of president eric arturo delvalle
delvalle was deposed by noriega's allies in the national assembly after the president tried to fire the defense chief. the reagan administration continues to look on delvalle as panama's constitutional president
the new government has named a u.n.-based envoy to replace delvalle's ambassador, juan b. sosa, but sosa refused to relinquish the embassy. the appointed successor, leonardo kam, showed up at the embassy on monday and left after what he said was a ``frank'' exchange with sosa
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., introduced a senate resolution urging additional economic sanctions against panama, including a trade embargo. an administration official, however, said the government is not contemplating any such action
kennedy's resolution also asks that the united states cut off all contacts with noriega because he is ``no longer the lawful commander'' of the defense forces
in a brief speech on the senate floor, kennedy said noriega ``is a threat to peace and security in the region.''
when a drug trafficker gets control over the governmental powers of a nation, it's a threat to other nations,'' kennedy said
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said the administration should go much further than it has in pressuring noriega to step down
this business of let's go slow, let's exercise restraint and caution, that is what has produced the situation. we've been going cautiously with this gangster for 20 years,'' d'amato said
a fire spread through a mobile home sales lot tuesday, destroying 45 homes, authorities said
high wind and a lack of water hindered firefighters at connor mobile homes. there were no injuries reported in the tuesday morning fire
the mobile homes were valued about about $10,000 each. about half the homes in the lot were destroyed
with the way the wind was blowing and just the three of us out here, there was nothing we could do. it got up under the houses and that was it,'' said tony cantrell, a connor salesman
fire department captain richard newman said the department received a report of a grass fire and that the trailers were burning when firefighters arrived
presidential candidates scrambled to discredit their rivals with increasingly rough-and-tumble television commercials a week before the nation's biggest primary day ever
sen. bob dole scored vice president george bush for his role in the iran-contra affair in one new ad. in another, rep. marvin leath of texas criticizes two democrats competing against his colleague, rep. richard gephardt
the candidates under attack _ bush, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee _ all have produced hard-hitting tv ads of their own and were expected to respond promptly
television is shaping up as the candidates' most important tool in the far-flung super tuesday contests on march 8. there are 712 republican delegates and 1,307 democratic delegates up for grabs that day in caucuses and primaries in 20 states and american samoa
super tuesday stretches across more than 150 media markets and more than 500 television stations, with a multi-million dollar price tag for any candidate who wanted to clog the air with commercials
most of the contenders were targeting their media spending to carefully selected areas where they thoguht they had the best chances of winning delegates. both dukakis and gore predicted they would in the end have spent the most for super tuesday; bush had the most money in the bank as the contest approached
dole and gephardt were first out of the box with negative ads
one dole spot depicts someone walking through snow but leaving no footprints. dole campaign manager bill brock said the message is that bush ``has held all these big jobs'' yet left no mark
another ad, the first to inject the iran-contra affair into the campaign, says dole was ``opposed selling arms to iran. bush supported the arms-for-hostages deal.'' the ad also accuses bush of waffling on taxes, taking a soft line on the u.s.-soviet arms control treaty, and opposing a textile bill popular in several southern states
in his ad on behalf of gephardt, leath said the missouri congressman ``stood with us for lower taxes, for an oil import fee to make america strong, for a tough trade bill to stand up for american workers.''
on all these issues, gore and dukakis were opposed to us. gore and dukakis even think the gephardt trade bill is too tough on the japanese, europeans and koreans. we're tired of hearing that you can't fight for america anymore. that's why 35 southern congressman are fighting for dick gephardt for president,'' leath says in the ad
gephardt also is using a slightly retooled version of a commercial that gave him the edge he needed to beat dukakis last week in south dakota. the ad called dukakis ``one of the biggest tax raisers in massachusetts history'' and mocked the governor's suggestion that struggling iowa farmers switch to growing belgian endive
the dukakis campaign has prepared several tough responses, including an ad that shows a weathervane swinging back and forth as a narrator accuses gephardt of flip-flops on issues
leslie dach, the campaign's communications director, declined to provide any scripts because he said final decisions on what would be used, when and where had not been made
but he said the general content would be along the following lines: ``he says he is leading the little guy's fight but his campaign is financed and supported by the big guys. his biggest contributors are america's biggest corporations. he has failed to show a set of principles or a set of values that give a rudder to his policies.''
in a footnote to the fierce super tuesday tv campaign, rep. jack kemp, r-n.y., began attacking pat robertson in ads running on radio stations in south carolina. the state holds a gop primary on saturday
the kemp ad asks if the former television evangelist has ``the qualifications and the judgment to be our next president'' and cites some of his more unusual positions such as a 1979 suggestion that public schools be eliminated. robertson later changed his mind
in addition to negative ads, the candidates are using more subdued biographical spots and traditional political testimonials. among them: former sen. barry goldwater endorses bush, former house speaker thomas p. o'neill of massachusetts praises dukakis, and rep. claude pepper _ an elderly florida legislator with enormous clout among senior citizens _ speaks kindly of gephardt
gephardt is also using the hyundai ad credited with putting his campaign message into sharp focus and helping him win last month's iowa caucuses. in the spot he criticizes south korea for putting stiff tariffs on u.s. autos and asks how many hyundais the koreans could sell here at $48,000 apiece
texas' capital punishment law, under which some 260 convicted murderers are awaiting death by lethal injection, was challenged tuesday in the supreme court
mark stevens of san antonio, a lawyer representing death row inmate donald gene franklin, argued that the law, as applied, stacks the deck in favor of death over life in prison
stevens said the jurors who sentenced franklin for the 1975 murder of a san antonio nurse were prevented from giving full consideration to ``mitigating circumstances,'' those factors suggesting life in prison as the appropriate punishment
consideration of particularized mitigating circumstances was not allowed,'' stevens contended
but william c. zapalac, an assistant state attorney general, urged the justices to uphold a federal appeals court ruling that said franklin was sentenced properly
noting that franklin was allowed to present any mitigating evidence he desired, zapalac added, ``franklin cannot reasonably claim that the jury could not see the relevance of the evidence he wanted to present.''
under texas law, capital case sentencing juries are asked two questions: whether the murder was committed deliberately and whether the killer poses a continuing, violent threat to society
if the jurors unanimously find beyond a reasonable doubt that the answer to both questions is ``yes'' a death sentence is imposed
but stevens told the justices that the judge's instructions to jurors at franklin's trial, similar to those typically used in texas, directs the jury to consider all mitigating evidence in light of the two questions
for example, stevens said the fact that franklin had been a well-behaved prison inmate for seven years could only be used to consider whether he was a continuing threat to society and not for some other reason
justice john paul stevens, no relation to the lawyer, asked zapalac why such evidence could not be used by jurors to decide that franklin was a man of good character ``who should not die.''
zapalac said franklin failed to show that any other kind of jury instruction would have helped him
franklin was convicted of abducting and killing 27-year-old mary margaret moran
his lawyer repeatedly said tuesday he was not attacking the supreme court's 1976 decision, in a case called jurek vs. texas, that upheld the state's death penalty law. but the justices seemed skeptical that overturning franklin's sentence could leave the 1976 ruling intact
chief justice william h. rehnquist suggested that stevens' arguments appeared to be ``cutting into jurek.''
justice antonin scalia said it seemed to him that the argument came down to whether ``the language of the statute'' did not allow full and independent consideration of mitigating circumstances
if the court were to rule that way, its decision could affect all texas death row inmates. out of about 2,000 death row inmates nationwide, 260 are in texas. that total is second only to florida, which has about 280 inmates on death row
a number of executions have been postponed in texas pending the court's decision in the case, which is expected by july
the case is franklin vs. lynaugh, 87-5546. museum</head>
after a struggle to fund an exhibit on the assassination of president john f. kennedy, the dallas county commission approved a $2.3 million contract to build an elevator to what was believed to have been the killer's perch
the eyes of the world will be on this project,'' said lindalyn adams, president of dallas county historical foundation. ``as sad as it is, it is the most important historical site in dallas.''
the foundation has worked 11 years to get the exhibit funded, and plans to raise $1.5 million more from private sources for additional renovations on the sixth floor of the former texas schoolbook depository
the warren commission determined that lee harvey oswald fired at kennedy from the sixth floor of what is now the dallas county administration building on nov. 22, 1963
the contract award was approved by a 3-2 vote monday to thomas j. hayman construction co., which could begin work as early as this week
the exhibit, ``the sixth floor,'' will be reached via an outside elevator that will carry an estimated 300,000 to 500,000 visitors annually to the exhibit without disrupting work inside
tony callaway, a partner in the architectural firm of hendrick callaway, said construction could be completed by november. foundation officials say they are unlikely to schedule the exhibit's opening nov. 22, the 25th anniversary of kennedy's assassination
we think it would be inappropriate,'' adams said
peace talks on afghanistan open their most crucial and fragile phase on wednesday, one that is widely hoped to produce a settlement to end a conflict that has claimed more than a million lives
but complex and potentially disruptive issues remain to be resolved during the united nations-sponsored talks before a package of agreements, drawn up during almost six years of bargaining, finally can be completed
u.n. mediator diego cordovez has said the new round of talks will focus on closing the gap between the varying timetables for withdrawing an estimated 115,000 soviet troops
but likely to dominate the talks is a question that is formally outside their scope: who will be in charge in kabul until all soviet troops have moved out?
delegates from afghanistan and from pakistan both said tuesday that they have come to geneva to finalize a settlement to end the 9-year-old conflict
but pakistan foreign minister zain noorani said his country would decide next week whether it was prepared to sign the peace package with the present marxist government of president najib, which it does not recognize
noorani said pakistan is continuing to press for the formation of a transitional government to coincide with the withdrawal of soviet troops. without it, he said, there can be no peace
but he said ``we have come to geneva with a constructive attitude to finalize the text'' of the four-agreement package
meanwhile, the head of the afghan delegation, foreign minister abdul wakil, told a news conference that he was looking forward to the new round with a ``sense of full optimism.''
the present leadership, he said, were ``not ambitious'' about retaining power. he said the timetable for the withdrawal was ``within negotiable range.''
the negotiations have come under mounting pressure since soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev announced feb. 8 that moscow will withdraw its troops beginning on may 15 if a final deal is sealed in geneva by march 15
he said the withdrawal could be completed in 10 months. pakistan originally demanded that the troops quit in three months but has gradually widened that span to eight months
pakistan wants the settlement to include the transitional government because it could oversee the safe return of more than 5 million anti-soviet afghan refugees, one-third of afghanistan's pre-war population
moscow has accused pakistan of creating last-minute obstacles to an accord and said the makeup of the government should be left to the afghans
the alliance of pakistan-based afghan resistance groups, claiming to represent 200,000 moslem guerrillas, responded last week by revealing its own plan for a government
it has ruled out any power-sharing with najib but offered a minor role to ``moslems presently living in kabul,'' a formula that could refer to moderates in the present government
yunis khalis, chairman of the seven-group alliance, vowed the guerrillas won't lay down their arms until the ``islamic government'' is set up
predictably, that concept has been rejected by najib and wakil, who heads the afghan delegation in geneva. wakil says he represents the ``only legal government in afghanistan which has been recognized by 80 countries.''
pakistan so far has not given its formal support to the guerrilla proposal and has hinted it prefers a more broad-based approach
the united states, which along with the soviet union is to guarantee implementation of the peace package, has been ambivalent in its reaction to the calls for an interim government
but the u.s. senate, in a non-binding resolution monday, urged formation of an interim government in kabul that is acceptable to the afghan resistance
u.s. undersecretary of state michael armacost, visiting pakistan last week, said the guerrilla plan was a ``very welcome step towards the resolution of the afghan problem.''
there has also been a lack of clear signals on when washington would be prepared to cut off its aid to the guerrillas, reported to have been about $700 million last year
the afghan monarchy was overthrown in 1978 and a communist government was installed. the soviets intervened at the request of the embattled new marxist government. picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng, reagan, as ... etc.</note>
president reagan was greeted by officials of belgium, and reunited with secretary of state george shultz, as he arrived today for a summit with america's nato allies
about seven hours after pledging that the united states will keep its troops in europe ``as long as europeans want them to stay,'' reagan's air force boeing 707 jetliner touched down on a windy, moonlit tarmac at brussels zaventem airport
he smiled and chatted amiably as he was greeted by shultz, who had just arrived from a meeting in london with jordan's king hussein. also on hand was belgium's prime minister, wilfried martens and foreign minister leo tindemans
following a five-minute courtesy get-together with tindemans in an airport salon, reagan was ferried by motorcade for an overnight stay at chateau stuyvenberg, a 1840 brick and stone palace one used as the favored residence of the belgium royal family
reagan, as he left the white house for a two-day nato summit in belgium, said the session comes at a historic moment for both east and west
for four decades, the combination of a strong common defense and pursuit of dialogue with the east has been a winning formula for nato,'' reagan said. ``it is a combination that can lead us to a future of peace, freedom and prosperity for generations to come.''
a throng of teen-age participants in the white house conference on a drug-free america, brought to the diplomatic entrance to give reagan a sendoff, sang ``god bless america'' as the president emerged
reagan attempted to calm allied fears that the u.s.-soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missiles portends an american abandonment of its long-time commitment to the european democracies
that historic agreement was possible because the alliance's steadfast political and military resolve backed up our negotiations with the soviets,'' reagan said
the nato allies are also concerned that the force of 326,000 u.s. troops stationed in europe might be cut due to the u.s. economic budget crunch
my atlantic colleagues and i will rededicate ourselves to maintaining the deterrent that has protected our freedom and prosperity for almost 40 years,'' reagan said. ``i will repeat to my colleagues my strong conviction that american troops will remain in europe, under any administration, so long as europeans want them to stay.''
as the first full-scale north atlantic treaty organization summit since 1982, the meeting has been touted as a chance for the 16-nation alliance to evaluate its goals and accentuate its solidarity
but the summit, reagan said, will not be held for ``self-congratulations.'' instead, he said, it will be a time for a rededication to the democratic goals that forged the alliance in 1949 in the face of the spread of soviet influence in eastern europe
if our common approach to the east over the years has given coherence to our message of peace and world freedom, it has been our unwavering commitment to defend ourselves that has given it credibility,'' reagan said. ``arms reduction can only succeed if it is backed up by a strong defense.''
his first priority, reagan said, ``is to maintain a strong and healthy partnership between north america and europe.''
reagan pledged anew to forge ahead with attempts to achieve a 50 percent cut in strategic nuclear arms, as well as a global ban on chemical weapons
he asserted that he also intends to press the soviets on human rights violations and its ``external aggression, '' apparently a reference to its involvement in nations such as afghanistan and nicaragua
the summit meeting comes as reagan prepares for an expected round of spring summitry with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, and as the allies must cope with the soviet public relations campaign that paints gorbachev as a champion of peace and arms control
for the most part, reagan will appear only in brief photo opportunities at the nato session. the meetings among the heads of state or government wednesday and thursday will be private
reagan is slated to deliver closing remarks on thursday
on monday, reagan previewed his slant on the summit in an address to the annual convention of the american legion
he promised to forge ahead with attempts to cut superpower strategic arsenals in half and to seek a ban on chemical weapons. but he also pledged that negotiations to reduce warsaw pact conventional forces will receive equal weight
the serious imbalance of conventional forces in europe must be addressed as an equally high priority,'' reagan said. ``warsaw pact tanks and artillery far outnumber our own. ours are positioned for defense, theirs for an offensive attack.''
reagan attempted to sweep aside european doubts about america's willingness to help its friends, but he advised that the alliance cannot stand still
the warsaw pact's numerical superiority and the soviet strategy which emphasizes surprise attack means that our remaining nuclear forces are fully capable of supporting nato's flexible response strategy,'' reagan said
at the same time we must modernize our chemical weapons to deter soviet first-use and we must provide for conventional forces that are capable of protecting free europe,'' reagan said
the reagan administration has failed to stop the heavy influx of illicit drugs into the united states, a group of congressmen told a white house conference on drugs tuesday
sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., said the administration has earned nothing more than a ``c'' grade for its efforts in the so-called war on drugs. rep. charles rangel, d-n.y., chided administration officials, including president reagan, for claiming the battle against drugs was being won
if we are winning the war on drugs, i wish the commanders would go out and tell it to the troops in the field,'' rangel said, drawing a standing ovation from a cheering crowd of about 2,000 at the white house conference on a drug-free america
it's tragic to believe we are winning this battle against drugs when we haven't even fired the first shot,'' said rangel, who is chairman of the house narcotics committee
he and six other members of congress criticized the administration, as well as their own colleagues, for not taking such actions as sanctions toward latin america countries who do not cooperate with the u.s. in trying to combat drug trafficking
they urged the creation of a drug czar to oversee the u.s. anti-drug efforts, the use of military forces for the interdiction of drugs from latin america countries and the mandatory, random testing of railroad employees
rangel and chiles were joined at the congressional forum of the five-day white house drug conference by sens. pete wilson, r-calif., and john c. danforth, r-mo., and reps. glenn english, d-okla., benjamin a. gilman, r-n.y., and e. clay shaw, r-fla
the conference, which was required by a 1986 anti-drug law, is bringing together drug abuse experts who will submit a final report and recommend solutions to the president and congress this summer
shaw told the enthusiastic crowd: ``we need to get away from a policy of containment. we want you to come up with a plan for victory. let's fight it like we fought world war ii, not like vietnam. let's fight to win.''
rangel and several others praised the role first lady nancy reagan has played during the past seven years in her anti-drug campaign, ``say no to drugs.''
thank god, we have nancy reagan,'' rangel said. ``she is the only voice we have in this administration. we have no domestic or foreign policy on drugs. if you want to fight this war, you have to put up the resources for the boys in the front lines.''
chiles and wilson also said there has been a lack of resources assigned to the the battle against drugs
nothing is a bigger threat internally or externally than the use of drugs,'' wilson said. ``we have to focus on the problem and set priorities before it engulfs us completely.''
chiles, wilson and rangel also urged reagan to impose severe sanctions against latin american countries, particularly panama, mexico and colombia, if they refuse to cooperate with the united states in combatting drug trafficking
under the 1986 law, the united states is to decertify and cut off aid to countries ``not fully cooperating'' with the united states to combat drug traffic
reagan decided tuesday that panama, afghanistan, iran and syria have not cooperated with u.s. efforts to stop the drug smuggling to american markets. but ann wrobleski, a state department official responsible for narcotics matters, said reagan planned no steps to penalize panama economically beyond measures already taken
reagan certified that mexico and colombia are cooperating with u.s. drug enforcement efforts, but ms. wrobleski said the president indicated that ``these countries should do more.''
reagan will ``wait and see'' if panama's military-dominated government improves its cooperation before deciding on additional sanctions, she said
the decisions concerning afghanistan, iran and syria will have no economic impact on them, partly because none is a u.s. aid recipient
chiles said many members of congress believe the administration has not used the certification process properly
this year, the good news is that panama is on the list,'' chiles said. ``on the other hand, mexico and colombia aren't. ... i think we have to continue to apply pressure against these countries.''
construction spending fell 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months, reflecting widespread weakness in all sectors of the building industry, the government reported tuesday
the commerce department said construction spending fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $395.2 billion in january following a revised 0.4 percent advance in december
economists said the decline was bigger than expected and will likely mean that construction will be a drag on overall economic growth in the first quarter of 1988
what was surprising about the figures was how widespread and pervasive the weakness was. virtually every category from housing to industrial to hotels and motels did poorly in january,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co
michael sumichrast, an economist and publisher of a construction industry newsletter, said he expects housing starts to fall by about 15 percent this year and non-residential construction to drop by 10 percent
i haven't found any area in the united states with strong housing activity. the only strong area is public construction, which i think will rise by about 4 percent,'' sumichrast said
the january decline was the largest since a 3.3 percent drop in march 1987, but some analysts said unusually severe weather in january may have contributed to the decline
residential contruction fell 2.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $191.3 billion as construction of single-family homes fell 2.2 percent and multi-family construction dropped 6.4 percent
analysts said single-family construction will strengthen in coming months because of recent mortgage-rate declines, but they forecast further declines in apartment building because of continued high vacancy rates
non-residential construction fell 2.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $90.9 billion, reflecting declines in office construction, hotels, factories and shopping centers
government construction spending was off 4.9 percent in january to a rate of $74.3 billion. the weakness in the public sector was led by a 3.9 percent fall in the largest government construction area, highway building, which declined to $24.8 billion
interest rates charged for price support crop loans made to farmers in march will be 6} percent, down from 7[ percent previously, the agriculture department said tuesday
milton hertz, executive vice president of the department's commodity credit corp., said the decline ``reflects the interest rate charged ccc by the u.s. treasury'' this month
america's preoccupation with the vietnam war and with the pow-mia issue is hurting u.s. interests in southeast asia, three american china specialists said tuesday after returning from two weeks in vietnam
they described a vietnam that is changing from a closed society dependent on the soviet union to a country more open to the west
the specialists said that if the united states does not take advantage of vietnam's new openness, it could cede influence in the region to the soviet union, china and japan
the united states must reassert itself in southeast asia,'' said helen chauncey, a professor of history at georgetown university. ``if it doesn't we will be left behind in what will be a realignment of political and economic forces.''
we have to stop letting the past determine our actions in the region,'' said brantly womack, professor of political science at northern illinois university. ``emotional topics like pow-mia issue are just red herrings.''
chauncey and womack were joined by frederic wakeman jr., a professor of history from the university of california, berkeley, in their call for a more open policy toward vietnam
wakeman urged increasing educational and business contacts with vietnam
in the long run our stakes in asia are enlarged by our training of the technocracy,'' he said, noting that china now has 20,000 students studying in the united states
the three specialists along with a fourth ``china hand,'' jonathan pollack, of the rand corporation, spoke at a briefing sponsored by the henry luce foundation, which supported their trip from dec. 29 to jan. 11
seven american china specialists took part in the voyage, which included stays in hanoi and ho chi minh city, once known as saigon, and talks with high-ranking vietnamese officials
for the first time, womack said, vietnamese officials, including foreign minister and vice premier nguyen co thach, are talking about vietnam's foreign policy in a ``post-cambodian future.''
vietnam invaded cambodia in december 1978, kicked out the chinese-backed khmer rouge and installed a puppet government in phnom penh
a stalemate ensued in indochina, with the soviet union and vietnam on one side and a resistance coalition, lead by prince norodom sihanouk, china, the united states and the free-market countries of southeast asia on the other
last year sihanouk split with the coalition and began direct negotiations with hun sen, prime minister of the vietnamese-backed government
nguyen van linh, vietnamese communist party chief, is pushing for economic change in vietnam, where the average annual income hovers around $125. he has recognized the need for foreign exchange and investment from the west
wakeman said south korean officials told him that both they and japan want to invest in vietnam because of its disciplined, inexpensive labor force
ever since the u.s. withdrawal from vietnam, american policy in indochina has been ``reactive,'' following the lead of china or the capitalist countries of southeast asia, such as thailand or indonesia, chauncey said
american officials who i've talked to express a deep-seated bitterness against the vietnamese,'' chauncey said. ``it's like, `they beat us so we'll let them stew in their own juice.'''
other american officials, womack said, think too much of the issue of american prisoners of war and soldiers missing in action
this issue is important to americans at home,'' he said. ``but it's hurting american interests abroad.''
a proposed electronic encoding system designed to prevent music from being copied by new digital audio tape recorders is flawed, the government said tuesday in a report that boosted efforts to introduce the new machines in the united states
there is no reason at this point why manufacturers should not be selling'' digital recorders in this country, said gary shapiro of the home recording rights coalition
but recording industry officials promised to sue any manufacturer that tries to sell the machines in the united states before the copying issue is resolved, either legislatively or through industry negotiations
digital audio tape, or dat, recorders can make copies of compact disc recordings without discernible loss of quality. the recording industry fears that such high-quality copying would cut into their compact disc profits
dat recorders costing about $2,000 were introduced last year in japan, west germany and france. but manufacturers have held off bringing them to the united states, where pending legislation in congress would require dat recorders to contain an anti-taping chip that would prevent home recordings
a spokesman for sony corp. of america, a dat manufacturer, said the study's results would not effect the company's decisions on when to introduce the recorders in united states
we're not rushing to market,'' sony spokesman stephen burke said. he said sony would have to evaluate the availability of software and other factors before deciding when to sell the recorders in this country
congress asked the national bureau of standards to study an encoding system proposed by cbs records in which a narrow band in the upper mid-range frequencies is removed from a recording. a dat recorder equipped with the anti-taping chip detects the ``notch'' and disables the machine's recording circuitry for a short period
the study found that the system is flawed because it doesn't always work, the ``notch'' can sometimes be heard by listeners, and the system can be bypassed ``for about $100 by a competent electronics technician.''
it's like selling you a camera that won't take certain pictures,'' said john lyons, director of the bureau's national engineering laboratory, describing the encoding system
lyons said the effect of the notch on the recordings ``is subtle. sometimes you can hear it and sometimes you can't.'' when the notch is discerned, it is often recognized as a missing note, he said
the bureau's testing team didn't study other anti-taping methods, he said. he added that while ``there are any number of ways'' of altering a recording to prevent copying, ``none of them is going to be fool proof.''
the home recording rights coalition said the results of the study were a victory for the consumer and signals the end of the legislation before congress
the coalition has been fighting all anti-taping efforts as infringment on the rights of consumers to make recordings at home, for their private use, of records, tapes and compact discs
jay berman, president of the recording industry association of america, questioned aspects of the study but said it virtually kills the cbs copy-code system ``as a viable political solution.''
but he said the recording industry remains committed to finding a solution through ``negotiation, legislation or litigation.''
berman said his is a $5 billion a year industry that is losing $1.5 billion a year to home copying. support...; add 2 final grafs of bush color bgng ``later in...</note>
vice president george bush said tuesday he wouldn't ``get into the gutter'' and respond to attacks by his republican presidential opponents
as the super tuesday collection of 20 primaries and caucuses draws near, bush toured the south and acted the part of front-runner
i have tried to wage an honorable campaign and i'm not going to get into this gutter answering every single attack,'' bush told supporters outside his broward county campaign headquarters downtown here. ``i want this nomination to be worth something after i win it and, believe me, i'm going to win it.''
i support the president. i have nothing to say about dole's charges, nothing at all,'' bush said later when asked by reporters to respond to dole criticism that bush has changed his version of the iran-contra affair repeatedly
bush began his day-long swing through south florida, scheduled to end in tampa with a foreign-policy lecture to political science students at florida international university in miami. he also briefly addressed a rally at the state university
things are going well but i am taking absolutely nothing for granted. i am convinced that whoever wins super tuesday will be the next president,'' bush said at the campus, where one of the introductory speakers was ``miami vice'' co-star michael talbott
bush also was joined for his trip by former arizona sen. barry goldwater, the 1964 republican presidential nominee, and florida gov. bob martinez
sen. bob dole stepped up criticism of bush in commercials and speeches that say bush has accomplished nothing of significance and questioning bush's role in the iran-contra affair
bush told the students that he was in charge of two meetings in which the 1983 grenada invasion was planned and he said he had helped form and head the south florida task force on drugs that began seven years ago
he expressed pride in the grenada invasion, saying: ``kicking castro out of grenada was a very good thing.''
bush said although there have been some slight improvements in relations with cuba and fidel castro's regime, he said there was no reason to expect a change in policy toward castro because he continues to ``support and export revolution.''
at the campus rally, bush took note of placards denouncing the new u.s.-cuban immigration accord that calls for normalized immigration of cubans in return for the return of mariel boatlift cubans. many in miami's large cuban exile community, which numbers more than 600,000, have said they strongly oppose sending any cubans back to cuba
bush pledged that cubans would not be treated in the same way as immigrants from other countries because they are fleeing oppression
later in the afternoon, bush drove a paving machine at the construction site of a development called mystic pointe, which will have 1,600 units for sale at an average $100,000 price
the project is adjacent to the prestigious turnberry isle development, which was mentioned in the national news last year when miami model donna rice disclosed she took a chartered trip to bimini with democratic candidate gary hart from the marina there in a yacht called the ``monkey business.''
a proposed free-trade agreement between the united states and canada will leave the u.s. auto industry at a competitive disadvantage, the united auto workers union told a house subcommittee tuesday
thousands of american auto workers' jobs would be at risk under the agrement's terms,'' said steve beckman, international economist for the uaw, in testimony before the trade subcommittee of the house ways and means committee
witnesses at the hearing, including a representative of auto parts makers and the state of michigan, center of the u.s. auto manufacturing, gave a mostly negative evaluation of the treaty's effect on the auto industry
the only witness who gave unqualified praise to the treaty was thomas hanna, president of the motor vehicle manufacturers association
the agreement takes on and resolves most of the trouble spots which were developing in the bilateral auto trade,'' he said
criticism of the pact, which seeks to eliminate nearly all tariff barriers between the u.s. and canada, centered on the failure of the treaty to eliminate present areas of discontent on the u.s. side
our current bilateral auto trade is skewed, to canada's benefit, by a number of trade-distorting practices,'' said rep. sander levin, d-mich., resulting in part from canada's domestic-content requirements and duty rebates on some auto parts
beckman said that by retaining canadian production incentives for honda, toyota and hyundai, the treaty provides ``a subsidy of canadian production, much of which will be sold in the u.s.''
hanna, however, downplayed the union's worry, saying the north american auto industry already has excess manufacturing capacity
canada's duty remissions programs ... are eliminated or phased out (in the agreement),'' he said. ``it makes no sense for the canadian government to lure more foreign auto investment, especially when much of the production would be headed for the u.s. market.''
lee kadrich, director of governmental affairs and international trade with the automotive parts and accessories association, said the treaty was ``a lopsided agreement that sanctions long-standing canadian protectionism.''
marc santucci, trade adviser to michigan gov. james blanchard, told the subcommittee the free-trade agreement would benefit the state in some areas, such as access to canadian electrical power and services resulting from increased trade
while important, these benefits cannot compare to the magnitude of trade in automotive products,'' santucci said
it is my view that the reagan administration sacrificed a critical opportunity to make significant changes in the terms of automotive trade to its imperative of getting an agreement,'' he said
for example, he said, canada's duty remissions program on auto parts, designed to foster canadian production, have been declared illegal under international trade agreements, yet the incentives will continue through 1997 for exports to third countries, allowing inroads by japanese and korean manufacturers
a sting operation caught 52 suspects who allegedly operated a $100 million poaching ring which dealt in tiger, bear, sea lion and rhinoceros parts, state officials announced tuesday
surrounded by bear gall bladders, bear-claw jewelry, skin parts, whole stuffed bears, skulls, dried abalone and the genitalia of seals and asian tigers, regional game warden chief chuck monroe said the investigation helped to ``wipe out the poaching of california's precious wildlife.''
an additional 23 people in southern california are expected to be charged as a result of ``operation ursus,'' the code name given the 23-month probe by the state department of fish and game
many of the animal parts were sold to asians who regard them as aphrodisiacs and tonics, he said
at one point, an undercover warden taking part in an illegal ``safari'' in the sierra was forced to kill a treed bear, monroe said as he described the complexity and danger of the probe
monroe said 74 misdemeanor complaints were filed against 52 defendants. the charges range from illegally killing bears to selling bear-claw jewelry at swap meets
so far, monroe said, agents have made 14 arrests and obtained three search warrants. those convicted of poaching can draw stiff fines and prison sentences, according to monroe
the display in the council chamber at colma city hall, just south of san francisco, represented $85,000 worth of exotic animals and organs seized in the sting, he said
the probe extended from the black bear range of northern california to san francisco and los angeles, with the arrests made over two months, said monroe
he singled out the yau hing apothecary ship in san francisco, object of a search that yielded ``bear galls, mounted bears, seal and tiger penises, abalone, rhino horn and powder.''
the probe recovered parts of animals taken outside the country and illegally shipped here, he said
russian bear gall bladders were sold in two cases, but one turned out to be from a cow, he said. the bear parts are purchased mainly by asians who believe eating the organs will transfer the bear's strength, health and courage
northern california arrests included a weaverville man for felony sale of 25 wet bear galls and five skulls; a fresno art dealer for felony sale of bear-claw rings and pendants; a san bruno exotic meat dealer for sale of bear hams, galls, skin and other bear and tiger parts, and a san bruno taxidermist for sale of a bear rug and skull,'' said monroe
in describing the illegal safari, monroe said the undercover warden was included in the party after passing himself off as a game hunter
he had been with them on several hunts,'' monroe said. ``when the bear was treed, the agent was with three outlaws, all of whom were armed. the time was 1 a.m. in a remote and steep forest. if he had refused to kill the bear, they surely would have suspected who he really was and his life would have been in danger.''
prior approval had been given for the killing ``if it became necessary,'' said monroe
although we regret the loss of the bear, we hope its sacrifice will prevent the loss of many other bears in the future,'' he said
while the increasingly widespread use of automobile lap-shoulder belts is saving hundreds of lives, the belts often are misused in ways that reduce their effectiveness, a federal study concluded tuesday
the national transportation safety board said the most common abuse of the car safety belts is that they are worn too loosely or _ often in the case of children _ are tucked under the arm or back because of concern about the high angle of the harness
the lap-shoulder belts are very effective and achieve about all that can be expected of them if they are properly used,'' said ntsb chairman jim burnett. ``but we have a lot of misuse and that problem has to be tackled.''
the safety board report is based on previous studies of seat belt use by other government agencies and the insurance industry as well as a detailed examination of 167 accidents in which at least one occupant wore a belt
lynne smith, one of the ntsb staff investigators involved in the study, said the findings were not meant to be a random statistical sample, but that the data is ``consistent with the finding of widespread (belt) misuse.''
an examination of the accidents showed that 21 percent of the motorists were wearing belts too loosely, reducing their protection, the safety board said. it also cited an insurance industry study of maryland motorists that put the estimate at about 25 percent
ms. smith said belts should be worn with no more than the width of a person's fist separating the belt from the body
the safety board urged the national highway traffic safety administration to require that safety belts meet standards as to the maximum amount of slack allowed or require that the belt systems be equipped with a ``pre-tension'' device that automatically pulls a belt tight a split second before a crash
in addition, the examination of accident cases by the ntsb showed that 7 percent of the belt users had the shoulder harness portion of their belt routed improperly under an arm or behind their backs
misuse of the belts was most prevelent among children, where one-third had belts not properly used. in some cases, children had belts routed under an arm or behind the back, two children were wearing a single belt or children wore belts with the seat in a reclining position, the report said
such misuse ... seriously degrades the protective capabilities of the lap-shoulder belt, reducing it to a lap-only belt with inferior crash protection,'' the safety board said
ironically, a number of auto safety pamphlets, including two distributed by the nhtsa and one by the american automobile association, have advised parents to place the shoulder belt behind a child if the harness crosses the neck or face
the safety board does not agree,'' the ntsb report said. ``... there is little evidence that small children or short adults are likely to be harmed by the shoulder portion of a ... belt.''
it said that in the accidents investigated it found no evidence ``that the shoulder ... belt induced more serious injuries to children than it prevented.''
the board called for the highway safety agency to revise its brochures
we have not had a chance to read (the ntsb report) and have no comment at this time,'' nhtsa spokeswoman betsy tyson said
among the accidents, according to the ntsb, in which belt misuse had tragic results, were:
_a head-on crash in which a woman passenger, who had loosened her shoulder harness extensively, was killed. her husband, the driver, had worn his belt snugly and ``walked away from the crash with moderate injuries,'' said suzanne stack, an ntsb staff researcher
_a crash in which a car struck a tree. the driver, who had worn his belt properly, escaped with minor injuries while the passenger, whose shoulder belt was routed under her arm, was killed
having an official flower and an official bird just isn't enough when for a state that depends on farming, so lawmakers dug up the idea of designating ``official iowa soil.''
proponents of a resolution declaring ``tama soil'' as the official soil of the state of iowa gained ground tuesday in the senate, winning agriculture committee approval of their measure
the lawmakers want to place tama, a thick, black topsoil found in at least 17 counties in east-central and eastern iowa, alongside the official wild rose, eastern goldfinch, oak tree and geode
tama soil represents the richest of soils found in the state,'' the senate resolution states
said sen. emil husak, ``it's the best we've got.''
a manners expert says a self-help video she plans to produce will be just the thing for young executives hoping to avoid ``power failures at power lunches.''
it's going to show young businessmen and women how to eat their way to the top with style and grace,'' marjabelle young stewart said tuesday
mrs. stewart, who has written 15 books on etiquette, said there was a growing need for well-groomed manners in the business world
instructions on how to hold silverware would be similar to a golf lesson, she said
i'll show them the proper grip and motion, everything,'' she said
mrs. stewart said more and more executives were scrutinizing the manners of prospective employees, taking applicants to lunch to ``see how they get along with the other members of the club.''
the video, ``the code of etiquette,'' will retail for $89.98 and is due for release in the spring, mrs. stewart said
it also may be useful for busy parents and could replace traditional manners lessons dispensed daily around dinner tables, she said
young working parents don't have time anymore to serve big meals every night and teach their children manners,'' she said. ``today, we're eating at the stove; eating out of the refrigerator; eating in front of the television.'' for deaf</head>
deaf president now'' was the cry, made by voice or by fluttering fingers, as about 1,500 people rallied at gallaudet university on tuesday to urge selection of the first deaf president in the school's 124-year history
today we are marching and speaking for our civil rights,'' allen sussman, former dean of student affairs, said in sweeping sign language to the cheering crowd of students, alumni, faculty members and administrators
i think it's high time that we are in control of our own lives and our own institution,'' sussman, who is a professor of counseling and psychology, told the associated press. communicating through an interpreter, sussman, who is deaf, said, ``i think we can do it much better and with more sensitivity than people who are not deaf
gallaudet, established by congress in 1864, is the only liberal arts college for the deaf in the united states
we need a deaf president now!'' student body president greg hlibok signed enthusiastically, leading the crowd in a signed and shouted chant of ``now! now! now!''
a presidential search committee gave the board of trustees a list of three finalists on monday to fill the post vacated by jerry c. lee, who resigned jan. 1 to go into private industry. two of the candidates are deaf and one can hear
the trustees were expected to name a new president this sunday after interviewing the finalists later this week, according to gallaudet officials. four of the 19 board members are deaf
the deaf candidates are harvey j. corson, 44, superintendent of the louisiana school for the deaf in baton rouge, and i. king jordan, 45, dean of gallaudet's college of arts and sciences. the third finalist is elisabeth a. zinser, vice chancellor at the university of north carolina at greensboro, who can hear
katherine ingold, a member of the search committee, said deaf applicants would not be given special preference
the committee's role is to find the best possible president for gallaudet university,'' she explained. ``but if there were two equally qualified candidates, one deaf and one hearing, of course the preference would be a deaf candidate.''
gallaudet has an enrollment of 2,200 university students, 400 high school students and 200 elementary school students. with senate hearing</note>
america's allies in nato should spend more money for defense, but congressional denunciations aren't the best way to get that done, defense secretary frank carlucci said tuesday
i quite agree with the thesis that our allies need to do more,'' carlucci told the house budget committee
but he added that ``i don't think it is very useful to simply berate the europeans on this.''
carlucci's comments came as president reagan was heading for europe to attend a two-day summit meeting of leaders of the 16-nation north atlantic treaty organization
rep. william gray, d-pa., the budget committee chairman, criticized nato nations for what he said was ``unequal sharing.'' he told carlucci ``our allies in nato are not doing, in my estimation, enough for their own defense.''
criticism of nato has long been popular on capitol hill, where legislators have complained time and again that american taxpayers are footing a disproportionate share of the alliance's defense bill
gray said the united states is devoting about 6 percent of its gross national product to defense while no other nato countries spend a little more than 3 percent
carlucci agreed that ``we need to make every effort to get our allies to do more,'' but he said they now do more than is ``generally recognized.'' for example, carlucci said, nato supplies 90 percent of the ground troops which would be used to halt a soviet attack
america's defense budget is 5.7 percent of the nation's gnp, not 6 percent, carlucci said. he also noted that american defense budgets have generally stayed even or declined in recent years
that wasn't good enough for gray, who noted that the recent reductions came atop large increases in reagan's first term
nato has long set a target for each member to increase spending by 3 percent a year after inflation, and most nations don't meet that target, carluicci said. the united states hasn't met the 3 percent target for at least four years, he added
both carlucci and adm. william crowe jr., chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, told the committee that nato needs to improve its conventional defenses in the wake of the treaty banning medium-range atomic missiles from europe
that is similar to the message reagan is carrying to nato allies and echoes a theme which the administration has been pushing since the treaty was signed dec. 8 by reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev
crowe detailed nato's shortcomings in non-nuclear weapons, but added, ``surely the prospect of having to fight 16 nations at once remains a sobering one for the kremlin.''
but, put candidly, both the level of (nuclear) deterrence and the nuclear threshold remain too low,'' crowe said. ``the chiefs have for a number of years consistently testified to that effect.''
it is essential for the nato members to correct'' the problems in non-nuclear weapons, he said
at the senate budget committee, yale historian paul kennedy said that u.s. allies ``ought to bear a larger share of the defense burden'' now that they have been rebuilt with u.s. help after world war ii
kennedy, author of the best-selling ``the rise and fall of great nations,'' said the united states should spurn protectionism and increase spending for basic technologies and for commercial research and development
jeane kirkpatrick, former u.s. ambassador to the united nations, agreed with kennedy that u.s. allies should bear more of the burden. but she criticized his view that there is a direct correlation between military spending and economic growth
sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., chairman of the panel, noted that ``the help we gave and the protection we've given have helped europe and asia grow back into power. now, they are friendly competitors. but while they've taken us to the woodshed in international trade, we're the ones paying for the guards at the woodshed door.''
it seems to me we are draining our power trying to do too much,'' said chiles. ``our adversaries are happy to see us try. our allies haven't done as much as they can to help.''
a 16-month-old girl pushed onto a fire ant mound by the family's dog has died of hundreds of insect bites, officials said tuesday
the bites probably would not have killed tiffany cheatham if she had not had a severe allergic reaction, said her physician, rex northup. she had been ``essentially comatose'' since she was hospitalized, northup said
tiffany was declared brain dead monday night, said kathy musial, spokeswoman for sacred heart hospital
the cause of death was anaphylactic shock in combination with toxic poisoning, northup said
tiffany was rushed to the hospital feb. 23 after the dog pushed her into an ant hill near her home in navarre, 20 miles east of pensacola, said chief don van derryt of the holley-navarre fire and rescue association
the girl's mother, lynn cheatham, and a neighbor had tried to remove the ants, taking off tiffany's clothes and putting her in a bathtub, but many of the insects were entangled in her hair
soldiers enforced calm in dakar tuesday following a day of rioting prompted by the announcement that the president was winning national elections. the president defended his decision to impose a state of emergency
streets were littered with stones and children played with spent tear gas cannisters on tuesday, a day after soldiers and riot police battled demonstrators. crews removed the shells of burned-out cars from the roads
riot police and soldiers were visible in much of the city, especially in the most densely populated neighborhoods. president abdou diouf met with members of his cabinet on tuesday to assess the situation
opponents had charged that the vote that gave diouf his second 5-year term was rigged. the president, in a communique read over national radio, said the voting was fair
the communique said diouf imposed a state of emergency to ``guarantee the legitimate aims of the people: peace, security, and economic and social progress.''
in an interview with french television, diouf also defended the decision to arrest the leading opposition presidential candidate, abdoulaye wade of the senegalese democratic party
i have the impression that our adversaries, as i had feared, are very bad losers and they had used many children in a maneuver to try to sow disorder and violence,'' diouf said
he said his actions were necessary to ``protect democracy.''
the preliminary tally showed diouf with 688,476 votes to wade's 299,998. two other candidates got less than 10,000 votes. the supreme court in this west african nation will announce the official results friday
radio broadcasts announcing that diouf was receiving about 77 percent of the vote sparked widespread demonstrations monday in the capital
the headquarters of wade's party, which was scene of considerable violence on monday, was quiet. the government said wade and other opposition leaders were being questioned about the riots
more than 260 people were believed to have been arrested during the violence monday
dakar's cheikh anta diop university also remained closed and riot police stood guard at several of the entrances
a week before the election, wade had said his party would become a liberation movement if the voting was rigged. on election day sunday and again on monday, wade and other opposition leaders accused diouf's socialist party of providing its supporters with cards to allow them to vote several times
diouf was widely expected to win re-election. opposition supporters view his government as a continuation of the leadership in senegal since it achieved independence from france in 1960. diouf succeeded president leopold senghor when senghor retired in january 1981
in another development, director of communications tidiane ndiongue apologized to a photographer who works for the associated press and was arrested for seven hours during monday's riots
the photographer, axel schulz-ebbers of west germany, said he was picked up outside opposition party headquarters and beaten. ndiongue said the ministry of information had informed police that accredited journalists were allowed to report on the disturbances
diouf's government has been praised by the united states and other western nations for maintaining a multiparty system, a rarity in africa. diouf also has been pro-western in international forums
a record-low number of rare right whales was spotted during an annual survey off the coasts of georgia and florida, the new england aquarium said tuesday
an aquarium team that spent february surveying the right whale population in their popular wintering grounds detected only one mother-calf pair and five whales traveling separately
the total was three below the previous low of 10 in 1984, said aquarium researcher scott kraus. the highest number spotted during the five years the survey has been conducted off the florida and georgia coasts was 26 in 1986, kraus said
he said it was premature to speculate on reasons for the apparent decline in the right whale population in the georgia and florida waters, which are considered popular calving grounds
we don't know whether the numbers are low because of a local problem that kept the whales away from that area,'' said kraus. ``or they may be somewhere down there and we are missing them.''
kraus said there were reports the water temperature had been abnormally high this winter. but he said it was not clear if that caused the whales to winter elsewhere
the aquarium will match the winter survey numbers with those recorded next spring when the whales return to waters from maine to nova scotia. that should help determine whether the right whale population has declined or if the whales chose a new location to spend the winter, kraus said
the surveys have been conducted in north atlantic waters for nine years and this was the fifth year of the survey off florida and georgia
the four prior surveys there have found right whales prefer to winter in waters five to 20 miles off the georgia coast and within two miles of the beaches of northeast florida
right whales are considered the rarest of the large whale species. the worldwide right whale population is estimated at 2,500. it it is believed that 240 to 350 live in the north atlantic
there are three types of right whales, which are known for their unusually large heads. the type found in the north atlantic are black right whales, which have black bodies and sometimes with white areas on the belly. black right whales grow up to 60 feet long
morning rush-hour was quiet tuesday as a massive rebuilding job began on one of the nation's busiest freeways, a project that had state highway officials ready for the worst
the $210 million overhaul will widen the dan ryan expressway from eight to 10 lanes, and while work is under way _ for six-month periods both this year and next year _ traffic will be squeezed into half the normal number of lanes
on tuesday several lanes were closed on each side of the freeway for building crossovers and making surface repairs
commuters and traffic experts have feared that the project could create massive traffic jams because the highway is one of the nation's busiest, carrying 225,000 cars daily, but things went smoothly early monday
the congestion was apparently zilch,'' said ed nash, a spokesman for the illinois department of transportation. ``the ryan was clear the whole morning and there was no buildup of traffic.''
the state had conducted a months-long publicity campaign, urging commuters to use alternate routes, car pool or take public transportation. the chicago area transportation study distributed 37,000 ride-sharing applications and doubled its list of car-pool applicants to 6,000
state officials say the overhaul of the three-mile stretch will greatly improve the commute on the 11-mile freeway
the work will cost more than the $179.7 million it took to build road 25 years ago
a defense attorney attacked the credibility of a pilot testifying tuesday in the smuggling trial of carlos lehder rivas, winning an admission that the man continued trafficking drugs while cooperating with the government
leverett francis, 66, testified monday that he made six cocaine flights in 1979. those flights, made with admitted smuggler ed ward, are those listed in the indictment of lehder, 38, and co-defendant jack carlton reed
lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders of colombia's violent medellin cartel of cocaine smugglers, is on trial on charges that he and others conspired to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the united states from colombia via norman's cay in the bahamas from 1978 to 1980
under cross-examination tuesday by defense attorney jose quinon, francis admitted he conducted other smuggling activity while we was cooperating with the government and testifying before a grand jury in 1980. francis is testifying under immunity from prosecution
he said he made flights to jamaica for other people in 1980, bringing in either hashish or marijuana
francis, a former navy pilot, bristled when quinon used the word `lie' when discussing inconsistent statements in his testimony and his grand jury appearances eight years ago
i don't like the word, `lie.' i looked it up in the dictionary last night and i suggest you do the same,'' he told quinon
quinon laboriously questioned francis about his grand jury testimony in 1980 and many times tuesday francis said he couldn't remember what he said in 1980
i'm sure the grand jury testimony as a whole is correct,'' francis said
lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise
reed, of san pedro, calif., is charged only with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy
defense attorneys and prosecutors got into several exchanges tuesday out of the jury's presence
after one of a number of bench conferences with the judge, defense attorney ed shohat accused u.s. attorney robert w. merkle of saying to him: ``you're going to sleaze yourself right into a hole, mister.''
shohat called merkle's remarks ``patently offensive.''
merkle, however, argued that he made the comment to assistant u.s. attorney ernst mueller and said: ``they're (defense attorneys) going to sleaze themselves into a hole.''
u.s. district judge howell w. melton said he didn't plan to take any action and told the attorneys to present the exchange to a grievance committee if they desired to do so
a middle-aged gunman riding on a motorbike fatally wounded the chief executive officer of a greek chemical company as he was driving to work tuesday. a left-wing group claimed responsibility
a police spokesman said alexandros athanassiadis, 59, was hit four times in the chest and stomach as he reached for a pistol that he kept in his car
the shooting took place at 8:15 a.m. in rush-hour traffic on kifissias avenue, a main highway leading north from the city center, according to the spokesman, who was not identified in line with police regulations
he said the attack was ``a carbon copy'' of the 1983 killing of capt. george tsantes, a u.s. navy officer attached to the american embassy who was shot by two men on a motorbike at the same kifissias avenue intersection
and the same terrorist group, the november 17 organization, asserted responsibility for both slayings
the spokesman gave this account of tuesday's attack
athanassiadis had the passenger window down and was chatting to someone in another car at a red light when two men on a motorbike came up on his right-hand side
a white-haired man in his 50s'' riding behind the younger, dark-haired driver fired at least six bullets at athanassiadis from a 45-caliber pistol
the two men turned down down a side road into the psychico suburb where the motorbike was found abandoned
athanassiadis died at the hygeia hospital during emergency surgery, dr. vassilis georgoulis said
a typewritten note found in the street near the intersection and signed ``november 17'' said athanassiadis was ``a classic capitalist ... indifferent to the health of the workers and the environment.''
athanassiadis was chief executive officer of hellenic chemical products and fertilizers and also was a director of greece's largest holding group, the non-profit bodossakis foundation
he had headed pyrkal, an ammunition and explosives manufacturing firm, until it was taken over by premier andreas papandreou's socialist government in 1982
the note claimed that a hellenic chemical products plant in western athens that athanassiadis planned to expand ``holds one of the largest responsibilities'' for air pollution in the capital
november 17 terrorists have asserted responsibility for 10 other killings since 1975. none of the slayings has been solved
it also boasted of carrying out the remote-control bombings of two buses carrying u.s. military personnel in april and august 1987 that wounded 26 americans and three greeks
other business executives said athanassiadis maintained a low profile, refused to hire bodyguards and always drove his own car
he kept a pistol beside him in the car ever since learning that he was probably on the november 17 hit list,'' said one businessmen, who asked not to be identified for fear of reprisal
it was the first fatal attack by november 17 terrorists since february 1986 when steel magnate dimitris angelopoulos was shot while walking to work in central athens
november 17 is named for the day in 1973 that troops crushed a student rebellion against the military dictatorship that ruled greece from 1967-74
in its previous declarations the group demanded the closure of u.s. military bases in greece and said the government had failed to reform greek society
government spokesman sotiris kostopoulos issued a statement expressing ``very deep sorrow'' at athanassiades' killing and saying ``the greek people as a whole condemn such terrorist actions.''
the cars of the white pass &amp; yukon railroad will roll along the gold rush trail of '98 this spring for the first time in more than five years, officials said tuesday
the railroad plans to reopen may 12 as a seasonal tourist line out of skagway, said marvin taylor, vice president and chief executive officer for the white pass &amp; yukon corp. ltd
everything is a go,'' taylor said in a conference call from skagway. ``we anticipate 50,000 passengers this first year.''
for a $65 ticket, tourists will get a 3{-hour, 40.8-mile round trip to the peak of the white pass. most of the route shadows the deadhorse trail, which miners followed into the klondike gold fields in 1898
the railroad took the place of the trail in 1900 and ran until october 1982, carrying passengers and freight the 110 miles between skagway and whitehorse, capital of the yukon territory
the line closed after losing its freight business during a worldwide mining slump. the 800 people of skagway lost 150 railroad jobs; whitehorse lost 50
white pass is trying to sell its freight equipment, and taylor said unless there's an unforeseen development boom in whitehorse, it's unlikely the full line will reopen
but tourism may prompt further expansion in 1989 and after, taylor said
the line will stop short of the canadian border this year because the railroad did not have time to negotiate the crossing
the reopening was assured when the alaska teamsters and united transportation unions agreed monday to contract concessions, taylor said. the primary concession allows the train to run with three-person crews instead of the traditional five-person crew used on freight lines, he said
the may-through-september business will employ more than 20 people during the season and four to six people year-around, taylor said
it will cost about $1 million to get the line running by may 12, he said
the line itself is in fairly good condition, but the passenger cars need substantial renovation, he said. the railroad plans to run up to four round trips a day, carrying an average of 250 passengers each. color on airport arrival; inserts 8th graf, bgng, his motorcade ... with material on trip to palace; subs 19th graf, bgng, besides the ... to restore dropped reference to the netherlands among list of nato member countries.</note>
president reagan, urging western solidarity in arms talks with the soviets, arrived tuesday for the first nato summit in six years after pledging that u.s. troops will remain in europe ``so long as europeans want them to stay.''
after air force one touched down on the tarmac at brussels zavantem airport in windy conditions, reagan was reunited with secretary of state george shultz, who had arrived from london, and met briefly with belgian officials
in a gesture of reassurance given in a departure statement tuesday morning at the white house, reagan pledged that american troops will remain in europe ``so long as europeans want them to stay.''
he also promised to protect nato's interests in any arms deals with the soviet union. ``we will never sacrifice the interests of this partnership in any agreement with the soviet union,'' he said
after stepping down the ramp from his boeing 707 jetliner, reagan smiled and chatted amiably as he was greeted by shultz, who had just arrived from a talks jordan's king hussein. also on hand were belgium's prime minister, wilfried martens, and foreign minister leo tindemans
posing for pictures at the airport, reagan said he was still troubled by congestion and cold-like symptons that had bothered him in washington. ``the allergies are still bothering me,'' reagan said, adding in an aside to shultz that his ears were stopped up after the long flight. reagan coughed loudly as reporters were ushered from the room
following a five-minute courtesy get-together with tindemans in an airport salon, reagan was ferried by motorcade for an overnight stay at chateau stuyvenberg, a 1840 brick and stone palace one used as the favored residence of the belgian royal family
his motorcade _ extending nearly 20 cars _ included the now standard anti-sniper team and reagan's armored limousine and a backup flown in from washington, complete with district of columbia license plates
the two-day meeting at nato headquarters in brussels, beginning wednesday, brings together the heads of state or government of the 16-member north atlantic treaty organization. the conference sets the stage for reagan's expected summit in moscow with soviet leader mikhail gorbachev in late may or early june
with the nato headquarters site under unusually tight security, canadian prime minister brian mulroney was the first to arrive. the representatives of 14 other countries were scheduled to arrive wednesday
in his departure statement, reagan hailed the newly signed treaty to abolish u.s. and soviet intermediate-range nuclear missiles (inf), but said, ``the purpose of this summit is not self-congratulations.''
our first priority is to maintain a strong and healthy partnership between north america and europe, for this is the foundation on which the cause of freedom so crucially depends,'' he said
reagan said the united states will continue to press for a 50 percent reduction in strategic nuclear weapons and a global ban on chemical weapons
beyond that, he said the nato leaders will try ``to give negotiations on conventional forces a new start, as well.''
if our common approach to the east over the years has given coherence to our message of peace and world freedom, it has been our unwavering commitment to defend ourselves that has given it credibility,'' reagan said
arms reduction can only succeed if it is backed up by a strong defense,'' he added. ``my atlantic colleagues and i will rededicate ourselves to maintaining the deterrent that has protected our freedom and prosperity for almost 40 years.''
the nato session opens wednesday with remarks by britain's lord carrington, the nato secretary general, followed by two restricted working sessions, a luncheon and dinner
another restricted working session is planned thursday, followed by closing remarks by carrington and reagan, and a news conference by shultz, who broke off his shuttle diplomacy in the middle east to join the president in brussels
besides the united states, the members of the alliance are canada, britain, west germany, france, italy, belgium, denmark, greece, norway, iceland, luxembourg, portugal, spain and turkey and the netherlands
alton g. keel, the u.s. nato ambassador, said on the eve of the summit that he thought the leaders would likely declare that nato places a high priority on negotiating conventional arms stability in europe
alliance sources, declining to be identified publicly, have said that such a declaration may be in addition to an overall statement which will boil down to a renewed pledge of confidence in nato policies and goals
it is hoped the new conventional talks can begin in earnest in the fall in vienna
there's a general consensus now'' on key elements of nato's negotiating position, namely, that cuts should be ``assymetric'' in view of the warsaw pact's large numerical advantage in conventional firepower, according to keel
the summit is designed to be a public display of alliance solidarity despite peace and disarmament gestures from the soviet union
it also is intended to reassure europeans that the inf agreement will not leave them vulnerable to superior numbers of warsaw pact tanks and artillery
the budget crunch in the united states has triggered some fears in nato about a possible reduction in the 326,000 american troops stationed in western europe
planners on both sides of the atlantic said the leaders planned to play down disagreements, such as the updating of nato's short-range nuclear arms, most of which are deployed by the united states in west germany, and disputes over basing u.s. forces in europe
despite the u.s. role as the leader and paymaster of nato, reagan will play a low-key role in public at the two-day meeting, delivering only a brief summary statement at the close on thursday
in all, the schedule called for reagan to be away from washington only 57 and one-half hours, including 15 hours and 15 minutes on air force one flying to and from brussels
he will return thursday evening, in plenty of time to celebrate his 36th wedding annivesary friday with his wife, nancy
reagan's themes for the meeting were carefully sketched out in advance in a series of public remarks, including an address broadcast to europe last week and a speech on monday to an american legion convention
he warned that the west must remain vigilant about the soviet union and be skeptical about its intentions. reagan also said nato must keep nuclear forces in place and up to date
the president said the warsaw pact's numerical superiority in non-nuclear forces _ the so-called conventional forces _ must be addressed with the same urgency as the problem of strategic nuclear weapons
and he suggested that nato members should pay a greater share of the alliance's defense burden
testifying to the house budget committee tuesday, defense secretary frank carlucci said america's nato allies should spend more money for defense. but he also said that congressional denunciation of alliance partners is not the best way to get that done
i quite agree with the thesis that our allies need to do more,'' carlucci said. but he added that ``i don't think it is very useful to simply berate the europeans on this.''
an air force plan to spend $6.1 million on world war ii-style leather jackets to boost flight crews' esprit de corps is drawing flak from civilians and retirees affected by budget cuts
i'm upset with this leather-jacket bit,'' hugh enyart, a retired air force major who now lives in nearby fairview heights, said tuesday. ``if we have to measure our patriotism by whether or not we have leather jackets, god help us, we're in trouble.''
about 280 of the 53,000 ``bomber'' jackets will go to flight crews with the military airlift command at scott air force base
to me it doesn't reflect the professionalism of the air force,'' said enyart, a former official of the air force association, a national organization that works to promote a strong national defense
it reflects a bunch of people wanting leather jackets,'' he said
the nation's armed services were ordered in november to slash 10 percent from their budgets for fiscal 1989, which begins oct. 1. the air force share of the reductions for the year amount to about $10.5 billion. smaller custs were ordered for the current fiscal year
critics say the jackets, which cost $115 each, are a prime example of waste
enyart said he had received calls from about 20 people _ civilians as well as active and retired air force personnel _ supporting his stance after local reports about his criticism of the jacket purchases during a time of budget austerity
wide-ranging spending reductions throughout the air force include curtailment of equipment purchases and personnel cuts. even retirees' medical benefits have been reduced, enyart said
a hiring freeze has been in effect at scott's military airlift command since dec. 8, and last month, an undetermined number of temporary part-time civilian jobs were eliminated at scott
on tuesday, the base's command began offering voluntary early retirement to eligible civilian workers
the jacket purchases should be cut before jobs, said carl denton, an official of the national association of government employees' local r7-23, which represents about 3,000 civilian workers at scott
it would seem to me that people putting hamburger on their table should come before they (air force officials) put a new jacket on a pilot's back,'' he said
the air force sees it differently
the air force plans to issue these flying jackets to primary crew members in order to enhance esprit de corps and to recognize the air force's front-line pilots, navigators, weapons officers and enlisted crew members for their important contributions to the nation's defense,'' said a statement tuesday from military airlift command officials at scott
the air force plans to distribute the jackets to active and reserve forces
the jackets are to be purchased during the 1988 and 1989 fiscal years, officials say. delivering them to flight crews is expected to take about a year, beginning in june
walden pond, the retreat idealized by henry david thoreau in 1845, is at the center of a debate over whether it should be preserved or whether it should, as thoreau wrote, ``belong to the public.''
the legislature's natural resources committee declined tuesday to adopt a bill that would ban swimming at walden in concord, 15 miles west of boston
the bill would eliminate a manmade sand beach, restrict fishing and boating and require construction of sound barriers beside nearby roadways. instead, committee members said they would consider expanding membership on the pond's citizen advisory panel
fencing off walden pond and banning swimming would be contrary to both the philosophy of thoreau and the wishes of the owners who gave the property to the state,'' department of environmental management commissioner james gutensohn told the committee
i'm sure the indians swam at walden pond, i'm sure henry david thoreau swam at walden pond and i'm sure the people of boston should,'' gutensohn said
the chief opponent of continued recreation at walden, mary sherwood of connecticut, did not attend the hearing though the legislation was sponsored by her group, walden forever wild inc
sherwood, a former concord resident, said in a telephone interview that 50 years of public recreation at the pond have endangered its fragile banks and spoiled a pristine site
they've turned it into another coney island,'' sherwood said. she charged dem officials with spending their spare time scouring thoreau's writings looking for a quotation that would support public recreation at the pond
gutensohn did slip a thoreau quotation into his remarks. the 19th-century naturalist philosopher said, ``as in many countries precious metals belong to the crown, so here more precious natural objects of rare beauty should belong to the public.''
a state pamphlet on the pond quotes thoreau as writing in his ``journal'' in 1850, ``when the frogs dream and the grass waves, and the buttercups toss their heads, and the heat disposes to bathe in the ponds and streams, then is summer begun.''
gutensohn said that the deed from the forbes, heywood and emerson families bequeathing walden to the state in 1922 specified that it be preserved ``for the public who wish to enjoy the pond, the woods and nature, including bathing, boating, fishing and picnicking.''
today the 62-acre pond in a 333-acre reservation receives 350,000 visitors a year. on summer weekends crowds frequently exceed its rated capacity of 1,000 visitors, according to don faron, supervisor of the reservation
state officials acknowledge that walden took a beating when little was done to prevent visitors from causing erosion and much done to render the pond unrecognizable to its 19th-century admirers
anytime you have a first-class resource you have a threat of overuse,'' said stuart weinreb, the state's project manager for the pond
in the 13 years that the dem has controlled walden, the state has spent $2 million on projects to upgrade and preserve the site. another $500,000 has been set aside for restoring the banks of the pond. gutensohn said the money will cover about half of the restoration job
in addition, the state plans to limit parking around the pond to keep down summertime attendance. say</head>
the cuban military has some surface-to-surface missiles in its inventory, but none has a nuclear warhead and none could reach the united states even if they did, u.s. officials said tuesday
the defense and administration officials commented under questioning prompted by republican presidential candidate pat robertson's continued insistence, in the face of denials, that cuba may have soviet-made nuclear missiles aimed at the united states
the officials said cuba has about five dozen frog-4 and frog-7 battlefield missiles, date to the 1960s
the frog-7, when originally introduced by the soviets, could carry either a conventional or nuclear warhead, ``but we're confident no nuclear warheads ever went to cuba for that missile and it doesn't have any range anyway,'' said one source who requested anonymity
according to the reference book ``jane's weapon systems,'' the frog-7 has a range of only about 43 miles _ or half the distance between cuba and florida. moreover, the rocket has no guidance system to direct it to a specific target
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater dismissed robertson's missile claim when the candidate first advanced it last month. he said cuba had been under extensive surveillance since the 1962 missile crisis and there was ``no evidence'' any other nuclear weaponry had ever been deployed there by the soviet union
the officials contacted tuesday endorsed that assessment, but most insisted they not be identified on grounds they wished to avoid entanglement in the presidential race
the sources said cuban president fidel castro long ago assembled the strongest military in the caribbean, but they said his forces posed little offensive threat to the united states
on the other hand, they said, cuba does serve as a major outpost for soviet forces, particularly surveillance units, and it supports communist movements around the world from nicaragua to angola and ethiopia
cuba is a horrible force for instability, but it is not a military threat to us directly,'' said one pentagon official
and it is certainly not a nuclear threat. they do not have any missiles that could reach the united states _ nuclear or conventional _ and they do not have any nuclear bombs to hang on the jets that could reach us.''
cuba's military power has not appreciably increased in recent years,'' said one administration official. ``rather, their forces have been modernized to keep pace.''
in overall terms, they really are not any more of a direct military threat to us than they were 10 years ago,'' said another source. ``it's serving as the host to the russians that bothers us.''
navy cmdr. robert prucha, a pentagon spokesman, said the defense department endorsed the most recent assessment of cuban military power published by the international institute for strategic studies in london. according to that assessment, the cubans have an active-duty military force of approximately 175,000, of which 145,000 are in the army, 12,000 in the navy and 18,500 in the air force
within the army, the pentagon believes the cubans have about 65 of the frog missiles, prucha said. also in the cuban inventory:
_a wide variety of soviet-made surface-to-air missiles that could be used against attacking aircraft, as well as short-range artillery rockets like the bm-21 and bm-24
_about 950 tanks, including 300 of the more capable t-62 tanks, and at least 50 bmp infantry combat vehicles
_two koni-class navy frigates made by the soviet union, along with three diesel submarines, 77 fast-attack patrol boats and 15 mine sweepers
_more than 250 soviet-supplied combat aircraft, including at least 50 modern mig-23 flogger ground-attack jets and more than 100 mig-21 jet interceptors
three years ago, adm. wesley mcdonald, then the head of the u.s. atlantic command, described cuba's forces as well equipped ``to defend cuba against anything short of a massive invasion.''
he said the cuban air force _ with aircraft like the mig-25s _ had ``the range to reach portions of the southeastern u.s.a. and most of the caribbean sea area.''
but that doesn't mean they have anything nuclear to hang on those planes,'' said one pentagon source. ``we maintain constant surveillance on cuba, including sr-71 (spy plane) reconnaissance
everything that goes in to cuba is monitored, and nuclear weapons haven't gone in.''
cia director william h. webster spoke out tuesday against efforts to place an independent watchdog at his agency like those already in place at 19 other federal departments
webster said a proposal by sen. arlen specter, r-pa., to place an independent inspector general at the spy agency ``will actually prove to be counterproductive to an effective inspection and investigation process.''
he told the senate intelligence committee that the presence of an investigator with access to personnel and secret records could deter foreign intelligence services and other sensitive sources from sharing information with cia, fearing its possible disclosure
the proposal for an independent inspector general at the cia grew out of last summer's iran-contra investigation, which found the agency's current inspector general ``lacked the manpower, resources and tenacity'' to uncover many of the abuses turned up during that probe
the current inspector general is chosen by the agency's director and lacks the institutional independence of the ig post at most other federal departments. the post is now held by william donnelly, a 33-year cia veteran appointed by webster
specter, a member of the intelligence committee, said the panel is unable to oversee the agency as thoroughly as an in-house watchdog would be able to do. he noted that other departments with sensitive intelligence operations, like the pentagon and the state department, have independent investigators inside their bureaucracies
specter's bill would permit the cia director to deny investigators access to documents or personnel if needed to protect sensitive secrets or an active covert operation. but the director would have to defend such an action to the congressional intelligence committees
both june gibbs brown, the pentagon's inspector general, and sherman m. funk, inspector general at the state department, testified they have had no problems with disclosure of classified information
charles bowsher, director of the general accounting office, congress' investigative arm, said a review of inspector general operations government-wide had found they substantially strengthen accountability and improve operations
we believe that a statutory ig would be as appropriate and effective for the cia as it has been for the other agencies,'' bowsher said
and he said he was concerned that making a tour of duty in the inspector general's office a part of routine career development for cia employees, as webster proposed, would further rob the office of independence
specter said that while he did not doubt webster's good intentions, ``the problem is that you're not going to always be director of the cia. our memories are fresh about a director of the cia who did not always forward information to this committee'' _ an apparent reference to william j. casey, webster's predecessor
democratic presidential candidate richard gephardt, described as ``middle america at its very best,'' received the endorsement tuesday of two former governors of south carolina
standing in the sun-bathed steps of the state capitol, the missouri congressman told supporters the nation's future depended on ``our ability to gain control of our economic destiny.''
former governors robert mcnair and richard riley defended the candidate against charges that his trade program was protectionist
mcnair said gephardt ``has faced up to putting america first with a fair, sound and sensible trade bill. one who believes if we're going to open our markets up, you open your markets up.''
mcnair said the gephardt bill was ``not a protectionist piece of legislation, as some have tried to portray it, but it is what's best for this country.''
he's not a protectionist at all,'' said riley. ``he's a pragmatist.''
riley, who served as governor from 1977 to 1985, said of gephardt, ``he's middle america at its very best.''
gephardt said he supported legislation that would limit the growth of textile imports to 1 percent a year
an estimated 45 percent of the jobs in south carolina are in the textile industry
the import restriction legislation is an issue in the republican as well as democratic race
republicans bob dole and pat robertson, campaigning for support in the south carolina gop primary this saturday support the bill. gop rivals george bush and jack kemp oppose it
for people here to have the kind of opportunity we all want, we have to have a new trade policy,'' said gephardt
this is a state that had a great textile industry, a great fabric industry,'' he went on. ``that industry is in trouble, has been in trouble in part because we have not had leadership and policies at the federal level that will guarantee fair treatment for the textile workers and the textile companies here in south carolina.''
the missouri congressman said that as president he would press for policies that ``will give the textile workers of south carolina an equal right to sell their products in markets all over the country and give them the right to not be impacted by unfair trade practices by countries all over the world.''
gephardt's campaign manager bill carrick described riley, who was governor of south carolina from 1977 to 1985, as a leader of the progressive wing of the democratic party in the state
he said mcnair, who was governor from 1965 to 1971, was a leader of the ore conservative wing of the party
he said their dual backing was ``a nice little bookend endorsement.''
earlier tuesday, gephardt visited former president carter in plains, ga. carter made it clear that with fellow georgian sam nunn not in the race he had no plans to endorse any of the democratic presidential candidates before the nominating convention next july
heavy snow fell in california's sierra nevada, shasta and siskiyou mountains tuesday on a generally gray day in the west, while thunderstorms dumped hail in oklahoma
snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 6 inches at blue canyon, calif., and 1 inch at austin, nev. crescent city, calif., received .87 inch of rain
a severe thunderstorm watch was posted tuesday afternoon for portions of southwestern oklahoma and northwestern texas
showers and thunderstorms developed across south-central oklahoma and the texas panhandle during the morning, and dime-sized hail fell near vanoss, okla
scattered snow was also reported in eastern and southern wyoming, east-central nevada, southwestern utah and western upper michigan
rain reached from central california across west-central nevada and into parts of oregon, idaho and utah
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 10 degrees at massena, n.y., to 86 degrees at mcallen, texas. the nation's cold spot tuesday morning was pellston, mich., with a low of 16 degrees below zero
for wednesday, the national weather service forecast calls for rain in the lower great lakes, michigan, the lower ohio valley and southern illinois. showers and occasional thunderstorms will reach from missouri across northern louisiana and northern mississippi, and northeast texas across eastern kansas
snow in the higher rockies will turn to rain at lower elevations, and scattered rain is expected in the pacific northwest
high temperatures will be in the 20s in minnesota, northern wisconsin, upper michigan and northern maine; in the 30s and 40s from southern maine across new jersey, the remainder of the great lakes, in iowa and northern missouri, the northern plains, and from colorado to montana; in the 70s from georgia and florida across the lower mississippi valley; in the 80s on the lower texas gulf coast; and in the 50s and 60s across most of the rest of the nation
the reagan administration on tuesday called attacks on iranian and iraqi cities a dangerous development in the persian gulf war and adds ``a new urgency'' to united nations work on an arms embargo designed to force a truce
phyllis oakley, a state department spokeswoman, condemned the missile raids and said they represent ``a serious escalation of the iran-iraq war.''
attacks on civilians achieve no military end,'' she said. ``they fuel the psychology of hatred which is responsible for continuing this destructive conflict.''
iraq said tuesday it fired 16 missiles into tehran. it was the first long-range rocket attack on the iranian capital since the war began in september 1980. iran said 27 civilians were killed
the official iraqi news agency said iran hit baghdad with two missiles late tuesday night, killing or wounding an unspecified number of civilians
last july, the u.n. security council adopted resolution 598 calling for a truce in the war and pledging to impose an arms embargo against either party that refused to heed the call. iraq has said it would accept a cease-fire but iran has declined to go along and the united states has been pressing the world body to impose the weapons ban on iran
we believe adoption of an arms embargo resolution to enforce 598 has taken a new urgency with the renewal of the war of the cities,'' mrs. oakley said
we urge all members of the security council to act on this now, without further delay, particularly permament members who have special responsibilities to provide leadership,'' she said
she was referring to the soviet union, said another state department official, speaking on condition of anonymity
the united states offered a compromise last week in an effort to satisfy u.s. demands for quick passage of a u.n. resolution against iran and meet a soviet desire for more diplomacy by u.n. secretary general javier perez de cuellar, the official said
it would permit immediate passage of an embargo followed by a 30-day delay in implementation and another peace effort by perez de cuellar
the official said that in response to u.s. pressure to accept the compromise, the soviet envoy to the security council, alexander m. belonogov has said he is awaiting a decision from moscow
on march 1, the rotating chairmanship of the security council will pass from the united states to yugoslavia
mrs. oakley said an arms embargo ``will make it more difficult for iran to pursue the war,'' but will not mean an end to the conflict if iran desires to continue the fight
negotiations between iran and iraq will also be necessary, she said
the family of a comatose man who was used as a human guinea pig filed suit tuesday against the doctor who carried out the experiment
pascal louette, 24, who went into a deep coma following an auto accident, died sunday after dr. alain milhaud placed him on a sabotaged medical device to see if the effects matched those of a similar case, currently the subject of a trial in poitiers
louette was considered clinically dead at the time of the experiment, which was performed at the regional hospital center of amiens
news of the experiment was made public a week ago and touched off a furor in france
health minister michele barzach suspended milhaud on feb. 24 from his duties as chief anesthesiologist at the hospital center
the louette family's lawyer, alain lhote, said his clients filed suit against milhaud for ``willful injury of a person unable to defend himself because of his mental or physical state.''
one can't treat a human being in the way pascal was treated,'' said lhote
he said louette's parents were not properly informed about the medical care their son was receiving and suffered ``a double traumatism: the loss of a loved one and also the theft of a soul which was stolen from them.''
the exact date of the experiment hasn't been made public. it was announced feb. 23 in court testimony at the poitiers trial. louette was injured late last year and transferred to the regional hospital center on jan. 19. he fell into a deep coma shortly thereafter and was kept alive on a respirator
milhaud's experiment was prompted by a trial of three physicians in poitiers, accused in connection with the 1984 death of a woman following an operation to remove a tumor
the woman, nicole berneron, received nitrogen oxide instead of oxygen during resuscitation after the operation. a report later showed the tubes supplying the two gases had been switched
the state prosecutor on tuesday asked for 15-year prison terms each for drs. bakari diallo and denis archambeau, both anesthesiologists. he did not ask for a specific sentence for dr. pierre desforges-meriel, charged with involuntary homicide
singer-actress bette midler and her husband have bought a 38-acre property on kauai island that the federal government confiscated in a drug case
u.s. marshal faith evans said midler and her husband, martin von haselberg, paid $1.5 million cash for the parcel, which includes a partly completed tri-level home and a panoramic view of the pacific ocean and a river
the property, situated near kilauea, was among 141 acres seized by the justice department in 1986 after authorities charged that the owners bought it with money from illegal drug sales, evans said
midler grew up in hawaii and attended the university of hawaii before moving to new york to pursue her career
pornographic film star john holmes was questioned again by police in the unsolved 1981 bludgeoning murders of four people as he lay gravely ill in a hospital bed, officials said wednesday
holmes, who starred as johnny wadd in a series of sex films in the 1970s and early 1980s, is suffering from aids, the los angeles times reported tuesday, quoting anonymous sources
holmes' attorney, mitchell egers, said wednesday that his client did not answer the questions
egers confirmed that holmes was hospitalized with a serious illness but refused to say if he suffered from aids. rumors that holmes was suffering from aids have been circulating in the pornographic film industry for about a year
the incurable ailment usually is transmitted through sex, shared hypodermic needles, tainted blood products and from pregnant women to their babies
holmes was acquitted in 1982 of the 1981 bludgeon murders of four people in the exclusive hillside community of laurel canyon. the crime remains unsolved
however, the times said a new witness had surfaced and was in custody out of state. that, combined with holmes' illness, prompted police to re-question him in his hospital bed, the newspaper said
detective tom lange, supervisor of the murder investigation, would say only that the case remained active
holmes, 43, the premier male sex film star of the 1970s and early 1980s, made hundreds of sexually explicit films and thousands of peep shows
he was featured as the detective johnny wadd in films such as ``tell them johnny wadd is here,'' ``liquid lips'' and ``blonde fire.''
holmes was cleared in 1982 of killing ronald launius, 37; william deverell, 44; barbara richardson, 22; and joy miller, 46, all of whom were beaten to death
prosecutors said the four were part of a theft ring for which holmes acted as a middleman to los angeles nightclub owner adel nasrallah, also known as eddie nash. holmes allegedly fenced stolen property for the group to nash, who allegedly paid for the loot with drugs
nash was sentenced later to eight years in prison for possession of two pounds of cocaine worth an estimated $1 million. he was released after serving less than two years
president reagan brought more to europe tuesday than just a message of western military solidarity. air force one ferried in three pizzas for nato ambassador alton keel
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater, who accompanied reagan to brussels on air force one, told reporters the pizzas were purchased in a suburb of washington, d.c, by deputy white house chief of staff kennethy duberstein
fitzwater described keel, a former acting national security adviser, as a ``junk-food freak.'' closure</head>
major american jewish groups said tuesday they have distanced themselves from the u.s. government's hotly contested move to close the plo observer mission to the united nations
they (u.s. officials) are not doing this at the request of the american jewish community,'' said phil baum, associate executive director of the american jewish congress
anti-terrorism legislation ordering the palestine liberation organization's mission closed by march 21 has put the united states in an isolated position at the united nations. an emergency general assembly session is under way on the mission's future
scores of speakers, including close u.s. allies, called the move a threat to the independence of the united nations and asked the united states to submit the dispute to binding arbitration
the state department and the united nations both say closing the mission would violate the 1947 treaty under which the u.n. headquarters is based in the united states. but attorney general edwin meese iii reportedly is going to enforce the legislation
the state department tried to head off the legislation, but major jewish groups supported it. they saw it as a way to get at their main target, the plo's washington office, according to baum, elan steinberg, executive director of the world jewish congress, and others
our hope was to induce the state department to use the powers it had to close the washington office,'' baum said. ``we wanted it to send a symbolic message that the plo is a terrorist organization and it was not welcome in the united states.''
in a meeting last year with deputy secretary of state john whitehead, the groups offered not to press for closure of the u.n. mission if the washington office was shuttered, the jewish leaders said
in september, the department ordered the plo office in the capital closed
baum said his group told meese in a feb. 12 letter it would not press for the u.n. mission's closure. he said meese has not replied
baum said major jewish groups sent a similar letter to congress on dec. 3
we recognized that the headquarters agreement was a complicating factor,'' he said
but by then the legislation had won the support of such presidential aspirants as sens. bob dole (r-kan.), jack kemp (r-n.y.) and paul simon (d-ill
it took on the life of its own,'' baum said
several speakers in the general assembly accused the united states of sacrificing international commitments to the pressure of domestic politics. they said closing the mission will further damage u.s. prestige at the united nations and cripple the u.s. middle east peace initiative
arab league spokesman clovis maksoud on tuesday laid much of the blame for what he called a ``corrosive legislative tantrum'' on the american israel public affairs committee, a powerful lobby
he said the reagan administration ``fell into the trap. it underestimated the hold of aipac on a majority of the congress.''
the committee and the zionist organization of america were the only jewish groups who kept lobbying against the plo u.n. mission once the government closed the plo washington office, baum and others said in interviews
the 159-nation general assembly is expected to approve a resolution wednesday calling for arbitration and saying closure of the mission would violate the treaty. another resolution asks the world court to rule on whether the united states must submit to arbitration
the resolutions are sponsored by the soviet union, several soviet allies and by members of the movement of nations professing non-alliance with either superpower
israel was initially scheduled to address the general assembly tuesday, but the address was later moved to wednesday because of the length of other speeches
here is the text of a statement released tuesday, purporting to be from the kidnappers of kidnapped lt. col. william r. higgins, as translated from the arabic by the associated press:
in the name of god, supporter of the oppressed, to the sons of our struggling people in lebanon and palestine, to the free men of the oppressed world
in addition to our previous statements on the detention of american cia agent col. higgins, we are keen to explain the following:
1. the propaganda that is being waged nowadays is aimed at minimizing the espionage role of col. higgins and diverting the issue of his detention into other incorrect objectives. it is also aimed at circumventing his political activity with certain suspicious currents and elements in the south
2. the attempts undertaken by the american administration and the criminal reagan (who) is moving inside and outside lebanon to ensure a quick release of higgins so that he will not reveal secrets and make confessions are aimed at stopping the investigation of this criminal at a stage that will not allow us to find out all about the american-israeli conspiracies against our people and nation. this is a failed attempt to wriggle out of the impasse the reagan administration is currently trapped in
3. but we declare today that we have uncovered solid facts about an american-israeli deal being hatched for south lebanon. once the investigation of higgins is over, we will place the details at the disposal of our ulema (moslem clergy) to make of them whatever they deem fit
4. we reiterate that we shall continue the investigation of this spy to complete his record, which is full of crimes. we shall put forward all the facts to our people at the proper time
5. israel's persistence in daily attacks to suppress the islamic uprising of the struggling palestinian people and the steadfast villages of jebel amel (shiite name for south lebanon), and the shuttles of american criminal shultz to abort the achievements of this uprising will make us more determined to put this criminal higgins on trial. this will be done after the completion of the investigation to make the world understand that any hand that reaches out to hurt (our) pride, islam and the dignity of our people will be chopped off
the organization of the oppressed on earth
prince andrew and his wife, sarah, took in a hollywood glamour tour tuesday that brought them face-to-face with a gregarious movie robot, bashful celebrities and curious everyday folk bearing flowers
the duke and duchess, midway through a 10-day southern california tour to promote britain, greeted such actors as vincent price, roger moore, jack nicholson, robin leach, roddy mcdowall, pierce brosnan and joseph cotten
i think they were modern and literate and good-mannered and were handsome people. i loved being here,'' cotten said after pausing with the royal couple at the academy of motion picture arts and sciences
jack lemmon and brosnan were visibly nervous, and humbled, by the meeting
it gives one butterflies,'' brosnan said afterward. ``i wasn't sure about bowing correctly. i didn't know what to say.''
lemmon said later that he realized that ``for them it was like doing a scene over and over about 100 times. ... it is such a grueling schedule for them. they couldn't have been more charming.''
the couple had started the day earlier at the showscan film co. a special effects studio in culver city
greetings, salutations, hello,'' said ``number 5,'' the impish robot from the movie ``short circuit.'' attended by a half dozen technicians, the robot presented sarah with a bouquet, then spun on its triangular tank treads and introduced sarah to company officials
as sarah entered the building, ``number 5'' commented: ``nice hat.''
thank you,'' replied the duchess, who also accepted a bouquet and a rose from fans in the small crowd outside the studio
the wildest scene in the studio visit consisted of two hair-raising rides for andrew in something called the ``dynamic animation theater.''
the prince and seven other people took seats on a hydraulically operated platform in front of a curved movie screen as a film shot from the perspective of the front seat in a roller coaster roared by
for the next several minutes, they were jolted up and down, backward and forward, and finally brought to a lurching halt. the duchess, who is three months pregnant, watched from a director's chair, telling her husband later, ``you looked very funny.''
the royal couple also saw a breakaway bottle smashed harmlessly over the head of their private secretary, lt. col. sean o'dwyer
the rain that has been dampening crowds for much of the visit eased for the day's events, which also included a luncheon at the bel age hotel in west hollywood that was held by the british academy of film and television arts
the royals heard actress anjelica huston salute british contributions to film, particularly in comedy. britons have an ability ``to puff themselves up to their most british, then burst the balloon,'' she said
dudley moore then gently mocked miss huston's serious speech, beginning his remarks: ``your royal highnesses, extinguished guests ...''
i was reminded of our legacy,'' the british entertainer said. ``the heritage of shakespeare and milton that courses through the veins of every red-blooded english film star who is living now, very nicely, thank you, in marina del rey.''
the yorks, both 28, are touring to promote trade and as patrons of uk@la '88, a festival of british arts. they are staying aboard the 416-foot royal yacht britannia in long beach. norwegian-swedish comments and changes throughout. no pickup.</note>
moslem kidnappers freed two scandinavian relief workers tuesday, nearly a month after they had been kidnapped in southern lebanon, and left a note saying the hostages were ``proved innocent.''
swede jan stening, 44, and norwegian william jorgensen, 58, employees of the u.n. relief and works agency, were released in sidon, 25 miles south of beirut
norwegian charge d'affaires peter raeder told the associated press, ``i saw them. they looked a little bit pale but in fairly good condition.''
reporters in sidon said the u.n. workers were freed at 8 p.m. and turned over to salah salah, a representative of the palestine liberation organization
they said salah took the two to sunni moslem leader mustafa saad, whose militia controls sidon. militiamen then drove the former captives to moslem west beirut and delivered them to unrwa security chief john carolan
unrwa's acting director, john fennessy, said the two were taken to a hotel in christian east beirut to rest
he expressed ``the relief and satisfaction of my colleagues and myself'' that the scandinavians ``have at last been released and are unharmed.''
stening and jorgensen were abducted near sidon on feb. 5. their release reduced the number of foreign hostages held by extremists in lebanon to 23
also on tuesday, a statement purporting to be from the kidnappers of lt. col. william r. higgins said the u.s. marine will be put on ``trial'' for espionage when his captors finish questioning him. there was no way of authenticating the statement
members of a group called the revolutionary cells kidnapped the scandinavians. in a handwritten arabic statement delivered to a western news agency in beirut late tuesday the group announced the two men had been released. a photograph of the scandinavians accompanied the statement
it did not say what they had been accused of, but in earlier statements the group claimed the men were involved with the intelligence service of an unidentified foreign power
u.n. officials blamed the abductions on palestinians acting individually without a political motive
government officials in norway and stockholm expressed gratitude to those who had helped secure freedom for the two
the one-paragraph statement from the kidnappers said:
after the two employees were proved innocent, they were released. we ask unrwa to reverse its decision to freeze its activities, and we remind them that we will not allow suspicious elements to use international agencies for cover.''
the u.n. agency, which cares for an estimated 280,000 palestinian refugees in lebanon, suspended most of its medical, social and educational services after the abductions
the statement on higgins was delivered to a western news agency in beirut without a picture of the u.s. marine, who was abducted feb. 17 near tyre
it was typewritten in arabic and signed organization of the oppressed on earth, the name of the group that claimed responsibility for abducting higgins, 43
the statement said israel's tough response to 12 weeks of palestinian riots in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, and the middle east peace shuttle of u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz ``make us more determined to try this criminal, higgins.''
it repeated the claim that higgins was a cia agent
it was the third statement issued since the marine from danville, ky., was seized by gunmen who stopped his u.n. car on the coastal highway
the organization of the oppressed on earth is believed made up of pro-iranian shiite moslems. it has claimed responsibility for kidnapping 12 lebanese jews in moslem west beirut since 1984 and says it killed eight of them
higgins is one of nine american hostages in lebanon. held longest is terry a. anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, kidnapped march 16, 1985
the marine colonel was the commander of 76 u.n. observers from 16 nations who monitor truce violations on the lebanon-israel border under a 1949 armistice agreement
his observers are attached to the 5,800-member u.n. interim force in lebanon that was sent into southern lebanon in 1978 as a buffer between israel and palestinian guerrillas
the statement about higgins said in part: ``the criminal reagan is moving inside and outside lebanon to ensure a quick release of higgins so that he will not reveal secrets and make confessions. but we declare today that we have uncovered solid facts about an american-israeli deal being hatched for south lebanon.''
in washington, the state department said it had no comment except to repeat the u.s. position ``that all the hostages should be released immediately and unconditionally.''
in stockholm, foreign minister sten andersson said of the release of the unrwa workers, ``i would like to express the government's great gratitude to all who have helped achieve this result.''
prime minister gro harlem brundtland of norway issued a statement in oslo saying: ``on behalf of the government and myself i'm extremely relieved and happy with the release of william jorgensen of norway and his swedish collegue jan stening.''
in vienna, unrwa spokesman ron wilkinson said stening and jorgensen probably would travel to vienna where the agency has its headquarters
he also said the agency will ``still have to think about our operations'' in lebanon, adding: ``we have to have certain guarantees of safety.''
eight bodies have been recovered so far since a small craft carrying about 45 illegal aliens from the dominican republic capsized near puerto rico, authorities said tuesday
authorities and a survivor say most of the 45 made it to shore safely after the boat sank sunday night near this small fishing village, about 85 miles west of the capital city of san juan
police lt. jose vega said two bodies were found monday and six more were pulled from the ocean near the beach tuesday
strong waves hampered the search, which was expected to resume wednesday
police maj. cesar gracia said the dominican residents boarded the craft on the east coast of dominican republic saturday night, when the weather was clear for the 90-mile trip across mona passage. as they neared puerto rico, large waves overturned the boat about 180 feet from shore
the boat was estimated to be 20 to 30 feet long
one survivor was hospitalized and another was taken into custody monday by the immigration and naturalization service in this u.s. caribbean commonwealth
aguada has been the landing site for many boats bringing illegal aliens to puerto rico in search of a better life. immigration authorities estimate the number of illegal dominicans living in puerto rico to be between 40,000 and 160,000
soldiers with tear gas fought protesters hurling stones in the poor, densely populated capotillo neighborhood of the capital tuesday. ten people were hurt and about 50 were arrested
the disturbances began with a strike to protest increases in the cost of living. schools and stores in the neighborhood closed, but traffic and activity were normal in the rest of santo domingo
elsewhere in this caribbean nation of 6 million, residents of azua and barahona provinces south of the capital burned tires, blocked roads and stoned businesses and cars
in similar protests last week, five people were killed and 20 injured in eight of the 26 provinces of the dominican republic, which shares the island of hispaniola with haiti. the unrest is the worst faced by president joaquin balaguer since he took office in august 1986
the inflation rate is running at about 30 percent a year. the foreign exchange value of the peso meanwhile has skidded. it takes 5.3 pesos to buy one u.s. dollar, about 72 percent more than the 3.85-1 ratio several months ago
many people are furious that a 5-gallon container of cooking oil has doubled to 84 pesos. taxi drivers resent paying 3.6 pesos for a gallon of gas that a few months ago cost 3 pesos
