new york (ap) _ aluminum maker kaisertech ltd. sued its chairman for millions of dollars tuesday, alleging he violated securities law by improperly engaging in profitable short-term buying and selling of company stock
the suit against alan e. clore came a day after the reclusive british investor agreed to sell his 27 percent stake in kaisertech to texas oilman charles hurwitz, a move that appeared to irritate kaisertech officials and signaled management turbulence at the oakland, calif.-based company
neither clore nor hurwitz are considered familiar with the aluminum business. clore acquired his position at kaisertech after a lengthy takeover struggle last year. hurwitz's intentions toward kaisertech remain unclear
asked if it was considered unusual that a company would sue its own chairman, kaisertech spokesman robert w. irelan said: ``it's the first time we've done it.''
in a statement, kaisertech said its suit filed in a manhattan federal court resulted from clore's disclosures in a securities and exchange commission filing monday about his sale of stock to a hurwitz-controlled company, los angeles-based maxxam group inc
kaisertech contended the sec disclosures showed clore and his affiliates made about $4 million in undisclosed profits via so-called ``short-swing trading'' _ trading done within a six-month period _ of kaisertech stock
under federal securities law, a company or its stockholders are entitled to recover such profits from a director or officer who engages in short-swing trading
clore, who usually resides in switzerland, could not be reached for comment on the lawsuit, part of a rapid series of events concerning the stock of the aluminum producer
in los angeles, the investment firm jefferies &amp; co. said it was selling 1.39 million shares of kaisertech stock to maxxam for $16.68 million or $12 a share
combined with the 6.2 million shares acquired from clore, plus an option to buy his 8.2 million convertible preferred kaisertech shares, the shares purchased from jefferies would give maxxam about one-third of kaisertech's approximately 45 million shares outstanding
wall street's reaction reflected skepticism about a possible takeover move. in composite new york stock exchange trading tuesday, kaisertech fell 12{ cents a share to $11.75, after rising $1.12{ in the previous session
kaisertech said in a statement monday it would have preferred that clore had sold his stock to a broader range of investors, reflecting concern about what maxxam intends to do with its stake. maxxam officials said it was premature to speculate on whether it would attempt to acquire more
clore's maneuvering to sell his kaisertech shares came against a background of heavy pressure on him to cut losses that stemmed from the october stock market crash
if clore hadn't found a buyer by a monday deadline, he could have faced default on loans he had obtained by using kaiser stock as collateral. after the stock plunged in october, lenders wanted repayment
his sale of stock came as the company was rebounding from six straight years of losses. kaiser has sold its chemical, oil and gas businesses, slashed debt and concentrated on its core aluminum business. secrets</head>
authorities told a group of activists tuesday that 170 soviet jewish families cannot be allowed to emigrate because members have been exposed to state secrets, a member of the group said
vladimir kislik, who has been trying to leave for 15 years, said 10 jews from moscow and leningrad met with officials of the communist party central committee and justice ministry
on jan. 20 the group had given vitaly siderov, a central committee official, a list of more than 300 families denied permission to emigrate and requested a review
siderov promised an answer within a month. the activists returned feb. 21, were told the review was not ready and were asked to come back tuesday, kislik said in a telephone interview
they met with siderov, alexander gorkovluk of the central committee's propaganda department and officials of the office of visas and registrations and the justice ministry, he said
from the list of 300 families, kislik reported, the officials said 25 people had been authorized to emigrate. he said 20 had received notification since the list was drawn up jan. 1
about 80 other people were refused exit visas because parents or spouses have not certified that they have no financial claims, kislik said. soviet regulations require an applicant for emigration to furnish such a guarantee
kislik said some families were refused for emigration because they do not have close enough relatives in israel, which ``fully contradicted'' what secretary of state george p. shultz said foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze told him last month in moscow
shultz told reporters feb. 22, after meeting with shevardnadze, that the soviet minister promised ``flexibility'' in applying rules that require applicants to have close relatives abroad
he said shevardnadze also told him ``categorically'' that the only barrier to emigration is past work involving state secrets
many people whom the government alleges were exposed to state secrets say they saw the information years or decades ago and that it does not compromise the soviet union
i last worked in atomic science 22 years ago and they are refusing me because of that reason even today,'' kislik said
he added that the officials indicated they would meet with the jews again to discuss the cases of 20 soviet jews who have heart conditions, cancer or other ailments and who want to leave. ``we also gave them a list of people from 60 to 82 years old who want to emigrate,'' he said
in february, soviet authorities allowed 723 jews to emigrate, according to the geneva-based agency that helps the emigrants resettle. that was a slight increase from the january total of 658
according to the intergovernmental committee for migration, jewish emigration from the soviet union last year reached 8,011, its highest level since 1981. first add should stand for ams as background.</note>
bob dole was locked in a tight race with george bush tuesday night in fractional returns from vermont's republican presidential primary, a low-key, low-stakes tuneup for super tuesday. michael dukakis had an early advantage over jesse jackson in the democratic race
sen. dole was flush with endorsements in his effort to challenge the vice president in his new england backyard. jackson, in the state with the fewest blacks in the nation, hoped to finish a strong second to massachusetts gov. dukakis as he did last weekend in maine
gary hart, the big winner here in 1984, was far, far back in the pack where he has been stuck all year
the elections were ``beauty-contest'' primaries. vermont's national convention delegates won't be apportioned until next month in party caucuses, and the candidates have practically ignored the state to concentrate on the south. the primary took place on town meeting day when vermont's 328,466 voters decided town budgets, road repairs and a host of other local issues
with just a handful of vermont's 262 precincts reporting, bush had 288 and dole 287. pat robertson, whose supporters said they were focusing on the april caucuses, had 61 votes. jack kemp was not active in vermont and had just 38 votes
among the democrats, dukakis had 336 votes and jackson 198. sen. paul simon, who made no real effort here, had 29 votes and rep. richard gephardt _
who campaigned several times in the state _ had 28. hart had 16 votes and sen. albert gore jr. was not on the ballot
dukakis, governor of neighboring massachusetts, boasted 15 paid staffers and up to 60 volunteers in vermont, while most organizations felt fortunate to have two or three paid staffers. but jackson's rainbow coalition has been active in vermont since his 1984 presidential campaign and prompted an uneasy mixture of concern and admiration from the dukakis organization
jackson hoped to do well in vermont to follow up a strong showing last weekend in maine and demonstrate he can win broad support from people of all races. ``the issue of another person's skin, ought not to be an issue,'' said chris wood of the jackson campaign
among the republicans, bush had the strongest organization, but dole was helped by heavyweight endorsements from sen. robert stafford, rep. james jeffords and former gov. richard snelling
vermont's primary was overshadowed by next tuesday's elections in which 20 states will apportion hundreds of delegates. the only thing at stake in vermont was news media attention, bragging rights and the bush-dukakis regional winning streak. they both already have won the new hampshire primary and the maine caucuses and have high hopes next week in massachusetts and rhode island

