minority students drew up a contract tuesday to end the eight-day takeover of a hampshire college building that was held to protest racism at the private liberal arts school
we all want it over,'' said anita fearman, a spokesman for the 40 black, hispanic, indian and other minority students who have occupied a dormitory office since feb. 23
a tentative agreement was hammered out late monday in meetings with the school's president, adele simmons, and two other administrators
students drew up the formal contract tuesday and college officials were expected to sign it wednesday. specifics of the contract were not released tuesday
protesters said they expected to continue holding the dakin house office until wednesday despite the apparent agreement
among the demands dean of faculty penina glazer said the administration agreed to was the hiring of a full-time adviser for the campus group that occupied the building, students of underrepresented cultures
the school also agreed to allow a professor to serve part-time as dean of multicultural affairs and to try to win grants to increase the number of third world books in the library, she said
the college was founded in 1965 as an alternative to the traditional education offered at nearby smith, mount holyoke and amherst colleges and university of massachusetts. students design their own courses of study and advance through three divisional examinations requiring them to complete individual research projects
about 100 of hampshire's 1,100 students are minorities
two weeks earlier, an occupation sparked by campus racial violence ended at at umass when chancellor joseph duffey agreed to demands including increase funding of minority student programs
meanwhile, in springfield, the massachusetts commission against discrimination has found probable cause in a complaint by roland a. wiggins, 54, a black professor at hampshire college, alleging he was denied a 10-year teaching contract in 1986 because of race
the panel will attempt to resolve dispute or, failing that, conduct public hearings, hurst said
wiggins, a music professor, said he had worked under short contracts since he was hired in 1979 and in 1985 had won backing of faculty, students and the college appointments committee for a 10-year appointment
the college cited complaints that wiggins often was unavailable to students, submitted evaluations late and had ``offered little leadership in the music program, although he was the senior member,'' according to hurst's report
no blacks have been granted 10-year contracts, the longest the college provides, hurst said in his report. the school does not offer tenure. six of the 86 professors at the college are black, he said. humanist protest, u.s. outlook, edits to tighten. picks up 17th graf pvs, slennet, 41 ...</note>
the post office on tuesday began postmarking nearly all letters mailed in britain with the words ``jesus is alive!'' as part of a private arrangement financed by an evangelist
jewish leaders criticized the christian cancellation as potentially offensive
the special postmark, which also contains a small cross, will last six weeks and was paid for by paul slennet, who sells religious literature at two bookstores in southend-on-sea, east of london. he said god told him to buy the postmark
the state-owned post office said slennet paid the equivalent of $88,500 for the privilege of having every letter mailed through 68 of britain's 69 sorting offices stamped ``jesus is alive!''
the post office has adopted various methods of boosting revenue under prime minister margaret thatcher's conservative government, which believes that state-owned services should pay for themselves
receiving the postmark will be all mail _ including that sent abroad _ excluding parcels, periodicals and those letters stamped by businesses that have their own franking facilities. nearly 52 million letters are mailed daily in britain
the printing of this slogan in no way confirms post office approval of its contents,'' said post office spokesman duncan marshall. ``the slogan is not considered to be contentious.''
shimon cohen, spokesman for lord jakobovits, the chief rabbi of britain, said his office was ``flooded with phone calls'' after news of the slogan appeared in newspapers tuesday
we recognize that this is a christian country and we have the utmost respect for the primacy for the church,'' cohen said in an interview
however, ``we do fear that the slogan that will be carried is by implication addressed to non-christians and could well cause offense and resentment. we've made our feelings known to the post office,'' he said
rabbi charles emmanuel, chairman of the assembly of rabbis of the reform movement of great britain, said: ``this country allows me freedom of religion, and an official organization should not have accepted such a commission that will infringe not only upon my rights but the rights of other non-christians.'' marshall said his office was aware of ``a number of complaints.'' asked if these had caused any change of heart, he said: ``i've had no indication of that.''
he said no complaints had been received from other non-christian groups
however, the british humanist association, a national association for the non-religious, said the decision showed ``insensitive disregard'' for other beliefs
imagine the furor if we had asked to have `jesus is dead' printed on hundreds of millions of letters,'' said association spokesman martin horwood
he said he is writing the post office asking that the postmark be withdrawn
in washington, a u.s. postal service official said the chance of something similar in the united states was unlikely. dick rustin, manager of the stamp information branch, said limits are strict on special cancellations and religious messages are excluded
britain's post office regulations require paid messages to be ``non-controversial, non-political and likely to be generally acceptable to the public,'' marshall said
slennet, 41, said he got the idea five years ago listening to a sermon in which the preacher talked about collecting stamps and postmarks
the lord has since confirmed to me in various ways that this is the right thing to do,'' he said in an interview. ``in 1986 that small quiet voice we hear when god speaks said `postmark'.''
he said that he has informed christian groups around the country of his idea and received contributions toward paying for it
slennet belongs to intercessors for britain, an evangelical organization. he said the slogan was chosen in the spirit of easter
the plymouth post office isn't printing the slogan because it already had been booked for one commemorating england's defeat of the spanish armada in 1588. right-wing groups probably not affected. picks up 6th graf pvs, another section ...</note>
the government tuesday proposed a bill to outlaw foreign funding of political activity, a move that could cripple anti-apartheid groups and churches thus far spared from the new crackdown on opposition
no court challenge of the restrictions would be allowed
last week, the government banned 18 predominantly black organizations from political activity, including the largest anti-apartheid coalition and largest labor federation
leading anti-apartheid clergymen vowed tuesday _ before the new bill was introduced _ that the churches would take over some of the programs of the banned groups and more aggressively confront the government
the new legislation, called ``the promotion of orderly politics bill,'' would prohibit all organizations from receiving money from abroad for political purposes and would empower the justice minister to seize foreign funds received by certain groups. his powers would be indefinitely retroactive
the foreign funds provision was not expected to hurt right-wing organizations, which receive most of their money from donations from within south africa
however, another section of the bill could apply to right-wing white supremacist groups that oppose the government's limited apartheid reforms. it sets a penalty of two years in jail or a fine of about $2,000 for anyone who ``says or does anything'' to foment hostility or violence between different racial, cultural or religious groups. the penalties would apply to anyone who displays a banner, emblem or slogan deemed to convey such hostility, and also to anyone who attends a gathering where such items are displayed
the south african council of churches, which includes most major protestant denominations and is engaged in civil rights work, has received more than 90 percent of its funds from abroad in recent years
the roman catholic church cooperates with the council of churches but receives substantial overseas funds separately
the rev. smangiliso mkhatshwa, secretary-general of the southern african catholic bishops conference, said the bill might be difficult to enforce
if the church says supporting the families of detainees and paying legal fees is the work of love, the work of evangelism, it is difficult to see how the government can define for the church what is pastoral and what is political,'' he said
in parliament, helen suzman, veteran member of the anti-apartheid progressive federal party, condemned the arrests monday of prominent clergymen who were protesting the government crackdown
about 25 church leaders, including anglican archbishop desmond tutu, and 125 other protesters were detained briefly after riot policeman blocked them from marching to parliament with a petition protesting the bans on opposition groups. after the most prominent clergymen were placed in police vehicles, a water cannon was sprayed on the other protesters, who were kneeling and singing hymns
mrs. suzman said tuesday police should have allowed the march to proceed, ``thus avoiding all that sensational publicity that has resulted in adverse headlines across the world and has added further fuel to the campaign for sanctions. this government has a death wish.''
law and order minister adriaan vlok said the clergymen had defied a request to disperse and ``scandalously provoked'' police. ``we have to once again take the blame for the misconduct of people who hide behind the cloth of sanctimony,'' he said
one of the arrested churchmen, roman catholic archibishop stephen naidoo of cape town, said in an interview tuesday that he and his colleagues considered it their duty to intensify the churches' challenge of the government
there is going to be in this country a continuing moral confrontation,'' he said
he predicted the authorities would deal cautiously with defiant clergymen because ``they are intelligent enough to realize they are dealing here with a great moral force ... and the moral sensibilities of people all over the world.''
the government has backed off before in the face of concerted church resistance, the last time in 1986 when many of the same ministers arrested monday had gathered at cape town's st. george's anglican cathderal to defy a ban on calling for the release of detainees. the prohibition was not enforced and was dropped from the next issue of emergency regulations
the rev. edward king, dean of st. george's, said it was significant that no one in monday's march had been charged and all were freed without bail. ``i think they're embarrassed by this; they don't want to put archbishops in jail. but they make their own nooses for their own necks.''
one of two ira men accidentally killed by their own bomb has been linked to at least 25 killings since 1979 and headed the police most-wanted list, the british news agency press association said tuesday
the agency quoted security sources it did not identify as saying brendan burns, 33, was believed to have directed ira bombing campaigns along the british province's border with the irish republic
burns and brendan morley, 30, were killed monday by the detonation of explosives they apparently were installing in a van about two miles outside crossmaglen in south armagh
the irish republican army, which is fighting to oust britain from northern ireland and unite it with the irish republic, said the men belonged to the organization
press association said burns was involved in an ira ambush that cost the lives of 18 british soldiers in warrenpoint, county down, in august 1969, when sectarian violence began in the protestant-dominated province
burns also was sought in connection with a land mine explosion that killed five soldiers at camlough, county armagh, in 1981, the agency said
it said he was linked with the killings of lord justice sir maurice gibson, the province's second-highest judge, and his wife. a land mine destroyed their car as they drove into northern ireland from across the border last summer
northern ireland's police force, the royal ulster constabulary, refused comment on the report tuesday night. robertson's assertion, with us officials commenting on robertson claim</note>
republican presidential candidate pat robertson on tuesday cited second-hand testimony from a senate subcommittee hearing 21 years ago as documentation that soviet intermediate-range missiles are based in cuba
however, several u.s. officials said tuesday the cuban military has some surface-to-surface missiles in its inventory, but none has a nuclear warhead and none could reach the united states even if they did
the former religious broadcaster said the information indicates a ``loophole'' in the u.s.-soviet arms control treaty awaiting ratification in the senate
robertson quoted 1967 testimony by paul bethel, a state department official from miami who said cuban refugees had told him of seeing missiles, and one of the refugees, identified only as mr. apud, who swore cuban soldiers let him know about missiles aimed at washington before he left in 1966
neither man testified he had personally seen the missiles, the transcript indicates
the testimony was given to the judiciary subcommittee to investigate the administration of the internal security act and other internal security laws. robertson read portions of it to supporters at a breakfast here and during a rally the night before in miami
i've been accused of bringing funny facts,'' robertson told the fort lauderdale gathering. ``ladies and gentlemen, the clear eyewitness, sworn testimony of witnesses before a senate judiciary committee is not funny facts. ... this is documented evidence.''
robertson's assertion that there are missiles based in cuba has been denied by the white house, congressional defense experts and cuban president fidel castro
several defense and administration officials were asked tuesday about robertson's claim. the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity because they did not want to become involved in the presidential race, said cuba has about five dozen frog-4 and frog-7 battlefield missiles, date to the 1960s
the frog-7, when originally introduced by the soviets, could carry either a conventional or nuclear warhead, ``but we're confident no nuclear warheads ever went to cuba for that missile and it doesn't have any range anyway,'' said one source who requested anonymity
according to the reference book ``jane's weapon systems,'' the frog-7 has a range of only about 43 miles _ or half the distance between cuba and florida. moreover, the rocket has no guidance system to direct it to a specific target
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said last month that cuba has been under extensive surveillance since the 1962 missile crisis and there was ``no evidence'' any other nuclear weaponry had ever been deployed there by the soviet union
robertson concentrated heavily on the cuban-american vote for the march 8 super tuesday primary during a two-day swing through south florida
the miami rally drew little more than half of the 1,500 people that campaign organizers had predicted in a show of the candidate's strength among hispanics
at a news conference following the breakfast, robertson refused to say how he obtained the missile testimony transcript
how i got it is my business, but the thing that's important is that it's available in the records of the united state government,'' he said. ``and, frankly, i think it shows that the staff work by the state department was not adequate on the inf treaty because there's clearly a cuban loophole.''
a cuban refugee who claims he saw a variety of missiles, including long-range surface-to-surface missiles, there as late as 1985 said he met thursday in miami with robertson
copies of a spanish-language newspaper, diario libre, with a headline proclaiming ``yes, pat! you're right!'' and maps drawn by the refugee to pinpoint the missile sites were distributed to campaign supporters throughout his south florida visit
the man identified himself only as e. rodriguez, saying he feared revealing his full name would result in retribution against family members still in cuba. he said he was an agricultural planner and had access to aerial photographs and to areas of cuba where the missiles were based
robertson said he couldn't vouch for the authenticity of the newspaper's account of the refugee's story
i'm not saying i have other than this proof,'' he said, referring to the subcommittee transcript. ``it's coming to me from many, many people now, people who are aware of it
but the issue is not can we prove or can we not prove. the issue is verification we have a treaty. there's a loophole in the treaty. we must put in verification of the cuban missile sites.''
he told reporters the only way to verify his claim was to personally go to cuba and look for the missiles. but, responding to a question, he said he would decline an invitation to do so should it be extended by castro, who he has described as ``a butcher and a tyrant.''
in the subcommittee transcript, apud said he was told by cuban soldiers he had known for many years that the missiles were nicknamed ``washington left,'' ``washington right,'' and ``washington central.''
robertson quoted bethel's acknowledgement, in response to questioning by sen. strom thurmond, r-s.c., that numerous refugees had told him they had seen missiles left in cuba after the cuban missile crisis and new ones constructed in 1964
bethel testified he could not state with certainty that intermediate or intercontinental ballistic missiles were in cuba, but that the state department also couldn't be certain they weren't there
the son of late president gamal abdel nasser of egypt was quoted tuesday as saying the united states and israel are defaming him and his brothers to ``settle old accounts'' with his father
the kuwaiti newspaper al-anbaa said the interview conducted in belgrade, yugoslavia, was the first with khaled abdel nasser since criminal charges were filed against him in cairo. it quoted him as saying he would return to egypt for trial even though he faced possible execution
khaled nasser is among 20 men charged in connection with four shooting attacks on u.s. and israeli diplomats and embassy workers between 1984 and 1987. two israelis were killed and six israelis and two americans were wounded
he and the other defendants are accused of membership in a clandestine group called egypt's revolution. the indictment demands the death penalty for nasser, 38, and 10 other defendants, and prison terms of up to life for the others
egypt has said it is trying to extradite khaled nasser for trial as one of three founders of egypt's revolution and its main financial backer. the group is committed to ending the israeli presence in egypt and egyptian commitment to the 1979 peace treaty with the jewish state
al-anbaa said algeria had offered political refugee status to nasser but he refused, saying: ``my father never imagined being such in any country and preferred to die while fighting his enemies rather than accept that. therefore i am determined to return to cairo because death in cairo is much better than living elsewhere.''
gamal abdel nasser led a bloodless military coup that ousted king farouk in 1952, and ruled as a fierce nationalist until his death in 1970
while he was in office, egypt faced the 1956 invasion by britain, france and israel and israel captured the sinai peninsula and gaza strip in the 1967 middle east war
nasser's successor, the late anwar sadat, led the country through the 1973 war with israel and signed the peace treaty with israel in 1979
in referring to ``a defamation campaign'' in the egyptian press against him and his two younger brothers, according to al-anbaa, nasser said it was ``not separate from the hostile american and israeli blueprint which has been employed over the past 36 years with the aim of obliterating nasser's legendary place in the hearts of the arab masses.''
the defamation campaign being launched against me and my brothers is but an american and israeli attempt to settle old accounts,'' he said
those who failed to face president nasser for 18 years of his rule and to eradicate his name from the conscience of the egyptian masses for 18 years after his death now return to launch their campaigns.''
michael dukakis won the vermont democratic presidential primary on tuesday, with jesse jackson running second. it was the massachusetts governor's third new england victory, following new hampshire and maine
a united nations report released tuesday said human rights violations including torture and abductions continue in chile but the overall situation is improving
the report presented to the 43-nation u.n. human rights commission said that since february 1985 ``there have been important changes which have improved the human rights situation . .. but much still remains to be done.''
it said specific problems are the increasing scope of military courts and ``violent and criminal activities of private gangs and terrorists.''
gen. augusto pinochet has headed chile's military government since the coup that ousted the elected government of marxist president salvador allende in september 1973
the report was prepared by costa rican jurist fernando volio jimenez under a mandate from the commission. volio jiminez visited chile in december and met with government officials and human rights activists
he wrote that ``a state of violence affecting fundamental rights continues to exist in chile, despite the government's general attitude condemning such violations.''
the report said many citizens are victims of intimidation by ``supposedly private individuals'' seeking to ``inspire terror in circles opposed to the political status quo.''
such intimidation is ``generally the work of private gangs ... having the secret support of some public authority,'' it said
harassment, mainly of people who recently returned from exile, has become more ``articulate, blatant and general,'' the report said
it also said the government has taken measures to try to prevent the torture of detainees, but ``torture is still practiced although, according to non-governmental sources, this revolting practice may have declined in terms of numbers.''
the report noted an increase in the number of civilians tried in military courts and the ``irregular conduct'' of those courts
it listed five cases of ``involuntary disappearances'' in 1987, following a year when no cases were reported, and said the recurrence is ``an especially serious situation.''
on the positive side, volio reported the government since february 1985 had permitted the return of about 4,000 chileans who were in forced exile. it said that according to the government, 350 chileans are still living in forced exile but non-governmental sources put the figure at 583
the report cited the cases of nine people killed in 1985-86 that have not been solved and said one investigating magistrate complained about lack of police cooperation and said he had received death threats
this situation makes things look gloomy for the cause of human rights,'' it added. tuesday</head> word `feet,' add quote from networks' attorney. picks up 8th graf pvs, `frances duncan...'.</note>
a federal judge tuesday gave the three major television networks the go-ahead to take exit polls at georgia voting places during the super tuesday presidential preference primaries next week
cbs, nbc and abc had sued state and fulton county election officials to stop enforcement of a 1985 law prohibiting exit polls or public opinion surveys within 250 feet of a polling place
u.s. district judge robert hall tuesday issued a preliminary injunction stopping the state from enforcing the new law beyond 25 feet of buildings in which polling places are located
the ruling, which came after a hearing on the lawsuit monday, allows the networks to conduct the exit polls during the march 8 primaries, as long as their poll takers are stationed no closer than 25 feet from the door
hall indicated he would rule later on the networks' contention that the law violates the constitution's first amendment guarantee of freedom of speech and of the press
while the state ``has a legitimate interest in protecting the `sanctity of the polling place,''' hall wrote in tueday's ruling, it appears the 250 foot prohibition on exit polls ``is not `narrowly tailored' to accomplish that goal in the `least restrictive means available,''' as required by previous court rulings on free speech issues
a more limited ban, keeping exit pollers out of polling places and 25 feet away from their doors, ``would likely satisfy even the most rigorous constitutional scrutiny,'' he wrote
we're delighted by the results,'' said floyd abrams, an attorney representing the networks. ``it will make it possible for more people to have more information more quickly about the election results and their meaning on super tuesday.''
frances duncan, the assistant secretary of state in charge of elections, said tuesday that copies of the judge's order will be sent to county election officials for relay to their precinct managers before the primaries next week
in exit polling, survey takers ask a random sample of voters leaving the polling place to fill out a written list of questions about whom they voted for and what issues are important to them, as well as such information as their age, sex and economic status
during testimony in monday's hearing, warren mitofsky, director of cbs news' election and survey unit, testified that exit polls are by far the most accurate and the quickest way to gauge what groups of people are voting for which candidate
but, he said, the 250-foot distance limitation effectively banned public opinion surveys of people leaving polling places because the surveyor is too far away from the exit to be able to intercept the voters randomly
the law had been enacted because elections officials, mostly in metropolitan atlanta, had complained that exit poll takers intimidated voters, according to testimony from former state rep. claude bray, who chaired the house state governmental affairs committee when it considered the measure
jesse jackson met with the south african ambassador tuesday and said he conveyed the ``outrage felt by freedom-loving peoples everywhere'' at the recent clampdown of anti-apartheid factions in that country
the democratic presidential candidate said he objected to pretoria's restriction of the activities of anti-apartheid organizations and monday's arrest of anglican archbishop desmond tutu and other top religious leaders
jackson told a news conference later that the ambassador, piet g.j. koornhof, asked for a follow-up meeting with rep. ronald dellums, d-calif., who attended the meeting and who is sponsoring legislation on sanctions against south africa because of its apartheid policy of racial separation
the democrat also called on the reagan administration to take several steps against the pretoria regime
he said he informed the south african ambassador of his proposals, which include:
_ ``comprehensive international economic and financial sanctions on apartheid.'' jackson said u.s. corporations and banks should be ordered to leave south africa
_ invocation by the administration of a special session of the u.n. security council to seek international support for such sanctions
_ broadcasting of news from south africa via ``a new radio free south africa.''
_ support for the so-called frontline states around south africa and aid to build rail corridor railways so that zimbabwe and zambia would not be dependent on south african trade routes
jackson said he attempted to telephone president reagan on the eve of reagan's tuesday departure for a north atlantic treaty organization meeting in brussels. jackson said he spoke with national security adviser colin powell and urged that reagan seek support from the nato allies for jackson's south africa proposals
jackson's press secretary, elizabeth coulton, said powell agreed the south africa situation would be raised at the nato meeting
campaigning earlier in maryland, one of the super tuesday states that holds its primary next week, jackson spoke to a downtown baltimore rally and blasted reagan for using ``government power to take from the poor and give to the rich.''
of his recent second-place finish in the maine caucuses, jackson told the crowd of a few hundred, ``there are signs we are growing every day.''
he also walked through baltimore's trendy lexington market food bazaar shaking hands with the lunchtime crowds. he stood on a large plant pot and shouted over the din, urging the crowd to vote for him
later, jackson flew to his hometown of greenville, s.c., and proclaimed to a church full of people, ``it's good to be home.''
i'm a son of the south...i know the south and its ways,'' he said
the british broadcasting corp. said tuesday the government has withdrawn its objections to a radio program that included interviews with intelligence officials
prime minister margaret thatcher's government won a court order in december preventing the broadcasting of the first program in the planned three-part series, ``my country: right or wrong.''
the government argued that the series, dealing with the tug of war between state secrecy and freedom of information, could harm national security
publicly funded bbc said the series portrays the work of britain's intelligence agencies and did not reveal anything an enemy could not already know
the government withdrew its objections to the program after its lawyers received a transcript of it from the bbc, the company said
the second and third programs have yet to be recorded
i am glad that we will be able to transmit this program,'' said john birt, bbc's deputy director general. ``i am only sorry it has been long delayed.''
he did not say when the program will be broadcast
the high court judge who approved the gag order had said the government was properly concerned that nine former and serving intelligence officials interviewed for the series may have broken their oaths of secrecy
bbc spokeswoman helen cleary said tuesday night: ``the bbc initially refused to turn over the transcripts to the government, arguing that would amount to pre-censorship. but the bbc later, during the legal process, had to provide the transcripts as part of its defense evidence.''
mrs. thatcher's conservative government had used the argument of lifetime confidentiality by security agents to prevent the publication in britain of ``spycatcher,'' a book by former agent peter wright, who now lives in australia. the book has been published in the united states. with comment from chinn's attorney. picks up 22nd graf pvs bgng: chinn was ...</note>
attorney general edwin meese iii's investment manager allocated stock-trading profits to meese's brokerage accounts under a procedure that a senator said tuesday raises questions of ``possible financial favors or gifts'' to the cabinet member
in a report by its democratic majority staff, the senate subcommittee on oversight of government management said stock trader w. franklyn chinn pooled meese's money with that of several other customers in 1985 and 1986 and, after completing stock trades, assigned profits or losses to the attorney general's account
the report said it appears that in seven instances, chinn allocated stock trades to meese's account in amounts exceeding the balance available in the account to pay for those trades
in the seven instances, the amount of the stock trades exceeded the balances in meese's account by $5,000 to $140,000
chinn turned a profit of nearly $40,000 for meese on a $50,000 investment in just 23 stock trades over a 19-month span
e. robert wallach, meese's longtime friend who is under indictment in the wedtech corp. scandal, in five of the trades was one of the customers whose money was pooled with that of the attorney general. wallach introduced meese to chinn, who became the attorney general's financial adviser in may 1985
chinn ``wasn't investing mr. meese's money, as much as he was assigning profits and losses to the accounts of mr. meese and his other clients at his own discretion,'' sen. carl levin, d-mich., the subcommittee's chairman, said in a letter to the office of government ethics
chinn's ``assignment of stock transactions retroactively to those accounts appears to have no relationship to the amount of money in those accounts,'' levin continued
because he did not allocate winners and losers to his clients' accounts until after the fact, he was effectively able to assign greater benefits to some _ including apparently mr. meese on numerous occasions.''
the procedure ``raises questions about possible financial favors or gifts, about possible conflict of interest, (and) about the judgment of the attorney general in being involved in a partnership with a director of a company (wedtech corp.) with mr. meese had directly assisted when he was working in the white house as counselor to the president,'' said levin
levin asked the ethics office for a formal finding as to whether meese has complied with federal regulations governing gifts and loans to public officials and whether he has violated an executive order prohibiting the appearance of a conflict of interest
justice department spokesman patrick korten said the issues raised by levin were matters that had been fully examined in congressional hearings last july and that now are before the independent counsel studying meese's dealings with wedtech. he said it would be inappropriate for the ethics office to get involved at this point
what senator levin is trying to do is wrap an 8-month old fish in today's paper,'' korten said. ``all we have here is a highly partisan effort to grab another headline on this thing and keep the meese pot boiling.''
meese has acknowledged interceding on behalf of wedtech when the bronx, n.y., defense contractor was seeking a $32 million, no-bid contract to build small engines for the army. within months of meese's intercession, wedtech was awarded the work
the report said that in one instance, chinn bought and sold 5,000 shares of a new stock issue in oliver stores inc. worth $30,000 on feb. 11, 1986
it wasn't until the next day, however, that chinn instructed imperial trust co. where one of meese's accounts was established, that 2,000 of the shares were to be recorded for meese's account. the transaction gave meese a profit of more than $1,700
in another instance, on sept. 12, 1985, chinn allocated a purchase of $80,000 worth of stock in rockefeller center properties to meese's account at the brokerage house of bear, stearns at a time when the account had a balance of only $51,000. the trade resulted in a profit of nearly $900
in a third instance, chinn bought and sold firemans fund corp. stock on oct. 23, 1985. it wasn't until mid-afternoon of the day he bought and sold it that chinn directed that 2,000 of the shares be assigned to meese's account. that transaction earned meese more than $900
levin said chinn assigned purchases to meese's and his other customers' accounts ``after it was known whether the purchase would yield a profit or loss
it appears that mr. chinn was able to decide just which of his clients would get profits and which would get losses,'' the senator said in his letter to the ethics office
one of chinn's lawyers, cristina arguedas, said that her client's stock trading has been examined at length by independent counsel james mckay, who is conducting a criminal investigation of meese. she said the independent counsel has found no wrongdoing in connection with the stock trading
one of meese's attorneys, nathan lewin, said the attorney general had set up a limited blind partnership with chinn's company under which meese was kept unaware of any of the details of chinn's stock trading. lewin noted that meese lost money on five of the 23 stock transactions
chinn was indicted dec. 22 with longtime meese friend e. robert wallach and a business associate, r. kent london, on racketeering, fraud and conspiracy charges in an alleged scheme to extract payments from wedtech in order to influence meese and other federal officials. all three have pleaded innocent
meese's involvement with wedtech has been under criminal investigation by independent counsel james mckay since last may 11. the attorney general has denied wrongdoing
a federal judge on tuesday overturned the texas ban on florida citrus fruit, and state officials began planning their next legal move against regulations allowing the shipments
the ban was imposed last month ban after the u.s. department of agriculture lifted a 3{-year-old federal quarantine on florida citrus that was prompted by outbreaks of citrus canker in florida
texas agriculture officials said the ban was necessary to protect texas' $65 million-a-year citrus industry from canker
the state now plans to seek an injunction against new federal rules that allow shipment of florida citrus meeting certain standards to other citrus-producing states, said max woodfin, spokesman for the texas department of agriculture
u.s. district judge james nowlin said tuesday that he lifted the state ban, imposed last month after the new federal rule took effect, because the federal regulation took precedence over the state rule
the ban was due to end march 12, when texas officials planned to have gathered information on the federal rule and take some permanent action
we feel we need to do whatever we can to protect the texas citrus industry,'' woodfin said
the injunction request will charge that the federal rule was issued abruptly and did not allow sufficient time to study its possible effects, he said
florida citrus mutual, a growers association, and tuxedo fruit co., a florida shipper and grower, sued texas last month to stop the emergency state quarantine
florida gov. bob martinez and agriculture commissioner doyle conner joined the court action
the lawsuit called the ban unconstitutional and invalid. it said the action would mean a loss of millions of dollars to the florida citrus industry
we expected this decision,'' conner said. ``federal rules and regulations supersede state rules and regulations as it pertains to plant matters. the law's a little different between plant and animal.''
canker, which can seriously damage citrus plants and fruit, was found in florida in 1984. florida officials said florida producers must meet strict standards under the new federal regulation in order to ship fruit to citrus-producing states, including texas
robert griffith, chief of the bureau of pest eradication for the florida department of agriculture and consumer service, said he had never heard of canker being found on mature citrus fruit that was ready to be shipped
it would be difficult to transmit canker from fruit to citrus groves, he said
the coalition government of socialists and conservatives, already under strain because of the kurt waldheim affair, could collapse over tax reform, according to comments by chancellor franz vranitzky on tuesday
the coalition has been strained for months over president waldheim's world war ii activities, and vranitzky said again tuesday he would consider resigning if that issue continued to affect his government's work
but socialist vranitzky, speaking with reporters after a cabinet session, dealt mainly with tax legislation
he said it was possible he would meet again this week with vice chancellor alois mock in a last-ditch effort to reach agreement on tax reform
mock is chairman of the conservative austrian people's party. waldheim, running as the conservative candidate, won the presidential election in june 1986. the term for the mainly titular presidency is for six years, and waldheim has rejected critics' demands that he resign
vranitzky said the question of new elections ``would lie close at hand'' if the tax dispute is not resolved
the last parliamentary elections were held on nov. 23, 1986, for four-year terms
vranitzky was asked about early elections and he said, ``i do not seek them but i do not shy away from them either.''
mock and vranitzky have had several inconclusive meetings on the proposed tax reform
the socialists insist that a major gap in the budget cannot be filled without imposing a tax on savings deposit interest. the conservatives strongly oppose such a tax
some political observers have said the combined tax dispute and controversy over waldheim may be too much for the coalition to survive
vranitzky, criticizing waldheim, said it was not enough for the president to keep restating his position
he said waldheim would have to contribute to resolving the crisis over his presidency ``in word and deed,'' but added he did not want to elaborate
waldheim served as a lieutenant in the german army in the balkans during world war ii. the world jewish congress and other groups say he was involved with army units that deported thousands of jews and other people from the area to nazi labor or death camps
an international commission of six historians, appointed by the austrian government to investigate waldheim's past, said he was ``in close proximity'' to some nazi atrocities in the balkans and knew they were going on but made no attempt to prevent them
the report, released last month, did not support allegations that waldheim was involved in atrocities. but it left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime
waldheim, a former u.n. secretary-general, has repeatedly denied any wrongdoings during the war
the derbyshire county council suggested a compromise tuesday in its campaign to have 16th century chesterfield school replace a latin motto on its stationery with an anti-nuclear slogan
the left-dominated council, which runs the boys' preparatory school in north-central england, had told the school to stop using stationery bearing a coat of arms and the motto ``non quo sed quomodo'' _ ``not whither but in what manner.''
the school was told to use standard-issue council letter paper bearing the slogan ``derbyshire council council supports nuclear-free zones,'' according to headmaster geoffrey price
price opposed the idea, and conservative member of parliament peter rost said tuesday he would ask education secretary kenneth baker to intervene
later tuesday, the council's labor party leader, david bookbinder, said the council would have no objection to the school keeping its motto on the stationery as long as it used the slogan as well
price said he welcomed the compromise but was puzzled by it
i have been suggesting this for a year or more but was told it was unacceptable,'' he said. ``however, so let it be.''
chesterfield school was founded in 1594. new graf 14, at another, with more robertson comment at news conference</note>
republican presidential candidate pat robertson said tuesday he will drop his libel suit against former rep. pete mccloskey rather than go to trial on super tuesday, the biggest day of the primary season
robertson, who was accused of avoiding combat duty in the korean war through his father's influence, said he wants to take the case to voluntary arbitration in an effort to clear his and his father's names. but he said if mccloskey refuses to do that he will drop the suit anyway
mccloskey's lawyer, george lehner, said a proposal to use arbitration was rejected by robertson's lawyers nine months ago, and he said to propose it on the eve of trial ``is a little disingenuous'' and ``a red herring.''
lehner has said repeatedly that mccloskey will not agree to settlement in the case unless robertson pays legal fees _ estimated at $400,000 _ piled up by the former congressmen
we are prepared to go to trial,'' lehner said after learning of robertson's announcement. ``if he wants to drop the suit,'' the lawyer said, robertson must ``pay the legal fees'' amassed by mccloskey to defend the case
mccloskey said it's ``not for him (robertson) to decide'' to drop the suit, saying he would oppose any motion by robertson to dismiss the case
i would rather go to trial. he's called me a liar all over the united states,'' mccloskey said in a telephone interview. ``i would much prefer there be a verdict as to which of us has told the truth.''
robertson's $35 million suit accuses mccloskey of defaming him in a widely publicized letter contending the former television evangelist had used the influence of his father, the late sen. a. willis robertson, to avoid combat duty in the korean war as a marine corps officer
the case had been scheduled for next tuesday, the same date as republican primaries and caucuses in 17 states, including florida where robertson was campaigning
in order to compete in that trial i would have to break off my campaign today and run the risk of losing florida, texas, south carolina and other parts of the south,'' robertson said at an airport news conference. ``that was an impossible decision for me to make and an unfair one.''
he has proposed that the issue be resolved by the iowa libel dispute program run jointly by the university of iowa college of law and the american arbitration association
robertson said if mccloskey refuses arbitration he would take pre-trial evidence and testimony already collected to an unspecified panel of experts and have them give a public opinion on mccloskey's contentions
if he doesn't (go to arbitration), we will prove to the american people that he truly doesn't want the truth to come out,'' robertson said
at another news conference later in orlando, robertson complained about the judge's actions, saying: ``she has done everything she can to get us to drop the case. i have done everything i could to make a settlement based on the truth.''
in his letter, mccloskey wrote that he and robertson had been on the same korea-bound troop ship in 1951 but that robertson was taken off the vessel in japan where he was given a non-combat post after telling other marines his father would arrange a transfer
mccloskey also wrote that when robertson later was sent to korea he was known as the ``division liquor officer'' because he made frequent trips to japan
robertson has denied that his father used any influence to get him off the troop ship
while campaigning in miami on monday, robertson called mccloskey a ``pathological liar'' and charged that he circulated the korea story in an effort to hurt robertson's political campaign
he also contended mccloskey is a supporter of vice president george bush, one of robertson's opponents in the campaign for the gop presidential nomination
more than 500 military police troopers fought about 2,500 striking coal miners in southern brazil on tuesday and dozens of people were injured, according to a union lawyer and a state senator
the melee took place in criciuma, a town in southern santa catarina state, 800 miles southwest of rio
the union lawyer, alfredo gava, told the associated press by telephone from the region, ``many miners from other companies and townspeople joined in the protest, which turned the city center into a war zone. by the end, there were more than 5,000 people throwing rocks and objects.''
gava said at least 30 police and miners were injured and one miner was arrested. the chief of local police, luis gonzaga schmidt, reported that five people were held for a few hours, then were let go
the chief put the number of injured _ police, miners and others caught up in the turmoil _ at 20
however, state sen. itamar da silva, who was at the site of the brawl, said that 33 military police and 33 miners were hurt
authorities said the troopers were under orders not to attack the strikers, but retaliated when they themselves came under attack
gava said the trouble began when police tried to remove striking mine workers who were demonstrating peacefully in front of a branch of the government-run bank, banco do brasil
the downtown square was almost completely destroyed,'' gava reported. ``miners pulled down walls to break up the bricks for ammunition against police and stoned houses and office buildings in the immediate area.''
tv globo, brazil's largest private network, showed a burning motorbike in the square and military police with truncheons and behind big shields rushing at miners. troopers threw tear gas and exploded concussion bombs to disperse the mob
gava said the miners had been striking for 21 days to force carbonifera prospera mining co. to adhere to a jan. 1 agreement for a 145 percent pay raise to make up for losses to 17 percent monthly inflation. pay scales were not immediately available
the company, along with five others in criciuma, signed the accord, but while the others paid up, prospera went back on the deal after the company was sold to the government-run national steel co., gava said
company representatives said over tv globo that prospera's responsibility to adhere to the agreement ended with the sale of the company
tv globo said the company had agreed to meet with union representatives wednesday
da silva, a social democrat, called the attack on the strikers ``unmotivated'' and said the state senate would investigate the fray. sted of 1955 to 1959 and that besser replaced shemp sted of curly; ams separate moved as a0867 on besser.</note>
joe besser, one of the later members of the three stooges and who played the whining brat ``stinky'' in ``the abbott and costello show,'' died tuesday. he was 80
besser was one of the stooges from 1956 to 1958, replacing shemp howard. he played the character joe, who would often whine, ``oooh, you crazy,'' as he was slapped around by moe howard
in the 1940s, his portrayal of an exasperated, whining child earned him a spot in olsen and johnson's long-running broadway show, ``sons of fun.'' in the 1950s and 60s, besser became a regular on several shows, including ``the ken murray show,'' ``the joey bishop show'' and ``the abbott and costello show.''
