a federal judge ruled tuesday that two companies who used young people in a church job-training program had violated child-labor laws and ordered stiff penalties for seven people who ran the program
u.s. district judge robert potter threatened to fine the seven $21,000 a day if they continued to use the children, as young as 9 years old. he wrote that the children were ``manifestly being exploited.''
shiloh true light church members acknowledged during the january trial that their children worked at construction sites and in shops where they carried bricks, laid foundations and more recently, operated forklifts and power saws
they said they had been doing so for at least 100 years
potter ordered mcgee brothers co. of union county to pay $98,225 in back wages plus nearly $36,000 in interest. mcgee brothers and co-defendant wendell's woodworking inc. of mint hill also were ordered to pay nearly $70,000 in court costs
spokesmen for the companies were not immediately available for comment. there was no answer at the company offices, and their lawyers were not in their offices
u.s. department of labor officials in atlanta said they had not received a copy of the decision and could not comment on whether the $21,000-per-day fine was retroactive to oct. 5, when potter issued an order to stop using the children
the minors are clearly dependent on the defendants' business for their employment and are the class of person whom the act is designed to protect,'' potter wrote in a 58-page opinion
they are manifestly being exploited by defendants in this case, whether or not they proclaim their purpose to be in furtherance of their religious beliefs,'' potter wrote
when the owners of the companies, both church members, continued the program for the church after potter's october order, the labor department asked they be found in contempt of the injunction and be fined $20,000 a day
on tuesday, potter said wendell's would be fined $5,000 per day and its two owners, wendell long and herbert long, be fined $500 each per day thay they remained in contempt of his order
the judge ordered mcgee brothers to pay $10,000 per day and order five brothers who owned the company to pay $1,000 each per day that they remained in contempt of the order. reagan</head> mubarak comment. pick up 13th graf pvs, instead, it ...</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz appeared ready on tuesday night to resume his diplomatic shuttle in the middle east after reporting to president reagan
a u.s. official said jordan's king hussein told shultz at a three-hour meeting in london earlier tuesday that he was interested in shultz's effort to set up arab-israeli negotiations
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said hussein did not directly endorse the u.s. initiative, but told shultz he appreciated the effort being made to open talks
it was a serious discussion, covering the whole waterfront,'' the official said. ``nobody is saying yes or no.''
a statement issued by the jordanian embassy in london said hussein reiterated jordan's position that an international peace conference should be attended by the five permanent members of the u.n. security council _ the united states, the soviet union, china, britain and france _ and ``all parties to the conflict, including the palestine liberation organization.''
shultz arranged to confer with reagan briefly tuesday night and more fully on wednesday before reagan begins his talks in the belgian capital with 15 other allied leaders attending a north atlantic treaty organization summit
shultz would return to the middle east at the conclusion of the summit thursday night and try over the next two days to get acceptance of the u.s. formula for negotiations to deal with both palestinian unrest in areas under israeli control and an overall arab-israeli settlement
he's a key, in my opinion,'' shultz said of hussein before their meeting at the king's residence in london's kensington district
he has immense standing and is a person who has been here a long time.'' talking to reporters on the way to london from the middle east, shultz acknowledged he made little progress in four days of shuttle diplomacy
he said he could detect a narrowing of differences, but ``i don't know if i could describe them in any way that would be perceptible to anyone else.''
yet, shultz said, ``assuming everyone continues the attitude they have to keep working, to keep working, we'll do it.''
president hosni mubarak of egypt, however, in his first comment on his talks with shultz, said tuesday he had reservations about the u.s. plan and he would disclose them only after a final formula was reached
mubarak and shultz conferred in egypt sunday. mubarak spoke to reporters while visiting neighboring sudan. egypt's middle east news agency carried his statements from khartoum
in amman monday, reporters were told that jordan was not putting pressure on the plo to form a mixed negotiating delegation for peace talks with israel
instead, it was reported, jordan had taken the position the plo was the sole representative of the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live on the israel-held west bank and in gaza, where clashes have killed more than 70 arabs
the u.s. proposal calls for israel, jordan and palestinians to open negotiations about april 1 on self-rule for the palestinians in israeli-held territory. talks on an overall mideast settlement would begin by december
shultz met twice with jordanian officials, but he had to seek an authoritative answer from hussein, who was in london for dental treatment
diplomatic sources in jerusalem, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said shultz told prime minister yitzhak shamir of israel he would return to the middle east after the nato summit if hussein gave at least qualified support to the u.s. proposal
on his flight to london, shultz stressed a need for the united states to step up contacts with palestinians
shultz confirmed the united states had persuaded israel to relax restrictions in permitting two palestinians, hanna siniora, a jerusalem editor, and fayez abu rahme, a gaza lawyer, to go to washington to meet with him five weeks ago
we have communicated with them in some important, substantive ways,'' shultz said of u.s. approaches to the palestinians
he said he had got the palestinians' reaction indirectly while in the middle east from egypt and jordan
it isn't as though there's no feedback, '' shultz said. ``there is feedback. it's not a substitute for directly sitting down with people, and that in a sense is what we've been calling for all along. in the end we've got to sit down together, so we have made a major effort to communicate with them.''
