the government has filed a lawsuit seeking at least $21 million from goodyear tire and rubber co. for allegedly falsifying price information about balloon-type devices used to guide bombs
the suit, originally filed last year by a competitor, was taken over by u.s. attorney rudolph giuliani and filed monday in manhattan
the suit names goodyear, a subsidiary called goodyear aerospace corp., and loral corp., which bought the subsidiary last year
goodyear is confident that once the facts in the case are examined objectively, the suit will be found without merit and the charges dropped,'' goodyear spokesman walt mcclenny said from his akron, ohio, office
the case involves two devices called air inflatable retarder assemblies that are used to slow and guide the flight of mk 500-pound and 1,000-pound bombs dropped from low-flying airplanes
the government charged that goodyear aerospace misrepresented prices and costs of the labor involved; that the company unlawfully induced a subcontractor to lower its price; and that it failed to disclose substantial price reductions proposed for a subcontractor
goodyear aerospace was the only maker of the devices from 1982 to 1986. irvin industries inc. entered the competition and filed a $100 million antitrust suit in 1986
irvin allegedly turned up information about fraud against the government that it used in another suit it filed in 1987. that suit was filed on behalf of the government under a ``whistleblower'' law that allows the government to take over a suit
the suit filed monday asks for at least $21 million in damages under the false claims act and common law theories. in addition, the government is seeking $10,000 for each unspecified false claim
a spokesman for loral, who asked not to be identified, said that those alleged practices would have occurred before loral bought the company and the potential for a lawsuit was known before the purchase
he added, however, that ``loral is confident the appropriate management practices are in place that are consistent with government procurement practices.''
mazda motor corp. said it is recalling 11,889 of its 1988 mazda 929 upscale sedans for possible improper positioning of an emissions-control hose
in a statement issued monday from los angeles, the japanese automaker said improper routing of a short section of the hose may put it in contact with the car's air-conditioning piping, leading eventually to a failure of the emissions-control system
owners are being notified by mail to take their cars to a mazda dealer for free inspection and repositioning of the hose if necessary. mazda said the procedure takes about 15 minutes
peugeot motors of america inc. said it was offering a $3,000 allowance to drivers who trade in their peugeots for the purchase or lease of a new peugeot 505
the dollar's declining value has resulted in higher costs for imported cars,'' said pascal h. henault, peugeot's u.s. president
since the resale value of used cars has not kept pace with new car prices, we're compensating by offering a $3,000 trade-in allowance.''
to qualify, customers must prove they have owned or leased a peugeot for at least four months and the new car must be delivered by may 31, the company said monday in a statement
j.c. penney co., which is relocating to texas, has decided to sell its midtown manhattan headquarters rather than lease the skyscraper as originally planned
the 45-story building could sell for up to $480 million, or $300 a square foot, according to real estate analysts
the expected price is well below the record $500 per square foot commanded by similar buildings in the area sold before the oct. 19 stock market crash
penney plans to move its headquarters to plano, texas, near dallas, by the end of june and had been trying to lease the building since last september
harvey mccormick, a spokesman for the giant retailer, said monday that penney already has received bids from prospective buyers, but he refused to name them
penney bought the building in 1977 for $55 million
william h. spoor, formerly at the helm of of pillsbury co., is coming out of retirement to take over his old job
the company announced monday that its board of directors at a regular meeting in naples, fla., elected spoor chairman and chief exectuive officer to replace john m. stafford, who resigned. it didn't give a reason for the management shakeup
contacted in naples on monday, spoor told the st. paul pioneer press dispatch that other management changes will be announced today. ``there won't be any firings, but we will be changing people and responsibilities,'' spoor said
spoor described himself as a ``very interim'' ceo, adding, ``this doesn't please me at all.''
the one thing this isn't is power plays and politics,'' he said. ``jack (stafford) and i are good friends. i chose him to succeed me.''
asked why stafford quit, spoor said, ``you'll have to ask him. it just reached a point where it was no longer worth it to him.''
johnny thompson, company spokesman, said stafford was unavailable for comment. he said his departure was voluntary and that he left with no ties to pillsbury
pillsbury also said the board of directors appointed a search committee to seek a chief executive for the company to succeed spoor
stafford, 51, presided in fiscal 1987 over the company's first earnings decline in 16 years. earnings were $1.82 million, or $2.10 a share, down from $2.08 million, or $2.38 a share, in fiscal 1986
stock analysts who were projecting fiscal 1988 earnings of about $2.80 a share were told by stafford in february to lower the projections by about 30 cents a share, thompson said
that may have been the straw that broke the camel's back,'' said craig carver, a food industry analyst with minneapolis-based piper jaffray &amp; hopwood inc. ``he has been under increasing pressure by the board. that may have been what did him in.''
carver said declining performance in pillsbury's restaurant division led to the the sharp earnings decline in fiscal 1987. but when stafford told analysts to lower their projections for fiscal 1988 earnings, he said it was because of an expected earnings decline in the consumer foods division, which includes frozen pizza, desserts and mixes
the announcement came as a surprise, carver said
spoor, 65, remained on the company's board of directors after retiring as chairman and chief executive in 1985. in september his involvement in the company increased when he was selected chairman of the executive committee
mcorp has agreed to sell its majority-owned mtech computer services unit to electronic data systems corp. for $281 million in cash and securities
the pact signed monday supersedes a $234 million tentative agreement reached last month with an investment group headed by robert m. bass of fort worth
under the agreement, mcorp, a bank holding company, would would receive $122 million in cash, plus about $159 million in undetermined securities from general motors corp., the parent of dallas-based eds
the agreement is valued at around $30 per share, both companies said
the bass offer included $187.4 million in cash and $46.6 million in subordinated debentures
the stock market stuttered at the start today after zooming to a new post-crash high on monday
the dow jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks slipped 0.50, or 0.02 percent, to 2,071.12 in the first half hour of trading
but in the broader market, stocks gaining in price slightly outnumbered losers in the early going by 397 to 372 with 432 issues unchanged
volume on the big board totaled 29.88 million as of 10 a.m. on wall street, down markedly from monday when early dividend plays on utility stocks touched off heavy trading
analysts said traders received mixed signals from economic data released this morning. the government said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but an upward revision for december eased fears of an imminent recession
the commerce department reported a month ago that the index had declined 0.2 percent in december after falling in october and november. today's report, however, revised the december calculation to show an increase of 0.3 percent
three consecutive monthly declines in the index is the traditional, but not infallible, signal of an impending recession
also today, the commerce department said construction spending tumbeld 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months. the drop followd a 0.4 percent increase in december and evidenced weakness in both housing and non-residential building, economists said
aside from the inconclusive economic signals, market traders were expected to focus on the latest rash of takeover deals, which helped propel monday's advance. analysts said they did not expect any sharp reversals like the one that followed the market's brief january rally
