script writers and entertainment producers, trying to hammer out a strike-averting contract settlement, called a recess today after a 21-hour bargaining session
the writers guild of america said in a brief statement that negotiators recessed at 7:15 a.m. and agreed to return at noon
both sides declined to say if an agreement was near, but alliance and union officials earlier expressed pessimism
the old contract for the 9,000 members expired at midnight monday with no resolution to the union's demands for greater creative control on the set and more money from television residuals
it doesn't look optimistic,'' said cheryl rhoden, spokeswoman for the wga, which represents about 6,500 writers on the west coast and 2,500 on the east coast
the situation is not good,'' agreed herb steinberg, spokesman for the alliance of motion picture and television producers
the writers produce scripts for productions ranging from daytime soap operas and talk shows to prime-time dramas and feature films
a strike would be felt first by daily daytime programs and talk shows, ms. rhoden said. she said it would take longer for the effects of a walkout to become visible on shows produced in advance that need fewer scripts
negotiators were still at the bargaining table at 5 a.m. this morning and were expected to wrap up today
west coast union members would vote tonight on whether to approve the producers' final offer or strike. east coast members will vote wednesday, and results of the two votes aren't expected to be available until about noon wednesday
brian walton, the guild's chief negotiator, said going into the final round of talks monday evening that the wga would stay at the bargaining table as long as possible
but he criticized the producers' alliance for allegedly spreading stories of widespread financial problems in the industry
steinberg responded that the industry as a whole was doing well but makers of one-hour television series are suffering because of difficulty selling their products into syndication
main issues separating the two sides were disputes over creative rights, residuals from foreign markets and residuals for one-hour programs
the median annual income for writers is $40,000, but about half of the wga's members are unemployed at any given time, ms. rhoden said
the entertainment arm of the writers' union, which has a reputation as one of hollywood's most militant, last went on strike three years ago. that walkout lasted two weeks before writers voted to accept a package offering them essentially the same terms as the one they had earlier voted down
ms. rhoden said the guild also represents about 600 television news writers, who struck abc and cbs last spring, but they operate under a different agreement and weren't affected by the negotiations
grain and soybean futures opened steady to lower today on the chicago board of trade
a late rally monday sparked some overnight farmer selling of corn and soybeans, and that helped limit further gains on the opening today, analysts said
wheat traders were encouraged by news of new purchases by the soviet union and by the agriculture department's announcement that it had sold less than 16 million bushels in last friday's weekly auction of surplus wheat
but advances in wheat futures were limited by concerns about this afternoon's usda auction, the first in a series of three weekly auctions that will replace the once-a-week sales, analysts said
that's taking a little edge off the enthusiam over the soviets buying wheat overnight,'' said jerry gidel, an analyst in chicago for g.h. miller &amp; co
in early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to \ cent higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.14{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to \ cent lower with march at $2.03} a bushel; oats were unchanged to } cent higher with march at $1.95 a bushel; soybeans were \ cent to } cent lower with march at $6.35\ a bushel
