live cattle were .30 cent to .55 cent higher with april at 71.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .28 cent to .60 cent higher with march at 80.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to .30 cent higher with april at 43.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .28 cent higher with march at 51.90 cents a pound
livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on monday
farmers who received some government information late have been given additional time to file their 1987 federal income-tax returns
the internal revenue service said monday it was granting special relief to farmers who did not receive agriculture department documents by the feb. 15 scheduled date. those documents are form 1099-g, which reflects certain government payments, and form 1099-a, on which acquisitions or abandonments of secured property are reported
farmers generally are not subject to penalties for underpayments if they file their returns by march 1. the irs concluded that farmers who failed to receive required information from the agriculture department by feb. 15 might be unable to meet the march 1 deadline
the irs said farmers affected by the delay should attach to their tax return a form 2210f on which they have written their name and social security number and, on the bottom right, the words ``farm waiver.''
with the extension, farmers will have to file returns and pay any tax owed by april 15, the deadline for most taxpayers
most mornings angel salazar can be found standing at the side of the city's majestic metropolitan cathedral, waiting with dozens of other unemployed tradesmen for a lucky break _ a day's earnings as a plumber
salazar, 25, has been coming for about a decade to this spot in downtown mexico city, a traditional gathering point for tradesmen looking for work
jobs this year, he says, are harder than ever to get
it's more difficult,'' he said, wearing a worn beige sweater against the chill of the morning air in this mountainous capital. ``there's less work and everything is more expensive.''
hundreds of tradesmen use this spot, within sight of the president's office at the national palace, to advertise their skills to prospective employers
an electrician sets a light bulb on top of his metal tool box, while a painter drapes brightly colored paint chips over his khaki-colored canvas bag, bulging with the tools of his trade. others list their varied skills on small pieces of wood
but this morning, there is little demand for their talents
mexico has entered yet another year of economic crisis, a year of uncertainty as the government embarks on a new, untested and so far unpopular economic program designed to halt the inflationary spiral
it will be a very difficult year,'' cautioned jonathan heath, senior economist at the forecasting firm of macro asesoria economica in mexico city
1988 may well be a watershed year, said abel beltran del rio, executive director of the ciemex-wefa mexico forecasting group in philadelphia
it is a very crucial year in a sense on the economic front,'' he said. ``we will know if we are going to conquer inflation.''
the answer hinges on the government's risky new program, called the economic solidarity pact, which was introduced late last year in an effort to rein in the worrisome inflation rate
the plan has logic and everyone wants to have the pact succeed because if it doesn't, we'll be in a mess because inflation is so high,'' said a high-ranking government official in a recent interview
we feel we can reduce inflation very quickly without the social costs of having a huge recession,'' said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity
overshadowing the program is the july presidential election
carlos salinas de gortari, the nominee of the ruling institutional revolutionary party, is virtually certain to be sworn in as the next president on dec. 1
but voter unhappiness over his role as a key architect of the government's policy during the nation's 6-year-old economic crisis may cripple his ability to govern
heath predicts the anti-inflation program will show results in time for the presidential balloting
the government will make sure,'' he said, ``that inflation comes down at all costs by the elections. ...''
what happens with inflation and growth will help determine what happens with the election,'' he said
government officials say the program should quickly bring down the inflation rate to 1 percent to 2 percent a month by year's end so that the yearly pace is 65 percent to 75 percent, less than half the record 159.2 percent of 1987
in december, alone, consumer prices soared 14.8 percent, which at the time was the biggest monthly gain since the government began collecting those statistics in 1968. the record was broken again in january, with a 15.5 percent increase recorded in consumer prices
a key part of the program was to have been an indexation plan, slated to go into effect this month to regulate increases in wages and prices. this past week, the government decided to postpone the implementation of that plan until april and instead announced a 3 percent increase in the minimum daily wage and a freeze on regulated prices of such things as gasoline, telephones and electricity
the government also urged private companies to join in the freeze and said the exchange rate for the peso would be held steady in march
we are going to reduce the increase in prices according to some guidelines,'' said one government official
several major stores, showing their support for the inflation fight, already have announced special sales or given cash refunds of the 15 percent sales tax imposed on consumer goods
moreover, the government has taken additional steps to open the economy to more imported goods, reasoning that foreign competition will over the long run force mexican manufacturers to produce better, cheaper products
it also sharply devalued the peso currency and promised to cut its deficit spending
despite the government's confidence in its handiwork, some private analysts remain skeptical
i certainly don't see anything good coming up for the next year and a half,'' said patricia nelson, financial editor of the english-language mexico city news and a frequent critic of government economic policies
they're not going to get inflation down ...'' she said. ``i really don't think there's much hope of getting it under 200 percent (in 1988).''
heath predicts an inflation rate of 151 percent this year and worries the inflation-fighting program will plunge the economy into a steep recession. others forecast a mild recession or a no-growth year
government officials acknowledge the program will brake the economy into a slight downturn in the first half of the year. but they predict a robust rebound by the end of the year for a final growth rate of 2 percent
the economy likely grew at an inflation-adjusted 1 percent in 1987 after a decline of 3.8 percent in the previous year
in the public's mind, the program has gotten off to a poor start
in unveiling the solidarity pact in mid-december, the government put into effect a series of hefty price increases on a variety of basic goods and services. most of the gains outstripped boosts in the minimum daily wage, which now stands at about $3.50
everyday we spend more,'' said gabino lara, 62, a plumber waiting for work near the metropolitan cathedral. he complained the minimum wage covers ``nothing ... absolutely nothing.''
intended to pull together people from all walks of life into a common front against inflation, the pact is proving an effective rallying point _ practically everybody seems to be against it. or at least not enthusiastically behind it,'' wrote the weekly magazine mexico journal
but officials contend the program will overcome its initial unpopularity
what would really worry me is not to take them (the economic measures). there's nothing free,'' said one high-ranking official
for some kansas farmers, sunflowers have become more than a state symbol
wild sunflowers have always flourished here _ hence kansas' reputation as the sunflower state _ but now, farmers in the northwest and north central part of the state are making money by growing the tall, green and yellow plants for sale to snack-food processing plants
we're the newest crop in the state, and the fastest-growing,'' said john featherstone, one of two california men who opened the ag dynamics sunflower seed processing plant in goodland, kan., in october 1986
the two sought to locate their plant at goodland, a small farming community near the state's border with colorado, because its high altitude, low humidity, long growing season and irrigation are perfect for cultivating the high-quality sunflowers used in snack foods, featherstone said
although most of the sunflower processing has been done in minnesota and north dakota, the prime growing area is shifting southward to kansas, officials said
according to an informal survey by the state department of agriculture, the total number of kansas acres planted in sunflowers increased from about 60,000 acres in 1982 to about 200,000 in 1987. farmers yield about 2,000 pounds of sunflower seeds an acre
from 1985 to 1987, the number of acres planted in non-oil seeds in kansas increased by about 41,000
sunflower seeds are used to produce oil and bird seed, in addition to snack foods
it's not ever going to take over wheat,'' said agriculture secretary sam brownback, ``but it does bring in some money for these people.''
it wasn't always that way. kansas has been strong in growing basic crops with stable markets, but has lagged behind other states in growing and marketing specialty crops
they can grow the stuff but the problem has always been marketing,'' featherstone said. ``marketing is more than just taking orders.''
when ag dynamics first moved into the goodland area, for example, some farmers were growing sunflowers for use in sunflower oil and bird seed. but growers were reluctant to venture into the snack-food market because they were unfamiliar with the crop and skeptical of its money-making potential
depressed prices for traditional money-makers, such as corn and wheat, convinced many to take the plunge into the sunflower business. ag dynamics helped ease the transition for some by guaranteeing a market their specialty crop
we cover his (the farmer's) product by selling contracts to roasters on the other end,'' featherstone said
but brownback cautions that each farmer must decide whether alternative crops such as sunflowers are right for his or her situation
many established farmers have no incentive to try alternative crops, brownback said, but smaller farmers with less capital or those with debts receive needed cash when they grow on contract
at the goodland plant, seeds are dehulled, cleaned, sorted and bagged and then shipped out of state to several nut companies, where they are roasted, bagged and distributed, brownback said
ag dynamics sells its sunflower seeds to about 40 nut companies, including planters. they also export about 25 percent of the crop to other countries, such as mexico
for the 1988 crop, they will contract with farmers to grow about 30,000 acres, featherstone said. their first year, they contracted for about 350 acres
improving the field-to-market organization has brightened the future for kansas sunflower growers considerably. processing plants in north dakota and minnesota also are beginning to contract with kansas farmers for the sunflower seeds they use to produce snacks
a major portion of the crop is now swinging down into kansas,'' featherstone said
and the quality of the seeds grown in northwest kansas is so good, brownback said, ``we're getting some people requesting kansas sunflowers.''
cesar nava has a small and prosperous tool business in this bustling provincial city. but like most businessmen throughout mexico, he complains that inflation is eating him up
it is chewing up his profits, his capital, and his working money. worst of all, he says he's even getting used to it
like most others _ rich and poor _ he is becoming ``confused, losing confidence in the system and i don't know what lies in store tomorrow.''
nava's trials and tribulations are typical of those afflicting business people in mexico
when the economic crisis hit mexico back in 1982, nava's dealership sold mostly electric motors of up to 3 horsepower and mills for grinding ``nixtamal,'' the corn dough out of which tortillas are made. ribbon-saws and other carpentry tools were a sideline
as inflation grew, sales slumped and credit began to dry up, nava quickly made carpentry tools his main line, which he sold to colonial furniture-makers throughout michoacan state
nava, 45, a mechanical engineer by profession, got rid of the many salesmen he had on commission, keeping four of the best. he gave them a salary plus commission, but also made them double as drivers, deliverers, bill collectors and service men
he also gave his customers credit, on easy payment terms
not one of them welshed. some were late with their payments, but overall my collection rate averaged 98 percent, far better than any bank in the state,'' nava said
i'd give them up to 10 months credit, at about 6 percent when the banks were charging more than 11 percent monthly,'' he added
by late october 1987, nava's business was thriving. the salesmen alone were earning an average of 600,000 pesos monthly, the equivalent of $351, a good wage at the time and about one-quarter more than their rivals were making
but last november, the government suddenly devalued the peso currency from around 1,708 to around 2,025 to the u.s. dollar in order to keep the price of mexico's exports competitive. nava's working capital of 40 million pesos shrank overnight in dollar terms from the equivalent of $23,400 to $19,700
the devaluation set off another huge round of inflation, so president miguel de la madrid's lame-duck administration announced an economic solidarity pact to keep worker's purchasing power _ and sales _ from shrinking even further
the de la madrid administration has said its main aim is to keep things relatively stable until carlos salinas de gortari, the institutional revolutionary party's shoo-in candidate, is elected next july 6 and takes over as president dec. 1 for a six-year term
salinas de gortari, who was the current president's budget and planning secretary, has promised to ``modernize'' the country, closing or selling hundreds of money-losing state companies, slashing the budget deficit, reducing unnecessary subsidies
if salinas accomplishes even half of what he has promised we will all be in good shape. the trouble is that they (candidates) have made promises and promises over the years, but have not fulfilled them,'' said nava
so people believe less every day,'' he said, describing himself as neither a supporter of nor an indiscriminate critic of the ruling party
meanwhile, he complains that in real terms his business is shrinking
i have raised interest rates to my clients to 8 percent monthly and reduced payment deadlines to a seven months, maximum,'' he said. ``even so, we have had to absorb a lot of the added costs (caused by inflation)
as a result, he said that, ``while the volume of sales in peso terms has gone up, the number of units sold has dropped.'' overall his net profits have dropped 10 percent since late october
it's psychological to a great degree. inflation is in part due to a lack of confidence,'' he said
the stock market stumbled today after vaulting to a new post-crash high on monday
the dow jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks was down 1.33, or 0.06 percent, to 2,070.29 at noon on wall street
analysts had expected to see the market follow through on monday's advance, but the move failed to materialize in the early going. some said the morning's activity was highlighted by big investors cashing in their gains
stocks losing ground outnumbered gainers by 775 to 602 with 461 issues unchanged
volume on the big board totaled 103.25 million at noon, off from 133.99 million at the same time monday when dividend plays on utility stocks ignited an early trading burst
it's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go next,'' observed eldon grimm, senior vice president for birr, wilson securities
analysts said traders found little to inspire them in the economic data released this morning. the government said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but an upward revision for december eased fears of an imminent recession
also today, the commerce department said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months. but as in the case of the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in december
analysts said the figures were in line with expectations and had little impact on trading
aside from the economic data, market traders were expected to focus on the latest rash of takeover deals, which helped propel monday's surge
among the most active stocks on the nyse, federated department stores gained 1] to 67~ following r.h. macy's offer of $73.80-per-share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding shares. campeau corp., which has been chasing federated with a bid of $68 per share, said macy's offer was ``simply not competitive.''
but other results were mixed. sears, roebuck was up \ to 38; general electric was down \ to 45\, pillsbury was up 1 to 37}, wendy's was down [ to 7]; and international business machines corp. was up ] to 117~
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks was down 0.51 to 149.95 at mid-day. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up 0.65 to 289.11
on monday, the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41 to 2,071.62, reaching its highest point since the october crash. the run left the dow average 20 points higher than the previous post-crash peak of 2,051.89 on jan. 7
analysts noted that while today's early performance was disappointing, the market appeared firm enough to avoid the kind of slide that followed the january advance. the day after hitting that peak, the dow plunged 140 points
texas international co. has suspended payment of interest and principal on subordinated debts totaling $155 million
the oklahoma city-based oil and gas company announced monday that interest payments on the $155 million subordinated debt had become more than the company can handle
payments on other debt obligations will continue, said james gregory, director of investor relations for the company
our business environment has simply come to the point where it is presently not in the best interests of either our shareholders or our subordinated debt holders for us to remain current on our subordinated debt as it is currently structured,'' said james a. kishpaugh, president and chief executive officer
the first payment suspended was a biannual interest payment of $869,000 due monday on the company's 10 percent second delayed convertible senior subordinated notes due dec. 31, 1993, gregory said. principal on those notes is about $32 million, he said. the company has about 11 other issues of subordinated notes, he said
the problem is we're not generating enough cash flow from our egyptian assets'' to be able to handle both current debt and move ahead in the company's exploration plans, gregory said
by the end of 1987, texas international had expected crude oil production to be between 3overy on the khalda concession in the egyptian western desert, gregory said
instead, the concession is producing 20,000 barrels daily, with texas international receiving about 10 percent of that, he said
gregory said the company plans to meet with creditors and establish a plan to allow it to continue its exploration activities in egypt and elsewhere. and second report on construction spending; also moving on general news wires.</note>
the government's chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but an upward revision for december eased fears of an imminent recession
the commerce department reported a month ago that the index had declined 0.2 percent in december after falling in october and november
three consecutive monthly declines in the index is the traditional, but not infallible, signal of an impending recession
in today's report, however, the december calculation was revised to show an increase of 0.3 percent
since it was created in 1948, the index has correctly forecast every recession the country has had with declines for at least three consecutive months. thus, the revision to december was taken by economists as a heartening sign that the country is unlikely to suffer a downturn this year
the leading index shows that this is a no-recession year for the u.s. economy,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co. ``we will have a slower economy but no recession.''
sinai predicted that overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national product, could dip as low as 0.5 percent in the current january-march quarter as factories cut back production to work off a backlog of unsold goods. but he said growth will gradually strengthen as the year progresses, aided by continued strong demand for u.s. exports
the economy will have a reasonably good year for an election year, especially in view of the mine field of risks that are around, ranging from the old age of the expansion to the effects of the stock market crash,'' sinai said
in a second report today, the government said construction spending dropped a sharp 2.9 percent in january, the biggest setback in 10 months, as widespread weakness in all categories from housing to non-residential construction and government building posted declines
the leading index has taken on added significance since oct. 19, when stock prices plunged a record 508 points, eclipsing the 1929 market crash, which preceded the great depression
since october's steep decline, however, a number of business barometers have shown strength, including continued declines in the unemployment rate. even the stock market has rallied in recent weeks, climbing more than 48 points on monday to close at its highest level since the october collapse
economists are looking for the economy to slow in the first half of 1988, but they now believe that the sluggish growth will not worsen into a recession
the national association of business economists said monday that while more than half of its members responding to a november survey believed the country would suffer a recession this year, that figure had now dropped to about one-fourth
the 0.6 percent january decline was led by a big increase in new claims for unemployment benefits, which averaged 351,000 a week in january, up 12.5 percent from the december level. since january, however, the weekly unemployment claims figures have been falling, further easing recession fears
in all, five of the nine available indicators showed weakness during january. after unemployment claims, the negative factors were a drop in building permits, a decline in manufacturers' orders for consumer goods, changes in raw materials prices and a drop in business delivery times
four indicators showed strength during the month, with a rise in stock prices making the biggest gain. other positive forces were the growth of the money supply, increases in the length of the average workweek and a rise in orders for plant and equipment
the various changes left the index at 190.2 percent of its 1967 base of 100
michael evans, head of a washington forecasting firm, until recently had been expecting a recession in the early part of 1988. but he said he was now less pessimistic because a variety of business barometers have rebounded after an initial shock from the stock market decline
the economy isn't out of the woods yet, but a recession forecast is a diminished probability now,'' he said
the overall economy, as measured by the gross national product, raced ahead at a 4.5 percent rate in the final three months of 1987. but almost all of that increase came from a big buildup of unsold products
analysts said production will be cut back in the current quarter while those high inventory levels are worked down. many economists think growth will slow to below 1 percent with some even expecting a negative gnp growth figure from january through march
but economists think growth will then slowly improve, allowing the economy to expand at around 2 percent for all of 1988, about half of the 1987 level
most of the growth in the economy is going to come from exports with consumer spending and home building continuing to be depressed,'' said john o. wilson, chief economist at bank of america in san francisco
financial reforms agreed to by leaders of the european economic community two weeks ago appeared threatened tuesday by italy's refusal to pay its share into the 1988 budget
sources within the 12-nation common market said italy's objections to the budget draft could lead other eec states to disavow their earlier consent to the reforms. ``once one country begins to question the agreement, all others will want to do the same,'' one official said
the official, who asked to remain anonymous in keeping with established practice, said the problem is likely to be sent to a meeting of eec foreign ministers to be held march 5 at konstanz, west germany
of course, we are very disappointed that we have to deal with this problem at this stage,'' said a german official who asked not to be named. ``the whole situation endangers the 1988 budget ... everything is blocked,'' he said
the much-heralded reforms, agreed in brussels feb. 13, were designed to rein in the eec's skyrocketing farm spending and give the trading bloc a sound financial footing for the next five years
but italy's objections had forced common market budget ministers last wednesday to suspend efforts to adopt the overdue spending plan
in a letter monday to west german chancellor helmut kohl, prime minister giovanni goria rejected the formula as offending ``the principles'' on which the reforms stand
an official message from rome tuesday said italy's contribution to the fund was at least $143 million higher than agreed at the summit
west germany, which currently holds the eec presidency, gave italy until noon tuesday to change its mind
but the deadline passed and the italian government remained adamant in opposing the new formula for calculating national contributions to a budget supplement set at 7.6 billion european currency units, or $8.2 billion
that amount is needed to bridge the gap between anticipated spending needs totaling the equivalent of $54.6 billion and revenue available under current eec rules
texas financier charles hurwitz has moved to gain control of kaisertech, the world's fifth largest aluminum producer, with an agreement to pay up to $230 million for a 32.1 percent voting share
hurwitz' bid to kaisertech chairman alan e. clore competed with a bid by marc rich, a swiss aluminum business owner. hurwitz, like clore, has no experience in the aluminum industry
the announcement monday said the company would have preferred that the british industrialist's' holdings be sold more broadly. clore was under intense pressure to sell from creditors
if clore hadn't found a buyer by a monday deadline, he could have faced default on loans he had obtained using kaiser stock as collateral. after the stock plunged because of the october market crash, lenders wanted repayment
the oakland-based company's stock rose $1.125 a share monday to close at $11.875 on the new york stock exchange
under the deal, los angeles-based maxxam group inc., a company controlled by hurwitz, agreed to buy from clore and his lenders 6.2 million shares of kaisertech stock for $12 a share
once maxxam purchases the stock, it has an option to acquire 8.2 million shares of kaisertech convertible preferred stock at $13.75 to $14 a share. maxxam also must pay $8 million to $10 million in expenses, the nature of which was undisclosed
in addition, maxxam is negotiating agreements with other parties to buy an additional 2.8 million shares of kaisertech common stock for $12 a share
it was not clear what effect maxxam's purchase would have immediately on the kaisertech board. all 14 seats are up for election shortly. included are eight board members appointed by clore, including clore and james pasman, kaiser's chief executive officer
the probable changes in kaisertech's executive suite and boardroom come as the company is rebounding from six straight years of losses. kaiser has sold its chemicals, oil and gas businesses, has slashed debt, and is concentrating on its core aluminum business
british aerospace plc has expressed interest in acquiring state-owned rover group plc, the moneylosing automaker that the government previously said it intended to sell
trade and industry secretary lord young said tuesday that the government would negotiate until april 30 with british aerospace, which was privatized in 1985. if the negotations fail, lord young said the government would explore other options for divesting its 99.8 percent stake in the automaker
rover group chairman graham day said he welcomed british aerospace's interest
for rover group we see this as a very exciting opportunity. the two groups are complementary and not competitive,'' he said. ``in addition, it offers a speedy route to privatization, with the minimum disruption to our management, work force, dealer network and suppliers.''
the government had said it would sell the rover group, makers of the land rover vehicle and sterling cars, by 1992
rover group is comprised of the austin rover carmaker and the land rover utility vehicle maker. it sold the leyland trucks unit last year
in rover's most recent earnings report, the group said it lost $74 million on revenue of $2.8 billion in the first six months of 1987. but the loss was 80 percent less than in the year-earlier period
the government took over the automaker, formerly called british leyland, in 1975 to prevent its collapse
general motors corp. has announced an agreement in principle to sell its fairfield auto parts stamping plant to cynba international inc
cynba, headed by automotive executive anthony barclae, proposes to continue operating the stamping plant, gm officials said at a news conference tuesday
gm declined to reveal the sale price. it is one of two plants in southwest ohio that gm is closing as part of a nationwide program to cut operating costs and stay competitive
gm shut down its norwood auto assembly plant last aug. 26, eliminating 4,300 jobs there, and plans to close the fairfield operation in august
barclae proposes to buy the fairfield plant and equipment. he also promises to try to hire laid-off gm employees, gm officials said
the deal is contingent on a feasibility assessment. barclae has 90 days to explore business opportunities and talk with city, state and united auto workers union officials and to decide whether to buy the plant
about 2,500 people once worked at the fairfield plant. current employment stands at 971
barclae owns and operates two sheet metal stamping and assembly plants _ shadyside stamping corp., in shadyside, ohio, and pigeon manufacturing corp., in pigeon, mich. he also operates cameo color coat inc., a detroit-based automotive corrosion resistance painting company
peter konzak of devils lake rummaged through the clutter of his briefcase and found a letter as proof that his invention, a ``pop-up scarecrow,'' has already earned him some attention, if not wealth
i am still invited to the johnny carson show. it is a standing invitation,'' the 66-year-old retired farmer said, answering questions about his scarecrow at the second annual north dakota inventors congress
forty inventors and manufacturers, most of them from north dakota, showed off gizmos, gadgets and thingamajigs at the show that ended tuesday
spokesman scot nething said only four of them had displayed their wares in last year's show. ``it's a whole new crop.''
the inventions showcased this year ranged from an ultralight airplane manufactured in edgeley to a swinging mailbox that a minot man devised after a neighbor complained about his mailbox getting knocked down by snowplows each winter
and then there was a lawnmower doubling as a fertilizer spreader, a clothes dryer vent closure, a crayon holder, a retractable engine heater cord and a wheel bearing packer
konzak's pride and joy stood at one side of his booth on the floor of the jamestown civic center
it was a steel contraption wearing fluorescent work gloves, decked out in red and yellow ribbons and sporting a dummy's head adorned with a cowboy hat
in a sunflower field, the clumsy-looking ``pest-scaring device'' jumps up from among the plants, twirls and whistles to startle blackbirds and keep them from feasting on the seeds, konzak said monday
all you need is one on 40 acres,'' he said. ``with the buzzer in here and all the stuff, it can pay for itself in one year.'' a battery and propane tank give the scarecrow its life
since getting his mechanical scarecrow patented in april 1986, konzak has made about 30 of them and sold them all at about $500 apiece, he said
but he said he hasn't made any money yet. ``i've just made my expenses. i put $20,000 into patenting this thing.''
business hasn't even been that brisk for the ultralight maker, jackson manufacturing co. of edgeley, which built its first ultralight airplane a year ago and has sold two so far, sales manager gene hanson said. a yellow one displayed at the inventors congress costs $7,450, not including options
ranchers can use them. retired people. anybody who likes to fly can use them. it isn't any different than boating, motorcycling and snowmobiling,'' hanson said. ultralights don't require pilots' licenses
gordon johnson of cando displayed his ``garda-a-lok,'' which he patented a year ago. it clamps around the outside door handle of motels or apartments, a lock over a lock. ``nobody gets into that room,'' he said
tonight, there will be one on our motel room when we leave it,'' he said
walt behrens of minot developed his damage-proof mailbox last fall and sold 16 so far at $46.90 each
the idea is simple _ a mailbox that swings back into place if a snowplow or other vehicle gets off the side of the road and bashes it
behrens, who retired after 28 years as an assistant airport manager, came up with the idea after a neighbor complained about how difficult it was replanting an uprooted mailbox when the ground was frozen
behrens said he provides his own testing laboratory: ``i got my own out by the road, of course, and i give it a bat and a swing to see how it's working.''
the dollar ended mostly lower against major foreign currencies tuesday after another sluggish trading session in europe. gold prices rose
traders said the dollar came under some mild selling pressure late in the day, possibly because of a slightly worse-than-expected u.s. leading indicators statistic for january
the commerce department said the index fell 0.6 percent in january, but the decline was partly offset by a revision in the december index to a 0.3 percent rise from a previously announced 0.2 percent fall
many dealers discounted the dollar's slight decline tuesday and said the market remains stagnant
the british pound, meanwhile, was boosted by higher interest rates in britain. sterling rose to $1.7775 from $1.7725 monday
other late dollar rates in europe compared with late monday included: 1.6855 west german marks, down from 1.6875; 1.3915 swiss francs, up from 1.3903; 5.7065 french francs, down from 5.7150; 1.8940 dutch guilders, down from 1.8945; 1,244.35 italian lire, up from 1,244.25; 1.2570 canadian dollars, down from 1.2622
the dollar rose in tokyo, closing at 128.63 japanese yen, up from monday's close of 128.12 yen. later in london, the dollar was lower at 128.30 yen
gold rose in london to a late bid price of $428.70 a troy ounce, compared with monday's late bid of $425. in zurich, gold was higher at a bid $429.50 compared with $426 monday
the metal closed in hong kong at a bid $433.80, up from $430.19
silver bullion prices rose on the london market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.29 a troy ounce, compared with $6.14 monday
looking at japan's trade figures for the past year is like looking at a glass of water _ the glass is either half empty or half full, depending on one's perspective
from the japanese side, the figures show improvement, with exports beginning to decline in volume terms after years of growth that provoked resentment among its trading partners
from the american side, the trade deficit with japan rose again, mainly because the soaring yen inflated the cost of japanese imports
in tokyo, government officials are optimistic that recent trade statistics show a trend toward reducing japan's huge trade surplus. but independent economists are voicing reservations over long-term trade prospects
referring to the latest u.s. trade figures, a ministry of international trade and industry official said the tide is slowly turning and that, although the figures showed the biggest deficit in history, the imbalance with japan actually decreased
it depends on whether you look at trade in yen or dollar terms,'' he said
japan's exports rose 5.6 percent in dollar terms but fell 8.2 percent in yen terms in the last three months of 1987, compared to a year earlier. at the same time, imports rose in terms of both dollars and yen
as for volume, japan's imports are growing, with a big increase from the newly industrialized countries and europe, though the increase with the united states was not so large,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
according to u.s. figures, the trade deficit last year was a record $171.2 billion, up from $156.2 billion in 1986. the united states' largest bilateral deficit again was with japan _ a record $59.8 billion, up from $58.6 billion in 1986 and $49.7 billion in 1985
ron napier, vice president and japan economist with the investment firm of salomon brothers inc., does see a short-term easing in the trade imbalance, but warns that good figures in the short term may be misleading
the first quarter looks good, and we will see a brief lull because japanese automakers have too much inventory already in the united states,'' he said. ``but i don't really think the figures for the final quarter of 1987 signal that japan's trade surplus has topped out. there were basically no trends in 1987.''
barriers keeping u.s. exporters out of certain japanese markets, such as highly controversial restrictions on imported beef, citrus fruits and rice, add to the trade imbalance problem and have come under heavy fire from the u.s. government
but the most pressing question now may not be barriers or exchange rates, napier said
i think that the yen-dollar rate is no longer a problem for u.s. exporters. more marketing focus is needed in this country, which traditionally has not been a target,'' he said
napier said the united states lags behind europe and the newly industrialized countries in expanding exports to japan because of a lack of distribution facilities, an insufficient sales force and scanty product representation
it was interesting to hear that u.s. steel would be exporting again, but that they chose europe as their market,'' he said
the official at the japanese trade ministry agreed
success depends on exporters' efforts,'' he said. ``exporters in the u.s. now have the chance to compete. japanese consumers are changing and there are more and more foreign products for sale in supermarkets here
domestic demand for foreign goods is increasing, so now is the time for the u.s. to try to expand in the japanese market. exporters should act immediately to take advantage of developments here,'' he added
as for the future prospects of japan's trade with the u.s., i think that with the yen-dollar rate our imports will continue to steadily increase.''
napier also offers some comfort to americans wondering if the trade imbalance with japan will ever end
the marketing focus is starting to change, with more attention being given to japan,'' he said. ``it may take awhile, but this will eventually have an impact.'' agreement</head>
a federal bankruptcy judge has approved the sale of kaiser coal corp.'s two northern new mexico coal mines to pittsburg &amp; midway coal mining co. for $97.7 million, a company official said
but the deal's consummation hinges on the resolution of a dispute over a coal delivery contract with arizona's salt river project, said fred meurer, pittsburg &amp; midway manager of public affairs, on tuesday
u.s. bankruptcy judge charles e. matheson on monday approved pittsburg &amp; midway's purchase of the york canyon complex _ two coal mines 35 miles west of raton, n.m. _ for $88.1 million in cash and the assumption of $9.6 million in kaiser's liabilities, said meurer
we're gratified at the ruling, and we'd like to close on the deal as soon as possible,'' meurer said
the bankruptcy judge's ruling was required because kaiser coal corp. and its parent company, kaiser steel corp., have been operating under chapter 11 reorganization since february 1987, said meurer
but he said that part of the agreement calls for his company's assumption of kaiser's 25-year agreement to supply 475,000 tons of coal per year from the york mines to the salt river project _ while the salt river project is trying to end the agreement through a petition to the bankruptcy court
prior to closure of this sale, this litigation must be favorably resolved,'' said meurer. he said matheson was scheduled to hear arguments march 22 and 23
when the deal is made final, pittsburg &amp; midway, a chevron corp. subsidiary, will gain control of a surface mine and an underground mine that together employ 275 hourly employees and 75 salaried workers, said meurer
he said the pittsburg &amp; midway has been managing the mines since january and laid off 74 employees on feb. 22
the mines produced 1.75 million tons of coal last year, meurer said
archer daniels midland co., a major processor of raw agricultural commodities, has signed a letter of intent to buy clc of america inc., a st. louis-based barge line, the companies have announced
the barge company emerged in december from a complex chapter 11 bankruptcy, during which it fended off several buy-out offers. adm agreed to pay about $60 million in common stock for the company in a transaction to be completed by june, company officials said
the acquisition will substantially increase archer daniels midland's ability to to transport grain and finished products, adm vice-president richard e. burket said monday
we've been doing a greater volume and have greater needs for river transportation,'' burket said
clc has a fleet of 515 barges, 13 line haul towboats, 12 switching boats and barge fleeting facilities in wisconsin, iowa, new orleans and st. louis
the transaction does not include morgan drive away inc., a subsidiary of clc that provides highway transportation of mobile homes, recreational vehicles and other commodities, clc officials said
industry observers view the merger as a mark of confidence in a barge industry slowly recovering from years of financial turmoil. clc faced a staggering pile of debts when it filed for bankruptcy in january 1986, but in the last two years, barge shipments have increased and barge rates have risen
the stock market crept ahead today after vaulting to a new post-crash high monday
the dow jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks recovered from a small loss earlier in the day to stand at 2,071.95, up 0.33, or 0.02 percent, at 2 p.m. on wall street
analysts had expected to see the market follow through on monday's strong advance, but the trend was mostly disappointing with two hours of trading to go. some said the morning's activity was highlighted by big investors cashing in their gains
stocks losing ground outnumbered gainers by 802 to 688 with 424 issues unchanged
volume on the big board totaled 147.54 million at 2 p.m., well behind the levels reached at the same time monday when dividend plays on utility stocks ignited an early trading burst
it's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go next,'' observed eldon grimm, senior vice president for birr, wilson securities
analysts said traders found little to inspire them in the economic data released this morning. the government said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but an upward revision for december eased fears of an imminent recession
also today, the commerce department said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months. but like the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in december
analysts said the figures were in line with expectations and had little impact on trading
aside from the economic data, traders focused on issues swept up in the latest rash of takeover deals, which had powered monday's surge
among the most active stocks on the nyse, federated department stores gained 1[ to 67| following r.h. macy's offer of $73.80-per-share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding shares
gaf corp., which received a sweetened buyout offer from its top management, dipped [ to 49~
other results were similarly mixed. sears, roebuck was up \ to 38; general electric was down ] to 45[, pillsbury was up 1\ to 38, wendy's was down [ to 7]; and international business machines corp. was up [ to 117|
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks was down 0.46 to 150.00. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up 0.79 to 289.25
on monday, the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41 to 2,071.62, reaching its highest point since the october crash
senior officials from britain, france, west germany and spain on tuesday ordered europe's airbus industrie to try to reach an agreement on industrial and commercial cooperation with mcdonnell douglas corp. by mid-1988
the decision emerged at the end of a one-day meeting of transport ministers and chief executives of the industrial partners in the european commercial aircraft group
aviation industry observers said it was the latest display of europe's eagerness to penetrate the lucrative u.s. market while trying to reduce trade friction over american claims of unfair competition by airbus
trade negotiators from the united states, the european community commission and the four airbus partner-countries are scheduled to meet in konstanz, west germany, march 18 to discuss u.s. claims that the europeans unfairly subsidize the consortium
french transport minister jacques douffiagues told reporters after the ministers' meeting that airbus' mandate is ''unlimited,'' although the negotiations would tend to focus more on planned aircraft than on existing programs
a cooperation accord with mcdonnell could take the form of a joint venture or co-production scheme, he said
douffiagues suggested that possible areas of useful cooperation between airbus and mcdonnell could include small short-range jets with between 100-150 seats as well as large aircraft with 350 seats or more. ''there is no upper limit,'' he said
''any agreement with mcdonnell must be balanced, taking account of the advantages and constraints for both sides,'' douffiagues said
douffiagues said part of the interest in an agreement is that it would ease airbus's access to the u.s. market, where the group has only three customers
a statement released after the meeting said airbus' mandate is to negotiate ''diligently'' and ''with a will to reaching a balanced agreement that is beneficial to the two parties.''
the industrial partners of the airbus consortium _ france's aerospatiale, britain's aerospace, messerschmitt-boelkow-blohm of west germany and spain's construcciones aeronauticas _ have had contacts with mcdonnell for almost two years now on eventual cooperation
previous talks with mcdonnell douglas on possible cooperation collapsed in 1986
w.t. grimm &amp; co., a firm that specializes in the purchase and sale of small to mid-sized companies and monitors the pace of corporate acquisitions, has become part of its own takeover statistics
wall street giant merrill lynch &amp; co. said tuesday it had acquired chicago-based grimm, recognized as a prominent source of information about merger and acquisition activity. the price wasn't disclosed
the acquisition of w. t. grimm further enhances our ability to provide fee-based services to small businesses and to the high net-worth individuals who own them,'' john l. steffens, president of the merrill lynch consumer markets, a subsidiary of the parent company, said in a press statement
the statement also announced the appointment of jeffrey s. feldman, a director of merrill lynch's business financial services unit, as president of grimm, which will remain headquartered in chicago. james j. kelly, grimm's principal shareholder, will become a senior vice president, the statement said
the stock market slipped lower today after vaulting to a new post-crash high monday
the dow jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks held its ground most of the day but weakened in afternoon trading, falling 13.26, or 0.64 percent, to 2,058.36 at 3 p.m. on wall street
analysts had expected to see the market follow through on monday's strong advance, but the trend was mostly disappointing with just an hour of trading to go. some said the day's activity was highlighted by big investors cashing in their gains
stocks losing ground outnumbered gainers by 890 to 640 with 415 issues unchanged
volume on the big board totaled 174.08 million at 3 p.m., behind the levels reached at the same time monday when dividend plays on utility stocks ignited an early trading burst
it's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go next,'' observed eldon grimm, senior vice president for birr, wilson securities
analysts said traders found little to inspire them in the economic data released this morning. the government said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but an upward revision in the index of leading economic indicators for december eased fears of an imminent recession
also today, the commerce department said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months. but as was the case with the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in december
analysts said the figures were in line with expectations and had little impact on trading
aside from the economic data, traders focused on issues swept up in the latest rash of takeover deals, which had powered monday's surge
among the most active stocks on the nyse, federated department stores gained 1[ to 67| following r.h. macy's offer of $73.80-per-share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding shares
gaf corp., which received a sweetened buyout offer from its top management, dipped [ to 49~
other results were similarly mixed. sears, roebuck was up [ to 37~; general electric was down ~ to 44|, pillsbury was up 1\ to 38, wendy's was down [ to 7]; and international business machines corp. was down ~ to 116|
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks was down 1.07 to 149.39. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up 0.06 to 288.52
on monday, the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41 to 2,071.62, reaching its highest point since the october crash
a management group led by gaf corp.'s chairman has raised its bid for the company to $1.4 billion, and the board of directors agreed to submit the offer to shareholders ``without endorsement,'' gaf said tuesday
the deal, now valued at $1.4 billion, would provide $46 in cash and junior securities with a face value of $6.50 for each share
in december, the group led by chairman samuel j. heyman had offered $1.35 billion, or $40 in cash and $8.50 in securities per share
that represented a downward revision from its $2.3 billion first offer, made in september, of $64 in cash and $2.50 face value in debt securities. heyman said rising interest rates made it impossible for the group to continue the original bid
a special committee of the board of the specialty chemicals and building materials company has agreed to submit the new proposal ``without endorsement'' to shareholders, gaf said
to permit that, shareholders must first vote on an amendment to the company charter
the amendment would allow shareholders to act in place of the board in considering a merger offer, as the heyman-led proposal has been presented
the committee had earlier rejected the $64-a-share proposal as being inadequate. gaf said it had decided to let stockholders decide based on the favorable opinion of the offer by salomon brothers inc., retained by the committee as financial advisers
the decision was also made following the committee's instructions to salomon brothers to solicit other possible purchasers, gaf said
the committee said that if it receives an ``economically superior alternative proposal'' for gaf, it could cancel its agreement with the buyout group
we think the price is a fare and full price,'' heyman said. ``it's seven times the price of the stock only four years ago.''
gaf stock, which reached a low of $31.50 after the oct. 19 stock market crash, has traded around $50 with speculation about an agreement
it was $49.75, down 25 cents, on the new york stock exchange in afternoon trading tuesday
the agreement will put the management offer ``to the test of the marketplace,'' said heyman, who wrested control of gaf in 1983 after a bitter proxy fight to oust former chairman jesse werner
during his tenure, gaf has made hundreds of millions of dollars in unsuccessful buyout attempts of union carbide corp. and borg-warner corp
we're primarily an operating company, but we're not retiring from the takeover arena,'' the 48-year-old executive said tuesday
heyman owns 2.8 million shares of gaf, or about 10 percent of its outstanding stock
he said the takeover would be financed by loans from a bank syndicate led by chase manhattan, a limited debt offering and the group's own money
gaf also said it had reached tentative settlements of lawsuits brought in connection with the buyout offer
du pont co. will pay $39 million to clean up ditches, lagoons and other groundwater sites contaminated by hazardous waste that seeped from its chamber works plant here, a company official said tuesday
the cleanup is part of an administrative consent order with the state department of environmental protection and represents the largest settlement by a single company for one location to date in the united states, said commissioner richard t. dewling
the company will construct a 2{-mile pipeline that will transport waste water from the plant to du pont's on-site water treatment plant, assistant plant manager stuart schenk said. construction is expected to be completed in 1991
in addition, three water basins and about six miles of unlined ditches on the 1,600-acre site will be cleaned up and no longer used to store waste water, schenk said
the company makes about 750 chemical products at the facility in the deepwater section of this salem county community. the waste water is generated by the manufacture of those products
the plant is also the state's largest commercial hazardous waste disposal facility and one of three existing industrial facilities seeking state approval to build an incinerator to burn hazardous wastes generated elsewhere in the state
midwest express airlines announced tuesday it will provide a free trip to corporate executives and consultants interested in looking at wisconsin as a business location
jose oller, vice president for marketing, made the offer to forward wisconsin inc., a milwaukee-based economic development and marketing concern aimed at attracting business to wisconsin
our support will entail complimentary air transportation for site inspection parties on their first visit to wisconsin from any midwest express on-line destination,'' oller said
that includes service to milwaukee, madison or appleton from atlanta, boston, dallas, new york, washington, philadelphia and newark, n.j
bp america inc., enjoying higher oil prices in 1987, reported a return to profitability
the former standard oil co., now a segment of british petroleum co. plc, earned $564 million in 1987. standard oil incurred a $188 million loss in 1986, its final full year not under bp's control
due to tax accounting requirements of the united kingdom, bp america could not report fourth-quarter net earnings, spokesman john andes said tuesday. the company's results were released monday
income from operations in the fourth quarter was $613 million, compared with $109 million in standard oil's fourth quarter of 1986. in all of 1987, operating income totaled $2.26 billion, compared with an operating loss of $242 million in 1986
the 1986 annual loss included $1.13 billion for writedowns and restructuring charges
operating income reflects what bp america contributed to its parent company's results. operating income does not include regular tax charges or interest payments on debt
the report was the first release of financial results by bp america since june, when british petroleum bought the 45 percent of common stock of standard oil co. that it did not already own
bp america sales were $15.4 billion, compared with $13.9 billion in 1986. for the fourth quarter, sales were $4.01 billion, up from $3.35 billion for the year-ago period
as these results show, bp america's performance is highly dependent on crude oil prices,'' said robert b. horton, chief executive officer of the company
in 1987, higher crude oil prices, lower costs and increased production have significantly improved the contribution made by the exploration and production segment,'' he continued. ``we also benefited from the resumption of activity at the bingham canyon mine (in utah) at a time of higher copper prices.''
grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower tuesday on the chicago board of trade
concerns about increased supplies offset bullish expectations of new export business, analysts said
it really turned into a quiet affair here after we were down early and then came back,'' said jerry gidel, an analyst in chicago for g.h. miller &amp; co
wheat posted the greatest losses, with pressure stemming from the agriculture department's auction of surplus wheat scheduled for later in the afternoon, gidel said
the auction marks the beginning of a series of thrice-weekly auctions which will replace the weekly friday sales the usda began in november
the agency has said it hopes to sell 10 million bushels of wheat in each of the new auctions compared to targets of about 25 million bushels for the old weekly auctions
at the close, wheat was 3} cents to 4{ cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3.11 a bushel; corn was unchanged to } cent lower with march at $2.03} a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to { cent higher with march at $1.94\ a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to } cent higher with march at $6.34} a bushel
unilever, the anglo-dutch home products giant, reported tuesday that its fourth-quarter net profit was flat as revenue slipped a bit
the company, which is made up of unilever plc of britain and unilever nv of the netherlands, said its after-tax profit was unchanged at 186 million pounds, which is the equivalent of about $331 million. sales dipped 0.7 percent to 4.45 billion pounds, or about $7.92 billion, from 4.48 billion pounds
unilever said pre-tax profit on its north american activities doubled to the equivalent of $178 million
for all of 1987, unilever reported a net profit of 756 million pounds, or about $1.35 billion. that was up 14 percent from earnings of 664 million pounds the previous year
sales for the year fell 3 percent to 16.55 billion pounds, or about $29.5 billion, from 17.14 billion pounds in 1986
pre-tax profit on north american activities also doubled for the year, rising to the equivalent of $425 million
unilever said that for the full year, sales gains were recorded in most product groups and substantial contributions were made by recent acquisitions, including the u.s.-based chesebrough-pond's inc., which was purchased in december 1986 for $3.15 billion
a brussels court on tuesday approved societe generale de belgique s.a.'s issuance of 12 million new shares in a ruling that could intensify the battle for control of belgium's biggest holding company
societe generale announced in january it was raising its capital to 40.2 million shares from 28.2 million shares, shortly after italian investor carlo de benedetti indicated he wanted to gain control of the company
de benedetti raised questions about the new capital issue in court, and the courts stripped the shares of voting rights in two previous decisions
tuesday's ruling would retore voting rights for those shares temporarily and if approved by a higher court, the issue would dilute the stake of all shareholders
belgian industrialist andre leysen, who is aligned with de benedetti, said he has an option on 10 million of the 12 million new shares
but the management of societe generale, which opposes de benedetti's bid, has said the option is no longer valid because leysen failed to form an alliance in support of societe generale early last month
societe generale director etienne davignon said the new shares are owned by seven companies from belgium, luxembourg and france that have formed an alliance which is siding with the 166-year-old company
the alliance claims to hold 52 percent of societe generale's original 28.2 million shares
de benedetti has claimed he and his allies control 47.2 percent of societe generale's shares, but davignon said it was only 43 percent
if a higher court confirms the capital increase, davignon said it would reduce de benedetti's stake to about 28.5 percent
meanwhile, de benedetti said in a statement from milan he intends to call a shareholders meeting to decide the future of the company after its public offer to buy more societe generale shares ends march 4
a source close to de benedetti said ``we are fully confident we will have a majority of shares at the meeting.''
leysen's holding company gevaert n.v said in a statement it was ``now in a position'' to buy the new shares as it had agreed to do on feb. 3
the shares were initially placed with a societe generale subsidiary but have since been sold to the seven companies allied with it, davignon said
the top official of societe generale, rene lamy, said last week the agreement with leysen was no longer valid ``since leysen has failed to cement a belgian federation'' in support of societe generale
leysen could not get a deal with several belgian and european groups to keep the company anchored in belgium earlier this month
instead, he reached a partnership agreement with de benedetti and the copeba holding company, the belgian subsidiary of the french paribas group
together they founded a new holding company called europa 92
the management of societe generale first announced the capital increase jan. 18, just after de benedetti said he wanted to take control and turn it into a holding company with interests across europe
societe generale has interests in about 1,400 companies worldwide and in about half of belgium's top 50 companies. it has an important stake in belgium's gas, electricity and petroleum sector and in belgium's largest bank
public service co. that was also a prerequisite for the modernization plan
although the energy issue has been resolved, the second issue _ namely productivity improvements in the workplace that would result in employment and security and profit-sharing _ must also be resolved with equal satisfaction,'' rediger said
the closure of the four mills would leave two shaped-products mills at indiana harbor works chicago, inland's only steelmaking plant
inland had previously announced its intention to close two of the mills even without worker concessions, olszanski said
an additional 500,000 metric tons of subsidized u.s. wheat has been sold to the soviet union, the agriculture department said wednesday
the sale, equal to about 18.3 million bushels, was handled by continental grain co., 100,000 tons; cargill inc., 375,000 tons; and mitsui grain corp., 25,000 tons
at recent prices averaging $2.75 per bushel, the wheat would have a farm value of about $50 million
more than 6.8 million tons of subsidized wheat has been sold to the soviet union under the department's export enhancement program, or eep, for delivery in the year that began last oct. 1
george j. pope, acting general sales manager for the department's foreign agricultural service, said that only 200 tons of wheat are still available to the soviet union under current eep authorization. there has been no official indication that a new line of subsidy may be approved
under eep, private exporters are given surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp. so they can sell a foreign buyer wheat or other authorized commodity at competitive world prices
pope said the subsidies, or bonuses, averaged $27 per ton on the latest sales, or about 74 cents per bushel. the subsidies for the soviet union have been available only for wheat
the sales also are part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of a long-term agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans, or 39.4 bushels of corn
in addition, 2.62 million tons of u.s. corn, 813,300 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal have been bought by the soviets for delivery this year
the stock market finished lower today after fighting to hold the gains that propelled it to a post-crash high monday
analysts had expected to see the market follow through on monday's strong advance, but the trend was mostly disappointing. some said the day's activity was highlighted by big investors cashing in their gains
it's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go next,'' observed eldon grimm, senior vice president for birr, wilson securities
traders found little evidence in the government's latest batch of statistics to satisfy their curiosity about the health of the economy. the commerce department said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but december's index of leading economic indicators was revised upward, easing fears of an imminent recession
also today, the government said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months. but as was the case with the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in december
because the figures were inconclusive, they had little impact on trading, analysts said
aside from the economic data, traders focused on issues swept up in the latest rash of takeover deals, which had powered monday's surge
lionel trains inc. will keep 1988 sales rolling with a tiny video camera that almost lets model railroaders feel like part of their prized layouts, a spokesman said tuesday
and in an effort to establish itself in other areas, lionel is making plastic parts for a new board game for would-be rail tycoons, marketing director john brady said
lionel hopes the high-tech, miniaturized ``railscope'' video camera, expected to be in stores in time for christmas, will be the ticket to higher sales
the camera is small enough to mount in a locomotive for an engineer's eye view of a model railroader's prized layout
it's just like getting small and becoming part of that layout,'' brady said. ``it's a simple idea that was not doable until this year.''
lionel developed the tiny black-and-white electronic camera with the help of james wickstead design in new jersey. the picture can be displayed on a standard television or even larger screen, although lionel will sell a 4{-inch monitor, brady said
railscope was introduced at the annual toy fair trade show in february in new york, he said, adding, ``i had people asking to buy the prototype.''
it will sell for about $300 in a model-train collectors market in which lionel's prices, for example, range from less than $75 for a train set to more than $1,000 for a locomoti
attached to each bomb were about 300 sticks of dynamite, according to a communique issued by the civil aviation office. the bombs and the dynamite were buried at the western end of the runway, and were connected to a 2,000-foot-long detonating cable that ran to a secluded ravine nearby, it said
the explosives were discovered on saturday, the communique said
according to la nacion, a government-owned and -operated daily published in santiago, the bombs represented ``a new extremist plot against the head of state's life.''
it cited unidentified security sources as saying the bombs were planted in late january, after it was announced that pinochet would attend an agricultural fair in la serena on jan. 29. the president later canceled the visit
in september 1986, pinochet survived an ambush of his motorcade by the pro-communist manuel rodriguez front, the country's principal leftist guerrilla organization. five of his bodyguards were killed in the attack by machine-gun and rocket fire
pinochet on tuesday credited providence with foiling the reported plot in la serena
god doesn't want to carry me off, so he helps me,'' pinochet told reporters in the southern city of puerto montt, where he was inspecting public works projects. his remarks were broadcast by santiago radio stations
it give me more enthusiasm to fight for my country, as i am doing,'' he said. ``i'm a lot luckier than they (extremists) think.''
he said it was only ``by chance'' that he did not travel to la serena as planned. ``there were a series of problems that obliged me to stay in santiago,'' he said without elaboration
