wal-mart stores inc. reported tuesday its fourth quarter-earnings jumped 34 percent as sales at the rapidly-expanding discount store chain rose 30 percent
wal-mart said that for the quarter ended jan. 31., it earned $247.1 million, or 44 cents per share, up from $184.3 million, or 32 cents per share, in the final three months of fiscal 1986
sales for the 1987 quarter rose to $5 billion from $3.85 billion
for the full year, wal-mart said its earnings were up 39 percent to $627.6 million, or $1.11 a share, from $450.1 million, or 79 cents a share, in all of 1986
sales for the year totaled $15.96 billion, up from $11.91 billion in 1986
wal-mart continued its explosive growth throughout 1987. as of jan. 31, 1988, the company had 1,211 stores, including wal-mart, dot drugs, sam's wholesale club and hypermart usa stores. on jan. 31, 1987, the company operated 1,035 stores
the company's stores are located in 24 states, primarily in the midwest and southwest
the dollar fell marginally against most key currencies tuesday, reflecting what dealers called a narrow trading range that has emerged over the past several days
gold prices rose overseas but were mixed in the united states. as of 4 p.m. est, republic national bank of new york quoted gold at $430.45 a troy ounce, down 15 cents from the price late monday
currency dealers said there was little news to influence the behavior of the dollar. they said a commerce department report on the index of leading indicators, an important economic barometer, failed to convey a definite trend
the department said the index fell 0.6 percent in january but it revised the december figure from a 0.2 percent drop to a 0.3 percent increase. that revision snapped a string of three straight monthly declines, which has often signaled an impending recession
we need something more specific to set the market one way or another,'' said zlatko glamuzina, chief currency dealer at the new york branch of the italian bank banco di sicilia
gary dorsch, senior money market economist at lns financial group inc. in chicago, said ``there appears to be very little impetus for traders to move out of the dollar's range, at least in the near term.''
by contrast, he said, currencies such as the british pound and canadian dollar seemed to be appreciating because of relatively high interest rates in britain and canada
we're seeing a lot of deflation in commodity markets and weakness in gold prices, which supports the idea that global interest rates will be steady to lower,'' dorsch said. ``so international money managers are searching for higher yields.''
the dollar rose in tokyo, closing at 128.63 japanese yen, up from the monday close of 128.12 yen. later in london, the dollar was lower at 128.30 yen. by the time trading concluded in new york, the dollar was trading at 128.32 yen, marginally higher than 128.24 rate late monday
the british pound rose to $1.7775 from $1.7725 monday on the london market. later in new york, sterling was quoted at $1.7766, more than the $1.7742 quoted late monday
other late dollar rates in new york compared with late monday levels included: 1.6864 west german marks, down from 1.6874; 1.3916 swiss francs, down from 1.3931; 1.2578 canadian dollars, down from 1.2592; 5.7100 french francs, down from 5.7155; 1,243.25 italian lire, up from 1,243
late dollar rates in europe compared with late monday included: 1.6855 west german marks, down from 1.6875; 1.3915 swiss francs, up from 1.3903; 5.7065 french francs, down from 5.7150; 1.8940 dutch guilders, down from 1.8945; 1,244.35 italian lire, up from 1,244.25; 1.2570 canadian dollars, down from 1.2622
gold rose in london to a late bid price of $428.70 a troy ounce, compared with $425 late monday. in zurich, gold rose to $429.50 vs. $426, and in hong kong gold closed at $433.80 vs. $430.19
on the new york commodity exchange, gold for current delivery rose 50 cents a troy ounce to $431
silver bullion prices rose in london to $6.29 a troy ounce, compared with $6.14 monday. on the new york comex, silver for current delivery fell 1.7 cents an ounce to $6.222. recapitalization</head>
american standard inc., target of a hostile $2.12 billion takeover attempt by black &amp; decker corp., said tuesday it was taking steps to sweeten the cash portion of a recapitalization designed to foil the bid
the company said it had begun talks with unidentified third parties regarding the possible sale of debt securities as a means of increasing the cash part of the recapitalization, which would pay shareholders $1.9 billion plus give them a stake in the recapitalized company
a recapitalization, in which a company restructures its amount of debt and equity, is used often to thwart unwelcome takeovers. the strategy usually plunges a company into debt, making it less attractive as an acquisition
under the american standard recapitalization plan, which would raise the company's long-term debt from $412 million to $2.3 billion, stockholders would receive $59 in cash, $5 worth of high-yielding debt securities and one new share of stock in the recapitalized company for each share of old stock
the company's announcement tuesday did not elaborate on how much it intended to raise the cash portion of the recapitalization but said there was no assurance that any change would be made in the existing proposal
in composite new york stock exchange trading, american standard stock rose 12{ cents a share to $68.62{. black and decker stock rose 62{ cents a share to $19.12{
black &amp; decker, a tool and appliance maker based in towson, md., has been attempting since late january to acquire american standard, a new york-based maker of plumbing, air conditioning and auto equipment
the stock market slipped off its post-crash peak tuesday but showed enough spunk to hold most of its recent gains
the dow jones industrial average of 30 stocks bounced off its lows late in the day, closing down 1.16 points, or a scant 0.06 percent, at 2,070.46
with an hour to go, the blue-chip average had been down more than 13 points, but traders took the opportunity to buy stocks, pushing the dow near monday's close of 2,071.62, its high-water mark since the oct. 19 collapse
stocks declining in price outpaced gainers by 7 to 6 on the new york stock exchange, with 811 issues declining, 696 gaining and 457 unchanged
big board volume totaled 199.99 million shares, against 236.05 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index dipped 0.28 to 150.18
the market's lackluster numbers belied its resilience, some analysts said. they noted that the market's previous post-crash high, reached on jan. 7, was followed the next day by a drop of more than 140 points
the relative firmness of prices tuesday suggested to some that the market had finally found its sealegs
the market had every reason to go down and it didn't,'' said michael metz, a technical analyst for oppenheimer &amp; co
traders are no longer afraid of a crash; they're afraid of missing a buying opportunity,'' said metz
others were not so sure. hugh johson, chief investment officer for first albany corp., characterized the market as ``almost lifeless,'' adding that uncertainty about the economy was still a drag on trading
a batch of government statistics released tuesday failed to satisfy the market's curiosity about the economy's health
the commerce department said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in january, but the december reading for the index of leading economic indicators was revised from a 0.2 percent drop to a 0.3 percent gain
the government also said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months. but as was the case with the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in december
it was a little frustrating,'' said johnson. ``we had hoped to resolve some of the uncertainty (about the economy) and we didn't.''
the only conclusion is ... we'll miss a recession (in 1988), but not by much,'' he said
aside from the economic data, issues swept up in the latest rash of takeover deals dominated interest as they had monday when the dow jumped more than 48 points
among the most active stocks on the nyse, federated department stores gained 1\ to a new high of 67} following r.h. macy's offer of $73.80 a share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding shares
j.p. stevens, which received a revised buyout offer from a management group and said other parties had expressed interest in the company, jumped 6\ to 54{, also a new high
other results were mixed. sears, roebuck was up { to 38\; general electric was down { to 45; pillsbury rose \ to 37; bethlehem steel rose ~ to 21]; atlantic richfield dropped ~ to 76; and international business machines corp. was down { to 117
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 230.18 million shares
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials dropped 0.62 to 308.81, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was down 0.60 to 267.22
the wilshire equity index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks lost $3.69 billion in value to settle at $2,632.042 billion
at the american stock exchange, the market value index gained 0.45 to 288.91. the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market closed at 367.32, up 0.37
wheat futures prices slipped substantially lower tuesday on the chicago board of trade as the agriculture department launched a new series of auctions aimed at reducing government stockpiles of surplus wheat
on other markets, other grains and soybeans ended mostly lower; energy futures retreated; most livestock and meat futures advanced; precious metals were mixed; and stock-index futures were higher
the usda's weekly auctions of suplus wheat, begun in november, have gradually lost steam. so on tuesday the agency launched a new series of sales to be held three times a week
the agency has set targets of 10 million bushels for each of the new auctions during the first two weeks, which creates the potential for adding 30 million bushels a week to the open market
the old weekly auctions usually had targets of 25 million bushels. sales in recent weeks had fallen well short of that goal, however, with less than 16 million bushels sold last friday
traders fear the new auctions, which divide the sales by regions of the country, will be more successful and depress cash prices by adding to available supplies of wheat, analysts said
the possibility of selling 10 milllion bushels the first time out is probably going to be a little tough,'' said jerry gidel of chicago-based g.h. miller &amp; co. ``but it's the fact that they're coming right back tomorrow, then on friday again, that has the market a little on edge.''
however, analyst jim quinton of agri-visor services inc. in bloomington, ill., said the new auctions probably would have little long-term impact on futures prices
quinton attributed tuesday's wheat losses of up to 5 cents a bushel to profit-taking by speculators
results from tuesday's auction will likely be released on wednesday
wheat settled 4{ cents to 5 cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3.11 a bushel; corn was unchanged to } cent lower with march at $2.03} a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent higher with march at $1.94{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher with march at $6.35 a bushel
energy futures prices, particularly for refined products, fell sharply on the new york mercantile exchange, where analysts said bulls and bears have been waging a technical tug-of-war
this market seems to be moving briskly within a range, which is what it probably will continue to do before it decides which way it wants to go,'' said peter beutel, an analyst in new york for elders futures inc
west texas intermediate crude oil traded as much as .46 cent lower, but settled .11 cent to .29 cent lower with april at $15.72 a barrel; heating oil was .82 cent to 1.15 cents lower with april at 43.47 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .93 cent to 1.10 cents lower with april at 45.29 cents a gallon
livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on the chicago mercantile exchange
cattle futures moved higher in mostly technical trading, analysts said
hog futures advanced on bargain buying after monday's sharp decline, said tom price, vice president of linnco futures inc. in chicago
live cattle were unchanged to .52 cent higher with april at 71.95 a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .85 cent higher with march at 80.42 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with april at 43.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .42 cent lower with march at 51.60 cents a pound
gold moved slightly higher while silver futures retreated a bit on new york's commodity exchange
gold for april delivery sank to $425 a troy ounce during the session, but rebounded to settle at $432.40
richard levine, vice president of elders' precious metals divison, noted that gold had touched $425 on monday as well, and predicted it would bounce off that level once more before falling to $400 a troy ounce in the next three or four weeks
silver drifted lower in featureless trading, he said
gold settled 50 cents to 60 cents higher with april at $432.40 a troy ounce; silver was 1.7 cents to 2 cents lower with march at $6.222 a troy ounce
