ted turner, tbs president and chairman, said the agreement affirms tbs' commitment to developing high-quality family programming. corrects globe newspaper from owner to publisher of globe in last graf.</note>
affiliated publications inc., owner of the boston globe, said tuesday it has bought a 40 percent equity interest in xyquest inc. of billerica, a developer of software for word processing and publishing systems
under the agreement, affiliated will pay $3 million for newly issued xyquest shares
xyquest, founded six years ago, developed the xywrite word processing line
in prepared remarks, affiliated president john p. giuggio said of the investment, ``this is an exciting young company with a promising future in electronic publishing. xyquest has an excellent management team, and we're delighted to be associated with it.''
xyquest president john hild said the company's long-term goals for product development include creating a full range of tools for writing and editing and continuing to expand into corporate word processing
affiliated is parent company of globe newspaper co., which publishes the globe. it also owns billboard publications inc., the globe pequot press inc., and a major interest in mccaw cellular communications inc
government reports tuesday painted a confusing picture about the health of the economy and led to indecision in the financial markets
the government said its chief barometer of future economic activity fell again in january, although an upward revision in december eased fears that the nation was headed for a recession
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 1.16 points to 2,070.46. it was equally quiet in the bond market, where the treasury's bellwether 30-year bond fell a slim [ point. the dollar was narrowly mixed
the commerce department's index of leading economic indicators dropped 0.6 percent in january. analysts discounted the sharp decline and instead focused on a revision that changed the index's showing in december from a 0.2 percent decline to a 0.3 percent increase
the leading index has taken on added importance since last oct. 19, when stock prices plunged a record 508 points, eclipsing the 1929 market crash that preceded the great depression
the upward revision for december broke a string of three consecutive monthly declines, which has often in the past been the signal of an impending recession. the index had fallen 0.1 percent in october and 1.1 percent in november
separately, the commerce department said construction spending fell 2.9 percent in january, the biggest decline in 10 months, reflecting widespread weakness in all sectors of the building industry
economists said the decline was bigger than expected and will likely mean that construction will be a drag on overall economic growth in the first quarter of 1988
what was surprising about the figures was how widespread and pervasive the weakness was. virtually every category from housing to industrial to hotels and motels did poorly in january,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co
economists said the december revision in the leading index and other positive signs provided evidence that the country is suffering few adverse effects from the market turmoil
sinai said it showed that ``this is a no-recession year for the u.s. economy.''
since it was created in 1948, the leading index has fallen three or more months during an expansion on 12 different occasions. on eight of those instances, a recession did follow. but four times the index gave a false signal of a downturn and the recovery kept going, although at a slower pace
analysts said the index is indeed sending a signal of slower growth for the first half of 1988, but they predicted that rising export sales would be enough to offset expected weakness in consumer spending and construction
the economy, as measured by the gross national product, raced ahead at a 4.5 percent rate in the final three months of 1987, but the bulk of that increase came from a buildup of unsold products. economists predict that production cutbacks will slash growth to a rate of 1 percent or less in the first three months of the year
for 1988 as a whole, many economists are forecasting growth of around 2 percent, just about half the 3.9 percent gnp increase registered last year
analysts said various business barometers have eased their fears of an end to the current recovery
industrial production and export sales are still rising, orders and employment continue to grow and the stock market is regaining its balance,'' said richard rahn, chief economist for the u.s. chamber of commerce. ``absent any policy blunders by congress or the federal reserve, i anticipate a strong second half.'' after 8th graf, ``analysts said''; also running on general news wires</note>
the government said tuesday that its chief barometer of future economic activity fell again in january, but an upward revision in december eased fears that the nation was headed for a recession
the commerce department's index of leading economic indicators dropped 0.6 percent in january. analysts discounted the sharp decline and instead focused on a revision that changed the index's showing in december from a 0.2 percent decline to a 0.3 percent increase
the upward revision for december broke a string of three consecutive monthly declines, which has often in the past been the signal of an impending recession. the index had fallen 0.1 percent in october and 1.1 percent in november
the leading index has taken on added importance since last oct. 19, when stock prices plunged a record 508 points, eclipsing the 1929 market crash that preceded the great depression
economists said the december revision in the leading index and other positive signs provided evidence that the country is suffering few adverse effects from the market turmoil
the leading index shows that this is a no-recession year for the u.s. economy,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co. ``the magic string of three or more declines which has often suggested a recession was broken.''
since it was created in 1948, the leading index has fallen three or more months during an expansion on 12 different occasions. on eight of those instances, a recession did follow. but four times the index gave a false signal of a downturn and the recovery kept going, although at a slower pace
analysts said the index is indeed sending a signal of slower growth for the first half of 1988, but they predicted that rising export sales would be enough to offset expected weakness in consumer spending and construction
the stock market, which closed monday at its highest level since the oct. 19 collapse, edged down a bit wednesday, with the dow jones industrial average dipping 1.16 points to 2,070.46. analysts said the signal from the leading index that the country would escape a recession this year was not forceful enough to prompt another wave of buying
beryl sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said he believed the three declines in the leading index in the past four months was accurately signaling slower but continued growth in the economy
the good news is that there is no series of three running'' declines, which could mean a recession, he said in answer to questions. he noted that the administration's own economic forecast calls for slower growth this year
in one indication that the economy has slowed, the commerce department said in a second report tuesday that construction spending fell a steep 2.9 percent in january to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $395.2 billion. it was the biggest drop in 10 months and reflected widespread weakness in all categories of construction
the economy, as measured by the gross national product, raced ahead at a 4.5 percent rate in the final three months of 1987, but the bulk of that increase came from a buildup of unsold products. economists predict that production cutbacks will slash growth to a rate of 1 percent or less in the first three months of the year
for 1988 as a whole, many economists are forecasting growth of around 2 percent, just about half the 3.9 percent gnp increase registered last year
but where half of the country's business economists in november were predicting a recession in 1988, that figure has now declined to 25 percent, according to the latest survey of the national association of business economists
analysts said various business barometers have eased their fears of an end to the current recovery
industrial production and export sales are still rising, orders and employment continue to grow and the stock market is regaining its balance,'' said richard rahn, chief economist for the u.s. chamber of commerce. ``absent any policy blunders by congress or the federal reserve, i anticipate a strong second half.''
three-fourths of the decline in the january leading index came from a big jump in new claims for unemployment benefits, which averaged 351,000 a week in january, an increase of 39,000 weekly claims from december. since january, however, weekly unemployment claims have been falling, further easing recession fears
in all, five of the nine available indicators showed weakness during january. after unemployment claims, the biggest negative factors were a drop in building permits, a decline in manufacturers' orders for consumer goods, changes in raw materials prices and changes in business delivery times
four indicators showed strength during the month, with a rise in stock prices making the biggest gain. other positive forces were the growth of the money supply, increases in the length of the average workweek and a rise in orders for plant and equipment
the various changes left the index at 190.2 percent of its 1967 base of 100
many analysts predicted that the january decline in the leading index would be followed by significant advance in the leading index for february, based on already known information about the economy
ford motor co. said it reached separate agreements early tuesday with bargainers representing workers at two plants in mexico, including one idled since feb. 8 by a strike
two-year agreements were reached with the council of automotive workers of ford motor co., representing about 1,000 hourly employees at the chihuahua engine plant and another 1,100 at the hermosillo stamping and assembly plant, ford said in a statement
chihuahua workers went on strike feb. 8, eight days after their previous two-year contract was extended, the statement said. production of 2.3-liter, four-cylinder engines for the domestic market and export to the united states and canada was to resume wednesday, it said
the hermosillo workers' contract expired at midnight monday. but ford did not indicate whether production of two- and four-door mercury tracers for export to the u.s. and tracer station wagons for export to the u.s. and canada was interrupted
william h. spoor, returning as chief executive officer of the pillsbury co., said tuesday the company has no intention of selling its burger king subsidiary despite the chain's flat performance in recent months
spoor, named monday to replace john m. stafford as pillsbury's chairman and chief executive officer, also announced several management changes at the minneapolis-based parent company
on wall street, pillsbury stock rose 25 cents a share to $37 in trading on the new york stock exchange
burger king, which generates 40 percent of pillsbury's sales, reportedly has seen its share of the hamburger chain market fall in recent months after rapid growth in the mid-1980s
burger king's share fell to about 16.8 percent in early 1987 from a 1986 high of 17.4 percent, the wall street journal reported in december
the company has said its average sales per store have been flat at about $1 million for the past two years
i want to say without qualification that burger king is central to pillsbury,'' spoor said in a statement at the conclusion of a two-day meeting of pillsbury's board of directors
that was true yesterday, it is true today, and it remains true for the company's strategic future,'' he said
spoor's statement made no mention of pillsbury's other restaurant businesses _ steak &amp; ale, godfather's and bennigan's _ and a spokesman said neither he nor stafford was available for comment tuesday afternoon
spoor had retired from pillsbury in 1985, but remained on the company's board of directors. his return as ceo was announced monday in a statement that gave no reasons for stafford's resignation
i pledge to take whatever steps are necessary in the next three months so that we will enter fiscal 1989 with momentum and a solid portfolio of businesses capable of returning superior shareholder value,'' spoor said in his statement
we have a clear strategy that will lead us successfully into the 1990s. fiscal 1988 is a disappointment in many ways, but our future is bright and fiscal 1989, which begins june 1, will be an excellent year and gratifying to our shareholders.''
pillsbury in fiscal 1987 reported its first earnings decline in 16 years: $182 million, or $2.10 a share, down from $208 million, or $2.38 a share, in fiscal 1986
stock analysts who were projecting fiscal 1988 earnings of about $2.80 a share were told by stafford in february to lower the projections by about 30 cents a share, a pillsbury spokesman said
spoor on tuesday announced four promotions in the top management of the company:
_john l. morrison, was elected a pillsbury executive vice president and was named chairman, u.s. foods. he was formerly a pillsbury vice president and president, international foods
_thomas r. mcburney, executive vice president, was named chairman, international foods. mcburney served previously as chairman, u.s. foods
_jerry w. levin, executive vice president, corporate development and chairman of the haagen-dazs co., was given the additional responsibility for pillsbury's industrial foods business. industrial foods was previously a part of u.s. foods
_james r. behnke, senior vice president for technology, was made responsible for pillsbury's research and development activities worldwide. management trying to `force' strike, picking up 7th graf pvs, `first to...'.</note>
a walkout by 9,000 movie and television script writers seemed likely tuesday as last-ditch contract talks ended with major issues unresolved and the union saying the producers' last offer appeared designed ``to force a strike.''
negotiators for the writers guild of america and the alliance of motion picture and television producers met for just two hours before calling it quits tuesday afternoon
the brief meeting followed a marathon, 21-hour session that lasted until 7:15 a.m. tuesday and made progress on ``25 to 30 lesser issues,'' said herb steinberg, spokesman for the producers
but the two sides remained far apart on the three major stumbling blocks _ a ``creative rights'' issue that would give original writers more control over the product, higher residual payments when programs are distributed in foreign markets, and a revision of residuals for domestic syndication in the stagnant market for one-hour programs
both steinberg and union spokeswoman cheryl rhoden confirmed there was no significant movement on those issues in the afternoon session
it (the producers' final offer) appears to be a company-generated package designed to force a strike,'' ms. rhoden said
she said the union will study the proposal but declined to say if union leaders would recommend that it be rejected until it is presented to members
the union's 6,500 west coast members were to vote tuesday night on the latest proposal from management, while the 2,500 east coast members are to vote wednesday afternoon
results from both votes are to be released wednesday evening, and a strike could come as early as thursday if the producers' offer is rejected. the union's old contract expired at 12:01 a.m. tuesday
first to feel the impact of a walkout would be daily daytime tv programs and talk shows that have a short lead time for scripts. the effects on prime-time programs and feature films wouldn't be visible unless a strike was protracted
for producers, the key issue has been obtaining relief on the payment of residuals for syndication of one-hour television programs. the market for such programs has dried up significantly, producers say
they are asking the writers to adopt a revised residual plan similar to one already approved by directors. under that plan, writers would 50 percent of the normal residuals if a program is put out in only limited syndication. if it is later put out in full national syndication, they get another 100 percent, making it possible for them to receive 150 percent of their normal payments
on the creative-rights issue, the union is seeking to get original writers the power to do the first rewrite of any material, plus the right to be on the set when the program is produced
the producers say such issues must be negotiated individually
on foreign residuals, the union claims writers haven't had a change in their payment schedule in 17 years. that schedule now is based on a single lump sum payment and varies widely based on individual negotiations
the entertainment arm of the writers' union, which has a reputation as one of hollywood's most militant, last went on strike three years ago. that walkout lasted for two weeks before writers voted to accept essentially the same terms they had rejected earlier
the median annual income for writers is $40,000, but about half of the wga's members are unemployed at any given time, the union says
affiliated publications inc., owner of the boston globe, said tuesday it had a net loss in its fourth quarter, partly due to its equity share of the loss suffered by its mccaw communications cos. affiliate
affiliated posted a net loss of $3.62 million in the quarter ended dec. 27, compared with a profit of $40.1 million, or $1.14 per share, in the same period a year earlier
revenue during the quarter rose to $135.6 million from $110.3 million a year earlier
affiliated said its equity share of mccaw's losses from continuing operations during the quarter was $19.2 million. affiliated said the operating loss stemmed from expansion of mccaw's mccaw cellular communications subsidiary and accounting changes relating to the unit
for the year, affiliated posted a profit of $201.1 million, or $5.73 per share, compared with $66.1 million, or $1.85 per share, a yer earlier. revenue rose to $490.1 million from $401.1 million in 1986
gains from the sale of discontinued operations and results from discontinued operations in 1987 came to $40 million against $26.3 million in 1986. earnings for 1987 included equity in an extraordinary $17.9 million credit from mccaw communications
mccaw, based in kirkland, wash., is the parent of mccaw cellular communications, the country's largest operator of cellular telephone systems
in addition to a major interest in mccaw, affiliated owns globe newspaper co., publisher of the globe; billboard publications inc., and the globe pequot press inc. editing to tighten. no pickup.</note>
gov. bob martinez joined a court action to block texas from banning fresh florida citrus on tuesday, the same day a federal judge in texas overturned the ban
the ban was imposed last month after the u.s. department of agriculture lifted a 3{-year-old federal quarantine on florida citrus that was prompted by outbreaks of citrus canker in florida
u.s. district judge james nowlin said tuesday in austin, texas that he lifted the state ban because federal rules allowing the shipments took precedence over the state rule
martinez had notified texas gov. william p. clements that he was joining a court petition to be filed by florida agriculture commissioner doyle conner supporting a court action brought by florida citrus growers
texas officials had refused to allow florida citrus into their state despite the lifting of the federal quarantine on shipments of florida fruit to other citrus-producing states. florida producers must take a number of actions to ensure their fruit does not introduce citrus canker into other states
a major foreign trade group asked the government wednesday to slow the south korean currency's appreciation against the u.s. dollar
in a report to the government, the korea foreign trade association said the recent sharp rise of the won against the dollar could lead to a series of collapses among exporting firms
a stronger won _ and conversely, a weaker dollar _ raises the costs of korean products in the united states, a major export market
the united states has been pressuring south korea to revalue its currency at a faster pace to help reduce the nation's growing u.s. trade surplus, which soared to $9.5 billion last year
the association said if the won's value rises 10 percent against the dollar, the average export profitability of south korean-made products would fall by 3.7 percent
the won has appreciated by 4.13 percent against the dollar so far this year, accounting for about half the range registered for all of 1987. as of wednesday, the won was quoted at 760.90 to the dollar, down 31.30 won from year-end 1987
if the won continues rising at that pace, its appreciation rate for all of this year could surpass 24 percent, the association said
